<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELSBY GETS OVER BAD MIAMI MEMORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Every fisherman has a story about the one that got
away. UCLA receiver Brad Melsby's is as fresh in his mind as
today's catch.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, in a spot once renowned for its Dolphins, he reeled
in a thing of beauty. He had that ornery sucker hook, line and
sinker until it released on him and was swept away by a Hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most such stories, this one had some 47,000 witnesses and
a national television audience to boot. ESPN's ``Fishin' Hole,'' it
was not. Nor, we're happy to report, was Melsby's setback in Miami
a black hole that swallowed him whole after spitting out the
Bruins' 20-game winning streak and their national-title hopes.
</P>
<P>
   The junior split end was bummed for a few days. But he soon
realized that his lost fumble after a marvelous catch late in the
fourth quarter of UCLA's game against Miami wasn't the sole reason
the Bruins were deep-sixed at the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It only seemed that way because that snippet from the game was
what all the sports highlights shows ran with. As excruciating as
it was for Melsby to watch himself lose that football over and over
and over again, it wasn't necessarily a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   The replays clearly showed he was down when the ball squirted
free at the Hurricane 26 with under three minutes to play. Miami
proceeded to drive 74 yards for the winning points.
</P>
<P>
   The more Melsby saw his innocence upheld, the easier it was to
let go of his personal guilt. Twenty-seven days later he's eager to
wade back into the current, bait the Wisconsin secondary and land
the catch of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't easy to be able to say, `Oh, well, that's the way it
goes,' after the Miami game,'' Melsby said after a recent practice
leading up to today's Rose Bowl date against the No.9 Badgers. ``I
don't think I'll ever be able to say that. I feel partly
responsible for what happened. But that's the chance you take when
you play.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from Melsby, that answer qualifies as a filibuster. There
are knees and ankles and knuckles in the Bruins' locker room that
are louder than the former Orange County prep standout.
</P>
<P>
   He is the quietest of communications majors, reserving most of
his words for the journals he keeps. His introversion should not be
mistaken for introspection, though it often is by outsiders who
persist in pursing the angle that Melsby is his own worst enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's been exaggerated a bit,'' said the redshirt
junior, who caught a 61-yard touchdown pass with 21 seconds left to
beat Oregon State in November. ``I'm hard on myself. But so are the
other receivers. (The difference is) I don't hide the way I feel if
I'm disappointed about a practice or a game. I show it. That's just
me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is kind of a perfectionist, but not to the point
where it's self-destructive,'' said junior offensive tackle Kris
Farris, who is Melsby's closest friend on the team along with
defensive end Pete Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Farris and Melsby are like Oscar and Felix, with Farris
scattering sentences all over the place and Melsby neatly
compartmentalizing his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Farris is playful, Melsby is pensive. Melsby is laconic, Farris
is loquacious. Farris can tick off the winners of the best-picture
Oscar. Melsby can rattle off Stanley Cup champions.
</P>
<P>
   They're so completely different, it's no wonder they get along
so well. They clicked from the start, though Farris couldn't be
sure at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 Farris, a very good player at Santa Margarita High, was
in awe of Melsby, who was putting up astonishing numbers at Los
Alamitos High (he would wind up the leading career receiver in
Orange County high-school history).
</P>
<P>
   So shortly after they both committed to UCLA, Farris called
Melsby on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of nervous,'' Farris recalled, ``because Brad was
pretty big-time. I was used to reading the daily report on Brad
Melsby in the papers. I asked him if he wanted to be roommates and
he said OK and the conversation sort of died right there. I wasn't
sure what to make of that. I was like, does he think I'm an idiot
for asking or what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the first day we moved in for our freshman year,'' Farris
continued, warming to his subject, ``I remember he cracked open a
Stephen King novel. All I wanted to do was talk to him, and all he
wanted to do was read. I was, like, what's this guy's story?''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later nothing _ and everything _ has changed. Melsby
can't crack open a book without getting completely sidetracked by
Farris' wisecracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living with Kris, it's been a lot of fun,'' Melsby said.
``He's helped me to see the humor in a lot of situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Melsby, Farris and Holland are so close, a single word that
sounds perfectly innocuous to anyone else who hears it can send the
three of them into hysteria. They have more inside jokes than did
Seinfeld's Jerry, George and Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   Much like that sitcom, their gig may be ending prematurely, in a
few months' time. Today's game could be Farris' last in a UCLA
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of strange,'' Melsby mused. ``Kris is so loose, and
he's the one who's going to have football be a part of his life for
so much longer.''
</P>
<P>
   That's mainly how things have changed between Melsby and Farris.
The way Melsby was celebrated coming out of high school, that's how
Farris is being lionized now. After winning the Outland Trophy,
he's hearing the siren song of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Melsby, meantime, has struggled to regain his freshman form and
promise after tearing the anterior cruciate ligament in his left
knee during spring drills in his sophomore year. The injury
effectively cost him two seasons as his physical and psychological
wounds were painfully slow to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness he always had fishing. If there's anything Melsby
catches better than footballs, it's fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lake by my house that my family had been going to
three times a year since I was seven,'' Farris said. ``I had never
caught any fish there but the first time I took Brad, he got a bass
within five minutes. That was the first time I thought fishing was
a skill.''
</P>
<P>
   Angling for answers, we landed Melsby's secret to fishing and to
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patience,'' Melsby said, smiling. ``That's the key.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
