</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-BLACKHAWKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS' OFFENSE ENDS THE YEAR QUIETLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ When the Islanders wake up on Friday, it will be a new
year. Too bad they will not wake up to a new season.
</P>
<P>
   They embarked on a three-game trip with high expectations,
having gone 3-1-2 in their previous six games.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents _ Florida, Tampa Bay and Chicago _ were considered
weak, Islanders Coach Mike Milbury said. There was even talk of
climbing back into the playoff chase.
</P>
<P>
   That was five days ago. The Islanders (13-22-2) lost to the
Chicago Blackhawks by 1-0 Thursday night at the United Center. They
have hit rock bottom, done in by a persistent problem: they can't
score.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, who are 1-12-3 in their last 16 games against
Chicago, were shut out for the second straight game, Thursday by
Jocelyn Thibault, extending their scoreless streak to 153 minutes
44 seconds. They lost 3-0 to Tampa Bay on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thibault was spectacular when he needed to be, making 28 saves;
Marcel Cousineau, the Islanders' goalie, was also splendid in
making 20 stops. Thibault's most important save came against six
Islanders skaters in the final minute. He thwarted Robert Reichel
from close range.
</P>
<P>
   With the starter Tommy Salo (broken finger) sidelined and the
backup Wade Flaherty ineffective, Cousineau started his second
straight game.
</P>
<P>
   Cousineau, who was making his 10th start in the National Hockey
League, has played well enough the last two games to perhaps
replace Flaherty as the backup once Salo returns next week.
</P>
<P>
   Cousineau's best save came late in the second period when he
made a sprawling stop of Tony Amonte's rebound shot.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blackhawks finally cracked Cousineau late in the second
when Bob Probert scored from a tight angle, deflecting the puck off
Cousineau, who was scrambling to back into position. Probert's goal
gave the Blackhawks' a 1-0 lead at 17:20.
</P>
<P>
   Thibault matched the Islanders' goalie save for save. He made
several superb stops to deny the Islanders. The best came in the
first period when he slammed the door on Zigmund Palffy's one-timer
from close range.
</P>
<P>
   After getting a goal and two assists in his first two games
back, Palffy has gone pointless in three games since. Playing with
Bryan Smolinski and Claude Lapointe, he was not a factor again
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The injury-plagued Islanders got a scare in the first period
when their captain, Trevor Linden, limped off the ice after Nelson
Emerson's slap shot hit his knee. Linden was in obvious pain, but
was able to return minutes later. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman RICH PILON left the game after the first period with
a back strain. He will be re-evaluated on Friday in New York. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
