A4470 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-STARS-BOS &LR;      01-01 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-STARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREAKING STARS OVERPOWER BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ And what a test it was.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins knew they had their work cut out coming to Dallas to
take on the league-leading and streaking Stars and finish off a
1998-ending road trip. How right they were.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins stayed with the Stars for most of two periods. But
that was it, as Boston absorbed a 6-1 loss at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Sergei Zubov made it 3-1 late in the second period
and Dallas took charge in the third, as Pat Verbeek put his second
goal past Bruin goalie Robbie Tallas for 4-1 at 4:11. The rout was
on.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas took less than two minutes to answer a tying goal by Ray
Bourque early in the second period. And when it was over, the Stars
had scored five straight goals, at one point scoring on four of
five shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a well disciplined, well-oiled team,'' said Bruins
coach Pat Burns. ``They're the best team in the league right now.
With the elements we had on our club tonight, it was tough. The
kids tried but they panic after a while and the puck keeps whizzing
by and whizzing by.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars ran their unbeaten streak to 13 _ 10-0-3 _ to set a
franchise record. They have not lost since Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who had ended a three-game skid and salvaged a
couple of points on this four-game trip with a victory Wednesday
night in Nashville, try to regroup Saturday against the Mighty
Ducks of Anaheim at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   The second Verbeek goal was set up by old friend Dave Reid.
Grant Marshall soon made it 5-1. To add insult to loss, defense-man
Craig Ludwig then scored his first goal of the year _ in fact, his
first goal since Dec. 20, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a team of spurts,'' Tallas said. ``They don't just put
the puck at the net. Every time they put it on the net it's a
scoring chance. I didn't come up with the big save tonight. I think
I came up with the average save and when the team needed a big save
I wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Down, 2-1, early in the second period, the Bruins stayed in the
game with a huge penalty-killing effort against the league's best
power play and then made a couple of good bids to tie it.
</P>
<P>
   Don Sweeney was called for holding behind the net _ a call he
didn't appreciate _ and while the Bruins worked on killing that
one, Darren Van Impe was called for tripping in front of the net.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Dallas a five-on-three for 41 seconds. The Bruins,
with tight defense limiting the Stars to mostly long shots and
Tallas being stingy with the rebounds, denied Dallas through that
spell and the rest of the Van Impe penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bruins couldn't catch a break at the other end.
Anson Carter and then P.J. Axelsson took turns hitting the post
behind Ed Belfour. Soon after his near-miss, Axelsson went flying
in front of the net and Burns wanted _ but couldn't get _ a
tripping call.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with 2:29 left in the period, Brett Hull fed Zubov coming
down the middle for a blast that beat Tallas to make it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins used a power play that carried over from the first
period to make it 1-1 at 1:11 of the second. Bourque got the goal,
his fourth of the year and first since Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two minutes later, the Stars were back in front when
Mike Keane backed away from the sideboards and beat Tallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins more than held their own in the first period, but
still came out of it trailing, 1-0. It's not a good idea to put the
Stars on the power play, and they quickly showed why.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov slid across from right point to left, took a pass from
Darryl Sydor, and ripped a shot that Verbeek tipped past Tallas.
The game was barely five minutes old and the Stars had the
all-important first goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty decent first period and then we let it get
away from us,'' Heinze said. ``Any mistake you make, they're going
to put it on your net, and we made a few. Then we got down and we
didn't respond.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
