<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDAISM-DISPUTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI COURT'S CONVERSION RULING DIVIDES L.A.-AREA JEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By YVETTE CABRERA  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- After a landmark ruling in Israel, the question
of who is a Jew was the talk of the day at Bea's Bakery, where no
true consensus emerged but opinions were as varied as the pastries
in the glass displays.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, handed down Wednesday by the chief judge of
Jerusalem, ordered the Israeli government to recognize Jewish
conversions performed by non-Orthodox rabbis and drew instant
criticism and praise over the much-debated issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the ruling is fantastic. I think it's wonderful, but
it's sad that it has to come from the court instead of the Jewish
ecumenical community,'' said suburban Tarzana resident Sandi Herzon
after shopping at the bakery.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we expect the world to get along with us if we can't
get along with each other?'' said Herzon, whose father was an
Orthodox rabbi. Today she is not affiliated with any of the Jewish
denominations.
</P>
<P>
   The Union of Orthodox Jewish Congregations of America declined
to comment on the issue Thursday, but other Orthodox leaders
throughout the country have criticized the decision.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Orthodox Jewish politicians also denounced the
decision, vowing to appeal the ruling and introduce a bill next
week in the Knesset, Israel's parliament, that would allow only the
Orthodox rabbinate to perform conversions.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview, Orthodox Rabbi Shmeul Miller said the
ruling is inconsequential because the real problem is that church
and state are not separate entities in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem of conversion should be a purely religious
issue,'' said Miller, a rabbi at a Mid-Wilshire synagogue near
downtown. ``The aspect of who decides who is Jewish is not an
aspect that should be ruled on by (the) state.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller also criticized the current focus on the conversion
powers of rabbis, saying the convert's commitment should be the
most important factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put emphasis on the rabbis' qualifications is not the
question,'' he said. ``The question is, who converts, and is the
person ready to accept the commandments fully?''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Orenstein, a conservative Jew who applauded the ruling, said
he was not surprised by the Israeli politicians' decision to
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their lawful right to do so, but I feel good about the
fact that the court did approve the ruling,'' said Orenstein, a
suburban Woodland Hills resident. ``But you have to be realistic
that the Supreme Court can overturn the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Jewish Federation Council of Greater Los Angeles,
response to the ruling was mixed, said John Fishel, executive vice
president of the council, an umbrella organization representing 250
associated bodies covering a wide spectrum of ideologies and
philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very complex situation, but I think for the most part,
most Jewish people here in Los Angeles who are concerned about
Israel . . . want to see this matter resolved so their association
and pride in Israel can continue unhindered,'' Fishel said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Marvin Labinger, executive director of the United
Synagogue of Conservative Judaism in Los Angeles, praised Jerusalem
Judge Vardi Zeiler for having the ``guts and courage to validate''
the non-Orthodox conversions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled to death, but we're also very, very cautious,
because the reaction has already set,'' said Labinger, a member of
the Board of Rabbis of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Many fear that a permanent split between Israeli and American
Jews will occur if Orthodox politicians succeed in legislating a
monopoly over conversions for the Orthodox rabbinate, Labinger
said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
