<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4481 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      01-01 2296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1998 WAS YEAR BEST FORGOTTEN FOR SEATTLE SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am thinking of a moment in sports, one that defines 1998, for
you, for me.
</P>
<P>
   And I don't know if I should apologize, but this moment is not
one of grandeur. It is no historic highlight.
</P>
<P>
   It is not John Elway flashing that toothy grin and shaking that
trophy in San Diego on Jan. 25, when Elway won his first Super Bowl
and where he made sentimentalists of all NFL fans, even
Bronco-haters.
</P>
<P>
   It is not Michael Jordan stealing the ball from Karl Malone and
swishing the winning shot in Game 6 of the 1998 NBA Finals _
sealing Sir Air's greatness with that 45-point exclamation and
perhaps giving us his last tongue-wagging look.
</P>
<P>
   It is not even Mark McGwire, whose biggest muscle was his heart
in a summer of '98 when Big Mac ignited with a homer derby along
with a willing, humble and gracious co-star, Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, memories of '98 begin with Glenallen Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, good ol' Glenallen _ the 7,999th Mariner left fielder since
Ken Griffey Jr. took over in center.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Glenallen was only the 53rd left fielder to play next to
Griffey, but what good is a reflection on the past year in sports
without a smattering of hyperbole?
</P>
<P>
   It does not detract from the fact that Glenallen Hill is the
symbolic person who demonstrated, in the promising baseball days of
March, that the Mariners' hopes in '98 were already dead.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it is sometimes in sports. The little things; the
offbeat, wacky moments; the back room, locker room, press room,
training camp incidents are often just as significant, just as
meaningful as those glorious, historic, cover-of-Sports Illustrated
moments.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, I would have to say that Glenallen, the surfer dude
from Santa Cruz, tried to warn us about a certain air of futility
'98, for the M's and for our other local rooting interests, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics almost lost to the Timberwolves in the first round of
the NBA playoffs, then lost their coach. The Huskies limped through
a disappointing 6-6 season, then lost their coach. The Seahawks ...
yeesh, '98 was a killer, wasn't it?
</P>
<P>
   But the weird start of it all was good ol' Glenallen Hill, who
accomplished the most presageful feat of '98 at Mariner spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   It came the moment Hill attempted to run down a fly ball, but
instead of catching it, twisted, stumbled and fell flat on his
butt.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, I think, finally picked up the ball as it rolled to the
wall. And later, after the disheartening Cactus League game,
skipper Lou Piniella tried to spin it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Glenallen wasn't brought here for his glove.''
</P>
<P>
   And Randy Johnson wasn't brought here for his good looks. But
the point is, bad stuff happens to teams that fail to patch major
potholes.
</P>
<P>
   Wacky M's, huh? Wacky Lou, too. And what a wacky year, at least
all the places this columnist visited in my sporting travels. More
on the Mariners later, as we take a look at the places and faces
that made 1998 a rollercoaster of results and emotion, and made us
eager to see 1999 get rolling.
</P>
<P>
   THE YEAR IN REAR VIEW
</P>
<P>
   University of Washington campus, Jan. 7: Red-alert news
conference is called by Brock Huard. After a great season and a
high-flying win at the Aloha Bowl, the Husky quarterback says he
will not enter the NFL draft. It is a terrific moment: A young man
with millions guaranteed to him deciding he wants to be a college
kid for another year.
</P>
<P>
   Nagano, Japan, Feb. 5: Innovative chefs in this industrial city
happily supply foreign journalists with braised bees and blowfish.
What a welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Nagano, Feb. 6: Skater Tara Lipinksi makes her entrance during
the Olympic Opening Ceremonies, hacking around with a quarter-ton
sumo wrestler named Akebono. She is enjoying her Olympic
experience, e-mailing friends, wandering around the Olympic
Village. She has the look of a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Nagano, Feb. 9: The mysterious Michelle Kwan makes her grand
entrance, late, to the Winter Games, causing a stir the way Greto
Garbo would. Kwan is rarely seen, except during practice sessions,
and the pressure builds.
</P>
<P>
   Hakuba, a mountain town outside of Nagano, Feb. 10: It is
finally sunny in the Japanese Alps. An American original named
Picabo Street boldly careens down the Super-G course and sets a
blistering pace. Her time holds. Picabo takes the gold.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Canadian snowboarder Ross Rebagliati is stripped of
his gold medal, temporarily, for testing positive for marijuana.
The Canadian says it was second-hand smoke from a party back home
in Whistler, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Nagano, Feb. 20: Lipinksi is exuberant, thrilling. The
15-year-old American wins the gold medal in figure skating, while
the silver medal is won by reigning U.S. National champion Kwan,
whose decision to remain in seclusion during the Olympics takes the
emotion from her performance.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks training facility, March 4: Just what the Seahawks
ordered. A dynamic runner, and motor-mouth talker, makes his
pumped-up debut. Ricky Watters says he is excited about playing for
the Hawks. You can't help but believe him.
</P>
<P>
   Hec Edmundson Pavilion, March 8: Lots of hooting and hollering
as CBS televises live the NCAA Tournament draw. The Washington
Huskies get a No. 11 seed in the East. Bob Bender's crew gets a
ticket to the big show ... and nearly cashes it in.
</P>
<P>
   Kingdome, March 31: Johnson gets the start in the Mariner opener
and leaves with a 9-6 lead against Cleveland. But, alas, the
bullpen woes begin on cue. M's lose 10-9 in a shocker that silences
the Kingdome crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Portland, Ore., April 19: Sonics beat Trail Blazers in season
finale, clinching Pacific Division crown with 61-21 record. The
post-game locker room finds Vin Baker and the gang thrilled to
finally get to the postseason. But will George Karl's future depend
on how these Sonics fare in the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   Kingdome, April 28: M's fire Nardi Contreras and bring in
pitching coach Stan Williams, hoping to shake up a bullpen that
could star in ``Backdraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jay Buhner's injured knee will require surgery.
Something says the heart and soul of the Mariners will be sorely
missed through the heat of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics practice facility, May 26: Much to the chagrin of the
Seattle sporting press, Karl, the Sonics' ``Incredible Leaking
Man,'' is fired by team president Wally Walker. Karl never did fit
in with the buttoned-down Walker and that was his charm.
</P>
<P>
   Camden Yards, Baltimore, June 1-2: The Mariners are just about
imploding. Johnson has all but wrecked team chemistry. David Segui
can barely wait to throttle the Unit. Joey Cora looks like he might
cry, but what else is new? And Sweet Lou is ready to kill.
</P>
<P>
   After a Johnson trade to the Dodgers is killed by Mariner
owners, and after the M's blew another game to the Orioles,
Piniella is found in the visiting manager's office. Cigarette smoke
is billowing from Piniella's lungs, nose and ears.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter dares ask Piniella if he was eager to trade
Johnson, Piniella's response makes the softshell crabs in the
Chesapeake Bay scurry for cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious things aren't working around here!'' Piniella
screams loud enough for all of Baltimore to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Paris, June 14: The U.S. World Cup soccer team is soon to flame
out, but that doesn't stop two American tourists from trying to
score tickets for the upcoming United States match against Germany.
Inflation is wicked, though. Scalpers want as much as $1,200 for a
pair of World Cup tickets. Instead, World Cup matches are watched
in Parisian cafes.
</P>
<P>
   Coors Field, Denver, July 6: The word is Hill has been cut by
the Mariners. ``We had to start shoring things up,'' the M's say, a
little late.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire are loving their home
run-king status, Griffey is causing a stir, refusing to participate
in the All-Star Game Home Run Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Junior does the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to be booed. This is not a time to be booed,''
Griffey says, then goes out and wins the darned thing.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, July 20: Warren Moon is a no-show at Seahawks training
camp. The veteran quarterback wants a new deal but the Hawks are
capped out and can't pay what Moon wants. Moon risks smudging his
image for this holdout that backfires.
</P>
<P>
   Kingdome, July 31: Baseball's trading deadline fast approaches.
As the clock ticks closer to 9 p.m., everyone wonders if New York
Yankee starter Hideki Irabu is going to walk across the field into
the Mariner clubhouse, while Johnson goes to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   That deal doesn't go down. Instead, there is shock, and
disappointment. Johnson is traded to the Astros for three minor
leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Three Rivers Stadium, Pittsburgh, Aug. 2: Johnson makes his
debut with the Astros. A cross-country flight lands me in
Pittsburgh just as Johnson is trying on his new uniform. Johnson
jokes that it has not been since Little League that his uniform was
so short.
</P>
<P>
   His good humor carries onto the field. Johnson beats the Pirates
in his return to the National League and his relief is obvious _ on
many fronts. Gushing like Snoqualmie Falls, Johnson raves about
Seattle. His attitude is a complete reversal of the sulking man who
found no motivation to pitch his best during his final games in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone felt sorry for Johnson during his tormented days final
days in Seattle, that sorrow started to fade.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans Stadium, Philadelphia, Sept. 5: Seahawks rout Eagles,
but the sporting public's attention is all on Sosa and McGwire.
Baseball's most momentous season is just heating up, drowning out
the start of the NFL season.
</P>
<P>
   Flushing, N.Y., Sept. 13: Patrick Rafter is a cat-quick
Australian who shows his serve-and-volley mastery in a second
straight U.S. Open tennis championship. But again, baseball is all
the world wants to hear about. On this day, Sosa ties McGwire with
62 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Kingdome, Sept. 22: Thankfully for Mariner fans, Griffey and
Alex Rodriguez still call the Pacific Northwest their baseball
home. As the M's swoon, the two superstars maintain and play out
the season with pride _ the only two M's to play all 161 games.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, Griffey tags Oakland for two homers (Nos. 54 and
55 on the way to season total of 56) and Rodriguez hits No. 41, on
his way to 42 to become only the third player in history to hit 40
homers and steal 40 bases in a single season. Fireworks go off. For
one moment, it seems good to celebrate these two great players.
</P>
<P>
   Springfield, Mass., Oct. 2: The NBA lockout drags on. Players
and owners squabble over $2 billion in revenues. A major stumbling
block in the negotiations is the ``Larry Bird exemption,'' which
allows teams to pay their own free agents whatever it takes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, former Celtic great Larry Bird is inducted into the
Hall of Fame. It's just in time to remind the world that few NBA
stars are worthy of Bird's (or Jordan's or Magic Johnson's)
exceptional status.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Stadium, Oct. 16: The great hitter Tony Gwynn leads his
Padres into the Bronx for a World Series date against the Yankees.
Gwynn shows his class by sharing his impressions of the hallowed
House That Ruth Built and giggles over the looney history in San
Diego. Gallantly, Gwynn tries to pretend the Padres have a chance
against this unbelievable '98 Yankee team.
</P>
<P>
   Hec Edmundson Pavilion, Nov. 17: For the first time since 1984,
the Husky men's basketball team is nationally ranked. Bender's crew
gets the nod at No. 14, up there with Kansas and North Carolina and
Duke ... for awhile anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer Arena, Dec. 22: Shock, sadness, a serious sense of loss _
the pioneer American Basketball League folds. The Seattle Reign is
out of business, despite a loyal fan base in this women's
basketball hotbed. The only hope is that the WNBA expands here, if
that is any consolation to the many women and men who worked so
hard to establish a grass-roots professional women's basketball
league.
</P>
<P>
   Living rooms in Seattle, Dec. 25: The Huskies are embarrassed by
Air Force in the Oahu Bowl. If this is holiday entertainment, no
one around finds much pleasure in the Huskies' scary performance.
</P>
<P>
   Mile High Stadium, Denver, Dec. 27: The Broncos look Super
Bowl-bound again. John Elway slings and Terrell Davis romps and the
Seahawks are trounced. The handwriting is on the wall for coach
Dennis Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks Training Facility, Dec. 28: Seahawk President Bob
Whitsitt holds a news conference to announce the firing of Dennis
Erickson. In a class move, Erickson talks to the media, says he
respects the team's right to make a change and promises he can
leave with his head held high.
</P>
<P>
   Don James Center, Dec. 30: After a month of rotten news, after a
year of rotten sporting events, the final shoe drops. Jim Lambright
is fired, ending a 35-year relationship with Husky football. The
pyrotechnics don't end there. Lambright accuses athletic director
Barbara Hedges of bowing down to angry boosters. Hedges says no
way.
</P>
<P>
   EPITAPH FOR 1998
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Joe DiMaggio: On Dec. 7, doctors in a Florida
hospital reported the Yankee Clipper to be in a deep coma, near
death. For three months, the effects of lung cancer had taken their
toll on the octogenarian who once roamed center field at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a miracle. Or the sheer will of a tenacious fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment was altered, DiMaggio pulled out of his coma and he
then squeezed the hand of his doctor. The next day, the intensely
private DiMaggio commanded his doctor to stop giving the media
updates about his condition.
</P>
<P>
   Joe D. was back to live some more. Amen.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 0126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
