<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4482 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI &LR;      01-01 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO'S PINKEL ON UW'S SHORT LIST FOR COACHING VACANCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Chipping away at her to-do list a day after she
announced the firing of football coach Jim Lambright, University of
Washington athletic director Barbara Hedges took care of an obvious
one.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Hedges called University of Toledo athletic
director Pete Liske, himself a former UW administrator, and asked
for permission to talk to Gary Pinkel about the vacant Husky job.
</P>
<P>
   Hedges spent much of the day interviewing UW assistant coaches,
whose contracts expire June 30. With the holiday weekend, she is
believed to be making some preliminary calls before pursuing the
search in earnest Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkel, 46, has led the Rockets to a 57-31-3 record the past
eight years. Before that, he was a player for former Husky coach
Don James at Kent State, and coached on James' UW staffs for 12
years, the final seven as offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Confirming Hedges' call, Liske left little doubt that Pinkel
would come to Washington quickly if offered the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think that would be one of his dream jobs,'' said
Liske, who said Hedges did not indicate when she would talk to
Pinkel or how quickly she hoped to have a coach named.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkel has not been returning telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Atlanta Falcons assistant Rich Brooks, the former
Oregon head coach, indicated interest in the job but said he has
not talked with any UW officials.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, the Falcons' defensive coordinator in a stunning 14-2
season, has acted as interim head coach through much of December in
place of Dan Reeves, who underwent open-heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, 57, coached at Oregon for 18 years, culminating in a
1994 Rose Bowl season. He headed the St. Louis Rams for two years
before being fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made it clear I'd be interested in a college job if it
were the right situation,'' Brooks said. ``I wouldn't want to go
back and take over a program like Oregon was when I took it over
(1977).''
</P>
<P>
   Washington would likely meet those terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably need to move relatively fast,'' Brooks said,
``so I guess (his involvement) is just a rumor.''
</P>
<P>
   One coach mentioned frequently who doesn't appear to be in the
picture is Virginia Tech's Frank Beamer, 52. Beamer's coaching
roots are in the South, and after he talked with both Clemson and
South Carolina earlier about openings, Virginia Tech, his alma
mater, re-worked his annuity, stipulating that he cannot interview
for another job while at Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Another coach drawing mention, Mike Riley of Oregon State, might
also find it hard to leave his job. With strong Corvallis ties,
Riley might find it difficult to turn his back on those who gave
him his first college head coaching position, and his contract
calls for a $300,000 housing allowance that must be reimbursed if
he leaves before another three years at OSU.
</P>
<P>
   Hedges has said she will have an advisory group interview
candidates she might choose as finalists. James is helping her
compile a working list.
</P>
<P>
   Without setting a timetable, Hedges says she wants to name a
coach as soon as possible to facilitate a quick transition for
interested recruits.
</P>
<P>
   The most high-profile player already committed to Washington,
USA Today second-team All-America kicker John Anderson of Boca
Raton, Fla., said the future of Husky special-teams coach Rick
Mallory would be pivotal in his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he stays on the staff, I'm definitely going there,'' said
Anderson. ``If he doesn't stay, I'm going to consider my other
options.''
</P>
<P>
   Another committed recruit, Cody Pickett, illustrated what the UW
program is up against as it tries to stanch damage before the
February date on which binding national letters of intent are
signed. Pickett, a quarterback from Caldwell, Idaho, said Arizona
State, one of his finalists, had already called him after the news
of Lambright's firing, seeking a campus visit.
</P>
<P>
   But Pickett _ whose finalists were Washington, Oregon, ASU and
Purdue _ said he would take no other visits until a UW staff is in
place, and then make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, everything's the same,'' Pickett said. ``I'm just
going to sit back and see what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
