<SLUG> BC-1999-RESOLUTIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YEAR BRINGS NEW BATCH OF RESOLUTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHARLINE CHIANG, ENRIQUE RIVERO, RICK ORLOV and KEITH MARDER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Promises, promises.
</P>
<P>
   If you're like most of us, you'll wake up today and start the
new year by ticking off a list of resolutions -- all holding great
hope for 1999, all made with the sincerest desire to change for the
better.
</P>
<P>
   Take 19-year-old Marcus Medina of suburban Mission Hills, who
with his fiancee, Perla Ramirez, 18, of nearby Pacoima, is
expecting a baby this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be a dad, so I want to better myself spiritually
because of my baby,'' said Medina, a process specialist. ``I'm
going to go to church more.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Fields, 47, president and chief executive officer of Fields
Aircraft Spares Inc. in suburban Simi Valley, said he has a simple
goal for self-improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``To lose some weight -- that really is my New Year's
resolution, to exercise more and lose some weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was the same as last year, he conceded. ``But I
didn't keep it last year,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Right. Who actually keeps resolutions?
</P>
<P>
   Not Aurora Liberato of suburban Granada Hills, who over her 80
years has learned the futility of resolving to undertake great
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never do,'' she said, ``because I don't even go through with
it. So why bother?''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Haglund, the actor who plays Langley, one of the Lone
Gunmen on the Fox TV series ``The X-Files,'' apparently knows the
pitfalls of grandiose resolutions, so his this year is ``to get
over this cold. I like to keep my goals really low so that I can
achieve them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The experts say it is natural to go back on resolutions, but
that shouldn't discourage you from at least trying to improve
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely think it's a healthy thing to do,'' said Drew
Yellen, a clinical and sports psychologist in suburban Northridge
who counsels patients on self-motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nothing else, it brings these things having to do with
improving ourselves to a conscious level,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the start of the last year of the decade and
millennium is provoking people to think harder than usual about how
they want to live out the remaining days of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it does is it forces you to put yourself in the context
of all of humanity,'' Yellen said. ``If you step back and think
1,000 years have gone by, there is a degree of humility.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most popular resolutions year in and year out are to
lose weight, quit smoking and spend less money. Some folks are much
more practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to get a job, for one. I've been unemployed for two
years. And try to get married,'' said John McKeon, 55, of suburban
Northridge, a hospital food server.
</P>
<P>
   For Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan, the new year is a new
chance to make the city better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reform, reform, reform,'' Riordan said. ``The last year of the
1900s will be a year of reform for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will spend much of 1999 focused on three issues that will
determine our city's future success -- charter, education and tax
reform. Angelenos must continue to be involved if we are to build
on the greatness we've achieved together.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Board of Education member David Tokofsky said he
will work ``to never allow the board president to have a meeting
past midnight again'' and ``to help curriculum bureaucracy identify
what a book is.''
</P>
<P>
   William Mellick, president and chief executive officer of 20th
Century Insurance, said his professional goal is to sell more
insurance, which may or may not be at odds with his personal goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine is to remember to keep a balance between my work and my
family,'' he said. ``That's not meant to be corny; it's something I
want to put out there as a personal commitment and a personal
resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, as this millennium winds down, many Americans will
continue to grapple with the conflicting demands of job and family.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams, 58, a retired firefighter living in suburban
Canoga Park, would like to go to Ireland with his family, but that
requires financial freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win a lot of money so I can relax, take more
vacations,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Yellen calls this the ``human touch'' phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we're turning the clock back to the '50s, to a time
of `Father Knows Best,' '' Yellen said. ``I call it a human touch;
that includes being kinder, being gentler, doing more things with
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone plans to take it easy, though.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Linda Duarte of suburban Sun Valley plans to heed words
of advice from The Artist Formerly Known as Prince.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to party more, have fun, meet new people,'' said
Duarte, 18, a student at El Camino High School in Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   And there always will be plenty of people like food server Zeke
Ragsdale, 19, of suburban Granada Hills, who is just saying no to
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so pessimistic about everything,'' he said. ``I made a
resolution not to make resolutions.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
