<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Brussels, Belgium) _ They had to struggle a bit to open
some recalcitrant bottles of champagne, but finance ministers from
11 countries celebrated New Year's Eve on Thursday by launching the
euro as Europe's new single currency. The countries permanently
locked the exchange rates for their currencies to the new euro,
setting the value at which euros will begin trading on Monday _
about 85 cents to the euro. By Edmund L. Andrews. (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   EURO-FATHERS (Hamburg, Germany) _ Three fathers of the euro _
Helmut Schmidt, Giscard d'Estaing and Edward Heath _ look back on
its conception. By Craig R. Whitney. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-DEFECTORS (Sihanoukville, Cambodia) _ Liberated at last
from a life of revolution, two Khmer Rouge leaders came to the
beach Thursday with their families, their leisure wear and their
sunglasses. But their holiday was a drab one, spent mostly behind
the dirty brown curtains of their tiny hotel rooms, trapped inside
by their fear of a small group of reporters. By Seth Mydans. (With
map)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-EMBASSY (Jerusalem) _ The U.S. ambassador to Israel
ordered the U.S. embassy in Tel Aviv closed Thursday after what
embassy officials called a ``direct and credible'' threat of a
terrorist attack against the building. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   TIBET-YAKHERDERS (Lhasa, Tibet) _ Tibet may be known around the
world as a mountainous region where a devoutly religious people
have been persecuted by their Chinese landlords, but everyone has
to eat. In Tibet, shopping for food inevitably includes a trip to
the yak meat market. By Seth Faison. (With photo and map)
</P>
<P>
   HONDURAS-DEATHTOLL (San Pedro Sula, Honduras) _ Two months after
a hurricane mauled this country, it is still unclear how many
Hondurans died in the storm, but the government has been forced to
retreat from its earlier conclusion that at least 7,000 people
perished. By James C. McKinley Jr. (With map)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GRAHAM-SUCCESSOR _ At the turn of the new century, with Billy
Graham now 80, the question arises who, if anyone, can take his
place. A look at the potential successors. By Laurie Goodstein and
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-BALLROOM (State College, Pa.) _ The e-mail messages
arrived first in a trickle, then in a flood. Students at the
Pennsylvania State University were contacting their president,
Graham Spanier, with a desperate plea. Nearly 1,500 undergraduates
were languishing on waiting lists to learn how to cha-cha and fox
trot. By Ethan Bronner. (With photos)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RENAISSANCE (Hilton Head, S.C.) _ President Clinton at
the Renaissance weekend. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   FUGITIVE-PUERTO-RICO (San Juan, Puerto Rico) _ Filberto
Ojeda-Rios is a federal fugitive in a highly publicized case: the
armed robbery of $7 million from the Wells Fargo depot in Hartford,
Conn., by militant Puerto Rican nationalists in September 1983. But
having eluded federal agents for eight years on an island only 100
miles by 35 miles in area, he has developed the appeal of a David
fighting a Goliath. By Mireya Navarro. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHICAGO-MURDERS (Undated) _ For the first time in many years,
New York was not the city that recorded the most killings in the
country last year, officials said Thursday. Chicago had more
homicides. By Michael Cooper. (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ In the first signs of discord among
Senate Republicans over impeachment, senators across the political
spectrum, from conservatives to key pragmatists, said they opposed
a proposal that would permit a preliminary vote on articles of
impeachment without a full trial. By Lizette Alvarez and Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-BANK (Tokyo) _ Taking a step toward revamping its ailing
banking system, South Korea sold 51 percent of Korea First Bank to
a group of investors led by Texas Pacific's Newbridge Capital. In
becoming the first foreign investor to take control of a South
Korean bank, the group beat out a bid by HSBC Holdings. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-BOOKS (London) _ In the last year, Borders has opened
stores in Australia, England, Singapore and Scotland. And in the
coming year, it plans to accelerate its expansion in
English-speaking countries throughout the world. Thus, while Barnes
&AMP; Noble and Amazon.com are battling over the so-far unprofitable
spoils of the Internet, Borders is investing in terra firma. It
approach has cheered some investors but also has raised doubts
among some analysts who wonder whether the chain has moved too
slowly to invest in electronic commerce. By Doreen Carvajal. (With
photo)
</P>
<P>
   BELL-AIRTOUCH (New York) _ Bell Atlantic Corp., already in the
midst of a huge merger with GTE Corp., reportedly is nearing a $45
billion takeover of AirTouch Communications Inc., the nation's
second-largest cellular phone company. By Laura M. Holson and David
Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS-QUARTER (New York) _ It was a time when words like
``Technology'' and ``Internet'' were synonymous with almost instant
paper wealth. It was a time when the stock market staged as abrupt
and stunning a turnaround as any in recent memory. It was the final
three months of 1998, a three-month period that left many
professionals rubbing their eyes in disbelief. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin. (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVIATA-OPERA-REVIEW (New York) _ Since Franco Zeffirelli's
elephantine new staging of ``La Traviata'' opened at the
Metropolitan Opera at the end of November, new singers have taken
over all the principal roles. Normally, the assumption is that the
original singers have moved on to other projects, but in this case
it seems likely that some of them were simply lost in the scenery
and may not be heard from again. A singer who wanted to hide out
for a while, in fact, could hardly do better than to get a role in
this staging. By Allan Kozinn. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   PERMANENT-COLLECTIONS (New York) _ Even at this time of year,
the city is rife with relatively quiet, empty places to contemplate
outstanding works of art and related visual phenomena, places
slightly or way off the beaten path _ be they the less popular
galleries of the Metropolitan Museum of Art or the Brooklyn Museum
of Art, the city's only indoor Earthwork (Walter De Maria's ``New
York Earth Room'' in SoHo) or the great scale model of New York
City at the Queens Museum of Art. By Roberta Smith. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Hempstead, N.Y.) _ Sports of The Times column
on the Jets, the perfect New Year's team: a squad of redemption and
rebirth. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MATCHUPS (Undated) _ Week 1 of the NFL playoff matchups,
with Thomas George predicting a couple of upsets among the four
wild-card games being played this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-BOWLS (Tempe, Ariz.) _ A set-up of the New Year's Day bowls,
which have less significance this year because the Fiesta Bowl,
which will determine the no-longer-mythical national champion of
college football, is being played on Jan. 4. By Joe Drape.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA-LABOR (New York) _ The league cancellation date of Jan.
7 approaches, but both sides say there are no plans to meet over
the New Year's holiday. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
