<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4563 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITRUS-ARIZONA-AZR &LR;      01-01 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITRUS-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA GROWERS PROFIT FROM FREEZE IN CALIF. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANE LARSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Citrus prices have been riding a roller coaster since
Christmas, thanks to a freeze that hit central California's lemon
and orange crops, and Arizona growers and packers say the wild ride
is not over yet.
</P>
<P>
   But if California's freeze turns out to be as severe as one
eight years ago, they say, Arizona's citrus industry will reap the
benefits of higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus prices jumped Christmas week as news of the freeze spread
and produce buyers panicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just totally crazy last week. People were calling who
we'd never talked to before,'' said Ed Foster, sales representative
for Empire Fruit Co. in Queen Creek. The company grows tangerines,
oranges and tangelos on 1,800 acres in Maricopa and Pinal counties
and ships them nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is emotion, people saying the whole crop is
ruined. Now the feeling is that the damage is not as bad as
initially thought,'' said James Mast, manager of the Mesa Citrus
Growers Association, which harvests and packs more than 5,000 acres
of citrus for the Sunkist label.
</P>
<P>
   This week's holiday slowdown also helped moderate the market,
industry watchers said.
</P>
<P>
   The freeze has increased demand for Arizona products, said Bill
Spencer, president of Associated Citrus Packers Inc. in Yuma, the
state's largest independent citrus grower and packer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect prices to stay at higher levels than we're used
to in the winter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices are up, and they're going to come up more. It will take
a while for the market to adjust,'' said Dave Crist, owner of Crist
Citrus Care, which manages 500 acres of citrus groves in the Yuma
area.
</P>
<P>
   The flurry in the market started when a pre-Christmas freeze hit
California's San Joaquin Valley, ruining an estimated $591 million
in citrus crops. Two days before Christmas, the California
Department of Food and Agriculture estimated that Fresno County had
lost all of its lemon and half of its navel orange crop, and that
Kern County had lost all of its grapefruit and lemon crop and 70
percent of its navel oranges. Tulare County lost 85 percent of its
citrus, the department estimated.
</P>
<P>
   California Gov. Pete Wilson declared the area an economic
disaster Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona growers warn, though, that fruit damage can take 10 to
14 days to show up. When new damage estimates come out, they may
show that the damage is not as bad as first thought.
</P>
<P>
   Because the two states grow so many of the same crops, Arizona
growers keep a close eye on what happens in California. For the
most part, Yuma and Maricopa counties, Arizona's main
citrus-growing areas, escaped the freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Some Arizona growers are comparing the situation to California's
Christmas 1990 freeze, which also decimated that state's citrus
crop and sent prices for Arizona's smaller supply soaring. So badly
were California trees and supplies hit that the price blip lasted
into the next year, growers say.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit by this year's freeze were lemons and oranges, and
growers say prices of those fruits are most likely to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Lemons, which are the citrus most susceptible to freezes, are
about halfway through harvest in Arizona. Both Crist and Spencer
predict prices will go up for the remaining part of the crop.
</P>
<P>
   A 38-pound carton of Arizona lemons that averaged $12.05 last
year was going for $7 to $32 a carton Thursday, depending on size
and quality, according to market reports.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for navel oranges, being harvested now, also have risen.
And if the 1990 freeze pattern repeats itself, ``I would be
expecting to sell our Valencias for a lot of money,'' when they are
harvested in February, Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   A carton of oranges, which averaged $6.55 last year, Thursday
was going for $9 to $30.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer and Crist also see prices of tangerines and tangelos
going up. Grapefruit prices are expected to remain stable, because
much of the California crop is grown outside the freeze area and
because Florida is a big grapefruit producer, too.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is the nation's No. 2 producer of lemons, behind
California; the No. 3 producer of oranges and tangerines, behind
Florida and California; and No. 4 behind those states and Texas for
grapefruit production.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona's citrus production is small compared with
California's.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not way we can fill the gap,'' Empire Fruit's Foster
said.
</P>
<P>
   Growers say it's too early to tell whether the California freeze
will have a big or a small effect on Arizona growers' bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer said growers have been battling an oversupply of citrus
on world and national markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when you get into a freeze like this and you've been
pounded season after season, and now you have short-term demand
exceeding supply, it's fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers who can usually name their terms have been having to take
Spencer's offer in recent days. He agreed to ship citrus to a
Boston buyer, for example, if the buyer would also take some
less-popular sizes of fruit off his hands.
</P>
<P>
   If the California damage is bad enough, ``It makes the picture
for the next couple years brighter'' for Arizona growers, Crist
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of damage is not going to come back right away,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   And higher citrus prices would help Arizona agriculture, which
has been struggling with down markets in cotton and wheat, said
Sheldon Jones, director of the Arizona Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   It also could open some international doors. If California can't
meet its export obligations, Arizona growers may be able to get in,
get recognized and receive the higher prices foreign markets pay,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the past week's gyrations are no different than those
of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who know what the reason is'' for rises and falls, Mesa
Citrus' Mast said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the problem of too much of a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices can get so high that it kills demand,'' Foster said.
``Last week it got to that point, and now the market is
adjusting.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jane Larson can be reached at jane.larson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
