<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4565 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROGERS&AMP;HART-AZR &LR;      01-01 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROGERS&AMP;HART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGING PRAISES OF RODGERS &AMP; HART  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, JAN. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KYLE LAWSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Opposites attract.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it explains Richard Rodgers and Lorenz Hart.
</P>
<P>
   There was Dick. Tall, attractive, with conservative tastes, a
ready confidence and work habits so disciplined that they verged on
the obsessive.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Larry. Barely 5 feet tall, with a face and form
that called to mind one of the guys from ``Snow White,'' an
unreliable alcoholic as self-destructive in his work relationships
as he was in his social life, an insecure genius filled with a
self-loathing he managed to conceal beneath a smart-aleck wit.
</P>
<P>
   Mutt and Jeff, surely, but talent drew them together. Hart was
the greatest lyricist of his day. Rodgers was the only popular
composer of the era to seriously rival George Gershwin as a
musician. Their legacy of song, spanning the years from 1919 to
1943, is one of the great American treasures.
</P>
<P>
   You get all that in the opening segments of ``Rodgers &AMP; Hart
Story: Thou Swell, Thou Witty,'' the latest installment of PBS'
Great Performances, which airs Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And you get plenty more before the show ends. Rodgers and Hart
were yin and yang with a touch of soap opera. Rodgers married
happily, worked productively and when he could take Hart's behavior
no longer, threw up his hands, found a new lyricist in Oscar
Hammerstein II and went on to ``Oklahoma!'' and a second creative
career even more successful than the first.
</P>
<P>
   Hart, a bachelor plagued by ambivalent relationships with women,
drank himself to death.
</P>
<P>
   The man went down rhyming. Late in the television show,
Broadway's Christine Ebersole sings ``To Keep My Love Alive,'' one
of the last songs Rodgers and Hart composed together. It was for
the 1943 revival of ``AConnecticut Yankee,'' and is the
laugh-out-loud saga of a woman who murders her many husbands ``to
keep my love alive.''
</P>
<P>
   It seldom gets better in the world of musical comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David Thompson, who earlier profiled Busby Berkeley
and Arthur Freed for Great Performances, ``The Rodgers &AMP; Hart
Story'' is a melange of home movies, film clips, still photos and
musical recreations of some of the duo's most famous songs.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, it's on the dull side, with long stretches where the
camera does hardly more than stare at the performers. John
Carrafa's musical staging is a particular disappointment: static to
the point of boring. Only once, during ``You Can't Kick It Around''
from 1940's ``Pal Joey,'' do things get anything like lively.
</P>
<P>
   But the music, performed in period style by Ebersole, Rebecca
Luker, Stanley Mathis, Susan Egan, Brian d'Arcy James, Mary Cleere
Haran, Ron Haines, Debbie Gravitte and Jane Krakowski _ a who's who
of rising stars in musical theater and cabaret _ more than makes up
for the program's cinematic shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   How many times do you get to spend an evening with talented
singers making the most of ``My Funny Valentine''; ``Where or
When''; ``Manhattan''; ``Bewitched, Bothered and Bewildered'';
``Mountain Greenery''; ``The Lady Is A Tramp''; ``Falling In Love
With Love ''; and maybe a dozen more?
</P>
<P>
   Among the loveliest moments are those devoted to Rodgers and
Hart tunes that are not as well known but are as contemporary in
mood and meaning as anything sung by Sheryl Crow or Alanis
Morrisette. ``This Funny World,'' written for 1926's ``Betsy,'' is
a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   And has there ever been a more bittersweet lyric than the one
Hart penned for 1938's ``Spring Is Here,'' perfectly matched by
Rodgers' haunting melody:
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) Spring is here. Why doesn't my heart go dancing? /
Spring is here. Why isn't the waltz entrancing? / No desire, no
ambition leads me / Maybe it's because nobody needs me . . . /
Spring is here, I hear. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The behind-the-scenes look at the partnership is equally
fascinating. There are telling comments from Mary Rodgers,
Richard's daughter; Dorothy Hart, Larry's sister-in-law; and Larry
Adler, one of Hart's closest pals. The quotes are unusually honest
for this sort of thing, and lend the proceedings an agreeable bite.
</P>
<P>
   There's also an amusing series of clips from ``Masters of
Melody,'' a 1929 film that featured Rodgers and Hart playing
themselves (with Hart coming across as a morose Marx brother), and
ho me movies that offer glimpses into the Broadway world of the
era.
</P>
<P>
   If for no other reason, the show is worth watching for these.
Other than still photographs, they are our only clues as to what
the actual performances were like of such classic musicals as``
Babes in Arms, Pal Joey'' and ``Jumbo.''
</P>
<P>
   If you think the Broadway tuner has fallen victim to scenic
overkill, you'll be amazed by the clips from 1935's ``Jumbo,''
produced by Billy Rose. Gaudy? It makes ``The Phantom of the
Opera'' look like a community theater production in Paducah. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
