<HEADLINE>
THE INS AND OUTS OF 1998 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999   The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Happy New Year. There are now 364 days to go before the Y2K
computer bug strikes, setting civilization's clock back to the year
1900. The bad news? Global commerce and communication will come to
a screeching halt. The good news? Only 18 more years until the Red
Sox win the World Series!
</P>
<P>
   Was 1998 _ star of the bestseller ``A Year in Full'' _ any less
mind-bending than the looming millennial meltdown? To paraphrase
William Jefferson Clinton, that depends what you mean by ``was.''
We think it ``was'' a year of unrelieved insanity. But then (silly
us) we think oral sex is sex, a cigar is just a cigar, a pretty
girl is like a melody, and Ken Starr is an extraterrestrial.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, based on the DNA stain on 1998's lapel, we are
prepared to state under penalty of perjury that impeachment was in
and censure was out last year, while wagging the dog was in but
wagging your finger at the American public was out.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Monica jokes were in, but dates with Monica were a total
gross-out. Presidential depositions were in, but presidential
kneepads were out. Finally, spiteful interns were out, while
spiritual advisers were in. Which may explain why Clinton _ star of
the bestseller ``A Man in Freefall'' _ is still in office.
</P>
<P>
   What a stupefying 12 months, huh? In came the revamped
Volkswagen Beetle, the redesigned Boston Herald, the Euro currency,
the eBay auction Web site, ESPN magazine, unisex bathrooms, index
funds, Apple's iMac, the Mach3 razor, and a spanking new $20 bill.
Which was fitting, because if 1998 was about anything, it was all
about the benjamins.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Toms, a quick tally: Wolfe in, Jefferson out.
</P>
<P>
   Out too went Welcome Wagons, Beltway blowhards, over-leveraged
hedge funds, fact-fudging columnists, $6 movie tickets, NBA
basketball, theme restaurants, Bill Gates's memory banks, and the
whole whiny ``Seinfeld'' crew, who should have quit while they were
ahead. If 1998 stands trial at the end of the day, let it be for
its overhyped finales and out-of-body-politic experiences.
</P>
<P>
   It was a get-down year for getting jiggy, that much is
indisputable. Flutie Flakes, waitress moms, and electronic books
were all in. Ditto for therapeutic magnets, cosmic magnetars, and
on-line shopping, not to mention buckwheat-hull pillows. Pop a
couple of Viagra, hop on your Money Mill treadmill, and take off
for Hartford _ man, it did not get any in-ner than that. A little
Indian cuisine, some swing dancing afterwards? Babe, you were in
like Jerry Springer in a roomful of brawling in-laws!
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, 1998 might have found you aboard the cruise
ship Ecstasy, putting out flames in the galley. Others who were out
to sea were Universal Pictures executives, designer Isaac Mizrahi,
WAAF DJs Opie and Anthony, talk-show host Magic Johnson, investment
gurus the Beardstown Ladies, miscast thespian Quentin Tarantino,
pseudojournalist Steven Glass, and the head headline writer in
charge at Boston magazine. Mayday! Lower the lifeboats and break
out the oars!
</P>
<P>
   Did it strike anyone else that 1998 seemed to arrive in pairs,
like ark-bound beasts seeking high ground in a storm? Let's see.
There were home-run heroes (Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire) in full
swing. There were literary Wolfe hunters (John Updike and Norman
Mailer) in high dudgeon.
</P>
<P>
   There were epic World War II movies and animated bug movies and
doomsday space-debris movies paired in theaters everywhere. There
were Bush brothers (George and Jeb) and Goldbergs (Lucianne and
that WWF wrestler guy), Olsen twins (Mary-Kate and Ashley), and
House speakers (Newt Gingrich and Bob Livingston) moving in and out
of fashion with dizzying speed. Whew! By year's end, we felt as if
we'd given birth to octuplets.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that would be less painful, we suppose, than going out
with 1998 Mom of the Year Mary Kay Letourneau. Who is not to be
confused with ``There's Something About Mary'' cutie Cameron Diaz,
owner of the in hairstyle of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Other notables we have crossed out of our 1998 datebook include
dad-on-the-lam Stephen Fagan, Dr. Jack ``You've Got 60 Minutes
Left'' Kevorkian, human cloner Dr. Richard Seed, ex-Chelsea Clinton
boyfriend Matt Pierce, ex-family values candidate Michael
Huffington, phony war heroes Joe Yandle and Tim Johnson, and the
entire population of Baltimore, the homicide-and-gonorrhea capital
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   If the travel itch hits, by the way, Indonesia is out and Nevada
is in.
</P>
<P>
   Did you score high on that pesky MCAS exam last year? You're in,
bro! Join the ranks of other 1998 overachievers: senior
space-shuttler John Glenn, box-office dynamo Adam Sandler, Minn.
governor Jesse ``The Mind'' Ventura, uber-chef Emeril Legasse, smut
mogul Larry Flynt, rap artist Sean ``Puffy'' Combs, the UMass
football team, the Backstreet Boys, Barenaked Ladies,
actress-singer Audra McDonald, chanteuses Lauryn Hill and Lucinda
Williams, author-editor David Remnick, golfers Se Ri Pak and Mark
O'Meara, novelist Ian McEwan, playwright Paula Vogel, and Nantucket
underground resident Thomas Johnson, star of the forthcoming
bestseller ``A Man in Landfill.''
</P>
<P>
   Or did your 1998 test score grade out as unsatisfactory? Then
sign up for our remedial pan-cultural tutorial and say hello to
rookie novelist William Weld, former U.S. News editor James
Fallows, fired Monica Lewinsky attorney William Ginsberg, onetime
Channel 7 news anchor John Marler, actress Calista Flockhart's
nutritionist, Gidget the Taco Bell doggie, and Monet's ``1904 Water
Lilies,'' which we're crating up and shipping out as soon as we can
establish proper provenance.
</P>
<P>
   For 1998, alas, there are no second chances. For you, valued
reader, we extend this special one-time-only year-end offer: a
chance to take the Official 1998 John Silber MCAS Makeup Exam.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple choice: You were in last year if you (a) wore cashmere,
(b) wore gray cashmere, (c) got your groove back, (d) converted to
DVD on your HDTV, (e) took your date to an oxygen bar, (f) drove a
Mercedes SUV, (g) started an herb garden, (h) modeled for the
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch catalog, (i) tuned in to ABC's ``Sports
Night,'' (j) finagled a Furby, (k) merged with SFX Entertainment,
(l) read Salon, or (m) all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Part II: You were, like, summa cum out of it if you (a) attended
college with Osama bin Laden, (b) fell into the liquidity trap, (c)
signed a New Yorker contract with Tina Brown, (d) invested in Paul
Simon's ``The Capeman,'' (e) read ``Nappy Hair'' to your
grade-school class, (f) took androstenedine, (g) partied with
Olympic snowboarder Ross Rebegliati, (h) mourned the passing of
ABC's ``Ellen,'' (i) purchased a Sony Handycam (X-ray vision
version), (j) thought Altoids were a marital aid, (k) inked Geraldo
Rivera to a network news contract, (l) wore a Zegna necktie to
impress the grand jury, or (m) all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Answers: (m) and (m), you moron. Now sit up straight and go out
and get a job.
</P>
<P>
   Sox hurler Pedro Martinez, he got game. Sox slugger Mo Vaughn,
he got the mongo bucks so now Mo be outta here. Curtis Martin, he
ran out on us too, to Tunaville no less. Sigh. Nomar in the infield
and Drew in the backfield are about all we got left, no? Elsewhere
in the sports world, out-of-wedlock kids sired by pro athletes were
so numerous that child-support payments were in. Major-league
baseball umps and NFL refs were so out to lunch, meanwhile, it made
us all go to the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of replay, we close our review of 1998 with a dimming
of the lights for some special friends we shall miss.
</P>
<P>
   To Frank Sinatra, Henry Hampton, Phil Hartman, Junior Wells,
Benjamin Spock, Carl Perkins, Jack Lord, Carl Wilson, Henny
Youngman, Fred Friendly, Lloyd Bridges, Wendy O. Williams, Linda
McCartney, Octavio Paz, Carlos Castaneda, Roy Rogers, Gene Autry,
Jerome Robbins, Shari Lewis, Dorothy West, E. G. Marshall, Allen
Drury, Akira Kurosawa, Betty Carter, Roddy McDowall, Sonny Bono,
Eric Ambler, William Gaddis, Ted Hughes, Bob Kane, Alan Pakula,
Flip Wilson, Jim Murray, Maynard Parker, Tammy Wynette, and
colleague Karen Avenoso, we wave goodbye with heavy heart and wring
out our hankie in fond remembrance.
</P>
<P>
   It was _ and we do mean ``was'' _ indeed a year in full.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
