<HEADER>
A4570 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-AWARDS-BOS &LR;      01-01 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-AWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
  
 IT'S ONLY ROCK 'N ROLL: THE 1998 awards  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here comes your 19th nervous breakdo _ whoops, sorry, wrong
Rolling Stones song. Here comes the 19th annual It's Only Rock 'n'
Roll Awards, a swipe through the pop music world of 1998 in which
we salute heroes and vilify villains. As always, our motto _ which
we copped from an old Streetwalkers album _ remains: vicious, but
fair.
</P>
<P>
   Bare Nekkid Spiritualist: Alanis Morissette She's over-wrought
and tangled up in words and in the ``Thank U'' video she bares more
than her soul. Message? Um, grrrl power? We're all naked before
God? Sex sells?
</P>
<P>
   Truth in Packaging: The Spice Girls Last year, they won the ``Go
Away Little Girl Award.'' This year, we've turned a &UR;  &LR; corner, sort
of, and say this: Silly, sexy, and light as a feather, the five _
scrap that, four _ exuberant young ladies from England are proudly
prefab, and their calculated pop confections are convincingly
nutrition free. They're a preteen girl's role model and a lecherous
old man's wet dream. Their Great Woods show _ replete &UR;  &LR; with adverts
on the big video screen _ was a hoot. They work hard for the money.
</P>
<P>
   Best Rock Mag: Mojo A repeat winner, the English glossy is hip
but not condescending or knee-jerk nasty like much of the Brit
press. Mojo says ``nay'' to demographic skewering by covering
veterans and newcomers alike. As a reader put it recently, ``Your
writers seem to enjoy music. Odd approach, but I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy O. Williams Memorial: Nashville Pussy Exhibitionistic,
sleazy, in-your-face raunch from Dixie's Motorhead. Just like KISS,
the spontaneity is an illusion _ the show never changes. But, also
like KISS, it's a darn fun show.
</P>
<P>
   You're Never Too Old to Rock 'n' Roll If You're Too Young To
Die: :Bob Dylan, Van Morrison, Pete Townshend (tie) Three cheers
for the old guard _ Bob and Van at the Fleet and Pete at
Harborlights _ and for intelligent, passionate reinvention of their
work. Put another way: The exact opposite of Eric Clapton turning
``Layla'' into middle of the road mush.
</P>
<P>
   You're Never Too Young to Sing About Being Old: Pulp Jarvis
Cocker's meditations on aging _ on the ``This Is Hardcore'' CD and
at the Paradise _ made for some of the year's most compelling
music.
</P>
<P>
   Rockin' Mom: Liz Phair Not only did Phair re-merge from long
hiatus as a more confident performer, she's writing sharper
melodies. Strong album, shows at Avalon. Edge intact.
</P>
<P>
   Oh-my-God Moment of the Year: Offspring During WBCN's River Rave
at Great Woods, singer Dexter Holland thought it'd be nice if he
encouraged the fans to whip up a paper-and-plastic storm. One
problem: Paper and plastic don't fly that far so it was mostly a
case of fans pelting each other. It was a total breakdown in order,
and, you know, it was cool.
</P>
<P>
   Best Genre Scramble: Firewater and Morcheeba (tie) Freakwater,
at the Middle East, assembled a tossed salad of sea chanteys,
waltzes, and rock, putting sax and violins to the best use since
early Roxy Music. We missed their local gigs, but Moorcheba's ``Big
Calm'' CD put a sexy, soulful, melancholic spin and a country twang
into trip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   Comeback of the Year: Cheap Trick Technically they never went
away and probably never will. They play 200-plus dates a year in
good times and bad. They played three in a row at the Paradise,
featuring their first three albums (one a night) and brought the
house down.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's of Pop: Garth Brooks Millions and millions served.
It's not the tastiest product, but you know what you're gonna get
time after time.
</P>
<P>
   Kraftwerk of the '90s: Air From the pop vacuum that is France
comes the surprising synth-based duo called Air. More aggressive
live at Karma than on disc, the nearly all-instrumental band
concocted many a percolating soundscape.
</P>
<P>
   Come Back Shane: Shane MacGowan A repeat winner. Yet another
year without a US album release and a scrapped Boston gig because
of . . . oh, health problems. On the plus side, the former Pogue
seems to have Keith Richards's constitution and keeps breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Worst Advertisement for a Tour: The Rolling Stones The world's
oldest rock 'n' roll band released yet another turgid live album _
why couldn't they have stopped with ``Get Your Ya-Ya's Out''? _ to
whip up the frenzy for the upcoming ``small-scale'' hockey barn
tour. Banks are taking loan applications for ticket buyers.
</P>
<P>
   New Wave on the March: Gary Numan, Bow Wow Wow, the Damned (tie)
I wouldn't have believed it if I hadn't been there, but all three
of these long-in-the-tooth Brit acts played the Middle East
Downstairs and were the furthest thing from nostalgic. The music
worked on its own, contemporary terms.
</P>
<P>
   Pee-wee Herman Wannabe: George Michael Nabbed in a public men's
room. What a way to be outed . . . but Michael redeemed himself
with his cheeky video and in an interview in Q. ``Two undercover
cops and a randy pop star who'd had a couple of drinks at lunch,''
said Michael. ``I was stupid, I shouldn't have done it, it's
against the law, but what happened that afternoon was totally
unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Punk's Not Dead (Old School Division): The Dictators and X (tie)
The 'tators strutted their cocky, crunching stuff at the Middle
East, reliving teenage wasteland but also claiming a lust for life.
X revisited its early years with original guitarist Billy Zoom back
in the fold, and it was hot and nasty at Avalon.
</P>
<P>
   Over Over Over Over the Top Schlock: Mariah Carey, Celine Dion,
Whitney Houston (tie) More syrup and sugar from our era's three
divas. Lesson: It's not just how well you sing, it's what you sing.
</P>
<P>
   There's Something About a Soundtrack/Ex-local Hero: Jonathan
Richman More people saw the former Modern Lover as the bard-Greek
chorus in ``There's Something About Mary'' than probably ever have
in his musical career. But Jonathan is on the ascent. He played a
series of fine shows at the Middle East and released a winner with
the Ric Ocasek-produced ``I'm Confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Best David Bowie Reinvention of Self: Beastie Boys and Madonna
(tie) The Boys check their misogyny at the door and ditch the
goon-squad raps for something approaching a social conscience _
while still braying up a good storm. More successful on disc than
live _ their Worcester Centrum Centre show had severe clarity
problems. As to the new, spiritual Madonna _ the anti-Courtney _
she came up with one of her best albums.
</P>
<P>
   Best Maintenance of Self: KISS It's always 1975 (or so) in
KISSland. These old stomping hard rock/pop songs are as much dumb
fun as ever and the pyro is unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   Local Heroes: The Mighty Mighty Bosstones Again, the ska-punkers
pay back the locals and salute the hometown with a skein of Middle
East gigs and a live album culled from last year's show there.
</P>
<P>
   Best New Local Band: The Willard Grant Conspiracy Its disc,
``Flying Low,'' featured sad, eloquent, contemplative music that
had deep resonance.
</P>
<P>
   Best Local Production: Boston Rock Opera's ``Preservation'' BRO
kicked up the Kinks's rock opera in grand style, telling the story
of corrupting power, immorality, and idealism gone rotten. Great
cast, great staging, great direction. A timeless work done proud.
</P>
<P>
   Best Mess: Hole ``Celebrity Skin'' is stellar and disciplined,
but the walking time bomb that is Courtney Love was in full view at
the Orpheum during WBCN's Xmas Rave. Drugs or no drugs, the woman
does not go gentle into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive Artist of the Year: Elliot Smith This is not
solipsistic sensitive; this is a perceptive singer-songwriter who's
attunded to life's inherent sadness and the struggles we all face.
A convincing album, ``XO,'' and Paradise set.
</P>
<P>
   Manson of the Year: Shirley Manson Garbage's energetic front gal
edges out Marilyn (still posing) and Charlie (still confined) as
well as the English pop band Mansun.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Down Below: Joey Kramer of Aerosmith. His car went boom and
up in flames while he was gassing up, but the resilient stickman is
back in the saddle. Still, you can't help but recall Spinal Tap and
its mysterious, mishap-prone drummers . . .
</P>
<P>
   Family Affair: The Wainwrights, papa Loudon, son Rufus, daughter
Sloan The family that sings together . . . slings arrows, Top-level
work all around with Rufus becoming one of the year's brightest
emerging talents and Loudon still delightfully prickly. He
serenaded an Indigo Girls audience at the Newport Folk Festival
with ``I Wish I was a Lesbian,'' and did not altogether charm them.
God love him.
</P>
<P>
   Gobbler of the Year: SFX The concert-promoting monster swallowed
up Don Law and everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial Bomb of the Year: Smashing Pumpkins Their ``Adore''
album tanked and they fired their manager. Yes, it was his fault.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
