u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-01 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BOUNCE BACK OR BE BOUNCED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First things first. Can your beloved Future Connecticut Patriots
win this wild-card game in Jacksonville? Sure. Why not? Do the
Jaguars look like the 1985 Bears to you?
</P>
<P>
   Well then, will they defeat the Jacksonville Jaguars and advance
in the tournament? Who am I, Nostradamus? Geez, I'm not even Chris
Mortensen. Or even Ron Borges. They can win; that's all I know.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, after listening to special teamsman
extraordinaire/nickel back Larry Whigham, I came away thinking I
should rifle the savings accounts and the available piggy banks and
put the whole wad down on your beloved Future Connecticut Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter (not yours truly): ``Can you guys bounce back from that
game on Sunday?''
</P>
<P>
   Whiggy: ``Of course. We're a championship football team.''
</P>
<P>
   They're not champions of anything right now, except, possibly,
the Commonwealth. (Not to downgrade our national 1-AA champion
Minutemen, but we'd probably have to take the Pats and the points
in that matchup). They are the once-upon-a-time champions of both
the AFC East and the AFC, period, and that's what Whiggy must have
been alluding to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have veterans here who have been to the Super Bowl,'' he
reminded us. ``We've got guys here who know how to win football
games.''
</P>
<P>
   These same guys also know how to oink-up a meaningful game, too,
and therein lies the problem confronting anyone in the process of
deciding whether they are a reasonable wager in this or any other
game. Consistency, thy name is most assuredly not New England.
</P>
<P>
   Such residual negativism does not fly far in the confines of the
local locker room. To them, there is only one reality: They'll be
playing on Sunday afternoon, and there are 18 other teams whose
players will be golfing, going to the movies or channel surfing.
</P>
<P>
   It is left to the media and fans to rehash and re-rehash the bad
stuff. We look at the Atlanta game, the St. Louis game, the Buffalo
heist (otherwise known as the Zebra Follies), and the reprehensible
second Jets game and we see a glass that has nothing more than a
teeny-weeny drop in the bottom. We can't help it.
</P>
<P>
   The coach and the players, when they think about what's
transpired during the past four months at all, think of the
Tennessee game, the Kansas City game, and the San Francisco game.
The bad stuff? What bad stuff? Anyway, are they playing the Jaguars
in the wild-card game or aren't they? That's all they want to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally,'' said Bruce Armstrong, ``you'd like to be getting
better and better as the season goes along. We've been an
up-and-down team. But this is why you play. We're in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The regular season is over,'' confirmed defensive end Ferric
Collons. ``It's all about getting to The Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   They might have that invitation to The Dance, but they aren't
exactly gonna be dancin' with the one that brung 'em. That Bledsoe
feller has that damaged digit. They may be in, but the star QB is
out. For now.
</P>
<P>
   To which the official party line is, ``So?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Zolak's our guy,'' asserted Collons, a large fellow who has a
rather forceful way with words. ``That's who we're playing with.
And he's gonna take us where we've got to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Down in Jacksonville, the Jaguars are welcoming back their own
starting quarterback. Mark Brunell has been idled by a high ankle
sprain, but the dynamic southpaw is expected back for what will be
the first home playoff game in the franchise's four-year history.
The Jaguars got by Pittsburgh (21-3) in the season's wrapup game
last Monday night with hulking (6-5, 245) rookie QB Jonathan Quinn
completing 10 of 19 for 192 yards and running for his first
professional touchdown. But a throwaway game in Week 16 is not a
playoff game, and thus the Jaguars will be happy to see Brunell
back, even if his ankle renders him less of a sprint-out man and
more of a pocket passer.
</P>
<P>
   The wary Patriots aren't buying into the idea that Brunell will
be anything less than his frisky self.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if he has to stay in the pocket,'' said safety Lawyer
Milloy, a former college teammate, ``he can still get it done. But
we're preparing for a healthy Mark Brunell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll prepare for him as we have in the past,'' agreed
Collons. ``We'll prepare for Mark Brunell and the things he adds to
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Another much-discussed Jaguar is running back Fred Taylor, a
1,233-yard, 17-TD man who began the season as the backup to James
Stewart and finished it as the obvious choice for AFC Offensive
Rookie of the Year. Listen to people rave about the ninth pick in
the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a very, very impacting rookie season,'' declared Pete
Carroll. ``He's powerful. He's real fast. Not just fast, real
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the ability to just break it,'' pointed out Bruell,
``and that's something we haven't had around here for a long time.
He takes the pressure off the passing game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big back,'' added Collons. ``He has exceptional speed.
He's an exceptional talent.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, sounds like we should just put him down for 175 and a couple
of scores and move on.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a meeting of two teams on the short list of NFL
clubs most affected by injuury this season. The Patriots had 14 of
their original 22 starters out at one time or another, and they
come into this game without their quarterback, their best wide
receiver, and two starting linebackers, to name a few. The Jaguars
lost their starting running back early _ what was his name again? _
and before the year was over they had 35 guys on injured reserve
and actually played three games with five different guys going both
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Hah! I just wanted to see if you were paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the Jaguars really have had has as many or more
primary players miss multiple games as anyone in the league. Tom
Coughlin, a k a Tuna Lite, enhanced his reputation by guiding his
squad to an 11-5 record and the AFC Central Division title. They're
notoriously tough at home, but let the record show that last season
the then-maligned Pats strolled into Alltell Stadium and came away
with an impressive 26-20 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It is memories like that one the Future Connecticut players will
carry with them onto the field Sunday. For the closing summary, we
will once again call upon Mr. Larry Whigham.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the end of a 16-game season. That one is over. Now
we're at the beginning of a four-game season.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, rah-rah-sis-boom-bah to you, too, Whiggy!
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
