<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4575 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-     01-01 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISHING UP PEACE, LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The contents are partly meant to be enjoyed by the preschool
set, but the marketing pitch is strictly tie-dyed and Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   In an ongoing bid to expand its presence in mainstream
supermarkets and to appeal to young and middle-aged consumers,
Annie's Homegrown of Wakefield, Mass. has just introduced an entree
called ``Peace Pasta &AMP; Parmesan,'' a righteous update to the
old-fashioned boxed mix of macaroni and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we look to the 30th anniversary of Woodstock next year,
it's important to teach our children well: Peace never goes out of
style,'' said company cofounder Andrew Martin when Peace Pasta
debuted this week. ``We hope children of all ages will enjoy this
totally natural reminder to give peace a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The packaging isn't subtle; it's as tie-dyed as Jerry Garcia
neckwear. And the pasta inside is shaped like tiny peace signs.
</P>
<P>
   Company values and a peace-and-love philosophy may also be a
good way to push product on a limited marketing budget, as Ben &AMP;
Jerry's proved with ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Annie's traces its roots to 1989, when cofounder Ann Withey and
a partner sold their Smartfood Popcorn business to PepsiCo, and
Withey decided to make a culinary career move from snack foods to
boxed pasta.
</P>
<P>
   With many health-conscious baby boomers seeking a more healthful
lifestyle, Annie's pasta dishes have been something of a hit at
natural-food stores. But when a company trafficks in macaroni and
cheese, children comprise a market that can't be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Annie's took aim at the children's market with
the introduction of BernieOs, which the company describes as a
``fun-shaped'' alternative to Spaghettios. The entree takes its
name from Withey's pet rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   (Bernie also does double duty as company mascot, and his cartoon
likeness can be found on Annie's packaging.)
</P>
<P>
   Children may indeed like fun-shaped pasta, but underage eaters
have apparently been slow to warm to the subtle flavorings of
Annie's signature cheese sauces.
</P>
<P>
   Sauces for many of Annie's original macaroni dishes draw heavily
on cheddar cheese. While these sauces are pleasing to ``the mature
palate'' of the middle-aged gourmet, Nardone suggested, children
have been underwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   So Withey began experimenting with cheese recipes that would wow
her 18-month-old daughter. After much trial and error, Withey hit
upon Peace Pasta &AMP; Parmesan, which features a boxtop likeness of
Bernie in full Woodstock hippie regalia.
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock notwithstanding, Nardone thinks Peace Pasta can tap
into popular nostalgia for the 1960s and '70s. ``McDonald's is
running ads with a flashback retro theme, and kids are wearing
bell-bottoms again,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Annie's Homegrown recently acquired Tamarind Tree, a line of
ethnic ``heat-and-serve'' foods that bills itself as a ``taste of
India.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Annie's, Tamarind Tree seems to market itself largely
through a company philosophy. A guru's ``14 steps to happiness''
are posted on Tamarind's Web site. The site also features quotes
said to be from Mahatma Gandhi, such as, ``A customer is the most
important visitor on our premises.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamarind Tree gives Annie's something it didn't have before, a
line of entrees that appeal to vegans, a fast-growing subset of
vegetarians who eschew dairy products as well as meat. Tamarind
Tree entrees include alu chole, a curried garbanzo dish, and dal
makhani, described as ``aromatic lentil chili.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, plans call for adding new varieties to both the
Tamarind Tree and Annie's Homegrown lines. The coming year could
also see more acquisitions for a company with projected annual
sales of $7 million, Nardone says.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nardone, nearly all profits have been plowed back
into paying slotting fees, the fees supermarkets charge for putting
products on their store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Annie's began last year with a presence in nearly all the
nation's health food stores, but only about 20 percent of
mainstream supermarkets. Now Annie's is in nearly 30 percent of the
nation's supermarkets, and, with products such as Peace Pasta &AMP;
Parmesan, it hopes to expand that presence even more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 1339EST &QL; 
