<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4576 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      01-01 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. AIRPLANE MAN TAKES A FLIGHT WITH THE BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Howling Wolf and Mississippi Fred McDowell. Not exactly
household names in the '90s, but they are the Delta-blues idols of
two women known as Mr. Airplane Man, a name taken from a Howling
Wolf song. The two women _ guitarist Margaret Garrett and drummer
Tara McManus _ play a raw mix of country blues and stripped-down
rock that is causing a sensation in Boston clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love Howling Wolf and Fred McDowell, but we also love Iggy
Pop and the Gun Club,'' says Garrett, who grew up in Boston suburb
Newton and has known McManus since they attended the same summer
camp 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were inseparable from the start and were always getting
into trouble,'' McManus adds.
</P>
<P>
   The two women are now both 28 _ a young age to be so steeped in
Delta blues _ but they've added a droney, psychedelic edge that has
hypnotized a growing legion of fans who have seen them play on the
streets and in the Plough and Stars, Toad, House of Blues (where
they've opened for Koko Taylor and R.L. Burnside), the Brendan
Behan Pub, and the Midway Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be able to support ourselves through this music,
but we're not into it for the money,'' says Garrett, a talented
slide guitarist. That dedication shows, because Mr. Airplane Man
exhibits sincere artistry, not mimicry. The group has released a
self-titled CD that slyly rearranges songs by Wolf (``Moanin' for
My Baby'') and McDowell (``Sun Sinkin' Low''), but also has
original tunes that make this a highly signable band. The CD is
available at shows and through the duo's Web site (at
www.vacant.org/airplaneman/). Parts of it were recorded at the home
studio of Morphine's Mark Sandman in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the music speaks for itself. People feel it,'' says
Garrett, who attended Clark University in Worcester, where she had
a Sonic Youth-style noise band named Blow. But her life forever
changed when she walked into the used-records store Mystery Train
in Cambridge and heard Howling Wolf's ``Wang Dang Doodle'' blasting
from the speakers. ``I became obsessed with Howling Wolf,'' she
says of the pioneering, primal bluesman.
</P>
<P>
   She and McManus (who is originally from Westborough) moved for a
year to San Francisco, where they hoped to launch their career, but
we ``didn't dig the music scene there, so we came back to Boston,
where people have responded really well,'' says Garrett. She also
has been tutored locally, studying Delta blues guitar with Michael
Tarbox of the Tarbox Ramblers (who play every Friday at the Green
Street Grill in Cambridge) and local legend Paul Rishell, who once
taught Bonnie Raitt. Garrett plays a '50s Kraftsman guitar and a
Gibson ES295 (``my prize gem''), while McManus plays a minimalist
drum kit, upon which she adds rhythms learned from her study of
African and Haitian music.
</P>
<P>
   They've also enlisted the services of first-time managers (and
husband and wife) Ted Drozdowski and Laurie Hoffma, known as
Barking Koala Management. Drozdowski, a former staffer at the
Boston Phoenix, was given a W. C. Handy award for blues journalism
in Memphis this year.
</P>
<P>
   His memory of first meeting Mr. Airplane Man is worth noting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were playing in front of the liquor store in Central
Square. I thought that was the coolest place,'' Drozdowski says of
that springtime meeting. ``Even if they sucked, I was going to give
them a dollar. But when I got up close and they were doing a Jesse
Mae Hemphill song, I was hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Mr. Airplane Man did a rare double by playing
at Toad in early Monday evening, then the Plough and Stars for two
later sets. At the Plough, before a packed house, they even did the
Velvet Underground's ``Mr. Rain,'' Mazzy Star's ``Blue Light,'' the
Gun Club's ``For the Love of Ivy,'' and Iggy Pop's ``I Just Wanna
Be Your Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a connection between Iggy Pop and everything else we
do,'' says Garrett. ``I'd feel it was wrong if we were just pulling
off a Mississippi Delta blues thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stone Crazy: Speaking of the blues, there's a veteran unit
around town that's starting to make waves. Stone Crazy includes
bassist Danny Klein (from the J. Geils Band), singer-harmonica
virtuoso Babe Pino, guitarist Ken Pino (who played 10 years with
Johnny Clyde Copeland), and drummer Mark Hyland. Stone Crazy
recently played at Mama Kin and tore the place up with a rockin'
set of blues that encompassed original tunes and scorching covers
of Otis Rush's ``Homework'' (a staple of the Geils Band) and
Freddie King's ``Goin' Down.'' Klein was outstanding, playing a
five-string Steinberger bass with all the relish that he's known
for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Goes Wild: Brad Pitt, Jeff Goldblum, Johnny Depp,
Bruce Willis, Juliette Lewis, Will Smith, Billy Bob Thornton, Kim
Basinger, and Keanu Reeves are among the film stars contributing
songs to the all-star album, ``Hollywood Goes Wild.'' Due out in
the first quarter of the year, the album will benefit Wildlife
Waystation, a sanctuary for wild and exotic animals in a national
forest in California. The executive producer is Ron Lovely, a
Boston resident who launched the idea after meeting Pitt at Les
Paul's birthday party in New York last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brad got there a half-hour early just so he could hang out
with Les Paul. Brad is a huge music fan,'' says Lovely, who then
solicited Reeves's participation after the latter's group Dogstar
played at Boston's Avalon club. Pitt's song on the disc is
``Midtown'' (from the film ``Johnny Suede''), while Dogstar's is an
original modern rocker, ``Your World.''
</P>
<P>
   An early listen to the album suggests that one of the most
talented stars is Goldblum, who does an original song with a bebop
jazz edge. Lovely, who has worked with Smokey Robinson and Eric
Clapton, says the album will come out on Hammer &AMP; Lace Records,
which released ``Women for Women,'' a disc whose proceeds supported
breast cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   for '98: Frank Sinatra, Carl Perkins, Carl Wilson, Tammy
Wynette, Sonny Bono, Linda McCartney, Junior Wells, Gene Autry, Roy
Rogers, Jimmy Rogers, Pat Clancy, Cozy Powell, Johnny Adams,
Charlie Feathers, Wendy O. Williams, Grandpa Jones, Nicolette
Larson, Junior Kimbrough, Falco, Floyd Cramer, Eddie Rabbitt, Rob
Pilatus (half of Milli Vanilli), Rose Maddox, Kenny Kirkland, Chico
Ryan (of Sha Na Na), Butch McDade (founder and drummer of the
Amazing Rhythm Aces), Eldon Shamblin (guitarist with Bob Wills &AMP;
the Texas Playboys), Jimmy Driftwood, Justin Tubb, and Charlie
Foxx, who wrote ``Mockingbird.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
