<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4577 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANGELS-AZR &LR;      01-01 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BELIEVERS THAN EVER ARE TOUCHED BY ANGELS  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, JAN. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Are angels among us, or do we create them?
</P>
<P>
   We know for certain that angels have appeared in art and
scripture since 3000 B.C. Angelology, the study of angels, was
developed in ancient Persia and absorbed into Judaism and
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are perhaps more reported angel contacts than ever
before. The angel phenomenon has deeply permeated our culture.
Besides its presence in religion, angels also have been prominent
of late in the secular quadrants of our culture. It's not unusual
for movies, books and TV shows to contain angel elements in story
lines.
</P>
<P>
   But are they (begin ital) real? (end ital) Are we experiencing
worldwide angel contact or worldwide angel hysteria?
</P>
<P>
   Mental illness aside, clinicians are reluctant to empirically
dissect matters of faith.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Bowers, a Scottsdale clinical psychologist who also has a
degree in theology, believes wish fulfillment may account for angel
contacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be some crossover at times between our imagination
and our desire to experience something,'' Bowers said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinical psychologist Larry Sidener of Phoenix said people often
develop a reality based on what they want to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, when people lose significant others in their
life, they talk about the idea that this person is still with
them,'' Sidener said. ``Well, is this true or is it wish
fulfillment?''
</P>
<P>
   We do know that our concept of angels is changing.
</P>
<P>
   They've gone from androgynous cupids of early Christian art to
winged heads of the Middle Ages. In the Renaissance, angels
appeared with complete bodies again, plus a halo and a second pair
of wings.
</P>
<P>
   If you've seen the film ``City of Angels,'' you know that people
today might think they look a lot like Nicolas Cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every hundred years, concepts of angels change because no one
can pin them down,'' said Linda Neff, angelologist and member of
Chandler Christian Church. ``They aren't corporal beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Neff believes she had an angel encounter when
she lived in Texas during a period of devastating brush fires. She
said the angel filled the sky, outshining the stars and the city
lights. The being had golden hair and wings but no discernible
facial features.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense of peace and security that enfolded me was
mesmerizing,'' Neff said.
</P>
<P>
   The brush fires abated shortly after the encounter, and Neff
turned to Bible studies to find out more about angels. She
discovered that along with their visual changes, some believe their
purpose has changed, too, evolving from Old Testament messengers of
God to the more secular concept of angels as pals or personal
bodyguards to serve man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angels serve God, not man,'' Neff said. ``They answer to God,
not man. They follow the instructions of God, not man. Too often,
the New Age concept of guardian angels is that of a supernatural
being provided for our benefit and pleasure. I think that is
entirely a misinterpreted view of angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Father Michael Diskin, assistant chancellor at the Phoenix
Catholic Diocese, agrees that it would be inappropriate to say that
angels serve the needs of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in accord with God's will, the role of angels may be for
the benefit of human beings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Diskin said he's not particularly bothered by the way angels are
culturally perceived as long as it doesn't take away from the
individual's relationship with God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, some people have deified angels,'' Diskin said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most prominent angelologist today is Doreen Virtue
of the Los Angeles area, a former clinical psychologist turned
angel medium. Her own encounters with angels led her to national TV
appearances. She has also written a dozen books, including ``Angel
Therapy'' (Hay House).
</P>
<P>
   Virtue defines angels as ``thought forms'' from the Creator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time God thinks about love, he creates these thought
forms, which are an extension of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The mission of angels, according to Virtue, is to raise our
consciousness, prompt our spiritual evolution and let us know that
all ends well.
</P>
<P>
   She said angels (begin ital) can (end ital) take on any form.
Even Nicolas Cage.
</P>
<P>
   Virtue also believes angel popularity has never been greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at the world,'' Virtue said. ``We're asking for
their help more. In my opinion, there are more angels on Earth than
ever. In my seminars, it's not unusual for one-third of the
audience to have had an angel encounter.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves two-thirds who may be asking the question: Are these
people losing it?
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix psychiatrist John Scialli said that in most cases where
people see angels or ghosts or have other experiences that science
can't explain, mental illness is not an issue if these are isolated
incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would other symptoms and a history of disordered
thinking if it was a mental illness,'' Scialli said. ``And since an
angel vision is usually comforting rather than disturbing, I don't
focus on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scialli said he's not so sure there are more angel contacts now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the media is just making this topic more acceptable to
talk about out loud,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A point not lost on angel entrepreneurs who are turning out a
glut of angel merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Neff said angel commercialism disturbs her. But Father Diskin
reserves judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commercialization to the extent that it reminds people that
there's a spiritual dimension to life doesn't bother me,'' Diskin
said.
</P>
<P>
   He himself received an angel golf pin with the premise that the
pin would improve his game.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should wear it more,'' Diskin said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
