<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4578 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-TAYLOR-EDWARDS-BO     01-01 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TAYLOR-EDWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS-TAYLOR: A CARRYOVER EFFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY AND MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are friends, so you never know in which direction their
conversations might go. But you don't need a transcript of their
chats to understand where they won't be going. Here's a hint: Nov.
1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Edwards and Fred Taylor have worked out together. They
have shared Southeastern Conference fields together. They have done
photo shoots in Florida together. They have run for pro football
scouts in Indiana together. They have both seen their names posted
on first-round draft boards. A few times this year, Edwards has
dialed Taylor in Jacksonville and Taylor has dialed Edwards in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   That may be a lot of talking and socializing, but there is
always one element missing from their conversations: Nov. 1, 1997.
That was the last time Edwards and Taylor played a game in the same
stadium. It was in Jacksonville's Alltel Stadium, also known as the
Gator Bowl. It is the same venue in which the Patriots and Jaguars
will play their AFC wild-card game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, now a Patriot, was a Georgia Bulldog back then. Taylor,
now a Jaguar, was a Florida Gator. But, hey, you didn't have to
bring that up, did you?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not something we talk about,'' Edwards said Thursday.
``We usually don't talk about stuff that happened on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   At least not with each other. But you know how friends are.
Sometimes no one has to say a word, but you still know that an
event has never really faded from memory.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, sizable underdogs to Florida, went into
Jacksonville and beat Florida by 20 points, 37-17. Everyone knew
about Taylor, who rushed for 85 yards in the loss. Not many knew
about a kid named Edwards, who rushed for 124 yards and had four
touchdowns that day. He scored in every quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that being a real good win for us,'' Edwards said.
``We were underdogs, as usual, and had never beaten a Steve
Spurrier team as long as I had been there. He had something like
seven consecutive wins against us. It was good to finally beat one
of his teams.''
</P>
<P>
   For three days, Taylor has given the stock answer _ the one he
knows the media in Jacksonville, a Gator-loving section of Florida,
want to hear _ when the name of Robert Edwards is brought up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got to hope Robert doesn't do what he did to us last
year,'' said Taylor. ``Robert beat us singlehandedly.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Taylor is away from the media throngs and is asked
about Edwards, he chuckles. Then a small smile crosses his face.
And then Taylor chuckles again. A wider smile. And again a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew him a bit from playing against him in the
Florida-Georgia game,'' said Taylor with a chuckle. ``I also met
him down at the Senior Bowl. We were playing in the same backfield
and we ran together for a whole week. So we were messing around
with each other the entire week.''
</P>
<P>
   A bigger chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert likes to mess around,'' said Taylor. ``Robert's a funny
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we were in that combine together and . . .''
</P>
<P>
   An even bigger chuckle at that memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two or three days that we were out in the combine, like,
Robert was playing around with my stuff,'' said Taylor. ``He was
just messing around and we were using each other's cell phone, and
fooling around. He'd be teasing me and I'd be teasing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Each Monday morning this season, Taylor has checked the
statistics from the New England games and compared them with his.
Taylor could see that Edwards was doing well, but, even if he won't
say it himself, Taylor was doing much better.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a case could be made that it is Taylor and not
Minnesota's Randy Moss who should be NFL Rookie of the Year. Moss
has two other outstanding receivers on his team to deflect
defensive schemes away from him, but Taylor has been the entire
Jacksonville running game since James Stewart suffered a
season-ending knee injury in the third game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart sank when I heard that James would be out for the
season,'' said Taylor. ``It happened real fast. I looked over at
the sidelines when he was down and it didn't look very good. I
didn't know if he was going to return or not. So I just did the
most I can while I was in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Which has been much.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics are statistics, so it must be noted that Taylor has
gained 1,223 yards on 264 carries this season for a 4.6-yard
average. More significant, though, is that Taylor has scored 17
touchdowns, the third-most by a rookie in NFL history. His 14
rushing touchdowns also are the third-most by an NFL rookie and he
already has the three longest runs in Jacksonville history (77, 70,
and 52 yards). The 77-yarder, it should be noted, came on Taylor's
first play in a Monday night game, against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did what I visualized: Monday night football, first play
of the game, (the Dolphins) are trying to kill somebody,'' said
Taylor. ``It was a predetermined cutback.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so good about Fred,'' said Tony Boselli, the Jaguars'
star tackle, ``is that he can break it anytime. Just give Fred a
crease and you know he can be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Leon Searcy, the Jaguars' other tackle, put it, ``When
he's running those long ones, I just sit back and enjoy it. It's
like being at a track meet, watching those 4x100s.''
</P>
<P>
   In last Monday night's game against Pittsburgh, Taylor displayed
his other side, his fierceness as well as his flash. On a pass
reception for a TD, Taylor ran over two Steelers to get into the
end zone, and on a 12-yard TD run straight up the middle, he bowled
over three Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think I'm strong, too,'' said Taylor. ``I just try
to have a winning attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Patriots are sizable underdogs to the Jaguars, just
as Georgia was a sizable underdog to Florida. The SEC is certainly
not the NFL. And Steve Spurrier doesn't have much in common with
Jaguars head coach Tom Coughlin. But one truth remains from the
college days of Edwards and Taylor. The team that runs best on
Sunday will most likely win.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will be playing with backup quarterback Scott
Zolak. The Jaguars' starter, Mark Brunell, probably won't be his
usually elusive self. He has a badly sprained ankle. So, once
again, the focus is on the friends. The runners, Edwards and
Taylor. They already don't talk about Nov. 1. Is there a chance
that they won't talk about Jan. 3, either?
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, I hope Robert does some good things _ just some _
and maybe have a flash or two,'' said Taylor. ``I don't want him to
do anything like the last time. This time I want us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards knows he will need some help from the Patriots' defense.
One Patriot was asked what he thought of Taylor. His answer was a
very revealing, ``Oh my God.'' He is not the player you want to
face when your starting middle linebacker is out for the season.
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor, the ninth player taken in last spring's draft, is
not the only runner who likes to punish people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to hit guys before they hit me,'' said Edwards, the
18th player taken. ``I want them to take the worst of the hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Running with power has not been a problem in Edwards's rookie
season. No one has questioned his heart. His speed? That's a
different story. He is constantly reminded that he was caught from
behind _ twice _ during the loss in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I believe I have the speed, there's no doubt about that,''
he said. ``That was just a matter of endurance, and it's something
I need to work on in the offseason. The pro season is longer than
the college season. But I wasn't trying to get caught on those
runs. It's just something that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday will be like a trip home for Edwards. His parents,
brother, and sister will be at the game. He has a few other
relatives in Florida, too.
</P>
<P>
   Once he arrives, he plans to call Taylor. He will not mention
Nov. 1 or Jan. 3. But by about 4 o'clock Sunday, there is a good
chance you will know who won simply by asking which rookie
1,000-yard rusher had the better game. If it makes the friends more
comfortable, they will not have to mention any dates over the
course of their friendship. The results, though, will always be in
the books.
</P>
<P>
   (This story was reported by Michael Holley in Foxborough, Mass.
and Michael Madden in Jacksonville, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4579 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BOS &LR;      01-01 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS DEFENSE SETS ITS SIGHTS ON FLUTIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ The climate inside the Miami Dolphins' locker room
at the practice facility at Nova Southeastern University was hot
and steamy. It was even hotter at Sam Madison's stall, where the
cornerback sat amid a clutch of reporters, responding to questions
about the incendiary remarks Buffalo Bills quarterback Doug Flutie
had made earlier in the week about Miami's secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it would be a bit of an understatement to say that
Madison merely ``responded'' to Flutie's bulletin-board comments
about how ``it will be important for the officials to pull their
flags out if (Miami's cornerbacks) start tugging and pulling as
usual,'' and how ``you can't cover Eric Moulds one-on-one; you
can't cover Andre Reed one-on-one.''
</P>
<P>
   Madison, a second-year pro out of Louisville, has never been
understated about anything in his brief NFL career. So he returned
fire with a jet stream of invective aimed at his intended target in
Saturday's AFC wild-card game between the Bills and Dolphins at Pro
Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Though Madison turned up the heat on the trash talk, Flutie was
unaware of the chain reaction his comments had caused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did it make a firestorm?'' Flutie asked. ``Oh, good. They get
excited about little things. What are they going to do _ play
harder now?''
</P>
<P>
   What Flutie did, actually, was fire up Madison's competitive
blast furnace, and Dolphin fans hope the quarterback's words have
the same effect on the rest of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Although Flutie is listed in the Bills media guide as being 5
feet 10 inches, Madison cut him down to size _ by 5 inches or so _
belittling a man who has ascended from underpaid backup to Pro Bowl
selection by leading Buffalo to victories in 10 of its last 13
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 5-5 and can't really see over the line and all he does is
scramble, so it really does (upset me) when somebody comes out and
says something like that,'' Madison seethed. ``That motivates me,
and their receivers are going to have to be ready to play Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the way they move the ball, they have to get him out of
the pocket because he's too short to see over the D-line.''
</P>
<P>
   Badda bing. So, Sam, what about Flutie's arm?
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been just Doug Flutie _ I mean, he's only 5-5 and he
just throws the ball up there and lets Moulds go up there and get
it,'' Madison said, firing another zing. ``But Moulds and Reed have
been doing a great job for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Badda bing bang. So, Sam, exactly how tall is Flutie?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's about 5-5,'' he said. ``Man, if I had Eric Moulds
and Andre Reed, I could get back there and play quarterback and let
those guys go up there and get it. I mean, he's not doing anything
spectacular. He's just forcing balls _ and what he does is force
balls _ and they've been making plays for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The camera lights went off, and the reporters dispersed to
cooler corners of the locker room. But Madison still smoldered.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's strong words to say we go out there and hold,'' said
Madison, who has been called for six holding penalties this season,
compared with 10 for his colleague, Terrell Buckley. ``Of course,
when you're playing press coverage, you're going to get a holding
call here and there. I've had six, and Terrell's had 10, but we've
played 1,000 snaps. That's great for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just go out there and play football. (Receivers) get away
with pushing every now and then and we get away with holding, so it
evens out. But we usually get the short end of the stick with the
holding penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, Buckley stood in front of his stall, unmoved by
Flutie's words. As a veteran, he knew they were basically a ploy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a wrassling fan, and it's just like when those wrasslers
get to talking,'' Buckley sniffed. ``(Madison) probably looks at it
as an insult or something like that. But, being a vet, I'm going to
wait until I get out there on Saturday. You don't want to spend any
energy getting mad now, you might be tired by the time the game
rolls around.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley started for the locker room door, then turned and called
out to Madison, who was still holding forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, 2-9,'' Buckley said. ``We'll let him know on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah,'' Madison replied, ``but I just had to let the short
man know he shouldn't be talking that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami's defensive linemen, meahwhile, wasted little breath on
Flutie's comments. With defensive end Jason Taylor out for the
season with a fractured clavicle, Shane Burton knows the Dolphins
must conserve every ounce of energy so they can contain Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a good offensive team and a good scheme, but a lot
of it is him,'' Burton said. ``He makes a lot of plays and he keeps
the guys going in the right direction. He's going to be a big
factor. If we let him run around and make plays, it's going to be a
tough day. But if we stop the run and get after him and hit him a
little bit, get him on the ground, we'll keep him down.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton's first impressions of Flutie from a 30-24 loss at
Buffalo Nov. 1 were predictable: ``For a guy as tall as I am,''
said the 6-6 defensive tackle, ``my first impression was, `Wow,
this guy is really tiny.' I mean, he's even shorter than Zach
(Thomas, Miami's 5-11 linebacker) _ and that's short.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, that was Thomas's first impression of Flutie,
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really know he was that short,'' said Thomas.
``That's what they say about me, too, but I'm impressed with him.
That's why he's going to the Pro Bowl. I just hope he doesn't have
a Pro Bowl day against us, but he's a great quarterback and he's
had all those great years up in the Canadian League, so he knows
what (the playoffs) are all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just hoping we can go out there and rattle him a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Rated the fifth-best passer in the AFC after completing 202 of
354 attempts for 2,711 yards and 20 touchdowns, Flutie proved
unflappable in that Nov. 1 victory. Against Miami, he passed for
206 yards and three touchdowns, rallying the Bills from a 24-14
deficit with 16 unanswered points in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got special talents, obviously,'' said Miami coach Jimmy
Johnson. ``He's got a knack for making plays and he makes great
decisions. On top of that, I think sometimes when people look at a
player like Doug Flutie, or a Zach Thomas, someone who may not fit
the scouting combine dimensions, you kind of look at them as an
overachiever. I don't think people realize the talent that these
individuals have, and Doug Flutie is a talented player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
