<HEADLINE>
DEADLY STORM LEAVES CLOUD OVER SYDNEY-HOBART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Christmas eve, two days before the start of the annual
Sydney-Hobart yacht race at the celebratory height of the
Australian summer, the weather forecast was ominous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere is in a chaotic state,'' warned the official
race meteorologist, Kenn Batt. ``I am concerned. It is shaping up
to be quite complex. It could turn into a rough ride for the first
few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Batt's words now seem both understated and prescient. The race
started last Saturday with 115 sailboats off on a 630-mile course
to the island state of Tasmania, but within 24 hours had been
devastated by a howling storm of hurricane strength that left six
sailors dead or missing, and dozens of wrecked or badly damaged
boats foundering in the Tasman Sea. Seventy of the starters were
forced to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, as the largest maritime search-and-rescue
operation in Australia's history continues, questions are mounting
amid claims that race organizers and participants knew of the
potential danger at least 24 hours before the storm tore the fleet
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from Batt's Christmas Eve forecast, the danger was
certainly not unknown. Winds gusting to 90 miles per hour and
churning up 35-foot seas that snapped masts, rolled and pitchpoled
hulls, could well have been avoided, says a rising chorus of race
critics, had only officials stepped in and abandoned the race as
the storm approached.
</P>
<P>
   The government of New South Wales has ordered a coroner's
inquiry, and the race's authority _ Cruising Yacht Club of
Australia _ has also begun to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney-Hobart, which started in 1945, is one of the three most
prestigious blue-water races in the world, alongside Britain's
Fastnet and the biennial Newport-Bermuda race off the US East
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``Hell on High Water,'' the Sydney-Hobart is known for
its boisterous conditions, a race course for only the most
experienced sailors and well-tested blue-water boats. But even so,
storms have exploded on this race before, though only one death had
been recorded in its 52 years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, 75-knot southerlies whipped the seas up to 35 feet,
snapping masts and smashing hulls. Two boats sank and 66 of the
starters were forced to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Even with that five-year-old experience fresh in their minds,
and with Batt's weather predictions leaving little hope for
reprieve, the fleet and race officials pressed on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two Sydney-Hobart races saw southerly busters early
in the race, and this year is no different,'' Batt warned the
skippers. The fleet, he said, would run into a brick wall southerly
early in the race.
</P>
<P>
   But some boats in the fleet were looking forward to the
boisterous conditions, remembering that similar southerlies helped
the German Maxi Morning Glory set a record in 1996 of 2 days, 14
hours, 7 minutes, and 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   As the race began, the US entry Sayonara, an 80-foot Maxi owned
and raced by billionaire Larry Ellison, was an odds-on favorite
because of her upwind potential.
</P>
<P>
   But three days later, after indeed winning this year's race,
Ellison was anything but the picture of the victorious yachtsman.
In fact, said the despondent skipper, blue-water racing may be over
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may reassess my attitude,'' he said. ``It will take a little
time to place this in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Another sailor, Richard Winning, owner and skipper of the yacht
Winston Churchill, which was sunk by the storm, has vowed never to
race again. Winning acknowledged that he had been given ``adequate
weather information'' but pressed on. Three of his crew members
were among those killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally won't race again,'' said Winning the day after he
was rescued. ``My decision is pretty well made up.''
</P>
<P>
   Two questions sure to get close scrutiny: Did the sailing crews
have adequate weather information both before the start and as the
race progressed, and more importantly, who is responsible for the
decision to continue or abandon a race?
</P>
<P>
   At one end of the spectrum is the view of Hugo van Kretschmar,
head of the Cruising Yacht Club, who believes the responsibility is
entirely with the skippers, that under international rules it was
not up to the club to abandon the race.
</P>
<P>
   His predecessor, Peter Bush, who will lead the club's inquiry,
said that while safety is the primary concern of any governing
body, the call to abandon the race would have been a difficult one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we called the race off when we were aware of the strength
of those conditions,'' said Bush, ``little else could have happened
other than what happened because these guys were already on the
race course.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, vowing an impartial inquiry, ``The single most
important aspect all the way along in this process, in the history
of this race, is that we make the event and all our yacht racing as
safe as humanly possible.''
</P>
<P>
   (Tony Chamberlain covers outdoor topics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
