<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR CONFERENCE CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a new year upon us, it is time for college basketball teams
to forget about non-conference opponents and tournament formats and
get down to the nitty-gritty of conference play.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick look at the emerging teams in the major
conferences.
</P>
<P>
   --Big East _ The University of Connecticut was the preseason
pick and the Huskies, who are No. 1 in the Associated Press poll,
have done nothing seriously wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Calhoun's team has beaten good and bad teams with
regularity.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a surprise _ and it's a minor one _ it's the
emergence of St. John's as a threat. The Johnnies have been a force
throughout November and December. Circle Jan. 30 on your calendar.
UConn at St. John's at Madison Square Garden. Tim Welsh has done an
outstanding job in turning Providence into a competitive team _
proof of which is the Friars' recent win over Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   --Big Ten _ Michigan State may not be as good as we first
thought and Ohio State may be better. Minnesota and Wisconsin and
Indiana all are emerging as solid contenders as well. Purdue has
been the most solid team in the conference for the past several
years. The Badgers have done a nice job under Dick Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, the Big Ten could be on its way to another
seven-berth NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   --Atlantic Coast Conference _ Duke is no surprise and North
Carolina has again showed it belongs in the Top 10. Maryland has
emerged as the most serious threat to the Blue Devils' quest for an
ACC title. Georgia Tech remains an enigma: capable of getting
destroyed by Kentucky, upsetting North Carolina, and getting
stunned by Hofstra.
</P>
<P>
   --Southeastern Conference _ Kentucky has been unpredicatable.
The Wildcats, like Georgia Tech, can beat anyone and lose to
anyone. Losing to Louisville was not a stunner, but a surprise
victory over Maryland was. It looks like it's going to be that way
around the league.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is a threat and so is Arkansas, but when it's showtime,
look for the Wildcats to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   --Big 12 _ Surprise, surprise, Kansas is not a mortal lock for
anything this season. The Jayhawks have proven they are very
beatable, even at historic Allen Field House. The problem is that
no one else has really emerged. Missouri and Oklahoma State could
step forward. But with the pressure off, the Jayhawks might
actually advance for more than a few rounds in the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   --Pacific-10 _ Stanford is still the solid choice. Washington
has been a disappointment. Arizona and UCLA remain darkhorse
threats and watch out for California, which knocked off North
Carolina earlier this week. Ben Braun has done a nice job of
bringing the Bears along after probation.
</P>
<P>
   -- Western Athletic Conference _ Utah, as coach Rick Majerus
noted, was ranked too high in preseason. New Mexico will be solid,
but the team we like is Texas Christian. Billy Tubbs's teams always
are entertaining and this year's version just might surprise some
players.
</P>
<P>
   --Atlantic 10 _ Total chaos. Take your pick. Rhode Island.
University of Massachusetts. Temple. Xavier. None has lived up to
expectations. Maybe with conference play order will be restored,
meaning Xavier and Temple will emerge as the front-runners. But
then again maybe it's one of those years. Can anyone say George
Washington?
</P>
<P>
   --Conference USA _ Cincinnati has stepped forward as one of the
elite teams in the country. Not a surprise. Not many people do a
better job of rebuilding and retooling than Bob Huggins. St.Louis
and Louisville have already pulled off huge upsets.
</P>
<P>
   --America East _ Delaware has been solid, but Hofstra, winner of
a watered-down Holiday Festival, has emerged. So has Maine. Boston
University and Northeastern have been up and down. Maine could be
the sleeper if Boston College transfer Andy Bedard continues to
play the way he has the first two months. After beating Georgia
Tech and Pennsylvania for the Holiday crown, Hofstra coach Jay
Wright said, ``It isn't the NCAA championship. But the Holiday
festival, to Hofstra is as big as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   --Ivy League _ Instead of Princeton, we have Penn. The Quakers
had some nice wins early in the season and nearly beat Kansas.
Princeton can't be taken lightly, as several teams have learned
this week in the Rainbow Classic. Harvard could play for a
runner-up position, which would be a solid accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   --Mid-America Conference _ Miami of Ohio is Top-20 caliber.
Toledo has already beaten Ohio State in getting off to its best
start in 32 years. Akron is off to its best start in a dozen
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lafayette has returned
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lafayette, under former Penn assistant Fran O'Hanlon, is off to
its best start since 1979-80 and has to be considered the favorite
to win the Patriot League. O'Hanlon has done a nice job of
rebuilding the Leopards from a 7-20 record three years ago to 19-9
last season . . . Tuesday night was college basketball's version of
the East Coast-West Coast challenge. Stanford beat Temple,
California beat North Carolina, Pepperdine beat Rhode Island, and
Portland State beat New Hampshire. Saving face for the Easterners
were Harvard, a winner over Santa Clara, and St. Joseph's, which
edged San Francisco . . . How bad is it getting for the Alantic 10?
This week Rhode Island lost to Pepperdine and UMass was beaten by
Davidson at home. It's getting so tough that when Dayton almost
beat Cincinnati it was cause for some relief. Near-wins now seem to
count for something . . . The hot games this weekend are Arizona
vs. UCLA and Duke vs. Maryland. The latter game is such a hot
ticket that some scalpers are asking _ and getting _ a $1,000 per
ticket. When Georgetown comes to UConn's Gampel Pavillion Saturday,
it will mark Hoya coach John Thompson's first visit ever to Storrs.
Which led long-time Big East watchers to remember when Syracuse
coach Jim Boeheim made his first visit to Gampel a few years ago.
After the Orangemen lost to the Huskies, Boeheim circled the
building's corridors in search of an exit, prompting him to mutter
to the writers: ``I never wanted to come into this place and now I
can't find my way out.'' Auburn is still unbeaten and off to its
best start in 30 seasons but the Tigers have yet to play a quality
oppoonent . . . Things are tough at Iona, which is 4-7 after losing
two game in the Holiday Festival. After a loss to Georgia Tech
Sunday, some Gael fans started a ``We want Tim Welsh'' chant,
begging the former Gael coach to return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
