A4585 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV03-BO     01-01 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV03-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BUMPY 20-YEAR ROAD, BUT WHAT A RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, January 03, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty years! One thousand forty Sundays. Not quite 1,040 Sunday
columns but a lot more than 1,040 cars. And a whole lot of Saturday
efforts, too. Not bad for a temporary assignment _ ``Try it for a
while and see how it works out'' is about how I remember the
authorizing words of then Sunday editor Tim Leland passing along
the decision of then Globe editor Tom Winship. Transportation
editor Abe Plotkin, who for years had written the centerpiece of
the Sunday Automotive section, was retiring, to be succeeded at the
typewriter by the middle-aged guy who edited the section.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years have flashed by as the temporary assignment gelled
into a career, hardened into the persona that is the Globe's auto
columnist. Twenty damn good years.
</P>
<P>
   There have been astounding changes in that two decades. The
technology of the automobile has changed radically, the players in
the world automotive game have changed just as dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, cars were basically rear-drive, big, made of steel,
and propelled by carbureted engines. Tires were bias ply, fuel
mileage was between 12 and 14 miles per gallon average, breaker
points were still the heart of most distributors _ and who ever
heard of a microprocessor under the hood?
</P>
<P>
   Today, cars are smaller, mostly front drive, contain a lot of
plastic parts and pieces, and the engines are fuel injected _
carburetors have gone the way of the buggy whip. Today, tires are
radial construction, fuel mileage is around 27 m.p.g., distributors
are passe _ what's a breaker point? _ and motors are micromanaged
by microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Chrysler Corp. was dying, American Motors was fading,
General Motors still dominated the market and was about to change
to front-drive cars on a wholesale basis, while Ford was resisting
front drive. The Volkswagen Beetle was the best-selling car of all
time and still going, but the Japanese were a growing market force.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Chrysler has survived, suffered another near-death
experience; AMC collapsed into the corporate bosom of Renault,
which regurgitated the remnants to Chrysler _ which is now merged
into DaimlerChrysler after having reinvented the car business by
inventing the front-drive minivan. General Motors cars are
virtually all front-drive, and the General has spawned a new
division, Saturn, while losing about half its market share. Ford is
the king of the hill, and the Japanese are still a force to be
reckoned with, but the Koreans are the price leaders. The old
Beetle is long gone, and a new Beetle is the darling of the youth
market.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, construction workers and farmers owned trucks, and a
sport/utility was a Jeep _ the sport/utility moniker hadn't been
invented yet.
</P>
<P>
   Today everybody owns a truck or a truck-based sport/utility _ or
so it seems.
</P>
<P>
   One thing remains the same: Back then, the electric car was
``just around the corner.'' Today, the electric car is ``just
around the corner'' _ and the corner is still moving.
</P>
<P>
   One thing changed that I had expected to remain constant: Volvo
still makes cars as solid as a brick but has ceased making cars
that look like a brick. It was enough of a shock for most Volvo
owners when that conservative Swedish automaker began making
front-drive automobiles _ and then all-wheel-drive automobiles. But
even with the new drivetrains and even with a certain softening
around the edges, the Volvos were still bricks. Rectangular,
angular, righteously angular in a world of jelly-bean cars.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the new S80 isn't a jelly bean, but it's no brick. There
it sat in the driveway, the only recognizably Volvo attribute its
distinctive grille with the diagonal slash proclaiming it a Volvo _
while the rest of the car sat there in rebuke, veritably screaming
out: ``The grille is lying.''
</P>
<P>
   It is stylish, this S80 sedan, graceful, un-Volvolike . . . but
wait. Once there was a stylish Volvo, the P1800, a gorgeous car
that came as notchback or squareback, a beautiful, graceful alien
automobile set down in a land of square, bechromed behemoths some
three decades _ or was it three aeons _ ago. Then, Volvo couldn't
give them away, forced reluctant employees to take them as company
cars. Now, they are collector cars, sought after, treasured _ but I
digress.
</P>
<P>
   The S80 is a beautiful car in the eyes of this beholder. It is
also a technical achievement; Volvo, which has been talking safety
for so long some people think Volvo invented it, has taken the S80
a step ahead in injury protection. The Volvo WHIP system turns a
passive headrest into an active preventer of whiplash injury for
front passengers in an S80, and the side curtain that deploys in a
collision is aboard to prevent head injury _ plus the usual front
air bags, antilock brakes, and traction control, a full package in
a front-drive car.
</P>
<P>
   The good looks compromise no interior room on the S80; the rear
seat offers plenty of legroom and lots of headroom, even with a
sunroof. Interior storage is a mixed bag. The glove box is nothing
to brag about, and the door bins aren't all that large _ but there
are four of them. A large covered bin between the front seats
offers two-stage storage, a top level suitable for envelopes, and a
deeper compartment that contains a coin holder and offers useful
room for larger objects _ a camera, for example. Seatback pockets
round out the storage package. The trunk is cavernous, although the
opening to the storage cave is a bit on the shallow side.
</P>
<P>
   Controls are generally neat, convenient, suitable for gloved
hands, but occasionally dip into needless complexity. Large buttons
on the radio, for example, testify to convenience, but one is
marked ``source'' and selects tape, CD, AM, or FM _ one twiddles
until one arrives where one wants to be. Heat/AC, on the other
hand, is a model of convenience and the dual controls do offer dual
zones and consistent temperatures. Radio controls are duplicated in
part on the steering wheel, and the cruise control is located
there, too.
</P>
<P>
   The tested model S80 is the base model, with normally aspirated
201-horserpower, 24-valve, 2.92-liter, 6-cylinder engine mated with
a 4-speed, automatic overdrive. A 268-h.p., tubocharged, 2.78-liter
engine is also available, but after driving the base engine, I'm
convinced you don't really need it (although I'm equally certain
it's even more fun to drive). The tested, normally aspirated combo
offered plenty of passing punch, very good acceleration; it is a
quiet, smooth mill that is very responsive, very satisfying. The
handling is typical modern Volvo, which is to say, precise, quick,
downright fun to drive. The ride is firm, the suspension soaked up
the washboard dirt roads very nicely. And the traction control came
into play now and then on ice and a wild evening of snow in the
north country.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel mileage is pretty good, too; over 945 miles charted, the
S80 delivered 22.8 miles per gallon. Price? That's the bad news;
this is a luxury sedan, base price $35,820 very well equipped, plus
$575 delivery. The tested model had a few options _ $450 cold
weather package (heated seats, headlight wiper/washer), $1,200
sunroof, and $1,595 worth of leather upholstery. The twin turbo
(T-6) S80 is $40,385 plus delivery. That's another big change in 20
years; somehow I find it hard to view $40,000 for this sort of car
as outrageous. The money's changed, actually; the dollar has fallen
in value vs. the commodities it prices.
</P>
<P>
   More changes are coming; Ford, owner and savior of Jaguar, is
courting Volvo. The other Swedish car maker, Saab, is already 50
percent owned by GM.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long bumpy road, these past 20 years _ and I
wouldn't want to have missed a single bump. Happy New Year. Bring
on the bumps!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
