<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV03-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE MORE, INTO THAT GRUNGY TUB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 03, 1999)   By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I saw in your column recently a formula to use to clean a
tub, which you said works wonders. Wouldn't you know it, I mislaid
the column and have to ask what that formula is.
</P>
<P>
   ANNA PETRILLO, Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. That is the story of the handyman's life, it seems, but here
it is, and I know it works because I used it years ago to clean a
``hopeless'' tub, and it has been pristine ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Wet the surface with hydrogen peroxide, then sprinkle a lot of
cream of tartar (a baking product, sold in supermarkets) on the wet
surface. Let it be for an hour or so, then scrub and rinse. This
will not restore the shine to the porcelain enamel; nothing will,
but the tub will be clean and bright.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm looking for inside storm windows made of glass. I do not
want acrylic or any other kind of plastic. Where can I get them?
</P>
<P>
   SHEILA CHERKAS, Chelsea, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are two outfits that I know of: Panel Air Corp. in
Brockton, Mass. (781-588-8900); and Innerglass of Simsbury, Conn.
(800-743-6207, 860-651-3951).
</P>
<P>
   Your preference for glass is well understood. In my opinion,
plastic does not stand up well either in place on the inside of a
window or in storage; it can scratch, discolor, and get foggy, and
does not clean well. Glass will stand up to anything except a hard
blow, will virtually never scratch, and will look sparkling and new
every time it is washed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Recently Debbie Onie of Brookline, Mass. called to ask about a
sporadic leak that was plaguing her condo; water was leaking from a
shower stall from a unit above her, but it happened only four or so
times a year.
</P>
<P>
   We replied that it could be a leaking shower pan, a leaking
drain, or something ``mysterious.'' The infrequency of the leak was
the confusing part of it all.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.G. of Littleton, Mass. called to tell us of her problem,
which was similar to Debbie's and equally sporadic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plumber put a block of wood 2 x 4 under the drain pipe
when he installed the shower pan to try to support it so it would
not move when when the shower was being used. As a result, the
shower pan moved but the drain did not, causing the leak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We broke through the ceiling, kicked out the 2 x 4, and it
never leaked again.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, M.A.G. Your solution is another one in the great and
mysterious realm of plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am covering the screens in my back porch with plywood for
the winter. Can I store wicker on the porch all winter long?
</P>
<P>
   ARTHUR, Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You sure can. The only place wicker should not be used or
stored is outdoors. It is porch furniture, not lawn furniture, and
should not be exposed to rain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have some old furniture that I want to clean up but not
restore or refinish. How can I clean it? Do you have any formulas
for cleaning and polishing? One of the pieces is an old wagon, with
big wheels with wooden spokes, designed to carry luggage at train
stations.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN MAY, Boxford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If some of the furniture is antique (that wagon sounds like
one, or at least a collectible), then they should not be refinished
or ``restored.'' Such treatment may reduce their value.
</P>
<P>
   To clean these items (varnished, shellacked, lacquered, stained,
painted, or left bare), wipe with a cloth wet with paint thinner.
Apply the paint thinner, let it sit on the finish for 30 seconds,
wipe moderately, then dry with a dry cloth.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of formulas for cleaning and polishing. Again
with antiques, be wary of applying anything but a cleaning agent
such as paint thinner. Is the handyman hipped on this subject?
Perhaps, but if I don't issue the warning, the antiques people will
get on me lik ugly on an ape.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the formulas: A polish: 1 1/3 pints olive oil,
2/3 pint alcohol, 1 teaspoon vinegar. Best results from more
rubbing with less polish.
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon turpentine, 3 tablespoons boiled linseed oil, 1
guart hot water. Keep hot in double boiler and rub with cloth wet
with solution; polish with dry cloth.
</P>
<P>
   4 oz. paint thinner, 4 oz. vinegar, 1 oz. alcohol, 4 oz. boiled
linseed oil. Apply with fine steel wool.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am building a house in Maine. A builder told me that OSB is
good for sheathing. Is it?
</P>
<P>
   MIKE DiGREGORIO, Wilmington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. OSB (oriented strand board) is good for sheathing, far better
than particleboard, which in my opinion shoud not be used for
sheathing anywhere. OSB has a rating very close to plywood of the
same the thickness, and has been used successfully in prefab
houses. Use 1/2-inch for walls, and 5/8-inch for roofs. For floors,
I suggest using plywood, whether you put down one layer or two.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
