<P>
   NYHAN-COLUMN (Undated) -- This final, fearful,
look-over-the-shoulder at the kind of year 1998 amounted to is
persuasive proof that Charles Dickens is always right (``best of
times ... worst of times''), that unprecedented prosperity in
economic terms can coincide with predictable mendacity and
persistent personal immorality, and that John Donne also hit the
proverbial nail on the figurative head: ``No man is an island ...
every man's death diminishes me.'' By David Nyhan.
</P>
