A4588 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV03     01-01 1474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV03-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE IS GOOD, BUT CHECK OUT MUTUAL FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 03, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am wondering whether my rented real estate is a good
investment for me. It is a two- family building which is taken care
of by property managers, and I am comfortable with the risks
involved -- possibilities of bad tenants, vacancies, and so forth.
It is in a good location and it is worth about $255,000 now. My
current cash flow from the property is $660 a month. If I keep the
property, I expect to see increases in both the rent and property
value, perhaps in the 1 percent to 5 percent annual range. I do not
pay taxes in the income from the property, because of depreciation.
The outstanding mortgage on the property is $113,000. I don't
expect much of a tax bite if I sell the property either now or
later. Is this a sound investment, or should I sell it and invest
in a mutual fund portfolio, from which I would expect annual
returns in the area of 7 1/5 percent after taxes?
</P>
<P>
   H.S., Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The way I'd approach the problem is this way: First add
together the expected annual income stream from the rental
property, plus the increase in your equity in the property which
you would achieve by making your mortgage payments. My guess is
that the resulting figure would be in the area of $15,000 -- $7,920
from rental income and the balance representing your increase in
equity. As you noted, that's far from a certainty; vacancies or
unexpected maintenance resulting from problem tenants could reduce
that figure, perhaps significantly. But on the other hand, if you
don't encounter those problems, you can expect the annual benefit
of owning the property to increase, through rental increases,
increases in the property value, and through a larger percentage of
your mortgage payments going against the principal in future years.
</P>
<P>
   Next let's consider the mutual fund alternative. If you were to
sell at this point, you would realize about $142,000. Depending on
your tax bracket, you would need to achieve pretax returns in the
area of 10 percent to 12 percent (and probably more) to deliver an
after-tax income stream of $10,650, representing your 7.5 percent
after-tax target. If you confine your view of mutual fund investing
to the last two or three years, that may seem like an easy target.
But we have been in a quite vigorous bull market, and you can't
expect the bully fund returns of the past three years (16.87
percent for the average domestic stock fund, according to
Morningstar Mutual Funds) to continue. In fact, you should expect
nothing much in excess of 10 percent average annual returns from a
stock fund portfolio, and that only over the long haul. In the
short haul, it seems to me reasonable to expect the returns of
funds to dip significantly, adjusting some of the excesses of the
recent past.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, if what you're looking for is an income stream, you
probably shouldn't be in stock funds in the first place. The yields
of stock funds are only token at this point, and if you combined a
$660 monthly sequence of withdrawals from a fund portfolio with
three or four years of poor market performance, you would see some
fairly significant depletion of your capital.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it seems to me that you understand the plusses and
minuses of real estate investment, and that your current situation
puts you in a better long-term position than you should
realistically expect from a mutual fund portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are in our mid-thirties and like many other
couples we did not begin thinking about retirement until recently.
At this point, we have $33,000 invested in IRAs, with $18,000 in
Fidelity Dividend Growth, $9,000 in Fidelity Equity Income II,
$3,000 in Janus Blue Chip Growth, and $3,000 in Janus fund. We
would like to retire in 20 years with at least $500,000 saved.
Would you diversify, and if so, how? How much should we save each
year to attain our goal?
</P>
<P>
   E.D., Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The answer you want is $4,652, or $387.73 a month. That
presumes you achieve average annual portfolio growth of 10 percent
over the 20 year period.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it also assumes that there is no inflation. So if the
question you meant to ask was how much would you need to save if
you wanted to have the equivalent of $500,000 in today's money at
the time you retire, the unfortunate answer is -- you probably
should double it.
</P>
<P>
   If inflation runs at 3 percent, you would need $903,055 in the
year 2019 to buy the same goods and services that $500,000 buys
today; if inflation were 4 percent, the unhappy figure would swell
to $1,095,561. At the 3.5 percent midpoint, the number comes out at
$994,894, which is where I got my suggestion of doubling that
$387-a-month figure.
</P>
<P>
   The attractive thing about the first answer is that you would be
able to achieve savings at the $387 monthly level entirely within
the limit of IRAs -- preferably Roth IRAs. But if you're going try
to go significantly beyond that level, you'll bump into the
$2,000-a-year- per-person maximum for IRAs, and you will have to
cast about for additional tax-deferred savings vehicles. The first
place is to look is with to your employers, who may have 401(k)
plans or similar tax-deferred savings vehicles. If such are not
available, ask for literature from the fund families that you are
now using about their variable annuity plans; these are retirement
savings vehicles that operate largely as mutual funds, but which
also carry a small element of insurance. The effect of the
insurance is two-fold -- it tends to cut the returns from these
investments by about 1/2 of 1 percent when compared to similar
mutual fund accounts, and second, the insurance is adequate to
allow the accounts to build on a tax-deferred basis. From my point
of view, the small reduction in investment performance is more than
worth the tax deferral. When you withdraw money in retirement, the
portion of the investment which represents portfolio growth will be
taxable, much as a withdrawal of funds from an IRA is; the amount
of the withdrawal representing your initial investment is not
taxable.
</P>
<P>
   As for your portfolio -- yes, I think it needs some work.
Although you are using four different funds, since all of them
concentrate their portfolios upon large-cap stocks, you haven't
achieved any significant level of diversification. I think over
time that what you'll see is that the four funds will tend to move
more or less in lockstep, reflecting the fact that they are all
drawing upon the same market sector for their investments.
</P>
<P>
   What you need is to move beyond the large-cap stocks entirely.
Yes, they've been golden in the past few years, but eventually the
other sectors will have their day, and while you want to retain
dominant positions in the large cap, you need exposure to other
parts of the market as well.
</P>
<P>
   You could treat any one or two of the funds you're now using as
your core holdings, but they should be limited to 50 percent or 60
percent of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to hold 50 percent of your retirement
savings in the core holdings, and then add positions representing
12 1/2 percent of then portfolio in these four sectors: mid-cap
stocks, small-cap stocks, international stocks, and a health care
sector fund. Staying within the fund families you are now using, my
choices would be Fidelity Mid-Cap Value, Janus Venture (a small-cap
fund), T. Rowe Price International Stock, and Fidelity Select
Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you discuss matters on the phone, or just supply the
answers that appear in the newspaper?
</P>
<P>
   J.E., Harwich, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I guess the first column of the new year is a good time to go
back over some of the basics, which seem to frustrate a number of
correspondents from time to time. The only advice I supply is that
which appears in the newspaper. I do not supply individual advice
to individuals who do not want their letters published, nor do I
supply answers to people whose letters are not selected for
publication. (Yes, it's fun, but it's also a lot of work.) In
addition, since I am a journalist and not a financial advisor, I
cannot advise individuals on a fee basis. Finally, I recognize the
frustration of many of my correspondents whose questions do not
appear in the paper; the number of letters received is many times
the number which can be answered in the paper. I seek to select
questions that are representative of many correspondents, although
sometimes questions which are simply too intriguing to bypass are
selected as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address, and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
