<HEADER>
A4589 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     01-01 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1998 IPOS: OFF TO A GOOD START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of them as a very small graduating class that turned out
to do suprisingly well in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about Massachusetts companies that took the plunge
and went public in 1998. There were only 19 local initial public
stock offerings, in line with the previous year's meager production
and far behind the IPO glory days of 1995-1996.
</P>
<P>
   But most of them made money for investors and only one turned
out to be a disaster. Technology companies and small banks
dominated the list, which also included a home electronics
retailer, a brokerage, consultants and a dental practice management
company.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an easy year for small stocks to gain much ground.
Most of them were hammered over the summer and only began to stage
a comeback in October.
</P>
<P>
   That pattern virtually killed the IPO market through the summer
and into the fall. Nationwide, IPOs only started reappearing in the
last months of 1998, when Internet stocks soared and sparked a
demand for any investment connected to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks like Earthweb and theglobe.com just revitalized the
market,'' said David Menlow, editor of the IPO Financial Reporter,
which tracks new offerings.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one, small Massachusetts IPO that tried to take
advantage of the Internet stock mania, with modest success. A $13
million IPO by Artifical Life Inc. of Cambridge, a small Internet
software company, hit the market in December with an offering price
of 8 1/2, soared to 23 1/2 in its first day of trading and has
since settled back to 13 3/4. That still represents a gain of 59.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   That was hardly the experience of the state's most successful
IPO of 1998. Mercury Computer Systems Inc. hit the market with a
weak start in January, to eventually become the state's most
successful IPO of 1998. But Mercury, which makes high-performance
computer systems, suffered its ups and downs along the way, like
most other small stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury shares, which hit a record high of 28 1/8 Thursday,
gained 167.9 percent for the year. Exchange Applications Inc. of
Boston, which makes software to analyze marketing databases, was
second with a gain of 78.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tweeter Home Entertainment Group Inc. of Canton, the audio and
video retailer, was the best-performing, non-technology stock. It
advanced 69.1 percent during 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the smaller banks that went public during the year saw
their stocks appreciate within a narrow band, from the teens to low
20 percent range.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury may have ended 1998 with the best performance of the
group, but the IPO nearly failed to get off the ground in January.
</P>
<P>
   A weak market for new issues at the time lowered the offering
price for Mercury shares below its estimated range of $11 to $13
per share. Underwriters made an offer of $10.50 and Mercury's board
thought it over hard before accepting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very bad month,'' recalled chief executive Jay
Bertelli. ``We had put so much energy into (the offering) we
decided that even though we may be leaving some money on the table,
it wasn't worth going back and doing this again some months
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercury was no young startup burning through cash. The company
had been operating for 15 years and turned profits through its last
eight.
</P>
<P>
   Executives had decided to go public to give Mercury a higher
profile and to create a stock-swap option if it decided to buy
other, smaller companies. They also wanted to give long-time
financial backers, including Memorial Drive Trust and MassMutual
Life Insurance Co., a financial exit strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury specializes in the design of high-performance computer
systems that process digital signals and transform data from
sensors. Its products are being used to upgrade submarine sonar
systems and are being built into some aircraft radar equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury is the rare technology company that still counts on
defense work for the lion's share of its revenue. Defense peaked in
recent years at about 80 percent of revenues, but has been giving
way to medical and other businesses since.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials anticipate medical revenues will grow faster
in the next few years on the strength of new products like digital
X-ray equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelli thinks Mercury will have a strong second act for
shareholders in 1999. Besides specific new products, the company is
preparing to market a new generation of existing products in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are bigger, faster and better products at approximately
the same price points. Typically whenever we come out with a new
product line it stimulates more activity for us,'' says Bertelli.
</P>
<P>
   So what does happen to IPOs after they've been public for two
years? The answer, based on Massachusetts companies that went
public in 1997, often isn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of 1998, nine of 18 companies we tracked were trading
lower than their IPO price, and the other half were valued higher.
But many of the stocks that lost ground were investment horror
stories. Three lost at least 95 percent of their value and eight of
the nine losers were down at least 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among the two-year winners from 1997, the big winner was Concord
Communications Inc. of Marlborough, up 305 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre (929-2918) can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
