<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLETRON-CHANGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWAGGER GONE, CABLETRON SETS FORTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.H. _ It was once known as a ``wild, wild West
company,'' with unusually aggressive sales tactics that helped it
climb to the top tier of computer-networking companies.
</P>
<P>
   But now the gunslinging swagger is gone from Cabletron Systems
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Net losses in three of the last four quarters, along with a host
of product transition issues, personnel changes, disappointments
internationally, and delays entering new markets, have raised
questions about the number three computer-networking firm's
long-term future as an independent company.
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron's two biggest rivals, Cisco Systems Inc. and Nortel's
Bay Networks unit, are seeking to provide corporate customers with
one-stop shopping for all their voice- and data-networking needs.
Cabletron has taken a narrower approach, with a product line
focused heavily on the data side.
</P>
<P>
   The narrower focus raises questions about whether the company,
based in Rochester, N.H., will be swept up in consolidation of the
computer-networking industry, and become part of a bigger, broader
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The networking industry is going through a sea change, a rapid
transformation, and Cabletron could be an attractive candidate to a
major player,'' said William R. Becklean, managing director at the
securities firm of Tucker Anthony Co., who predicts that Cabletron
will be snapped up within five years.
</P>
<P>
   With a reputation for well-designed, well-built products and
fierce customer loyalty, Cabletron has long been seen as a
``Mercedes-Benz of the computer-networking business,'' said
Becklean.
</P>
<P>
   But even that reputation may not protect it from takeover, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with $400 million in cash, no debt, and a stock price in
the $8 range _ down sharply from $24 a share 13 months ago _
Cabletron could be an especially tempting takeover target. It
closed at 8 3/8 Thursday, down 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   But Craig Benson, the company's cofounder and chief executive,
maintains that the 15-year-old firm is not for sale. Benson insists
that recent problems in moving from an old to a new product line
are behind the company now and that Cabletron will rebound this
year.
</P>
<P>
   He also points to a major new contract to supply Compaq Computer
Corp. with computer-networking products. Last year, Cabletron
acquired Digital Equipment Corp.'s networking business, with
expectations that Digital would purchase a sizable portion of the
networking unit's output.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after the deal was signed, however, Compaq acquired
Digital, and the division's sales slowed to a trickle. Cabletron's
Compaq deal, Benson maintains, holds more promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked through the hard parts of turning the company
around in the past 2 1/2 years,'' says Benson. ``I think Wall
Street senses that we can succeed and be different from our
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   His optimism is based, in part, on the firm's recent acquisition
of Yago Systems Inc., a small Sunnyvale, Calif., developer of
high-speed switching equipment for computer networks. Yago products
are the cornerstone of Cabletron's attempted comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron also is banking on a payoff from its acquisition of
NetVantage, a developer of low-cost switches for small-firm
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can provide customers more fully developed high-speed
switching systems than our competitors,'' said Plyush Patel, Yago
cofounder and senior vice president of Cabletron's West Coast
division, which employs 100 members of the company's 6,200-person
work force.
</P>
<P>
   With Patel, Benson has brought in new management in the past
year to improve marketing and sales. Cabletron also has spent $40
million for internal computer and software systems, as well as
staffing to handle the company's far-flung operations.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes are the legacy of Donald Reed, the former NYNEX
Corp. executive whom Benson recruited to Cabletron with much
fanfare in August 1997. Reed joined as Cabletron president and
chief executive, with the goal of moving the company in a new
direction, selling products to phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed, whose NYNEX career was mostly in regulatory and public
affairs rather than in technology, had a difficult transition in
the fast-moving world of computer networking. He resigned after
seven months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don Reed gave us the systems and strategies that we lacked,''
said Benson, who remained chairman during Reed's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Also gone from Cabletron is its other cofounder, the colorful,
hard-driving Robert Levine, who was the company's chief salesman.
Levine, who was known for his body-building regimen, right-wing
politics, and a survivalist mentality, retired when Reed joined the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Under Benson and Levine, who formed the company in Levine's
Ashland garage, Cabletron had prospered for more than 10 years. It
earned a reputation as a creative computer-networking company that
built a strong relationship with customers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of its aggressive image came from Levine, whose antics
included crashing his tank into a tree and brandishing a hunting
knife at Cabletron sales meetings to pump staffers up about killing
the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders say such eccentricities are long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we were once known as the `wild, wild West company,' ''
Benson said with a shrug, ``but it's an image that no longer
exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, a more buttoned-down Cabletron is trying to carve out a
more limited role for itself as a provider of data-networking
equipment for corporations.
</P>
<P>
   That's in sharp contrast to Cisco and Bay Networks, which want
to sell to both telephone carriers and corporations a one-stop
communications and networking solution for voice, data, and video.
By offering an array of products and services from a single
supplier, Cisco and Bay Networks hope to retain customers who are
finding the complexities of telecommunications too difficult to
manage on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron early on bucked the trend of its West Coast
competitors, who bought their way into new markets. Instead, it
stuck to its engineering strength and developed nearly everything
internally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabletron repeatedly failed to look at how markets were
changing and react to them,'' said Glenn Gabriel Ben-Yosef,
president of Clear Thinking Research Inc., a telecom consulting
firm. ``Their competitors changed and adapted much faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Competitors like Cisco, Bay Networks, and 3Com Corp. spent
heavily to acquire young companies that could develop a new
generation of networking products faster than the big companies
could design them internally.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Cabletron is now far behind in the second tier of
computer-networking companies, with annual revenues that have been
stuck between $1 billion and $1.5 billion for more than three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Benson acknowledged the industry changes, but stressed that
Cabletron will not follow them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there are plenty of opportunities in the
data-networking side, and there are significant numbers of
customers who don't want to get locked into a single supplier,''
said Benson. ``Our challenge is to deliver in 1999 what we have
been preparing for in the past two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Wall Street analysts are optimistic about Cabletron's
more focused strategy. ``Cabletron can turn around, but it will
take a lot of time to rebuid the momentum, so right now it is still
too early to call them out,'' says Timothy Luke, telecommunications
analyst for Lehman Bros.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
