u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      01-01 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAMES FANNED BY FIRING STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ A story about the possible ouster of
Patriots coach Pete Carroll was strategically placed in the media
this week. The story is true. Carroll does face a realistic
possibility of not returning next season, according to sources, if
he loses badly to Jacksonville in Sunday's wild-card game or there
are signs of more chaos and unrest on the team.
</P>
<P>
   While it was evident that Carroll has a great deal of support
among the majority of his players, he may not have it among a few
veterans who have owner Robert Kraft's ear.
</P>
<P>
   Such players have spoken this week in anonymity about a lack of
organization, game plans that don't exploit the players' talents
against the other teams' weaknesses, and the fact that too many
younger players on the roster have not been able to adequately fill
in for injured players.
</P>
<P>
   That last complaint may point more toward Bobby Grier than
Carroll, as it is Grier who has been ``shopping for the groceries''
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Those who speak favorably about the coach talk of his hard work,
motivational skills, and great knowledge of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Others say he's a work in progress who will only get better if
he gets the time and backing of ownership, and that he has had to
deal with many injuries to key players this season.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has not addressed the comments about his future, as he
prepares for a playoff game under some pretty tough conditions: (1)
Both Drew Bledsoe and Terry Glenn are missing from his offense; and
(2) he's coming off the sin of all sins, losing to Bill Parcells
and the Jets in a terrible way.
</P>
<P>
   An upset Kraft went right to the coach's office following the
Jets game, then disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, a report surfaced in the Herald's Inside Track
column saying that Carroll's job was in jeopardy and that there
already was a short list of candidates being considered as a
replacement. Atop that list was Bill Belichick, the Jets' assistant
head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick is Parcells's heir apparent in New York _ and that is
in writing. That doesn't mean Kraft couldn't lure him away with a
huge offer, but it seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick's hiring would appease some of New England's veteran
defensive players who feel he is the best defensive mind in the
game and someone they respect. But it seems unlikely that Belichick
would leave the Jets and come back to New England, even though he
and Kraft always seemed to get along.
</P>
<P>
   A more realistic candidate is Chris Palmer, the offensive
coordinator of the Jaguars and Drew Bledsoe's former quarterback
coach here. Palmer would be familiar with most of the Patriots'
offensive personnel.
</P>
<P>
   If Kraft does make a change, he would have some serious
perception problems. Many would criticize him for firing a coach
who made the playoffs two years in a row. He would be called by
some a knee-jerk, meddling owner, and that could hurt his chances
of attracting top coaching candidates in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move also would run counter to the philosophy Kraft
espoused when he chose to let Parcells leave. He hired a man with
one year of head coaching experience and asked him to get into the
playoffs and be successful, and to do it by developing younger
players.
</P>
<P>
   Firing Carroll would invite charges of being impatient and
succumbing to the pressure of some fans and media. Kraft may be
accused of firing Carroll only because he couldn't beat Parcells.
While it's true that the Patriots face the Jets twice a year, the
reality is that Parcells won't be coaching forever. In fact,
stories already are surfacing that he would call it quits and let
Belichick take over if the Jets get to the Super Bowl this year.
</P>
<P>
   A firing would invite all of that criticism, in addition to the
heat Kraft already is taking for the Hartford move.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Belichick was hugely unpopular in Cleveland as a
head coach, a big target of fan abuse. He also has a poor track
record of handling the media, which has to be taken into
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it makes more sense to think that if Kraft were to
replace Carroll, he would try to get an established, big name coach
like a George Seifert (who wouldn't take the job because he's a
friend of Carroll's).
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Carroll may have to change some of his
coaching staff _ again. One would think that Ernie Zampese would be
allowed to continue to work with the offense so Bledsoe won't have
to adjust to another coordinator. But Carroll may have to look at
some of his positional coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll may indeed save himself Sunday because he has a team
that seems to flourish in times of adversity. There aren't enough
detractors in the locker room to make the team quit on him in a big
game; but there are enough supporters who want him to be the coach
next year and beyond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
