<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLS' DEFENSE NEVER RESTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Leave it up to Florida State coach Bobby Bowden
to best describe the job that the University of Tennessee's defense
has done this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like . . . cockroaches,'' said Bowden at Thursday's
Fiesta Bowl media day, an event which brought preparations for
Monday's national championship game betwen the No. 1 ranked
Volunteers and No. 2 Seminoles into its final stages. ``They don't
eat things. But they sure do mess things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Mess things up? Indeed they do. Tennessee coach Phil Fulmer says
his defensive unit, like the rest of the team, is a blue collar
unit, one devoid of big egos and big stars for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Tennessee defense that came up with big plays in the
Vols' 220-17 overtime win over Florida in September, a victory that
jump started the Vols towards the SEC East title and subsuequently
to the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Tennessee defense which completely shut down Georgia
when it looked like the Dawgs' were growling about being a player
in the SEC East race.
</P>
<P>
   All of this came as surprise to lots of people outside the
Tennessee family.
</P>
<P>
   Who could blame them when you looked at a defensive line in
which three players, Shaun Ellis, Billy Ratliff and Ron Green, all
who were coming off career-threatening injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Or when you saw a secondary that had to replace three starters
from last year's team.
</P>
<P>
   Or when the leader of the defense was a linebacker, Al Wilson,
who didn't know from play to play, much less game to game if he
could perform at anything close to the All America level he had
shown in previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   And who could blame those skeptics since a recurring shoulder
injury has forced the 6-0, 226 pound senior linebacker to miss
three games this season and come in and out of most of the other
games he has played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody on the team has respect for him because he plays the
game the way it should be played,'' said linebacker Eric
Westmoreland, part of a linebacking corp that has gotten
progressively better since the opening game of the season, a 34-33
shootout victory over Syracuse, including not allowing a touchdown
in the last two games. ``When he comes on the field everyone knows
he's on the field. He's so intense. And that brings out the
inteneseness on the whole defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson says he likes the fact that the Vols, despite being
unbeaten and ranked No. 1 are underdogs to Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been underdogs all year,'' he says. ``That's kind of the
motto for this team. Tennessee's not going to get the job done;
they're not a good football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one more challenge to us, to prove to everybody that
we can be one of the elite teams in college football.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is not afraid to take a role that is somewhere between
captain and coach. ``My personsality is to be a leader and at the
same time the leadershp role was given to me (captain),'' he said.
``I try to set an example for the young guys down the road, when
it's their turn to be leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who was an amateur boxer growing up in Jackson,
Mississippi, says that his boxing career forged his personality.
``I think the aggressiveness was there,'' he said, ``but boxing
really brought it out a little more. Being in teh ring and being
able to fight really helped out a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson knew coming into the season the Vols would have to fill
some holes, pick up the pace on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Now he and the Vols are one game away from a goal that was only
a dream back in August and a dream that even the Vols didn't think
was really possible of being fulfilled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
