<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLER DERBY GETS NEW WHEELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the day, before professional football, basketball,
baseball, and hockey dominated televised sports, there was Roller
Derby, one of those loosely defined activities that blended
entertainment with athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   It started in 1935, and exploded in the '40s, becoming the
highest-rated programming on television in 1950. By 1963, Roller
Derby was shown on more than 100 stations across the country, and
in San Francisco, the Bay Area Bombers were second only to the San
Francisco Giants at the box office. Seven years later, with stars
nicknamed Toughie and Thumper, Roller Derby attracted a record
crowd of 19,500 at Madison Square Garden; later that summer, that
was broken when more than 28,000 fans came to the Oakland Coliseum.
By then, 15 million viewers were tuning in every week to watch what
amounted to pro wrestling on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   It was fun, often scripted, and filled with the bluster now
considered normal in professional sports. The attendance figures
and ratings numbers don't sound like much compared with today's
standards, but Roller Derby earned a solid place in sports lore.
People such as Joanie Weston, The Blonde Amazon, and Ralph
Valladeres, the Guatemalan speedster, made the game personable,
much the way Hulk Hogan and Jesse Ventura did for pro wrestling.
But Roller Derby ended in 1973, a lack of money and dwindling fan
interest prompting founder Leo Seltzer to pull the plug.
</P>
<P>
   But it's back now, armed with a multimillion-dollar cable
television contract with The Nashville Network. The debut is set
for Jan. 15. The game will basically be the same, just faster, with
in-line skates replacing the old four-wheelers. Seltzer's son Jerry
is commissioner of the newly named RollerJam, and he is ecstatic
about the return of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be able to survive just with nostalgia,''
Seltzer said. ``We just want a small piece of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Roller Derby is clearly alternative sports programming but has
the potential to capture X Games fans, largely because the athletes
understand the value of braggadoccio and buffed bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bone-jarring, in-your-face, muscle-in-motion excitement,''
reads a RollerJam news release. ``Where winning is survival.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   The league will have six teams. Eighty men and women (Roller
Derby was the first equal opportunity sport) trained for six months
down in Florida, eight hours a day, and learned about whips, jams,
and blocks. The object is for a ``jammer'' to lap the four-person
pack. Basically, everything is legal, including elbows to the head,
hair-pulling, and all-out assault. Violence, well, let's just say
it looks damn real.
</P>
<P>
   Several American Gladiators are in the mix, as well as former
dancer sometimes employed by Madonna. Sean Atkinson, a.k.a. Atk
Attack and a former Golden Gloves light heavyweight champion, will
skate for the California Quakes. Executive producer Stephen Land
told Sports Illustrated that Atkinson was ``frighteningly
violent.''
</P>
<P>
   Pasi Schalin, who once played for the NHL's Edmonton Oilers,
will skate for the Florida Sundogs. His wife, Susanne, is also on
the team. She is a model. Another Sundog, David Gletty, a.k.a.
Gator, is a tree surgeon, mountain climber, and alligator wrestler.
The New York Enforcers have Tim Washington, a.k.a. Titan, a cousin
of Marvin Hagler. Teammate Brain Gamble holds two black belts, and
Jannet Abraham is one of the female stars. She is an ordained
minister, thus her nickname, ``Minister of Pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Seltzer said the uninitiated will be a little confused because
Roller Derby doesn't have a ball or a puck to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams can score and be scored upon at the same time,''
Seltzer said. ``It resembles a mad scramble.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's a good thing in today's age of sports entertainment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
