<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV03-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEST OF TIMES . . . WORST OF TIMES' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 03, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This final, fearful, look-over-the-shoulder at the kind of year
1998 amounted to is persuasive proof that Charles Dickens is still
always right (``best of times . . . worst of times''), that
unprecedented prosperity in economic terms can coincide with
predictable mendacity and persistent personal immorality, and that
John Donne also hit the proverbial nail on the figurative head:
``No man is an island . . . every man's death diminishes me.''
</P>
<P>
   That goes for every man's and woman's hunger, despair,
homelessness, and uninsured childhood illness, if I may extrapolate
on behalf of Brother Donne. Lamentations on behalf of the departed,
and sonorous bromides upon the inevitabilities of life and death
abound this time of year, and I will do my part. But it's
ever-more-difficult to remain unconvinced that it is human nature
to turn a tin ear to the bleats of the impoverished. There is a
media-magnified surfeit of heartstring-tugging photos, direct
mailers, TV spots, and Net gigabytes in honor of the poor, the
downtrodden, the left-behind.
</P>
<P>
   So I'll try something different this year: My glance back at '98
will come through a cursory review of the lives, and inevitable
deaths, of some of the luckiest folk on earth: i.e., those that
went to Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   The January-February issue of Harvard magazine fell my way, and
it was more than morbid curiosity that took me through the graceful
and understated obituaries edited by Deborah Smullyan '72,
identified as are all members of their
Harvard-Radcliffe-graduate-school cohort by year of graduation.
</P>
<P>
   From Donald Chisholm Hagar '22, the deceased president of Rapid
Service Press of Boston, to Edward Teed Wilcox '49, a longtime
Harvard administrator who'd been shot down from his B-24 in 1944
and smuggled US prisoners out of Germany through Switzerland to
France, Smullyan summarizes in one pithy paragraph what one can
summarize out of a person's life.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard obits recount the successes of individuals who were,
mostly, smart and lucky, in the sense that their education and
accomplishments gave them the sort of lives most Americans would
envy from the outside. One gent took and passed the Maryland bar
exam at age 75, apparently just for the hell of it; he didn't seem
to need the money. One had been named head of the New York state
commission on horseracing by Nelson Rockefeller, which conjures up
the image of endless summer afternoons at the track, and mint
juleps at Churchill Downs in the company of stylish women.
</P>
<P>
   One Oklahoma banker had written jokes for The Harvard Lampoon,
and wound up winning a Planned Parenthood award. Two women were
stout opponents of abortion. There were surgeons, bankers, lawyers,
diplomats, and academics. Many loved nature, and put in a lot of
time or money rescuing the environment that obviously nourished and
sustained their spirits.
</P>
<P>
   One had been a Naval aviator in his 20s who still flew at 81.
John Henry Cutler '32, who got his PhD in '36, in the pit of the
Depression, was editor of The Duxbury Clipper. He wrote two books
about editing a weekly (``Put It on the Front Page, Please!'' and
``Cancel My Subscription, Please!''), which sentiments I can relate
to. He was also ghostwriter for James Michael Curley's
autobiography, ``I'd Do It Again,'' a title that sums up my views
on newspapering for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Joseph Halle Jr. '32 wrote 23 books. Ruth Glover Monsees
'33 ran the Girl Scouts in Portland, Maine, and was a licensed ham
radio operator. One man had been with the Seabees on Guadalcanal;
another, of Turkish extraction, analyzed aerial photos during that
war. Miriam Littlefield Brooks '36 was a 60-year member of the
Weston-Wayland Shakespeare Club. Former US Senator Floyd Haskell
'37 left the GOP over Nixon's invasion of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of these people were active on boards, committees, and
civic enterprises. You'll recognize Cleveland Amory '39, the
animal-rights activist. John P. Nevins '39, who died in Vermont,
led a motorized artillery unit from the Normandy beaches into the
heart of France. Dr. Parker Wheat '39 was the fourth generation of
his family to practice medicine in Manchester, N.H., and served in
both World War II and Korea. One member of the Class of '40 died on
vacation in Paris; there are not many better ways to go.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Whitmore Woodward '40 won the Silver and Bronze stars,
the Distinguished Service Cross for heroism at Omaha Beach on
D-Day, and the Croix de Guerre; this lifelong resident of Rockland
did his bit and more. One doctor advised President Kennedy on
mental retardation. Another discovered how bovine cartilage could
help cancer patients. Frederic Cole Talbot '43 of Weston flew more
than 50 dive-bomber missions off the USS Essex during the war and
won the Navy Cross for helping sink a Japanese battleship in Leyte
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Eaton Pentlarge '45 was a wartime welder at Bath Iron
Works, bore four children, and later co-founded Parents and Friends
of Lesbians and Gays in Maine. Basil M. Carlos Mavroleon '82, a
onetime Wall Street trader who chucked finance for journalism and
joined Afghan mujahideen in attacking Russian convoys, ``was found
dead in his hotel room in Peshawar, Pakistan, on Aug. 27,'' where
he was on assignment for CBS's ``60 Minutes'' for a piece on
terrorist Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Basil was unlucky. The luckiest chronicled in this batch?
Perhaps Thomas Anderson Fennell Jr. '48, ``an internationally known
orchid grower,'' who, after his Orchid Jungle in Florida was
clobbered by Hurricane Andrew, won $6.7 million in the Florida
state lottery and closed the business.
</P>
<P>
   Amen to Mr. Fennell, and to all the other Harvardians. In the
long run, we're all dead, no matter how smart, accomplished, or
lucky. Maybe God's a Yale man after all. Happy New Year.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
