<HEADER>
A4604 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV03-B     01-01 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV03-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1999: C'EST FACILE! 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 03, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Markets for the euro will open Monday for the first time. Eleven
currencies now locked into fixed exchange rates, trading as one,
against the dollar mainly. How these two currencies will fare
against one another is, for the moment, anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists think the new European Central Bank will keep
interest rates high to fight inflation and attract funds while
European finance ministries ease taxes to promote growth. Does that
sound familiar? It's the same recipe of tight money and easy fiscal
policy that sent the dollar soaring during Ronald Reagan's first
term.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Starting Monday morning, markets will do the
reconciling. It is all bookkeeping for now; new coins and banknotes
are still three years away. Meanwhile, comic books are promoting
the new currency to European consumers under the slogan ``C'est
facile'' _ it's easy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen new Internet companies have registered offerings with
the Securities and Exchange Commission, according to Securities
Data Co. These initial public offerings are likely to go forward
during January and February, so long as listed shares like
Amazon.com, America Online, and Yahoo! stay high.
</P>
<P>
   What's keeping the Internet stocks at their stratospheric
levels? Perhaps you noticed that Charles Schwab's market value last
week surpassed that of Merrill Lynch. At around $25 billion, the
biggest on-line brokerage firm was worth slightly more than the
biggest brokerage on Wall Street _ at least briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Who are the customers in this new be-your-own-broker world? My
newsroom friend Frank Hertz offers the following anecdote: ``I was
listening to the radio and scanning the wires when the business
report came on the radio:
</P>
<P>
   ``Skymail stock going berserk. . .opened up 10 points. . .now up
to 14 and rising (Buy it, Frank!). . .up now 18 points (It's only
9:45 _ BUY IT, FRANK!!!). . . it was rock-bottom at 2 in October. .
. (Okay I'll log on to Schwab and buy it). . .now it's at 32. .
.Ahhhhh
</P>
<P>
   ``So I log on. It's at 28. I put in an order at 29. By the time
I click my mouse, it's at 31. I say screw it, put in a market order
instead. By the time I click my mouse again, I've bought it at
$34.75.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock rose almost 25 percent in three minutes, but here's
the clincher -- I was still glad I bought it at that price! The
rush of it all. I felt like I was doubling-down in Vegas _ nothing
was going to stop me. I wanted it to go up to $50 and then I'd
sell.''
</P>
<P>
   The price reached $48, Hertz reported. Two days later Skymail
had dropped to $20. Next week? He may yet be rich.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those following the breathless press coverage of how Hughes
Electronics and Loral Corp. aided China's satellite launching
agency after it blew to bits one of Loral's expensive satellites _
and several dozen people _ rejoiced last week when The Washington
Post put the story of Vector Microwave Research on its front page.
</P>
<P>
   The incredible story of the black-budget firm _ founded in 1984
by Donald Mayes _ may not resolve the issue of whether Loral
committed treason when it gave the Chinese guidance technology that
could just as easily enable them to take out New Delhi with a
ballistic missile as hoist another communication satellite into
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the story illuminated just how bizarre, complex,
and widespread is the international market for advanced weapons
technology. Vector is one of a few specialists in ``foreign
materiel acquisition'' _ meaning the delivery to the Pentagon by
hook or by crook of the latest Russian, Chinese, and North Korean
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that technology often flows both ways, and Vector
has been under investigation since last year for a variety of
practices, including the possibility that it traded to the Chinese
the technical specifications for US Stinger missiles for some
Chinese missiles it wanted. Stingers are hand-held rockets very
useful for bringing down planes _ including, potentially,
commercial jet-liners.
</P>
<P>
   The theft of US high-tech military secrets over a 20-year period
also was the subject of a mostly secret report last week by a
select committee of the House of Representatives. Another flourish
of anti-Clinton rhetoric designed to pave the way to try the
president for treason? Or a dispassionate survey of security
problems?
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some harm in some of the (Loral) transfers of
technology that occurred,'' Rep. Norm Dicks of Washington, the
ranking Democrat on the committee, told a press conference, ``But
it's also fair to say that this is not the only problem we
uncovered.'' His counterpart Christopher Cox (R-Calif) concurred:
``We were rapidly led to considerably more serious national
security problems than the Hughes-Loral cases.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Y2K problem turns out to be no problem at all for the
world's biggest corporations, you can thank the Germans. The giant
software firm SAP AG has skyrocketed to global prominence by
selling complicated software programs to corporations designed to
link their manufacturing, purchasing, finance, and payroll
functions. Now SAP is even advertising on National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Its vast system known as R/3 amounts to a whole new layer of
extremely robust code on top of whatever older bug-prone systems
these companies still have in place. As one hard-working
bug-spotter put it, for much of the manufacturing world, SAP is the
solution to the millennium bomb _ and the chief beneficiary of it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So 1999 dawns rich in possibilities. Even the impeachment crisis
seems headed for a swift resolution. There are many theories about
what caused it _ a great religious re-awakening; the reversion to a
form of Dixie; neo-conservatives of whom it has been said they
``wouldn't take yes for an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   However much they might disagree on the means to achieve it,
however, there was one goal for 1999 upon which all Americans could
agree: that there should be better men and better women. Happy new
year!
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
