<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEER HUNTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it works, don't fix it'' is a common business axiom that's
been modified by the software industry: ``If it works, make a lot
more of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a personal-computer game called Deer Hunter became a
smash hit. And an unlikely one at that.
</P>
<P>
   WizardWorks, the publisher, didn't flood the media with press
releases and demo copies. It's appeal seemed to be a limited
audience.
</P>
<P>
   And hunters couldn't do much. They basically waited in one spot,
looking through binoculars at graphics that were ho-hum.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other games, Deer Hunter was not universally available.
For months, its only distribution point was Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, sales took off, and by the spring of 1998, Deer Hunter
was at the top of the sales charts. (A demo of the game can be
downloaded from:
www.pcgameworld.com/gamedemos/d/deerhunter/index.htm. That last
period is the end of a sentence, so don't include it on the Web
address. Be aware the demo file is about 7 megabytes and takes a
long time to download, even with a fast connection.)
</P>
<P>
   Or if you'd rather spend the money to get the program instead of
the time, it should be available for less than the $20 price when
it was popular.
</P>
<P>
   The price is also lower because Deer Hunter II was recently
released. Hunters can now move about (they were pretty much
confined to blinds and tree stands with the first version), and a
crude map used in the first version has been replaced by a
global-positioning system in this one.
</P>
<P>
   There are also more weapons, more places to hunt and improved
graphics, although they still fall somewhat short in detail
compared to other outdoor games. This version carries a street
price of about $20, the same as the previous version when it was
introduced.
</P>
<P>
   There's also another game with a different twist on the Deer
Hunter theme: Deer Avenger, developed by Cendant Software and
published by Simon &AMP; Schuster Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   The reverse action, where hunters become the hunted, takes place
in the deer-friendly states of West Virginia, Connecticut and
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Bambi has to attract his prey, so the game includes some traps,
including a ``Free Beer Here'' sign to use for a lure.
</P>
<P>
   The program was written by Brian McCann, staff writer for ``Late
Night with Conan O'Brien.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a cute parody, with unsuspecting hunters ranging from
inbred good-ol' boys to L.L. Bean-equipped yuppies.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there are variations on the original.
</P>
<P>
   The one closest to the original concept is African Safari Trophy
Hunter 3D from the same company that brought out the Deer Hunter
title. It was developed in cooperation with Lee Pivar, a safari
hunter for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters can track down elephants, zebras, kudas and elands in
two Zimbabwe hunting areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continuing to build on the success of our Deer Hunter
franchise by publishing titles that expand the genre even
further,'' said Paul Rinde, senior vice president of product
acquisition and development for WizardWorks.
</P>
<P>
   There are a choice of weapons, including bolt-action rifle and
double-barrel rifle, or those who don't want to hunt can pick the
observer mode to watch 3-D animals.
</P>
<P>
   Another game from WizardWorks combines the Deer Hunter concept
with the get-even theme of Deer Avenger: Carnivores has a
dinosaur-fantasy theme. Players can go on a prehistoric hunt for a
Tyrannosaurus, Triceratop, Stegosaurus or other dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike deer, however, dinosaurs tend to get even when they're
winged or missed by a hunter.
</P>
<P>
   If a hunter's shot isn't on target, said Rinde, he or she ``will
become potential prey in a dinosaur attack.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 10 dinosaurs to hunt, each with different
characteristics to keep the game fresh.
</P>
<P>
   There are six different environments and a choice of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   If you really don't want to kill them and risk making them
extinct again, tranquilizers can be used instead of weapons, and
you can haul them back to Jurassic Park. A trophy room, where
specimens are displayed in 3D, can also be used.
</P>
<P>
   A demo of Carnivores is available from the WizardWorks Web site,
www.wizworks.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is The Ledger's associate editor. He can be
reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. His recent computer
columns are on the Internet at theledger.com/business/tech/)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
