<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV07-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday Jan. 7)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was in first grade, my best friend ran away. She came to
my house, carrying her sleeping bag, extra clothes and some
favorite books.
</P>
<P>
   As one of six children, she wanted to escape the noisy chaos,
the shared bedroom, the scramble for the last of the food at the
dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   Her plan was to live at my house forever. After all, there was
just me and my parents. I had a whole room _ indeed, an entire
double-bed _ to myself, plenty of toys, and if I wanted seconds, on
anything, from meatballs to fruit cocktail, all I had to do was
ask.
</P>
<P>
   To Christine, it seemed like paradise.
</P>
<P>
   What she didn't know is that I would have traded with her in a
second. I longed for the easy camaraderie she had with her
siblings, the secrets she gleaned from her older sister, the cool
basement studio that held her older brother's surrealistic
paintings and interesting record collection, where records like
``In the Year 2525'' and ``American Pie'' were always on the
turntable.
</P>
<P>
   Her house buzzed with laughter and fights and games. Her mother
was always tending to the younger ones, so Chris got away with lots
of stuff my mom would have stopped in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   But it was more than that. It was being a part of something
larger. At my house, things tended to revolve around me: my
bedtime, my piano lesson, my Brownie meeting, my homework.
</P>
<P>
   How I longed to move through a family that surrounded me, not
one that existed because of me.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't spoiled or sheltered, not in the way that dampens one's
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   But an only child is just that ... the only child. The tip of
the triangle. And not only that: I was the only child of an only
child of an only child. My family tree led straight to ... me.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the late 1960s, I was a rarity. The kids on my street
came in packs of two to six.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, only children are back in vogue. The most recent
census statistics, from 1995, show that 18 percent of women who say
they have completed child bearing have only one child _ a 50
percent increase from 1985.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it's a biological reality.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, decide on a one-child family. They like the
idea of more time, money and attention lavished on one child,
rather than spread among several. They cite studies that show only
children to be more articulate and better students.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, they say, only children fit more easily into a
dual-career, fast-paced lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Cousins and close friends, they claim, can fill the void left by
no brothers or sisters.
</P>
<P>
   True, onlies do benefit from the extra resources, says Susan
Newman, a social psychologist who wrote the book, ``Parenting an
Only Child.'' But friends don't share your family history, saying
things such as, ``Remember the time we did this ... and didn't you
just love that trip we took?''
</P>
<P>
   Sibling relationships endure over time, and grow especially
valuable when pitching in to care caring for aging parents, and to
have family left after parents die.
</P>
<P>
   For some, though, being an only child is a rich and rewarding
experience. They grew up extremely close to their parents, and
grandparents, willing to share whatever they have with others, not
knowing the mechanics of selfishness or competition.
</P>
<P>
   Despite my childhood longings, who knows if I really would have
liked having brothers or sisters? I'm sure there would have been
times where I, like Christine, would have ditched them all for a
bit of peace and seclusion.
</P>
<P>
   So, because I couldn't convince my parents to have another or
adopt, (my sole request for five straight Christmases), I did the
only thing I could: grew up, got married, and had more than one
baby.
</P>
<P>
   And does my oldest, the beneficiary of this gift of a younger
sister, appreciate the enormity of what I have given him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez,'' he grumbled, one evening a while back. ``Now we have a
baby who cries and messes up everything and bites. What could be
worser?''
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe it takes a few decades to appreciate the finer points
of having a sibling.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a New York Times Regional Newspapers feature
writer. She has master's and specialist degrees in marriage and
family counseling.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
