<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4658 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-WATCH-$ADV03-N     01-01 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET WATCH: TIME FOR SOME PLAIN TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 3)  
 (bl)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tornados that hurtled through world markets in 1998 varied
in nature, scope and power. But they all had something in common:
Their risk to investors was hidden.
</P>
<P>
   That was true for the shock of Russia's defaulting on its debt
last August and the ensuing whirlwinds that swept the United States
bond market. It was true in the near-collapse of the giant hedge
fund Long-Term Capital Management and in the accounting
irregularities that hammered shareholders in Cendant, Sunbeam and
Livent.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the problem is known as a lack of transparency _
the ability of investors to see through an investment, to make an
informed decision to buy, sell or do nothing. True transparency is
crucial to investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all investors bother to investigate before they
invest. Many plunge first and ponder later. But for those who
perform due diligence on their investments, it is alarming, indeed,
that wide swaths of markets remain opaque. Many are found overseas,
though there are dark corners, too, in U.S. markets, where
securities laws have demanded full disclosure for more than 60
years.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors are getting less information today than they were
a few years ago. Consider, for example, the recent decision by
Fidelity Investments to stop sending shareholder reports and fund
prospectuses automatically to many participants in 401(k) plans it
manages. Now, shareholders get this information _ on fund holdings,
fees and a description of a fund's investment policy _ only if they
ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that most people don't read the shareholder reports,''
said Debra McConnell, a spokeswoman for Fidelity. ``This was a
decision based on our broader initiative to communicate more
effectively with plan participants. It reduces clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's move is a straw in the wind. There are other, far
more troubling transparency issues in U.S. markets today. Though
the bond market is far bigger than the stock market, for instance,
no electronic pricing system for all types of bonds is available to
individual investors. This makes it almost impossible to see
problems like the flight to Treasury bonds that froze the rest of
the bond market in September.
</P>
<P>
   A second problem area is accounting. As companies find it
imperative not to disappoint Wall Street with bad earnings reports,
aggressive accounting tactics become more common. (As the
accompanying chart shows, tens of billions in earnings are
disappearing into a variety of one-time charges _ some taken by
companies that have made these once-rare events into regular
occurrences.) This makes companies' books more difficult to
penetrate.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is a practice that the Securities and Exchange
Commission calls selective disclosure, in which public companies
divulge information first to favored Wall Street analysts and later
to the public. Some companies deny the press access to conference
calls or meetings with analysts. This puts small investors at a
disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   All these areas are of concern to the SEC. Last September, for
example, SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt Jr. asked the National
Association of Securities Dealers to develop a system for tracking
bond trades and a program to detect fraud in bond markets. Levitt
has also been trying to crack down on accounting fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Transparency issues rarely get attention when stock prices are
rising. But as Levitt seems to realize, that is exactly when they
should be tackled, before disaster strikes. In the meantime,
investors should demand all the information they can get.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 1611EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
