<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4659 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-FARR-ART-     01-01 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-FARR-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEL FARR: A `HOUND DOG' HUNTS ON WALL ST.
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Calif.)  (For release Sunday, Jan. 3)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK PARK, Mich. _ A year ago, when the Rev. Jesse Jackson
organized a Wall Street conference on race, Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin rose to speak and then asked for questions. One came
from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   `` Rubin,'' a man piped up, ``why not take money
African-Americans are investing in pension funds and invest it into
their community?''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin looked puzzled, and then joked, ``Jesse, you must have
planted that question.'' Jackson rose. ``No. That's Mel Farr,''
came the response. ``He's the biggest African-American auto dealer
in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Mel Farr's first taste of Wall Street, and now he's
going back in search of something he says black America _ no less
than his own bustling company _ is very much in need of: financial
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Farr, a former professional football player who operates 15 auto
dealerships out of the Detroit area, is trying to raise $45 million
in a private placement of asset-backed securities that would help
take his business into the most blighted areas of the nation. Some,
like Jackson, see his effort as a test case of whether Wall Street
will do more than pay lip service to the cause of black
entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, Farr was driving a black Lincoln Navigator
around his complex of Lincoln-Mercury and Ford dealerships here,
talking about how he's managing a talent pool that comes from the
``bottom of the barrel,'' selling to the urban underclass and still
making a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auto manufacturers have abandoned urban areas,'' he said. ``I
met a Ford dealer once and he said, `That dog won't hunt.' And I
said: `You got the wrong dog. You got a Labrador retriever; you
need a hound dog.' And I am that hound dog.''
</P>
<P>
   On this morning, just after 8, Farr is headed to a meeting with
the mostly black sales force at one of his dealerships. He is a
ruggedly handsome 54-year-old, and the only hint of his former
career is a small scar above his right eye, a result of a tackle.
As he works the small crowd, his tone changes from folksy to
inspirational.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning,'' the group of about 25 calls back in unison.
</P>
<P>
   Farr talks about setting goals, and like a church congregation,
the listeners respond with nods and shouts of ``yes.'' At one
point, he singles out a man named Gary who used to work as a
hospital orderly. ``How much did you make this year?'' Farr asks.
``One hundred thousand dollars,'' Gary replies, to much applause.
</P>
<P>
   Set goals, Farr repeats. ``If it is to be, it is . . .'' he
says, allowing his voice to trail off. ``Up to me,'' the sales
force chimes in, completing his sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Farr sells mostly to black Americans he calls ``financially
challenged'' _ those with virtually no credit _ and finances their
purchases at interest rates of up to 25 percent. And he is quick to
repossess cars whose owners fall behind on payments. ``I'm giving
them an opportunity nobody else would give them,'' he says
unapologetically. ``Traditionally, that market would not be able to
pay, so you have to price for it.''
</P>
<P>
   He got into the car business after retiring in 1974 from the
Detroit Lions (where he was an All-Pro running back). Since then,
he has acquired mostly small, bankrupt showrooms to create the
nation's largest chain of black-owned dealerships, with 817
employees and more than $600 million in annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is flying around the country, sometimes in his personal
turboprop, trying to raise money for expansion to cities like
Atlanta and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Jackson, he obtained an audience last year with
James Dimon, then co-chief executive of Salomon Smith Barney. But
Dimon told him the financing deal was too small.
</P>
<P>
   So Farr went to a smaller investment bank, Quadrant Financial,
prepared the private-placement papers and began meeting with
pension fund managers and other institutional investors to make the
case for Triple M, his financing outfit that makes loans to people
with bad credit. So far, he says, he has raised $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it's a hard sell. A few meetings, he said, went
something like this: ``Well, what are you going to do with the
funds?'' To which he answered, ``I'm going to loan this to
African-Americans with bad credit.'' They said, he recalled with a
chuckle, ``Isn't there an easier deal than this?''
</P>
<P>
   There may be, but Farr says he has worked out a formula that
insures a nice profit, especially given the absence of competition.
</P>
<P>
   Farr knows what it is like to overcome long odds. Growing up in
segregated Beaumont, Texas, he had to drink from separate water
fountains for blacks, eat standing up at separate restaurant
counters and ride in the back of the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know a single white person until I went to UCLA,'' he
said. At the University of California at Los Angeles, he was an
All-America running back; he was drafted in the first round by the
Detroit Lions and won Rookie of the Year honors.
</P>
<P>
   After injuries cut his professional football career short, he
fell back on a childhood passion: cars. His father had sold used
cars out of the family's front yard, and Farr began roaming the car
lots of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Today, his base of operations is the Mel Farr Automotive Group
here, which he publicized a few years back by appearing in
commercials as ``Superstar Mel Farr,'' wearing a red cape. He has
found jobs at the dealership for his sons, Mel Jr. and Mike (also
former pro football players); his daughter, Monet, and his brother,
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the template,'' he says, strolling the corridors. ``I
want to do this all over the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in his office just after 3 p.m., Farr takes a call from
Jackson. They make small talk about football, then turn to the
topic of Wall Street and Jackson's follow-up conference on race
later this month. In the days leading up to that, he says, he
expects to get the $45 million he is seeking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a real partnership,'' he says, speaking into the
phone. ``All I want you to do is set 'em up. I'll do the rest.''
Reinforcing the point with a football metaphor for Jackson, a
former college quarterback, he adds, ``If you throw it up, I'll
catch it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
