<HEADER>
A4660 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOCKS-COLLATERAL-ART     01-01 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-COLLATERAL-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SITTING PRETTY WITH ZERO DOWN: IN SOME MORTGAGES, STOCK IS
COLLATERAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 3)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic on
using stock as collateral in mortgages is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By BARBARA WHITAKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last summer, Robert Cramer asked his financial adviser to sell
about $250,000 in stock so he could make a down payment on a
million-dollar triplex in Malibu, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer, a lawyer, was no stranger to the mortgage process; at
the time, he owned five properties. But this time, his adviser
talked him into taking out an innovative mortgage that allowed him
to use stock as collateral without putting a penny down on the
house. For the deal to pay off financially, the stock's return
would have to match or exceed the 7[ percent interest he would have
paid on a down payment. But it was a gamble he was willing to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been highly favorable in my situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mortgage, offered by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, goes by the
name of Flex Source. Other firms offer this type of stock-backed
mortgage, but it isn't for everybody, assuredly not the faint of
heart. With a Flex Source mortgage, home buyers must place
securities equal to 39 percent of the purchase price or appraised
value in a brokerage account; if the market plunges, they must add
to the portfolio so its value never dips below 33 percent of the
purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has advantages: Because they are not selling shares to
raise a down payment, buyers avoid paying capital-gains taxes, and
they can hope for big gains if the bull market continues.
``Historically the stock market makes you money,'' noted Margaret
Klein, a Morgan Stanley associate vice president and Cramer's
financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Dow bobs up and down, a homeowner's fortunes can bob
with it. Cramer paid $965,000 for his oceanfront home, so he had to
put up stock valued at $377,000, Ms. Klein said. To play it safe,
he placed $400,000 worth in the account.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't safe enough. In the 60 days running up to his Sept. 30
closing, the market fell sharply and he had to add $89,000. Since
then, stocks have surged, and he has made up that amount _ plus
$68,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``How attracted you are to this kind of deal is going to depend
on what you want to get from your investment, and on the economy on
down the road,'' said Keith Gumbinger, vice president of HSH
Associates, a financial publisher in Butler, N.J. ``If you think
we're going into a period of slow growth and poor profits, this may
not be the time to get into this.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say people nearing retirement or those who prefer
traditional mortgages _ in order to build equity in their homes _
should probably stay away from stock-backed mortgages, while
aggressive investors might want to consider them.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch is credited with developing this form of 100
percent home financing. About seven years ago, it introduced Parent
Power, a program that allowed parents, grandparents or other
sponsors to pledge securities in lieu of a down payment to help
first-time home buyers. Parent Power became so popular that Merrill
created an offshoot, called Mortgage 100, that enabled individuals
to buy their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   In many traditional mortgages, home buyers pay 20 percent down
to avoid buying personal mortgage insurance. On a $300,000 house,
this would be $60,000. While a down payment helps reduce the
monthly payment, financial advisers recommend looking at how much
that money would earn if it was invested. The nothing-down loan is
a wash if the money grows at the same rate as the interest rate on
the mortgage. Using the above example, with a fixed 7 percent
interest rate, Merrill Lynch calculates the break-even point over
seven years to be $89,400. If the money returned 10 percent, it
would grow to $120,500, leaving the homeowners $31,100 richer than
if they made a down payment. But if the money returned 5 percent,
it would grow to just $85,100, $4,300 short.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schatsky, a fee-only financial adviser and lawyer in New
York, cautions against rushing into 100 percent financing. ``The
reasonable argument for why to do this is you can't afford the tax
bite,'' he said. But other options might accomplish the same goal,
he said, such as simply borrowing against your stock account and
using the proceeds as a down payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caution, caution, caution,'' he said. ``It sounds convenient,
but the cost might well be too expensive for many.''
</P>
<P>
   Gumbinger said this sort of financing has grown as the stock
market has surged but has remained ``a specialty niche.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' he said, ``is if you don't think you can
afford to lose, then you probably shouldn't gamble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
