<HEADER>
A4661 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-CULTURE-DISCLAIME     01-01 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CULTURE-DISCLAIMER-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CULTURE OF MONEY: DISCLAIMERS ARE HAZARDOUS TO OUR HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 3)   Daniel Akst is a novelist and financial journalist. His column on
the cultural dimensions of money and business appears the first
Sunday of each month. E-mail: culmoney(AT)nytimes.com.  
 (bl)  
 By DANIEL AKST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An invitation came to spend the weekend at a vacation home in
the mountains. There would be hiking, gourmet meals and
companionable guests, all friends and significant others. But when
I arrived, my hosts had left a request: that I read the disclaimer
they provided and sign where it said I wouldn't sue.
</P>
<P>
   Because they were friends of my wife-to-be, I supplied my
signature to avoid making a scene. And, anyway, isn't that how we
get through the rest of our lives?
</P>
<P>
   Disclaimers are everywhere. Join a gym, visit a hospital or park
a car, and you are likely to have one shoved under your nose. The
flip side of ``go for it!,'' disclaimers are among the defining
tropes of fin de siecle America, figuring as prominently in the
culture of money as yellow cabs in the iconography of New York.
They give the same queasy color to our discourse, too. A symptom of
fear and a sign of collective distrust, they suggest that we are
ruled by literal-minded finger-pointers who make it too risky to
take responsibility for anything.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents, for example, are increasingly printing
disclaimers on tickets and itineraries. One popular version ducks
responsibility for ``terrorist activities, social or labor unrest,
mechanical or construction failures or difficulties, diseases,
local laws, climatic conditions, abnormal conditions or
developments'' or anything else said to be outside the travel
agent's control.
</P>
<P>
   The tautological ``void where prohibited'' is heard daily in
advertising, as are fast-talking announcers who, at the end of
radio commercials about car leases and the like, squeeze in all the
required legalese with the speed and intelligibility of an
auctioneer.
</P>
<P>
   It is now standard practice for many publishers to slap a
disclaimer on each work of fiction (you know: ``any resemblance to
blah, blah, blah is purely coincidental''), even though the book is
clearly labeled a novel. One movie even used a disclaimer as its
title _ ``Batteries Not Included.''
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that disclaimers are a form of disclosure, they
are difficult to criticize. After all, openness is practically
sacred nowadays as a cultural attribute _ witness all the talk
shows with dysfunctional families. In business, disclosure has been
the sensible basis of securities regulation since the days of
Franklin D. Roosevelt, giving investors the facts to fairly
evaluate risks.
</P>
<P>
   But the very pervasiveness of disclaimers is inverting their
intended effect, by burying truly relevant information in an
avalanche of boilerplate warnings and denials that any rational
person must train himself to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   See how this syndrome plays out on Wall Street. Prospectuses for
new stock offerings constantly warn investors that there can be no
assurance of practically anything, including the sun's rise on the
morrow. Yet all those investors keep bidding up the price of new
Internet stocks into the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet itself offers vast new opportunities for the
repudiation of responsibility. Web pages often carry disclaimers,
and weirdly, so do people's postings in discussion groups.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of Usenet, the vast bulletin-board-like
network of public sites where online denizens do their opining,
many people's postings included a warning that ``the opinions
expressed are the writer's alone and not those of his employer,''
whose identity was obvious in the poster's Net address. It's common
now to see strident posted or e-mail opinions softened with
``YMMV'' _ your mileage may vary.
</P>
<P>
   In this unheroic age, when we all try to reduce our comments to
what lawyers call obiter dictum (things said in passing), it's
tempting to lump the spread of disclaimers with other cultural
phenomena, like the tendency of some young people, particularly
women, to inflect declarative sentences upward at the end? In a
kind of grammatical disclaimer? (I'll stop now.)
</P>
<P>
   These developments are in keeping with the assault by literary
critics on the authority in ``authorship,'' so that even financial
journalists are joining novelists in embracing disclaimers. For
example, James J. Cramer's stock-market investing column on
Thestreet.com, has the following disavowal attached: ``Under no
circumstances does the information in this column represent a
recommendation to buy or sell stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Maybe he's actually discussing horoscopes in some kind of
code. Or maybe he's just been talking to his lawyers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 1618EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
