<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-E-COMMERCE-$ADV04-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET COMPANIES: THE SMALL GET BIG, THE BIG GET BIGGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago, the choice for Lycos, then a struggling Internet
search engine, was to make acquisitions or become irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reached 14 percent of the Internet users,'' recalled Robert
Davis, chief executive of Lycos Inc. Yahoo Inc. was at 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never going to grow into a powerhouse,'' he said. ``We
had to buy our way to being a powerhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is exactly what Lycos has done. It has bought five
companies, for more than $300 million in stock, in the last year,
increasing its audience to 38 percent of Internet users and giving
itself a somewhat better chance of staving off irrelevancy.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Internet executives and investment bankers agree, the
pace of deal-making by Internet publishing and retailing companies
is likely to accelerate as more and more of the concerns that have
started in recent years realize that they need to grow in order to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Internet you have to get bigger fast,'' said Mark
Shafir, head of Merrill Lynch's technology merger practice in San
Francisco. ``It's going to be the land of the titans pretty
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward consolidation began last year, when many deals
were driven by the desire of smaller companies to end grueling
battles for market supremacy. Most notably, CD Now and N2K, the two
leading online music stores, agreed to merge in order to fight off
impending competition from Amazon.com. And Media Metrix, a
privately held company that measures the audience of Internet
sites, bought its archrival Relevant Knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The existing titans, meanwhile, moved to extend their dominance.
America Online Inc., the biggest Internet company, used
acquisitions to reach new audience groups in addition to its core
of chatty teen-agers and their technology-challenged parents. It
bought Mirabilis, the Israeli creator of the chat service called
ICQ that appeals to an international audience. And America Online
plans to acquire Netscape Communications Corp. to get Netscape's
World Wide Web site, which appeals to business users, as well as
its online server software.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Microsoft Corp. bought Hotmail, a free e-mail
service, to funnel users to its own revamped MSN portal service.
And Amazon.com bought Junglee, a service that searches for products
for sale around the Internet, as a way to transform itself from a
book and music store to a vast electronic mall.
</P>
<P>
   The surging prices of Internet stocks will help create a handful
of new Internet titans as both big traditional companies and
smaller start-ups struggle to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Take Yahoo, rated at the top among search engines, or portal
services, as they are now called because of the role they try to
play as the front doors to people's Internet journeys. Yahoo now
has a market value of $23 billion, about as big as that of CBS Inc.
That makes Yahoo simply too expensive for any company (save perhaps
Microsoft) to buy. But it's easy for Yahoo to use its highly valued
shares as currency to make acquisitions of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to use your paper while you have it,'' said David
Braunschvig, a managing director at Lazard Freres. ``It costs you
nothing to get big.''
</P>
<P>
   While Yahoo and Amazon have, so far, made relatively small
acquisitions, their market values will give them the opportunity to
make even bigger deals this year, investment bankers contend.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the rise in Internet stock values creates nothing but
headaches for traditional retailers competing with companies like
Amazon and for big media companies competing with Yahoo. These
companies cannot pay as high a price for acquisitions, nor can they
offer their employees high-flying stock bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a big company, you won't be able to keep your
engineers for a long time if they see all their buddies at small
public companies become very rich from the stock options,''
Braunschvig said.
</P>
<P>
   The solution for an existing company is to take a part-interest
in a publicly traded Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   The prototype of his arrangement is Walt Disney Co.'s purchase
of 43 percent of Infoseek, another struggling search-engine
company. But rather than paying cash, Disney exchanged Starwave, an
Internet production company it owned, and only $90 million in cash
for Infoseek stock worth $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing financial benefits, such deals help the
bigger companies keep up with the frantic pace of Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Merger experts predict that media companies will make alliances
this year with the remaining independent portal companies,
including Lycos, Excite, Alta Vista and maybe even Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, for all the appeal and wealth of the publicly traded
Internet startup company, and all the high-profile initial public
offerings last year, statistics show that small technology
companies are less likely to go public than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   There certainly will be more public offerings this year, like
those last year of Ebay and Broadcast.com. Coming up early this
year is the offering for Ivillage, a woman's interest Internet
service. Later, most likely, will be an offering for Buy.com, an
ambitious online store that has grown rapidly by selling computer
products at cost in hopes of making money on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Yet statistics compiled by Broadview, an investment bank, show
that last year, for the first time, there were fewer initial public
offerings of small technology companies than there were
acquisitions of them by bigger companies.
</P>
<P>
   Stock can be sold more easily and with less notice when it's in
a larger company than when a founder bails out of his own company's
stock. Holding onto stock in one's own company after going public,
however, has not proved to be prudent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the companies that have gone public since 1991 are
trading below their IPO value,'' said Alec Ellison, a managing
director of Broadview.
</P>
<P>
   So for those companies that don't see their way to being titans,
a quick sale to a more established operation may be both easier and
more lucrative than going it alone and risking irrelevancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``By going public,'' Ellison said, ``they may not get the
strategic resources that a sale to Big Brother would provide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
