<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWYEAR-RESOLVE-ARTS &LR;      01-01 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYEAR-RESOLVE-ARTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STOICS HAVE A STAND ON EVERYTHING, EVEN ON DINNER PARTIES AND
SEX  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After being off the best-seller list for nearly 2,000 years, the
Stoic philosopher Epictetus has been revived, thanks to Tom Wolfe's
new novel, ``A Man in Full'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux).
</P>
<P>
   In prison, Conrad Hensley, one of Wolfe's main characters,
requests ``The Stoics' Game,'' a new spy thriller, but receives a
copy of Epictetus' ``The Stoics'' by accident.
</P>
<P>
   When Conrad discovers that Epictetus spent time in prison as a
young man, he can't stop reading. He begins to identify with
Epictetus, who was tortured, enslaved and threatened with death.
Conrad finds profound meaning in the philosopher's teachings.
</P>
<P>
   Epictetus was born a Roman slave in about A.D. 50. He was given
his freedom around 68, but later was exiled to Nicopolis in Greece,
where he taught logic, physics and the ethics of Stoicism.
Epictetus wanted each man to see that he alone was responsible for
his deeds because he had acquiesced to the circumstances that
produced them. The capacity to choose and refuse was of immense
importance in his philosophy. Epictetus wrote nothing, but his
teachings were set down by his disciple Flavius Arrian in the
``Discourses'' and the ``Encheiridion'' (``Manual'').
</P>
<P>
   Now you can see how your own New Year's resolutions stack up to
Epictetus' principles for living. Joyce Jensen compiled these
excerpts.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that you ought to behave in life as you would at a
banquet. As something is being passed around, it comes to you;
stretch out your hand and take a portion of it politely. It passes
on; do not detain it. Or it has not come to you yet; do not project
your desire to meet it, but wait until it comes in front of you.
</P>
<P>
   Be not elated at any excellence that is not your own. If the
horse in his elation were to say, ``I am beautiful,'' it could be
endured; but when you say in your elation, ``I have a beautiful
horse,'' rest assured that you are elated at something good that
belongs to a horse.
</P>
<P>
   Has someone been honored above you at a dinner-party or in
salutation or in being called in to give advice? Now if these
matters are good, you ought to be happy that he got them; but if
evil, be not distressed because you did not get them. Now it is the
same way also in life. You have not been invited to somebody's
dinner party? Of course not; for you didn't give the host the price
at which he sells his dinner. He sells it for praise; he sells it
for personal attention. Give him the price, then, for which it is
sold, if it is to your interest. But if you wish both not to give
up the one and yet to get the other, you are insatiable and a
simpleton.
</P>
<P>
   Some things are under our control, while others are not under
our control. Under our control are conception, choice, desire,
aversion and, in a word, everything that is our own doing; not
under our control are our body, our property, reputation, office
and, in a word, everything that is not our own doing.
</P>
<P>
   Do not seek to have everything that happens happen as you wish,
but wish for everything to happen as it actually does happen, and
your life will be serene.
</P>
<P>
   You can be invincible if you never enter a contest in which
victory is not under your control.
</P>
<P>
   Lay down for yourself, at the outset, a certain stamp and type
of character for yourself, which you are to maintain whether you
are by yourself or are meeting with people:
</P>
<P>
   Do not laugh much nor at many things nor boisterously.
</P>
<P>
   Refuse, if you can, to take an oath at all, but if that is
impossible, refuse as far as circumstances allow.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid entertainments given by outsiders and by persons ignorant
of philosophy. For you may rest assured that if a man's companion
be dirty, the person who keeps close company with him must of
necessity get a share of his dirt, even though he himself happens
to be clean.
</P>
<P>
   In things that pertain to the body, take only as much as your
bare need requires. I mean such things as food, drink, clothing,
shelter and household slaves; but cut down everything that is for
outward show or luxury.
</P>
<P>
   In your sex life preserve purity as far as you can before
marriage, and if you indulge, take only those privileges that are
lawful. However, do not make yourself offensive or censorious to
those who do indulge, and do not make frequent mention of the fact
that you do not yourself indulge.
</P>
<P>
   When you do a thing that you have made up your mind ought to be
done, never try not to be seen doing it, even though most people
are likely to think unfavorably about it. If, however, what you are
doing is not right, avoid the deed itself altogether; but if it is
right, why fear those who are going to rebuke you wrongly?
</P>
<P>
   Everything has two handles, by one of which it ought to be
carried and by the other not. If your brother wrongs you, do not
lay hold of the matter by the handle of the wrong that he is doing,
because this is the handle by which the matter ought not to be
carried; but rather by the other handle _ that he is your brother,
that you were brought up together, and then you will be laying hold
of the matter by the handle by which it ought to be carried.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of one who is making progress are: He censures no one,
praises no one, blames no one, finds fault with no one, says
nothing about himself as though he were somebody or knew something.
When he is hampered or prevented, he blames himself. And if anyone
compliments him, he smiles to himself at the person complimenting;
while if anyone censures him, he makes no defense. He has put away
from himself his every desire, and has transferred his aversion to
those things only, of what is under our control, which are contrary
to nature. In a word, he keeps guard against himself as though he
were his own enemy lying in wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 1651EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAPHIC-NOVELS-1000&AMP;A     01-01 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAPHIC-NOVELS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMIC MINDS MEET WITHOUT BAM! ZAP! OR SPLAT! 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By SARAH BOXER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A middle-aged guy with long, dirty hair and a sweatshirt was
weighing his options. ``Girls?'' he said, raising one hand like a
dish on a balance scale. ``Or comics?'' He raised the other.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, a younger man with red eyes, a turquoise mohawk
and eyebrows scarred from having too many rings drilled into them
pondered the comic book thoughts he has whenever he walks through a
door. ``The thing I find myself thinking is, `Now I'm going to go
through that door.' Is that the Captain America in me speaking or
my own comic brain?''
</P>
<P>
   It was just another academic gathering, a recent conference at
the University of Massachusetts, Amherst, to celebrate the 20th
anniversary of the first graphic novel. At the opening reception
the comics groupies were out in force. There was a buffet with two
kinds of fried chicken, warmed-over spanakopita, raw vegetables
with onion-soup dip and fluorescent lights.
</P>
<P>
   The guest of honor had no body piercings and no sweatshirt. He
was Will Eisner, the 82-year-old creator of the comic book hero
``The Spirit'' and the author of ``A Contract With God,'' the first
graphic novel, written in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who does not know, a graphic novel is a serious
literary work in comic book form, like Art Spiegelman's ``Maus'' or
Jules Feiffer's ``Tantrum.''
</P>
<P>
   If comics are ``those bright, colorful magazines filled with bad
art, stupid stories and guys in tights,'' as Scott McCloud jokingly
put it in his book ``Understanding Comics'' (Kitchen Sink Press,
1993), then graphic novels are their earnest offspring. The tights
are gone, the stories are often grim, and the drawing isn't exactly
comic.
</P>
<P>
   During the conference Eisner traced his own path through comics,
from strips to books to underground comics to graphic novels. In
the depths of the Great Depression, he said, newspaper comic strips
were so popular that pulp publishers started selling comics in
magazine form, as comic books. Soon there wasn't enough material to
fill them. Eisner started a company with his friend Jerry Iger to
produce new material. He worked with Bob Kane, the creator of
Batman, before Batman was born. Eisner created his own hero, the
Spirit, a masked, gloved dead man with no special powers. But
Eisner's heart was in reality.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, it was censorship that opened the door to
literary comic books. In 1954 ``The Seduction of the Innocent,''
Frederic Wertham's book about the nasty effects that violent,
gruesome comics have on children, moved comic book publishers to
abide by a ``comics code,'' a self-imposed decency standard. Some
comic book artists cleaned up their act. The rest went underground.
The world of comics split into the cute and fantastical mainstream
and the down and gritty underground.
</P>
<P>
   Graphic novels grew from the second strain. In 1978 Eisner
created ``A Contract With God,'' a comic book story about Frimme
Hersh, a Jewish immigrant who becomes a slumlord when he discovers
that God has broken his sacred contract (if you are good, good
things will happen to you). The story was set on a street of
tenements in the Bronx. Eisner drew on life experience. He used
rain to connote emotion, which came to be called ``Eisner spritz.''
</P>
<P>
   Grim realism had come to the world of comics. A bond was forged
between American comics and the social realism of artists like Ben
Shahn and Kathe Kollwitz. (The imagery of many graphic novels seems
to be stuck in the 1930s.)
</P>
<P>
   There was something earnest and something hideous about them.
The playwright Tony Kushner once described the experience of
reading a book-length comic as ``thrilling, alarming, faintly
nauseating.'' He was describing a cartoon history of the Soviet
Union, it turns out, but he hit upon a truth about graphic novels:
``The flat black called to mind mud, excrement, and the burnt bones
that are the source of a carbon soot pure enough for India ink.''
</P>
<P>
   Graphic novels are anti-escape literature.
</P>
<P>
   Some artists didn't like it one bit. As Eisner recalled, Rube
Goldberg, the inventor of comic contraptions, scolded him for his
pretensions: ``We're vaudevillians. Never forget that. We tell
jokes!'' Eisner ignored him. And he even called his comic book a
graphic novel to get the attention of serious publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner's graphic novel has inspired others. Professors teach
courses on comic books and graphic novels in departments of
comparative literature, English and Judaic studies. (The creators
of Superman, Batman, Sandman, Mad magazine, ``Maus,'' ``Tantrum,''
and ``Julius Knipl: Real Estate Photographer'' were all Jewish.) A
course on Surrealism includes ``Gasoline Alley,'' ``Jingle Jangle
Tales'' and ``Krazy Kat'' as required reading.
</P>
<P>
   There are academic conferences. At this one, Samuel R. Delany, a
professor of comparative literature at the University of
Massachusetts, invoked Charles Baudelaire, Edgar Allan Poe and
Walter Benjamin to analyze Eddie Campbell's ``From Hell,'' a
16-part comic about Jack the Ripper. James Reibman, a Samuel
Johnson scholar, discussed the Gothic revival in ``The Crow,''
James O'Barr's ``saga of love and violent retribution.''
</P>
<P>
   A panel of scholars and cartoonists addressed the issue of black
superheroes. As William Foster, an English professor at Naugatuck
Valley Community Technical College in Waterbury, Conn., put it:
It's all fine and good to have comics with black schoolteachers
fighting drugs in the city, ``but who is standing toe to toe with
Superman?''
</P>
<P>
   Do comic books really deserve such sober treatment?
</P>
<P>
   At least some do, says James Young, the author of ``The Texture
of Memory'' and a professor at the University of Massachusetts,
Amherst, who spoke on behalf of Art Spiegelman's ``Maus.'' He
argued that this comic isn't just a shocking presentation of a
Holocaust story; it is the perfect form for it.
</P>
<P>
   The generation born just after World War II, he explained, does
not really have memories of the Holocaust. ``They remember what the
survivors passed down to them in diaries, stories, videos. What
distinguishes them is their sense of vicariousness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maus,'' he said, expresses that vicariousness better than any
other form could.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, ``the son, Artie, recalls what happened at the hand
of the father as the father recalls what happened at the hands of
the Nazis,'' Young said. The reader sees competing stories: what
the father says and what the son hears. The mixture of words and
images allows for that kind of layering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you read it is the way you make sense of things,
letting the eye do what it has got to do to get through a page.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, as McCloud argues in ``Understanding Comics,''
the real drama happens between the panels as readers are forced to
fill in the missing information.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why one of the tenser moments of the conference
happened between the panels: not during a lecture but at a lunch,
when some cartoonists and scholars turned to the question of the
proper way to read a comic book. Text first? Pictures first? Or
both together?
</P>
<P>
   One man said: ``I read the story first, then go back and look at
the pictures. It sets me up emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Cruse disagreed. ``It will diminish your enjoyment of the
story if you peek ahead,'' said Cruse, author of ``Stuck Rubber
Baby,'' a comic about a gay man coming out in the Bible Belt. The
pictures, after all, are ``about subtext,'' he said; they
``illuminate what's not being said, what's being avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   Delany said he distrusted people who read comics without looking
at the drawings. ``It's like people who go to  &UR; see &LR;  the opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Inge, a humanities professor at Randolph-Macon Women's
College in Lynchburg, Va., said, ``For me an opera is to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Delany smiled, ``You're not a purist.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a purist? That hurts! Somebody call Superman!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
