<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4676 &Cx1f; taf-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-BOOKS-$ADV04-NYT     01-01 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-BOOKS-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MARRIAGE MAELSTROM INDUSTRYWIDE, AS THE HIGH-TECHNOLOGY PLOT
THICKENS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Monday Jan. 4)  
(DW) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a year of page-turner mergers and major deals with
unexpected plot twists, the book industry is preparing for still
more radical changes that could come with further consolidation,
expanded online sales and increased clout for the nation's leading
bookseller, Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that we probably have experienced as an
industry more change in the last 12 months than in any period in
the history of the business,'' said Jack Romanos, president of
Simon &AMP; Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed in every respect, from the mergers and
acquisitions activities on the publishing and distribution side to
the creation of the behemoth publishing company,'' added Romanos,
whose own company was recently split up by its parent, Viacom Inc.,
and its educational division sold to the British media conglomerate
Pearson PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the season for whale watching, with behemoths
swallowing behemoths: the German media conglomerate Bertelsmann AG
announced in March that it would buy Random House; then in October
it formed a partnership with Barnes &AMP; Noble in its online venture,
Barnesandnoble.com. A few weeks later, the bookstore chain
announced that it had agreed to buy the leading book wholesaler,
Ingram Book Group, a deal that seemed to roil the book industry in
the United States more than any other deal.
</P>
<P>
   David R. Brodwin, an associate partner at Andersen Consulting,
the management consulting firm, said that behind the scenes it was
apparent that some of the major publishers were starting to explore
counter moves.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the possibility, he said, that one of the major
Internet portal _ or Web gateway _ companies will use its
overvalued stock to invest in or buy a publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that there are conversations taking place to put
together a consortium of some sort to counter the concentration of
power that the Ingram and Barnes &AMP; Noble combination represents,''
Brodwin said. Although he declined to name the companies, he did
say they might be considering a purchase of the second-largest
wholesaler, Baker &AMP; Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The publishers have lost power over recent years as retailing
has consolidated,'' Brodwin added. ``And to the extent that the
consolidation continues, the publishers will lose or are threatened
with further erosion of their market power, which could be
reflected in further price increases and pressures on terms of
trade such as credit.''
</P>
<P>
   The urge to consolidate has hit the entire book market _ from
regional distributors that are buying smaller independent
publishers to foreign media conglomerates that are forming
alliances across borders, including German acquisitions in the
United States or moves by the largest French publisher, the
Hachette Livre unit of Lagardere Groupe, to acquire a majority
stake in a British consumer book company, Orion Publishing Group.
</P>
<P>
   The unglamorous side of the business _ distribution _ has become
critical for publishing companies trying to deliver double-digit
profits for their corporate owners in a sluggish market for popular
books.
</P>
<P>
   From 1996 to 1997, consumer book purchases grew by less than 1
percent, failing to keep pace with population growth, according to
the Book Industry Study Group, a nonprofit research organization
based in New York, in its most recent report on purchase patterns.
</P>
<P>
   With sales growing slowly, distribution has become a critical
element for publishers and booksellers. It is particularly
important in the book fight that has gripped the leading online
booksellers, Amazon.com Inc. and Barnes &AMP; Noble, which are trying
to cut costs and speed delivery to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Middelhoff, the chief executive of Bertelsmann who
personally negotiated the deal to buy a 50 percent stake in Barnes
&AMP; Noble's online site, said he had set a goal of overtaking the
market-leading Amazon.com by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Most publishers and analysts expect online sales to increase
this year. Such competition is causing some trepidation among
independent booksellers, a group whose share of the market amounts
to 17 percent. Large chains make up 25 percent, but today most
books are sold outside traditional outlets, in discount stores,
warehouse clubs and book clubs, and through online retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet book-selling will grow significantly,'' said Albert
N. Greco, an associate professor of business at Fordham University,
who tracks the publishing industry. ``The speed, convenience and
availability of online retailing will overshadow traditional
bookstores and cut into their margins.''
</P>
<P>
   The electronic retail war has helped to push some of the bigger
alliances that have taken place, including the
Bertelsmann-Barnesandnoble.com-Ingram linkage. Such alliances are
raising broader questions about what the ultimate impact will be on
the diversity of literature in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overriding issue is increasing concentration,'' said
William Petrocelli, co-owner of Book Passage, an independent
bookstore in Corte Madera, Calif. ``I view it as a major threat to
writers and readers, as well as to independent booksellers. It
seems to me that as fewer and fewer people are making critical
decisions along the chain of distribution for books, the more
likely it is that diversity, quality and innovation will suffer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
