<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4680 &Cx1f; taf-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-DIVERSIFICATION-     01-01 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-DIVERSIFICATION-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS DEBATE THE PLUSES AND MINUSES OF DIVERSIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(mk) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What good is diversification, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   After years of injury, watching the nation's stocks handily
outperform foreign stocks, owners of globally diversified equity
portfolios last year suffered the insult of seeing the value of
nearly all their investments decline during the summer downturn.
When the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 12 percent in the
third quarter, stocks in places like Japan, Switzerland and Mexico
also fell, offering investors little, if any, downside protection.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was not the only year in which diversification seemed
to provide little value. Over the last three years, investors whose
portfolios contained only U.S. stocks would have had better returns
with less volatility, according to Frank Russell Co., a Tacoma,
Wash., money-management and investment-advisory concern. Those
investors would have seen average annual returns of 27 percent
through November, compared with gains of 21 percent for people who
put a third of their money in a mix of foreign stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, then, that a lot of people are questioning the
notion of diversification. Many individual investors are already
shunning overseas stocks, putting the bulk of their retirement
funds in domestic stocks. Even some professional investors are
throwing in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financial advisers seem to be abandoning this idea as fast as
clients,'' said Paul Solli, managing director of Financial Design
Associates, an investment advisory firm in Larkspur, Calif. And
some institutional investors, like pension funds, have been slow to
rebalance their portfolios by taking money away from the booming
domestic market and moving it overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The events of the last year have clearly underscored the limits
of diversification. With the domestic markets soaring, despite a
few drops along the way, any foreign exposure has tended to reduce
the overall returns. ``It's the ugly side of diversification,''
said George Sauter, a managing director for Vanguard Group, the
giant mutual fund company. And when a global shock like Russia's
bond default occurred, the tremors were felt everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of diversification say that the last few years
have been atypical. ``It's been an exceptionally unusual run in
U.S. equities,'' said Ernest Ankrim, director of portfolio research
for the investment management business at Frank Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most troubling aspect of the last few years _ world
markets that moved together, defeating the whole purpose of
diversification _ may be a short-lived phenomenon, according to
David Harding, director of global investments for
Nicholas-Applegate, an investment firm based in San Diego. ``You
have had these periods where there is higher correlation, and they
have not lasted,'' he said. For example, correlations between
domestic stocks and their foreign counterparts rose for a while,
and then dropped in 1987 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the United States, few need convincing that
diversification still makes sense. Asian investors who put some of
their money in the U.S. market or some of the European markets
clearly benefited.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask an investor in Singapore, he would reply that it
worked,'' Harding said.
</P>
<P>
   Diversification also makes sense because no one anywhere knows
what the future will bring. While the U.S. market has lately been
the best performer, it is unlikely to keep beating other markets,
analysts say. During other periods, foreign stocks have performed
better than domestic stocks: Over the 10 years ended Dec. 31, 1992,
for instance, Morgan Stanley Capital International Europe,
Australasia, Far East index, or EAFE, gained an average of 17.1
percent a year, versus 15.4 percent annual returns for the Wilshire
5000 index, a broad index of the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look back in history, there is no one asset that
dominates consistently,'' said Arthur Micheletti, chief economic
and investment strategist for Bailard, Biehl &AMP; Kaiser, a
money-management firm in San Mateo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   When will diversification become popular again among American
investors? The probable answer is only after they have watched
their solidly domestic portfolios trail foreign stocks _ which
strategists say could be sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``To abandon diversification in this environment,'' said Ankrim
of Frank Russell, ``would be the poorest decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
