<SLUG> BC-1999-TRAVEL-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL PRICE RISES AHEAD FOR ROAD WARRIORS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(DW) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time business travelers fly to their destinations, hop
into rental cars, check into hotels and sit down for meals, it will
most likely cost their employers 5 percent to 7 percent more than
it did last year. That is, if they are among the lucky ones who get
to travel at all.
</P>
<P>
   While even 5 percent would be almost double the 2.8 percent
inflation rate forecast for this year by PricewaterhouseCoopers,
corporate travel managers do not seem overly concerned, probably
because anywhere within that range would be an improvement over
last year's 8 percent rise over 1997 travel costs. If costs do
exceed expectations, corporations are not helpless to rein them in.
</P>
<P>
   For example, until the stock market started declining last
summer, corporate America had been content to impose travel
policies on employees at a measured pace. But by the fall that
gradual approach had become a gallop.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 450 major companies in October by the National
Business Travel Association found that 56 percent had cut back on
the number of employees who travel and 53 percent had replaced some
travel with videoconferencing and teleconferencing. In the wake of
big cutbacks recently announced by manufacturing companies and
financial institutions alike, there is every reason to assume that
travel costs will not escape corporate belt-tightening.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a preliminary projection of 1999 business travel
costs by American Express expects them to rise an average of 5
percent to 6 percent _ not much higher than the 4.8 percent rise
forecast by Runzheimer International, the management consulting
firm in Rochester, Wisc., and not much lower than the 7 percent
increase forecast by Travel One, the management company based in
Mount Laurel, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But the forecasters agree that all bets are off if, as American
Express put it, ``current economic turmoil overseas and stock
market instability in the United States translates into lower
demand for business travel.''
</P>
<P>
   A good many road warriors expect to see that lower demand. In a
recent survey of 1,348 frequent corporate travelers, compiled for
Business Travel News magazine by Plog Research Inc. of Reseda,
Calif., 49 percent said that they expected a decrease in company
travel this year and 56 percent expected a decrease in the number
of travelers.
</P>
<P>
   That survey did not pinpoint where the travelers expect the
decreases to come from, although the source of any substantial
savings is fairly obvious. Air travel accounts for 42 percent of
companies' travel and entertainment budget, according to American
Express, while meals and entertainment account for 22 percent,
lodging 21 percent and car rentals 8 percent. Communication and
miscellaneous items make up the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Since corporate travel managers know that, in the words of the
old adage, the place to go duck hunting is where the ducks are, the
most likely target for cutting costs _ on paper, at least _ is air
fares. Yet corporate travel managers do not expect air fares to
fall this year, although they disagree about how much they are
likely to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Runzheimer, for example, expects overall fares to rise an
average of 5.1 percent, but about 10 percent on the hundreds of
routes without nonstop competition. American Express has forecast
an average fare increase of 4 percent to 5 percent, while Travel
One expects domestic fares to jump a whopping 9 percent. It reasons
that airlines are in no big hurry to expand capacity even though
the number of passengers remains at record high levels, and that
except for Southwest Airlines and Pro Air in Detroit, low-cost
competitors have had little impact on business fares.
</P>
<P>
   If the forecasters are right, business fares to Europe will
increase about 6 percent, while fares to Asia and the Pacific
region may rise as much as 5 percent. While 5 percent is not out of
line with historic trans-Pacific fare increases, travel management
companies say any such rise this year will seem much higher in view
of the fact that just a few months ago some struggling Asian
airlines were practically giving away trans-Pacific tickets (many
of which were bought by American companies with business in Asia).
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the major airlines in the Asia-Pacific region survived
the 1998 economic crisis by restructuring routes and re-examining
capital expenditures to decrease operating expenses,'' said Clint
Cable, general manager of that region for Rosenbluth International,
the Philadelphia travel management company.
</P>
<P>
   The forecasters expect car rental prices to rise between 5
percent and 8 percent, the result of a combination of higher rates,
insurance, airport fees and surtaxes imposed by cities; for
example, Houston's average surcharge for midsized car rentals has
risen 24 percent since 1997, according to American Express.
According to Michael Boult, director of supplier relations for
Rosenbluth, ``Car rental is also a convenient target for higher
Federal, state and local taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   The only break business travelers can count on are in restaurant
prices, which none of the forecasters expect to rise more than
about 2.5 percent. But given the large percentage of travel budgets
spent on meals and entertainment, corporations are still paying
close attention. Most of this scrutiny is in the form of spending
limits, but some companies are going beyond that. One major
midwestern company, for example, not only scrutinizes the
entertainment portion of expense accounts, but occasionally
contacts guests whose names appear on expense accounts _ ostensibly
to inquire if they found the food and service satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel rates have been climbing for several years and show no
signs of stopping or even slowing down. PricewaterhouseCoopers
projects a 3.9 percent increase, to $81.77 a night, an average that
includes budget and economy motels. For business travelers, though,
American Express forecasts a jump of 7 percent to 10 percent in the
top 25 business cities, while Runzheimer expects rates in downtown
hotels will rise about 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, New York's room rate has averaged $245 for several
months, 15 percent higher than in 1997, according to
PricewaterhouseCoopers, while a standard room at a luxury New York
hotel has ranged between $350 and $700 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Sky-high room rates and sky-high occupancies are also pretty
much the outlook for 1999 in Boston, Chicago, Los Angeles, San
Francisco, Washington, and other major cities _ depending, of
course, on the stock market's gyrations and the global economic
health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
