<HEADER>
A4684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBRARIES-ART-NYT &LR;      01-01 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBRARIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPARING NEW YORK, LONDON AND PARIS: A SIMPLE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the year of the library. Last summer, London inaugurated
the new British Library; in October, Paris witnessed the grand
opening of the new National Library of France; the next month the
New York Public Library unveiled its renovation of the Main Reading
Room at its flagship 42nd Street branch.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of millions of dollars were spent as the years went by.
So, now that their doors are open, which is the best?
</P>
<P>
   With help from Alan Riding in Paris, Sarah Lyall in London and
Joyce Jensen in New York, The New York Times undertook a completely
unscientific and unofficial comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation of the New York Public Library's 85-year-old
reading room was by far the most modest of the endeavors, and the
only one that was privately financed: the real estate developer
Frederick Rose and his wife, Sylvia, paid for the make-over. It
took 16 months and cost $15 million. Richly colored murals,
sculptured ceilings dripping with gold leaf and big windows
prompted one veteran user to call it ``the Versailles of New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   The British Library at King's Cross, which took 36 years and
$843 million to complete, threatened to become one of the biggest
white elephants London had ever seen. But it opened to rave
reviews, winning praise for its imagination and detail, from its
soaring airy spaces to its automatically adjusting lighting.
</P>
<P>
   The National Library of France, which took 10 years and cost
$1.5 billion, was promoted as ``the first library of the third
millennium.'' Almost immediately after its October opening, a major
breakdown of the computer controlling the delivery of books to
researchers was followed by a strike of 800 members of the
library's 2,800-member staff. The strike was settled after 17 days,
but the research area will be closed on Sundays and Mondays through
Jan. 31 and on Sunday and Monday mornings through June 30 while the
library further tests its computers and trains its staff.
Researchers are not happy, but prefer this to a complete shutdown
of the research area. (The public area is working well and is open
daily except on Mondays.) And because of the computer problems, the
automatic delivery of books within 20 minutes has been suspended.
</P>
<P>
   The National Library of France was the snootiest (no place to
even ask a research question) and also served the worst food
(although the New York Public Library avoided this question
altogether by not serving any food inside the building).
</P>
<P>
   For the key comparison _ waiting time for books _ the libraries
were asked to produce a classic work of fiction, ``I Promessi
Sposi,'' by Alessandro Manzoni, and one of nonfiction,
``Civilization of the Renaissance in Italy,'' by Jacob Burckhardt.
(The Manzoni was written in Italian, the Burckhardt in German, so
there would be no hometown language advantage.)
</P>
<P>
   The race opened with New York and London neck and neck:
Burckhardt made it out of the stacks a bit more quickly in London
than in New York, but the British Library suffered a heartbreaking
setback when an unusual glitch delayed the arrival of the Manzoni
for hours. Alas, Paris, because of its human and mechanical woes,
was left at the starter's gate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
