<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4687 &Cx1f; taf-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-HMOS-$ADV04-925&AMP;     01-01 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-HMOS-$ADV04-925&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMOS ARE SET FOR MANY MORE MERGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(lb) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is bound to be a better year for the health-care industry
than 1998, which, to borrow Queen Elizabeth's mournful phrase, was
an annus horribilis for some of the United States' biggest
insurance, hospital and physician practice companies.
</P>
<P>
   After several years of mediocre earnings, and only small
increases in profits last year, many big health-maintenance
organizations have raised premiums 8 percent to 20 percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The managed-care companies are racing to push their revenue
ahead of the growing cost of care, especially for heavily
advertised prescription drugs, as well as new surgical equipment
and more consultations, tests and referrals to specialists by
physicians. Incomes of many types of doctors continued to rise last
year, and hospitals, with notable exceptions, thrived.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs generally set their monthly premium charges based on
estimates extrapolated from past experience. Seriously misjudging
costs, as several big companies did last year, invites financial
trouble _ premiums typically cannot be raised again until the
following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the managed-care industry's losses in 1998 are worse than
expected, 1999 is unlikely to be a stellar year _ the early 1999
pricing is already locked in,'' said Arun Kumar, a director of
Standard &AMP; Poor's. ``It will probably be a break-even year, with
small profits, if any at all.''
</P>
<P>
   And Robert Reischauer, former director of the Congressional
Budget Office and now a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution,
said employers might resist HMO price increases now that growth in
corporate profits is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   The difficult conditions are likely to be reflected in another
round of health-care mergers and acquisitions. Aetna Inc. agreed
last month to buy the Prudential Health Care unit of Prudential
Insurance Co. of America, making Aetna the nation's biggest
managed-care company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some recognizable players won't be here in a year _ they will
be absorbed by other companies,'' said Dr. Peter Kongstvedt, a
partner in the Washington office of Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
   Several of last year's big losers are still not out of the
woods. ``There are alarming signs of fragility in the corporate
health-care sector in an otherwise strong economy,'' said Jeff
Goldsmith, an independent consultant based in Charlottesville, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Permanente, the nation's biggest HMO, with 9 million
members, reported big financial losses for the second consecutive
year. (It is, however, projecting a tiny profit in 1999.) Oxford
Health Plans, one of the largest HMOs in the New York region, was
also struggling with red ink. And state regulators in New Jersey
recently took control of the 194,000-member HIP Health Plan of New
Jersey, the troubled unit of Health Insurance Plan of Greater New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals, too, have had some rough times. Columbia/HCA
Healthcare Corp., the nation's biggest for-profit hospital chain,
was still struggling to shed unprofitable units, regain the
confidence of customers and investors, and settle government
charges that fraudulently inflated expenses were charged to
Medicare and other government programs.
</P>
<P>
   The government also joined a lawsuit last year based on similar
charges against Quorum Health Group Inc., another hospital company.
</P>
<P>
   In Pennsylvania, the 13-hospital nonprofit Allegheny Health,
Education and Research Foundation system filed for bankruptcy
protection in July. Tenet Healthcare Corp., a for-profit hospital
chain, agreed to buy eight Allegheny hospitals in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   There was also trouble for companies that bought the practices
of physicians. Medpartners Inc., once a high-flying player in
physician practice management, left that business, casting doubt on
the ability of physician groups to meet Wall Street demands for
quarterly earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance premiums are again rising more rapidly. And that means
employers will be paying more for care, adding to pressure on
profits and, potentially, prices.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who pay for their own care faced especially steep
increases in monthly premiums. The alternative was to pray for good
health and go without insurance. The pool of uninsured people
continued to rise by more than 1 million annually, to 43.1 million
in 1997, the latest information available from the Census Bureau.
The increase also reflected overall population growth and welfare
policies that forced millions of low-income people off state
Medicaid rosters.
</P>
<P>
   Economists, while admitting that they often misjudged the
strength of the economy, said a general slowdown would swell the
ranks of the uninsured and add to pressures on Medicaid, which is a
major, if not the largest, item in most state budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Growth in federal payments for Medicare has also slowed, cutting
into a formerly lucrative business for many managed-care companies.
Last year, HMOs in 30 states announced they were leaving
unprofitable Medicare markets, forcing more than 440,000 elderly
Americans to scramble to replace their coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar of Standard &AMP; Poor's said a ``legislative backlash'' might
try to restrain managed-care companies from exiting certain markets
by threatening to blackball them statewide.
</P>
<P>
   On another cost-sensitive front, recent federal laws are
straining the computerized information systems of health plans just
as computer problems related to the year 2000 are casting a broad
shadow, Kongstvedt of Ernst &AMP; Young said. The HMOs must computerize
their Medicare systems and must also track measures intended to
show the quality of care they provide.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We will know in 1999 whether the health plans and Blue Cross
plans will be able to make it past the year 2000 problems,''
Kongstvedt said. If their computer systems cannot distinguish
between the new year and 00, meaning 1900, they may have to go to
outside contractors for information services.
</P>
<P>
   The HMOs would also be vulnerable to computer glitches at the
federal Medicare financing agency, state Medicaid programs and
managed-care drug companies, and in the records and billing systems
of hospitals and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Adding yet another big uncertainty for managed-care companies,
lobbyists for doctors and consumers have pushed through
patient-protection laws and regulations in most states that the
health-maintenance organizations say will raise their costs.
Similar proposals are likely to be revived in Congress, where they
were blocked last year by insurance and employer lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs were manipulated ``into doing the job that most other
companies have to do for themselves'' _ squeezing down expensive
services, said Ian Morrison, a health-care consultant and senior
fellow at the Institute for the Future in Menlo Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are going to regulate them and prevent them from doing
the things they were supposed to be doing in the first place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
