<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4692 &Cx1f; taf-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-ECON-$ADV04-NYT-     01-01 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-ECON-$ADV04-NYT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD ECONOMIES ON A TIGHTROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(rl) 
 By SYLVIA NASAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last fall, with global financial markets imploding and recession
fears rampant, Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve,
told a group of business forecasters that he had been ``looking at
the American economy on a day-by-day basis for almost half a
century'' but had ``never seen anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even Greenspan could have foreseen the chain reaction that
began with a currency crisis in tiny Thailand. Who would have
thought that stock markets as distant as Moscow, Rio de Janeiro and
New York would tumble like dominoes? Or that an avalanche of
bankruptcies and the near collapse of the high-flying hedge fund
Long-Term Capital Management would follow and credit markets around
the world would virtually freeze up? Or that a series of three
modest interest-rate reductions by the Fed _ and similar actions by
its counterparts abroad _ would restore calm and confidence in a
matter of weeks?
</P>
<P>
   Predicting the economy's ups and downs has always been tricky.
</P>
<P>
   History is full of famously wrong forecasts, from the economist
Irving Fisher's assertions throughout the Depression that recovery
was imminent, to Greenspan's statements two months after the 1990
recession began that chances of a downturn were minimal.
</P>
<P>
   A 25-year study by the National Bureau of Economic Research, a
private group in Cambridge, Mass., concludes that growth estimates
for the year ahead typically err by 100 percent or more and that,
computer age or no, they have become no more accurate over time.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when economists were sure a slowdown was in the
works, proved a case in point: growth was much faster and inflation
and unemployment stayed much lower than predicted.
</P>
<P>
   What now? The economic expansion that began in 1991 is about to
become the second-longest since America entered the industrial age
in the late 19th century. This alone suggests that the likelihood
of recession is rising, but almost no one is predicting one in the
foreseeable future. And even economists at J.P. Morgan, one of the
few bears, say such a downturn will be ``the shortest and mildest
recession we've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most economists say that this year is going to look the
way they thought 1998 would look. Growth is supposed to slow
sharply, profits to shrink, inflation to creep up, unemployment to
edge up a bit. The Blue Chip consensus of 50 forecasters expects
growth to slow to 2.2 percent, compared with 3.7 percent last year,
and inflation to accelerate to 2.2 percent from 1.6 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they may be wrong. But that is exactly the kind of soft
landing that Greenspan and other central bankers have been hoping
for.
</P>
<P>
   Three forces, economists say, may bring it about: a sluggish
world economy, a growing profit squeeze and a less than ebullient
stock market. The unsettled global economy should continue to drag
down growth in the United States. Merrill Lynch expects growth in
the 45 biggest economies to slow to just over 1.25 percent, from
3.5 percent in 1997 and 1.75 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's economies, which absorb a third of American exports, are
likely to keep shrinking, though not as fast as last year _
assuming that Japan will hit bottom. South America, which accounts
for one-tenth of American exports, will merely stagnate as long as
Brazil doesn't collapse; growth for the continent should be around
1 percent. Mexico, as big a trading partner as South America and
struggling with the effects of plunging oil prices, is already
slowing. As monetary union begins, Europe will be growing about 2
percent, down from nearly 3 percent last year. Some of the biggest
risks from abroad continue to be financial.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpectedly aggressive easing by the Federal Reserve and
foreign central banks has reduced but not eliminated the global
liquidity squeeze. Even now, AAA-rated corporate bonds are still
more than 2 percentage points over Treasury bonds, only slightly
below the recent peak spread of 2.25 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``While equity markets are roaring ahead, credit markets are
still depressed,'' said Bruce Steinberg, chief economist at Merrill
Lynch. ``That will slow growth because the marginal borrower is not
able to get credit.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing pinch on corporate profits, already under way in the
last six months, is also likely to retard growth. Per-share
operating profits for the companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index are down 3 percent from a year ago. Total corporate
profits reported by the Commerce Department are also lower than a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Profit margins are beginning to erode, and there is no relief in
sight. The problem is that incredibly tight labor markets _
unemployment is now 4.4 percent and job growth remains solid _ have
been pushing wages up faster than robust productivity gains. Thus,
labor costs per unit of output have been rising inexorably. With
lots of excess capacity at home and abroad, a result of the 1990s
investment boom, most companies are finding it impossible to pass
along higher costs to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pricing power out there in corporate America right
now,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the stock market is not likely to give the economy much
extra kick, the way it has in recent years. Although stock prices
no longer look as outrageously high as they did a year ago,
somewhat lowering the risk of a plunge, few forecasters expect
American households to keep reaping the huge capital gains that
have propelled spending faster than income.
</P>
<P>
   Economists expect these forces to affect individual parts of the
economy in various ways. The trade deficit will continue to widen,
but, barring another international crisis like last summer's, the
deterioration is not likely to be as sharp as it was in the last
year, when it shaved 1.5 percentage points from growth. This is in
part because slower growth in business and consumer spending means
less of a surge in imports.
</P>
<P>
   Capital spending, booming in the first half of last year, has
already flattened. Most economists are predicting sluggish growth,
but not outright cuts in spending, in the 12 months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   One factor that may cause spending to keep rising is that
capital is a bargain right now. ``I can buy more,'' said Ken
Matheny, an economist at Macroeconomic Advisers in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Government has not contributed much to spending in the last few
years, and 1999 will be no exception, despite a small lift from the
$500-per-child tax credit and the emergency spending measure passed
in October to skirt the spending caps.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, who have been spending all their income and more, are
due to behave in a more restrained manner. They have been on a
tear, with car sales stronger last year than at any other time in
the last decade. Most economists expect consumer spending to grow
about 2.5 percent this year, about half of last year's pace and
roughly in line with income growth. One reason is that job growth
is apt to slow as the profit picture continues to darken.
</P>
<P>
   But Ken Goldstein, an economist at the Conference Board, one of
the most bullish forecasting groups last year, says consumers will
surprise forecasters once more. He says last fall's rash of layoff
announcements by Fortune 500 companies has led to an exaggerated
sense of how fast the labor market is weakening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hullabaloo about layoffs is ridiculous,'' Goldstein said.
Most job cuts since 1991 have been by attrition, he added. And
first-time claims for unemployment insurance were no higher in
December than they were a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The red-hot housing market is also set to cool. It is still in
great shape, with new construction of single-family homes running
at its most rapid pace in 20 years. But few people expect mortgage
rates, already the lowest in a generation, to keep falling, so
fewer families will be refinancing. And fewer families will be
cashing in stock market gains to renovate or trade up. Besides,
housing starts have been outpacing family formation for several
years.
</P>
<P>
   With all the uncertainties, the only sure thing is that things
will not turn out precisely as predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Arrow, a Nobel laureate in economic science, likes to
tell his students the story of a group of statisticians (of which
he was one) in the Pentagon during World War II who were
responsible for forecasting the number of rainy days in Europe a
month ahead of time. At some point, the statisticians concluded
that the forecasts were worthless and asked Gen. Henry H. ``Hap''
Arnold, chief of the Army Air Forces, for permission to stop making
them. After a few weeks the following reply came from Arnold: ``The
commanding general is well aware that the forecasts are no good.
However, he has to have them for planning purposes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 1744EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
