<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4693 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-STRATEGIES-$AD     01-01 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-STRATEGIES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRATEGIES: TO FORECAST 1999, DON'T DWELL ON '98
</HEADLINE>
 Mark Hulbert is editor of the Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Alexandria, Va. His column on investment
strategies appears every other week. 
E-mail: strategy(AT)nytimes.com. 
(For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(bl) 
By MARK HULBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm going to break with the tradition of most year-end market
retrospectives, which tend to highlight a few of last year's events
and pontificate on their grand significance for the new year.
Instead, I will argue that most of what shook the markets in 1998
has little or no significance for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, the stock market suffered its most severe
correction in years, but that tells us nothing about what stocks
will do this year. Nor is the crystal ball brought more sharply
into focus for knowing that small-capitalization stocks were
massacred in the first three quarters of 1998 before coming to life
again in the last three months. The same goes for virtually every
other event that has received so much attention in year-end
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Let me hasten to add I do not think the markets are entirely
random. They aren't. But we need to rise above the statistical
noise of the market's month-to-month and even year-to-year
gyrations, and to focus on developments that are much more
long-term.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the meaning of last year's correction. According to my
reading of data from Ibbotson Associates, a Chicago research firm,
we are neither more nor less likely to experience a correction or
bear market in 1999 because of the summer selloff of 1998. We can
make that conclusion by going back much further _ to 1925, in fact
_ and examining the market's historical performance over seven
decades.
</P>
<P>
   In all the years since 1925 that followed a correction of at
least 10 percent, the market has produced an average gain of 11.8
percent a year and has risen 65 percent of the time. Those figures,
however, are not all that different from the market's overall
averages: During all the years since 1925, the market has returned
an annual average of 13 percent and risen 70 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you might say, consider the performance of small- and
large-cap stocks. Don't year-over-year trends in their relative
performance tend to persist? That's the conventional wisdom, but I
wouldn't bet the house on it.
</P>
<P>
   It is true, according to the Ibbotson data, that there is a
slightly-better-than-even chance that the relative performance of
small caps in any given year will be the same as in the previous
year. But it is not as well known that the pattern is heavily
dependent upon 10 of the last 75 years _ the period from 1974
through 1983, a period in which small caps outperformed large caps
every year. If you take away that decade, the statistical basis for
the conventional wisdom essentially disappears, and you are left
with a random relationship between the year-to-year relative
performances of small- and large-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   My skepticism about short-term phenomena extends to the track
records of financial advisers, too. This month, many investors will
choose a mutual fund, pension fund or newsletter on the basis of
how it performed in 1998. Who can blame them, with the financial
press inundating them with myriad lists of the best and worst of
1998? But one year is not nearly enough to separate those advisers
and managers with genuine ability from those who are merely lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a hypothetical portfolio that always invested in the
previous year's market-beating newsletters. Specifically, imagine a
portfolio that every year would be divided equally among all
newsletters that beat the market the previous year. For the 18
years that I have monitored the newsletter industry, such a
portfolio would have made a dismal 6.8 percent annualized return _
about what you could have earned in a money market fund. The stock
market itself gained 16.4 percent a year, on average, over this
period.
</P>
<P>
   Not all track records, however, are this unhelpful. My research
shows that past performance is meaningful only when measured over
periods of more than five years, and preferably more than 10.
</P>
<P>
   It thus makes more sense for investors to pay attention to what
the top-performing newsletters are saying over the long term. On
balance, they are cautiously bullish, with an average recommended
equity exposure of 60 percent. Only one of the top five _ Fabian
Premium Investment Resource _ advocates full investment; another,
Dow Theory Letters, is outright bearish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
