<SLUG> BC-1999-AD-COLUMN-$ADV04-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MORE MERGERMANIA  
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(ART ADV: Graphic on U.S. ad spending is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A year ago, Madison Avenue was asking: Will 1998 be
as busy a year for agency and account acquisitions and
consolidations as 1996 and 1997 were?
</P>
<P>
   Now, after enduring another frenetic 12 months, Madison Avenue
is asking another question: How could anyone have even asked that
question? As a result, few are asking the question about 1999; the
tumult of the last three years is widely expected to keep on
keeping on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace of acquisitions will continue,'' said Lauren Rich
Fine, an analyst who follows advertising for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. in
New York. ``Some of that stems from the large agencies' need for
market share growth that clients alone can't satisfy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you get market share growth,'' she added, ``that can
stave off any uncertainties about what clients will do'' about
their ad budgets for the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Vick, president and chief operating officer at Young &AMP;
Rubicam Inc. in New York, echoed Ms. Fine. ``The consolidation of
agencies is not over by any means,'' he said. ``There's no doubt
the multinational communications companies will continue to get
bigger and stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   As mergermania rages, said Edward Meyer, chairman, president and
chief executive at Grey Advertising in New York, ``we're all
focusing much more of our attention on marketing services'' outside
the realm of traditional advertising like direct marketing, sales
promotion and media buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made three acquisitions in the media business in the
last year,'' Meyer added, ``and we're in there trying to buy
whatever is still around.''
</P>
<P>
   James Dougherty, advertising industry analyst at Prudential
Securities in New York, said he agreed that deals in marketing
services ``and other specialty communications will clearly
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   That will come, he added, as spending for advertising and
marketing campaigns remains relatively strong.
</P>
<P>
   Despite dislocations in local economies, ``I think the
advertising industry's rolling,'' Dougherty said. ``While there are
some soft pockets, there are no really serious signs that
conditions in 1999 will be materially different from 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason he gave was that ``you now have a real engine
of growth in the United States,'' where ad spending is rising at a
higher rate than overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``One percent growth in the United States,'' Dougherty said,
``is worth a lot of Taiwans.'' America is the world's largest
single advertising market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marketers, the guys who make stuff, have already gone through
growing profits by lowering costs and saving money,'' said Alan
Gottesman, managing director at West End Communications/Consulting
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the way to grow profits has shifted from saving more to
earning more,'' he added, ``and the way to earn more is to sell
more stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will drive marketing service companies' revenues over the
next couple of years,'' Gottesman predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like saying, `The answer is up; what was the
question?''' he said, chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Russell, an industry analyst for Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter in New York, listed three reasons he was optimistic about ad
spending in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   One is ``the continuing thrust from the pharmaceutical
industry,'' he said, to advertise prescription drugs directly to
consumers. The second is the growing number of campaigns to
discourage smoking that are sponsored by state and federal
governments. The third reason is the rising demand for Internet
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is not interesting as a percentage of total ad
spending,'' Russell said, ``because it seems to be 1 percent for
every business. But its very growth makes it interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick at Y&AMP;R said he believed that ``the rate at which electronic
commerce transactions take place on the Web will triple by the end
of next year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not only because of the technological explosion,'' he
added, ``but because people will finally realize their Visa is no
less secure online than at the Gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Some anticipate that conditions for the advertising industry
will improve further in the final months of 1999 as the year 2000
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have an Olympics and a presidential election in 2000,''
Dougherty of Prudential said, both of which stimulate demand for
commercial time and ad space, ``and the millennium on top of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer at Grey is also bullish on the millennium, predicting that
it will generate significant spending in the form of contests,
sweepstakes and other promotional pitches.
</P>
<P>
   As for what advertisers will tell consumers about 2000, ``the
messages will run the gamut,'' Meyer said, ``from boring
seriousness to outrageous mockery.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. In other words, not unlike advertising before the
millennium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
