<SLUG> BC-INVEST-AUTORACING-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING ALONG FOR THE RIDE IN THE AUTO RACING RUSH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., N.C.) (For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(bl) 
By VIRGINIA MUNGER KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball, basketball, hockey _ such is the televised fare on
which American couch potatoes have long gorged themselves. But
these days, it is auto racing that captures more TV viewers than
any sport except football, according to A.C. Nielsen, the ratings
company.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, attendance at auto races is growing at the breakneck
pace of 10.5 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, auto racing stocks roared ahead 31.3 percent, according
to Wheat First Union, a brokerage firm in Richmond. That compares
with a 26.7 percent gain for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
and a 3.5 percent loss for the Russell 2000 over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The run-up has everything to do with shifting tastes. Once
perceived as a working-class pastime in the Southeast's tobacco
belt, auto racing has gone national, and fancy new facilities are
being built in large markets from Fort Worth to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, television networks have been paying more for the
rights to broadcast the races. The rights to broadcast the three
dozen races in the Winston Cup _ the premier stock car racing
series _ generated $79 million in broadcast fees last year,
according to Tom Thomson, an analyst at Wheat First Union, up from
$49 million in 1997. For 1999, he expects $93 million.
</P>
<P>
   Investors can gain exposure to racing by buying the shares of
track owners. ``The way the business is structured is very
favorable,'' said Scott Barry, an analyst at Raymond James &AMP;
Associates. ``These are wildly profitable companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The blue chip is International Speedway, of Daytona Beach, Fla.,
which owns the track where the Daytona 500 is run. The company is
headed by Bill France Jr., who is also chief executive of NASCAR,
the National Association for Stock Car Racing, the sanctioning body
that awards Winston Cup race dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we have the best company in the group with
International Speedway,'' said Scott Swanson, an analyst at Roger
Engemann &AMP; Associates, a money management firm in Pasadena, Calif.,
that owns 350,000 shares of the company. The stock, which closed
Thursday at $40.50, sells for 36.8 times 1999 projected earnings of
$1.10 a share. Swanson said the stock could reach $45 or more in
the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway Motorsports, based in Harrisburg, N.C., has the same
number of Winston Cup race dates as International Speedway _ 10.
But its tracks have more seating, the source of its higher margins
_ 19.5 percent, according to Thomson, whose firm holds a seat on
the company's board. Barry calculates the group's average net
profit margin at 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway Motorsports stock closed at $28.50 last week. Thomson's
12-month target is $42.
</P>
<P>
   Penske Motorsports, run by Roger Penske, the former driver who
built a network of automotive companies, has struggled this year as
a result of declining attendance at Indianapolis 500-type race
events. These races, which feature so-called ``open wheel'' race
cars, are not as popular as the NASCAr variety. Still, some
analysts think that Penske, now trading at $26.625, has more
potential for investors than Speedway Motorsports. Barry has a
12-month price target of $32 on Penske.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are risks in the sector. Weather-related delays
in races can hurt television ratings, raise costs and depress
earnings. The small-capitalization stocks are volatile, and they
tend to run up before the start of the racing season in February,
Barry said. Best to wait until April or May, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 1755EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
