<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Jan. 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Windswept heavy snow will lash a large area from the central
Mississippi Valley through the southern Great Lakes as low pressure
moves northeast from the lower Mississippi Valley. The strong winds
will cause blowing and drifting of the snow, reducing visibility to
near zero at times.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, snow will mix with ice over southern Indiana to
southern Ohio as warm air arrives a few thousand feet above the
ground. South of the Ohio River mainly rain will fall as strong
breezes from the south develop.
</P>
<P>
   Bands of potent thunderstorms with heavy rain and a few
tornadoes will sweep east from the southern Mississippi Valley as a
cold front surges into the region. Behind the front, colder and
drier air will spread from the southern Plains to the western Gulf
of Mexico coast.
</P>
<P>
   After a frigid dawn in the Northeast, clouds will increase.
Light snow will spread from the eastern Ohio valley on Saturday
morning to southern New England on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, patches of freezing rain and sleet will develop
near the southern Appalachians, where a shallow layer of cold air
will be overrun by warmer air. Any ice will change to rain
throughout the Southeast and Middle Atlantic States by Saturday
night, as mild winds from the Atlantic increase.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, heavier snow will mix with ice on Saturday night
while coastal areas of southern New England have a change to rain.
Increasing onshore winds will cause coastal flooding from the
Carolinas to New England.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, mainly dry weather will prevail. Offshore winds
will keep the California coast unusually warm.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Cold Funnels
</P>
<P>
   Cold-air funnel clouds descended ominously from the clouds over
Lake Champlain on Friday. Cold-air funnels are typically innocuous,
hovering like alien spacecraft and seldom lowering to the ground.
Unlike tornadoes, which rely on steamy surface air to initiate
thunderstorms that spawn twisters, cold-air funnels form despite a
lack of sultry air near the ground. Instead, they depend on pools
of cold air several thousand feet aloft to promote rising, rotating
columns of air. As pressure lowers in the spinning column,
condensation occurs just below cloud base, revealing the funnel
cloud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
