<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4700 &Cx1f; taf-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-NEWSPAPERS-$ADV0     01-01 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-NEWSPAPERS-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPERS ARE TRYING NEW MARKETING TECHNIQUES TO WIN LOYAL
READERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., Texas, Ariz., N.C.) (For release on Monday, Jan. 4)  
(nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most newspapers, the numbers game played out in the
twice-yearly audited circulation figures has been a losing
proposition for the last 14 years. The figures, which are often
considered a basic measurement of the industry's economic health,
have dwindled more than 10 percent, to slightly more than 56.7
million copies from a peak in 1984 of 63.4 million newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, reactions have ranged from a heavy dose of
price-cutting to a willingness to exercise unused marketing
muscles. But this year a new set of remedies is being readied as
some newspapers prepare to sell themselves in different ways and
different places on different days. Others are enlisting the people
in their circulation area as partners in their marketing drives.
</P>
<P>
   To find the latter strategy one need only head to New England,
to the Blackstone Valley area of Rhode Island. There, The
Providence Journal is betting that the devotion of communities to
their high school athletes can translate into permanent circulation
gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal, bought (along with nine television stations) in
1997 by the A.H. Belo Corp. of Dallas for $1.5 billion, is not
fiddling around with its pricing. Its cover price has been 50 cents
since August 1990. Instead, it is looking for targeted sports
coverage to produce targeted circulation gains.
</P>
<P>
   A pilot program last spring to marry sports coverage, marketing
and circulation is becoming routine this winter. It gives high
school athletic directors a chance to propose which of their
athletes should be profiled in articles designed for the editions
delivered to the neighborhoods around the school.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the newspaper interviewed and profiled the teen-age
volleyball or baseball or soccer players every Tuesday and
Thursday. Before publication, high school assembly announcements
mentioned the upcoming articles. Stores and newspaper boxes in the
neighborhood heavily promoted the player profiles. The work was
recognized as a largely promotional vehicle; the athletes sign
legal releases before participating in the interviews and photo
sessions, according to Peter Phipps, the newspaper's deputy
managing editor.
</P>
<P>
   Such blending of journalism and marketing has been taboo at many
newspapers, but the economic payoff was quick: The pilot program
pushed single-copy sales up 7 percent, about 250 copies, according
to Michael Dooley, the Journal's circulation director.
</P>
<P>
   And the new readers appear hooked; The paper has held on to
those circulation gains, helping stem a long-term decline that has
left the Journal with a daily circulation of 167,381 _ down about
24 percent from its daily peak of 219,000 in 1982. This year, the
program is being moved to the areas around Pawtucket and Woonsocket
in the Blackstone Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal, like many other newspapers, is also working to keep
subscriber revenues steady by asking home-delivery subscribers to
pay and renew by leaving credit card information on file with the
company. The number of subscribers who pay by credit card is still
small _ 7,000 out of more than 125,000 subscribers _ but it is more
than double the 3,000 of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, there is the same kind of credit card push, and the
circulation strategies are becoming more complex and
computer-dependent. Leon Levitt, the circulation director for The
Arizona Republic, said he was trying to make it more attractive for
subscribers to renew by using the growing data base of demographic
and economic information on its customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Republic wants to use data it gathers on subscribers to
decide, for instance, which readers would stay with the paper if
their discounted $2.25-a-week offer were continued, and which
readers would continue to take the paper even when the introductory
offer ends and the $3.80-a-week rate starts. After it kicks in, it
may also mean giving away papers to lower-income subscribers for
two months to win their loyalty, Levitt said.
</P>
<P>
   While The Republic is in a market most of Levitt's peers would
envy _ booming with new residents _ its circulation growth has not
kept pace with the region's population growth, he said. As of Sept.
30, it was selling an average of 435,330 copies daily and 553,495
on Sundays, down about two-tenths of a percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Another option being tried by several newspapers _ including The
Republic, which is owned by Central Newspapers Inc., and The
Charlotte Observer, owned by Knight Ridder _ is finding new
middlemen. Apartment managers take out subscriptions at a discount,
and they in turn offer it to tenants as part of the rent. In other
programs, customers pay for cable and newspaper service in one
bill.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from the bygone days of the newsboy collecting
quarters door to door. But John Murray, vice president of
circulation marketing for the Newspaper Association of America,
points out that the Internet, like television, is creating a
generation of news consumers with no habit of paying for the
product. This, he said, makes direct payment increasingly
problematic. More of the cost, he believes, will be borne by
advertisers _ who already provide about three-quarters of the
industry's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The Republic is also refining another strategy, though it is not
quite ready to put it into action. Instead of the old trio of
subscription options _ Monday through Saturday, Monday through
Sunday and Sunday only _ he wants to experiment with
have-it-your-day offerings. For someone who does not want to read
the paper on Monday or Tuesday but wants the grocery coupons on
Wednesday or Thursday or the entertainment news on Friday, why not
a Wednesday-Thursday-Friday-Sunday subscription?
</P>
<P>
   ``Up till now, we've been in the habit of doing things for our
convenience,'' not the customer's, he said, adding that the key is
developing an electronic route list that can change daily and that
carriers can download in the predawn hours before they begin their
routes. There is even talk, he said, that porch delivery _ as
opposed to leaving a paper at curbside _ could be offered for a
premium.
</P>
<P>
   Like the days of delivery, the bundle of paper delivered may
also be streamlined to suit the customer, he said. ``The biggest
stopper any salesman gets,'' Levitt said, ``is people saying they
have no time to read. We've been almost our own worst enemy. The
product gets bigger and bigger with more bulk, and that's not what
people want.'' Electronic route lists, based on refined subscriber
data bases, could shrink the pile of daily inserts. ``Advertisers
could give inserts for just people with pools or just people who
wear glasses,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
