<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4701 &Cx1f; taf-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-BRITAIN-$ADV04-5     01-01 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-BRITAIN-$ADV04-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR EUROPEAN COUNTRIES STAY OUT OF MONETARY UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(lb) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The European Union's single currency, the euro, was
meant as an act of unification. But initially at least, it has
created a division among the 15 member nations.
</P>
<P>
   While 11 of the nations are in the monetary union, four _
Britain, Denmark, Greece and Sweden _ are not. And that means a
bumpy adjustment for all of them. Effectively, the four ``out''
countries have forfeited direct influence over the currency's
evolution; yet such is the scale of the new currency _ second only
to the U.S. dollar _ that it will transform markets and trade
throughout the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four, only Greece _ which, as the European Union's
weakest economy, failed to meet the criteria for the euro _ would
have preferred to tie its currency, the drachma, to the euro. Like
other southern European nations, Greece sought to hitch its economy
to the powerhouses of France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In northern Europe, however, the view of the euro is quite
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe tends to be viewed as a good thing if you are, for
example, one of the southern countries where there's a clear
economic benefit from European Union transfers and lower interest
rates,'' said Katharina Hoyland, an economist with J.P. Morgan &AMP;
Co. ``The political and economic benefits are much less obvious
from a Scandinavian perspective, where there are some concerns that
as a small country they'll lose sovereignty to Brussels.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are certain to be economic reverberations for the
four countries as their currencies fluctuate in value against the
euro.
</P>
<P>
   Though Denmark has an agreement with the European Central Bank
to support its currency, the krone, within a narrow band against
the euro, all three of the northern countries had currency problems
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The economic crisis in Russia exposed the Danish and Swedish
currencies to market jitters in September, forcing the Danish
central bank to intervene and raise interest rates, while the
Swedish currency sank in value. British exporters have complained
that their ability to compete has been hurt by the strength of the
pound against the German mark, the strongest currency in the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The four nations are expected to pay a premium for remaining
outside the monetary union, in the form of higher interest rates.
The risk is least acute in Denmark, which has pegged its rates _
currently 3.5 percent _ to euro averages. In Sweden, the deputy
central bank governor, Lars Heikensten, said his country was ``in
no hurry'' to lower its short-term benchmark from 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's interest rate is 6.25 percent, despite three rate cuts
in three months. Greece, always an economic and political maverick
in the union's affairs, has the highest rate of all, 12.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 euro nations agreed last month to start the euro with an
interest-rate target of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the risk that foreign investors in Europe will
shun nations outside the monetary union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine you are a United States investor and you look at the
euro area and say, `This is a great consumer market,''' said Cyril
Blesson, an economist with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``Everything
else being equal, would you invest outside it? No.''
</P>
<P>
   That is an issue even for Britain, which has long attracted
investment and business from the Continent because of its cheaper
skilled labor and lower taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The broader question is whether being out is going to make
investors want to locate somewhere in the euro area rather than in
London,'' said David Mackie, an economist with J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The debate over the euro is being closely watched in Britain,
which has the largest economy of the four outside countries. Some
economists see advantages in remaining outside the monetary union
at a time when British short-term interest rates are roughly twice
as high as the norm in the euro countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with being in EMU is that you have got to accept a
common interest rate from the north to the south,'' said Mackie,
referring to Europe's Economic and Monetary Union, which underpins
the euro. ``And that interest rate may or may not suit you.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Britain's own unresolved debate about joining the
euro is almost certain to fuel disputes over such issues as the
position by France and Germany that some tax rates within the 15
European Union nations should be more closely aligned _ a move seen
in Britain as threatening the competitive advantages of low
corporate and other taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll probably be bickering about lots of things,'' Mackie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, there is the betting about when the four out
countries will join the euro. Greece says it will be ready by 2001.
And the odds are that Denmark and Sweden, where public opinion
surveys suggest that resistance to the euro is easing, will join by
2002, when euro notes and coins come into circulation.
</P>
<P>
   This timetable could leave Britain as the last one out. Even
though Tony Blair's Labor government is much more welcoming to the
euro than its Conservative predecessor, it remains leery of public
opinion broadly opposed to the new currency. That inevitably means
a delay in deciding whether Britain joins. The government says it
will hold a referendum on membership only after the next election _
and that may be more than three years away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
