<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4707 &Cx1f; taf-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-ASIA-$ADV04-ART-     01-01 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-ASIA-$ADV04-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIA REGAINS CONFIDENCE AS ITS STABILITY RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Like a cyclone victim emerging from a storm cellar
to survey the damage, Asia ended 1998 with equal measures of shock
and relief. Shock at the enormity of the devastation wrought by the
economic crisis; relief that its storm-tossed markets and
currencies had finally regained their footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, everyone was stuck with a very gloomy picture,''
said Neil Saker, the head of economic research at SG Securities in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to cuts in interest rates in the United States and
the strengthening of the Japanese yen, Saker said a modicum of
confidence had returned to Asia. Stock markets and currencies in
Thailand, Korea and Malaysia have risen steadily since October.
Even fragile Indonesia has gained ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've turned the corner and we're in a period of stability,
which is the prelude to real recovery,'' Saker said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Asia could easily falter again. Experts said the blow
could come from a number of places: the United States, if its
growth slows; Japan, if it cannot revive its moribund economy; or
within Asia itself, if social unrest in Indonesia or Malaysia
spreads and scares off returning investors.
</P>
<P>
   Even without fresh shock waves, the region's recovery will be a
protracted and painful affair. After predicting that Asia would
follow a pattern similar to that of the Mexican currency crisis _
in which that country tumbled abruptly into recession but climbed
out just as fast _ most economists and international agencies are
now scaling back their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In recent reports, the World Bank and the International Labor
Organization both predicted that most of Asia's economies would
barely eke out positive growth this year. The World Bank forecast
that Indonesia's economy would shrink 2.5 percent, on top of an
estimated 15.3 percent decline in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And the supercharged growth that led people to marvel at the
``Asian Miracle'' may be gone for good. After growing at an average
annual rate of 6.8 percent between 1991 and 1997, the World Bank
projects that East Asia's four major economies _ Indonesia,
Thailand, Malaysia and the Philippines _ will grow at an annual
rate of just 2.8 percent between 1998 and 2007.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus is that it will take two to five years for Asia
to recover,'' said Mac Overton, a portfolio manager at MBF Unit
Trust here. ``If you have a serious injury, it's not like you can
go out and play ball the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for Asian governments will be to pursue
disciplined policies during this convalescence. Banks will have to
be shut down, corporate assets will have to be sold and millions of
workers laid off, all at a time when unemployment has tripled in
Korea, Thailand and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The economic stress is already fraying nerves. Indonesia has
been riven by clashes between students and soldiers, as well as
between Christians and Muslims. In Malaysia, crowds rallied to
denounce Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad for ousting and
imprisoning his change-minded deputy, Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is no recovery in a year, these social problems will
multiply,'' said Marc Faber, the head of his own investment firm in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia may have less time than that. President B.J. Habibie
has begun to close unprofitable banks and take over debt-ridden
conglomerates. But his hold on power is tenuous at best. Although
Habibie has pledged new elections in the middle of this year,
student protesters say he has been irredeemably tainted by his ties
to his predecessor, President Suharto, and should step down
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an economist, how can you run a restructuring when it is
being influenced by the political process?'' asked Mari Pangetsu,
the executive director of the Center for Strategic and
International Studies, a research group in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   Although Indonesia's neighbors are in less precarious shape,
they, too, face internal pressures that could derail changes. In
Korea, the chaebols, the corporate leviathans that dominate the
economy, are obdurately resisting efforts to slim down their
empires.
</P>
<P>
   The president of South Korea, Kim Dae-jung, recently summoned
the leaders of the five top chaebols to his residence, the Blue
House, for a curt lecture on the need to reduce their debt and spin
off unprofitable operations.
</P>
<P>
   In Thailand, Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai is pushing for a
bankruptcy law that would allow the government to begin weeding out
insolvent companies. But Chuan's campaign is being threatened by
opposition from ``vested interests'' in the corporate sector,
according to James Stent, the senior executive vice president of
the Bank of Asia, Thailand's 11th-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   Looming above all these stop-and-go efforts is Malaysia, which
has chosen a radically different remedy for its ills. Rather than
accept the prescriptions of outside agencies like the International
Monetary Fund, it has imposed sweeping capital controls on its
currency and financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Economists warn that the controls could sabotage Malaysia's
overhaul efforts. For now, though, they are shielding Malaysia from
the vagaries of the global economy. Some experts in Kuala Lumpur
argue that the economy is even perking up a bit. Outside analysts
fear that if Malaysia thrives while the rest of Asia languishes,
other countries will follow its example.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem comes if growth doesn't pick up in 1999,'' said
Simon Ogus, the managing director of Asian economics at Warburg
Dillon Read in Hong Kong. ``Then Malaysia may serve as a siren call
for other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is an even more fundamental debate under way, about
where countries should put their emphasis in economic policy. The
conventional wisdom here has been that Asian countries must export
their way out of recession. Only by selling rubber, palm oil, cars
and computer chips to their neighbors _ as well as to the United
States and Europe _ could they hope to recover.
</P>
<P>
   But now some economists argue that Asian countries cannot depend
on each other or on the West to fuel a recovery. Fred Bergsten, the
director of the Institute for International Economics, a research
organization in Washington, said these countries must first revive
demand in their domestic markets. To do that, he said the
governments should increase public spending and relax their
monetary policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to me that they're continuing to go downhill,''
Bergsten said. ``They really have to put a concerted strategy in
place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 1826EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
