<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4708 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-WITH-CALLINAN-     01-01 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-CALLINAN-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH: JIM CALLINAN OF ROBERTSON STEPHENS EMERGING GROWTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (editors: in reference to E(ASTERISK)trade, replace (ASTERISK) with
the symbol, without parentheses) 
(bl) 
By WILLIAM R. LONG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a hectic year for Jim Callinan, manager of the Robertson
Stephens Emerging Growth Fund, but a rewarding one.
</P>
<P>
   While the small-capitalization stocks that Callinan buys were
lurching wildly, his employer, Robertson Stephens Investment
Management, was being offered for sale by its owner, BankAmerica,
which itself was being acquired by Nationsbank. So for much of
1998, Callinan was juggling the care of a volatile, high-turnover
portfolio with the work of making presentations to prospective
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   He teamed up with Sandy Robertson, a co-founder of Robertson
Stephens, to try to lead a buyout of the business. After that
effort failed, Callinan joined a group led by Randy Hecht, the
firm's president, that made its own, successful bid in November.
</P>
<P>
   The firm will be renamed RS Funds when the sale is completed,
probably late this month.
</P>
<P>
   The market, of course, has been far from tame, and Callinan has
taken investors on a particularly wild ride. At the nadir of the
summer stock selloff, his fund, which has $387.7 million in assets,
was down 48 percent from its July peak. But Emerging Growth has
bounced back, a result of its aggressive yet eclectic investing
style. Its 1998 return was 24.1 percent through Dec. 24, according
to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher. The average
small-growth fund, by contrast, was off 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Callinan, 38, began managing Emerging Growth on July 1, 1996,
having arrived with a stellar record from Putnam Investments. Since
then, the fund has returned 18.5 percent, annualized, through Dec.
24, versus 4.8 percent for the average fund in its
small-capitalization category, according to Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the fund's unique approach to the markets. Callinan and
the fund's four analysts often start their search for stocks by
scouting what he calls emerging subsegments of growing industries,
like Internet commerce or the genomic area of biotechnology. They
look for companies that are gaining market share and have expected
revenue and earnings growth of at least 20 percent a year, as well
as increasing profit margins and high returns on equity. And they
seek companies with the business models, competitive advantages and
strategies that will help them achieve such results.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his style is flexible enough so that the fund also looks for
chances to buy attractive stocks when they have been beaten down.
Initial public offerings play a big role, too, in his investment
choices. ``Whenever there's an IPO period that's pretty intense, we
buy a lot of stocks, and then we kind of, over the next six months,
filter through them and get rid of the bad eggs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer Callinan paid $12 each for shares of Knight/Trimark
Group of Jersey City, N.J., parent of Knight Securities, a market
maker that buys and sells 6,500 Nasdaq stocks. He bought more after
the price fell to about $7 at the end of August. The stock traded
last week at $$23.9375. Callinan considers Knight/Trimark an
Internet-related play because half of its business is in stock
trades for online brokers like E(ASTERISK)trade.
</P>
<P>
   He estimates that Knight/Trimark's earnings will grow from 92
cents a share in 1998 to $1.60 in 2000 and that the stock will be
trading this time next year at 15 times 2000 earnings, or $24.
</P>
<P>
   Callinan didn't catch any shares of International Network
Services at their initial offering price of $20 in 1996, but he
bought some soon thereafter at about $30. It climbed to $52,
Callinan sold, and the price dropped to a low of $15.25 in 1997.
``So we bought it back,'' he said, in the fall of 1997, ``in the
teens,'' and then bought more in 1998, ``in maybe the low 20s.''
Since then, he said, ``it has just been a superstock.'' It closed
at $66.50 last week.
</P>
<P>
   International Network Services, based in Sunnyvale, Calif.,
specializes in telecommunications systems engineering and
consulting. Callinan predicts that it will grow rapidly as
communications systems are updated, in part to handle growing
Internet traffic. He has a 12-month target price of $101 a share.
</P>
<P>
   A pure Internet play for the fund is Earthlink Network of
Pasadena, Calif., an Internet services provider with a rapidly
growing subscriber base, now at one million. Sprint Corp., with a
28 percent stake in the company, is committed by contract to
deliver 150,000 new subscribers a year to the company through its
Earthlink Sprint access service. But Callinan sees Earthlink's
subscriber base as growing much faster: In 1999, he predicted,
``they'll have 1.6 million; the year after that they'll have 2.3
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Callinan expects Earthlink to earn 45 cents a share this year
and $1.36 a share in 2000. He bought the stock at $30 in February;
it closed last week at $57. His target price is $120 within 18
months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
