</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVE-RETREAT (Phoenix) _ A journal: Conservatives ring
out their year at the Weekender retreat, formerly known as the Dark
Ages Weekend where disgust with the President is so pervasive that
he seems to have replaced the Soviet Union as the organizing
principle around which conservatives can rally. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   MISSOURI-RIVER (Nebraska City, Neb.) _ Big changes are coming to
the Missouri River, America's longest, stretching from Three Forks,
Mont., to St. Louis. The fracas over the river's future is fierce
as environmentalists, farmers, barge operators, recreation
boosters, hydroelectric utilities, Indian tribes and municipal
leaders all try to make sure the river stays _ or becomes _ what
they want it to be. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   METHADONE-POLICY (New York) _ Methadone frees, but it also
imprisons. It is a wizard at blocking the yearning for heroin, but
much less so the simple craving to get high. It is highly addictive
in its own right, with fiendish withdrawal symptoms. At more than
moderate doses, it can leave some patients in a barely functional
daze. Methadone is one bridge to a new life, but there are many
other rivers to cross. All of which goes a long way toward
explaining why methadone has long been caught in the cross-currents
of social policy, though never more so than right now in New York.
By N.R. Kleinfield.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-U.S. (Gillette, Wyo.) _ The lowest oil prices in two decades
are shutting down of vast swaths of the nation's oil industry. Low
prices and foreign competition, which favor the Exxons and Mobils
over the wildcatter mean that the oilman in jeans and boots,
legendary for his enterprise and daring, is giving way to the
oilman in a suit. By Allen R. Myerson.
</P>
