<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4711 &Cx1f; taf-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-DECADE-$ADV04-2T     01-01 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-DECADE-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEWING A LABEL ON A DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(rl) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some decades in the life of the business world are easy to
label. The 1960s saw a rebellion against the established order.
Inflation dominated the 1970s. Deals branded the 1980s. But the
1990s, so far, seem to be the fill-in-the-blank decade.
</P>
<P>
   As the decade opened, Japan was an economic powerhouse, Eastern
Europe had its post-World War II borders, Democrats controlled
Congress and Republicans ran the White House. By its midpoint,
Japan had stumbled, parts of Eastern Europe were a killing field,
Republicans controlled Congress and Democrats ran the White House.
As the decade ends, Japan is an economic quagmire, Eastern European
capitalism is a question mark and it is not clear that anyone
controls anything in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Nine people, who view the business world from different vantage
points, were invited to name this decade. Their suggestions follow.
</P>
<P>
   One caveat, as Richard Jenrette, one of the founders of the
investment banking firm of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, said: ``It
ain't over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of 1928, you would have said the 1920s were the
most prosperous decade ever,'' Jenrette said. ``There is something
wonderful about the eighth year; 1988 was the peak of the 1980s,
and 1968 was certainly the peak of that decade. But that ninth year
_ it can suddenly rise up and bite you.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Jenrette calls the 1990s ``probably the most
prosperous, felicitous overall decade we've had this century.''
Whatever the decade's ninth year brings, he suspects the future
will see the decade as a time when the world began to question the
``rugged `let-the-markets-rule' philosophy'' of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decade may be the beginning of a kinder, gentler
capitalism,'' he suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some funny things happen on the way to the millennium,''
Jenrette said, citing the political shifts to the left that have
occurred during the decade in Britain, France, Germany and Italy.
``And we just had a big swing back toward the Democrats in this
country,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on? ``I think the world tried the rugged brand of
capitalism, and not everybody found it to their liking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Jules Kroll, a former prosecutor, founded Kroll
Associates, a large corporate detective agency in Manhattan. He is
now chief executive of the Kroll-O'Gara Co., a corporate-security
concern formed in 1997 by a merger with an armored-car maker.
</P>
<P>
   As Kroll sees it, the decade has been a flashback to
``Network,'' the 1976 film by Paddy Chayefsky. ``You remember that
great line, `I'm as mad as hell, and I'm not going to take this
anymore,''' Kroll said. ``Well, I think the 1990s have been like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   People around the world spent the decade removing their leaders
over issues of corruption, he said _ in Brazil, Mexico, Indonesia,
Italy, Japan, Pakistan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can list an extraordinary number of individuals outside
the United States who have been removed or forced out by
accusations of corruption, proven and unproven,'' he said. ``It
seems to be based on people simply saying, `We've had enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the private sector, Kroll said, the decade has become the era
of the megafraud. ``Partly that's because there are just more zeros
out there _ the economy is so much bigger than it was in the 1980s
and everyone is playing with bigger chips.''
</P>
<P>
   But the growth in the use of esoteric financial derivatives has
also played a role, he argued. ``Most boards of directors, most
regulators, really don't understand the importance of this
derivatives activity,'' Kroll said. ``It is scary that so few
people understand it. It is the advent of these derivatives that
has opened the doors to the institution-threatening, and
nation-threatening, financial debacle.''
</P>
<P>
   For Maria Livanos Cattaui, who helped organize the prestigious
World Economic Conference in Davos, Switzerland, and who is now
secretary general of the International Chamber of Commerce in
Paris, the label for the 1990s ``is absolutely obvious: This has
been the decade of globalization.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the economies of the world have been inching closer
since the first caravans set forth centuries ago. ``But never has
the world been so intensively pulled together,'' she said.
Technology has dramatically altered ``the speed with which ideas _
and capital _ can whiz around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In her view, globalization was encouraged by the demise of the
Soviet Union in 1991. ``That unleashed all the capital and energy
that had previously been locked in this global power struggle,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cattaui warns against any nostalgia for a less-connected,
slower-paced world. ``When cars first came in, we didn't have any
uniform rules of the road,'' she said. ``Road systems all developed
nation by nation, with some driving on the left and some on the
right.'' And after more than a century, there still are no global
rules to govern electricity. ``You cannot take your computer from
home and plug it in anywhere else in the world,'' she said with a
laugh. ``The voltage is different, the outlets are different, even
the silly plug is different.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, she argued, today's business leaders and government
officials are doing a much better job of developing standards for
trade documents, global financial transactions, compatible computer
software and international telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Globalization need not mean homogenization, after all,'' she
said. But, she added, it must mean better cooperation among
regulators and better communication among corporations about their
exposure to risk.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab, chairman of the financial-services company that
bears his name, said, ``I think the dominant theme of this decade
is confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   With the collapse of the Soviet Union, Americans were freed at
last from what he called ``that awful, final what-if'' _ the
nuclear nightmare. ``That gave us personal confidence with respect
to our own and our families' security.''
</P>
<P>
   But the decade has also been marked by growing confidence in
``the sustainability of the United States growth story,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That may be based on the broad access to the Internet and the
speed with which this technology is spreading, Schwab said.
Already, more than 70 percent of his company's relationships and
contacts with customers have been over the Internet _ ``up from zip
a few years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But the can-do spirit he sees as dominating the decade cannot
obscure the battle lines that stretch into the future, running
between ``the high-tech and the high-touch'' approaches to business
growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seen from the 1990s, he said, the future belongs to ``the firms
that get that balance right _ providing high-tech service but also
helping people, face-to-face.''
</P>
<P>
   To Nicholas Negroponte, the 1990s may turn out to be the decade
when both nations and corporations began to go the way of the buggy
whip.
</P>
<P>
   Co-founder and director of the Media Laboratory at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Negroponte is a pioneer in
the application of computer technology to everyday life and the
author of the 1995 best seller ``Being Digital'' (Knopf).
</P>
<P>
   In an interview by e-mail, he called the 1990s ``the digital
decade.'' From the emergence of the Internet to the Year 2000
computer bug, ``it is a decade where the biggest asset is having
none.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained, ``The energy, people, spaces and vehicles needed
to move physical things from country to country are suddenly a
liability in an age of weightless, sizeless, colorless bits which
move at the speed of light.''
</P>
<P>
   As he sees it, the bits of electronic information ``make the
world very small, borders truly meaningless and territory almost
irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Negroponte also sees the face of the future in the ``shockingly
high'' valuation the stock market is putting on new technology
companies with little revenue. It is, he said, ``a future that
tells us today that we are clueless about who will be our
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   But while investors may be in for a roller coaster ride, the
professor is optimistic: ``We're in a decade which is the first
hint of people belonging to a single planet. Kids born today will
grow up feeling like global citizens way much more than adults do
today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Children will be the agents of change,'' he added. ``A kid's
grasp of the digital world will look and feel genetic.''
</P>
<P>
   But it may be the old, not the young, who give the 1990s their
defining label, in the view of Richard Leone, president of the
Century Foundation, formerly the Twentieth Century Fund, a public
policy research foundation in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   For Leone, what is ``new under the sun'' in this decade is the
aging of the world's population, thanks to improvements in public
health and a dramatic drop in birth rates.
</P>
<P>
   Leone, former chairman of the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey and former president of the New York Mercantile Exchange,
thinks this graying of the population will challenge both
government and business.
</P>
<P>
   For government, ``the key issue is the same issue we had when
the baby boomers were young,'' he said. ``The things that the young
and the old need are things that we once tended to supply with
public money. But that will be harder in the future,'' especially
for nations that do not yet have a secure social safety net.
</P>
<P>
   For business, the global graying will present big opportunities
for those that guess correctly about the aging population's
preferences. ``With everyone living longer, attitudes about the
importance of saving and investment are going to proliferate,'' he
predicted. ``Anything to do with aging and the extension of
vitality and vigor into one's later years will see dynamic
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Wasserstein, chief executive of Wasserstein Perella Group,
thinks the dominant theme of the 1990s has been its volatility.
</P>
<P>
   While Wasserstein, one of the leading dealmeisters of the last
decade, agreed that globalization and technology have left their
imprint, he said they came mixed in with ``immense frustration and
false gods.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the foundations here are not as strong as one would
think,'' he added. ``There are a lot of false leads.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the exuberant bidding for Internet stocks when,
``in fact, the Internet may be technologically obsolete.'' For
example, in the course of the same decade, Japan was hailed as a
triumph and then collapsed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, he said people optimistically ``assumed a legal
system in Russia that doesn't exist.'' He added, ``It is quite a
remarkable period.''
</P>
<P>
   While Wasserstein is hopeful that the world has changed for the
better, he noted that ``if you are in Brazil right now, it may not
look that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In many of the emerging markets, the glory of an entire decade
has been wiped out in the last few months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Wall Street, the 1990s were the beginning of ``the new
era of consolidation,'' he said. With stock and bond offerings sold
globally and with mergers valued in the billions, he added, Wall
Street is likely to become a place where only about five giant
firms will survive. ``The problem is, there are about 30 people who
think that they are one of the five.''
</P>
<P>
   Esther Dyson is a computer industry consultant and venture
capitalist and the publisher of Release 1.0, an industry
newsletter. For her, the 1990s will go down in history as the
decade when the Internet started to be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``A major issue of the decade was that we got wired,'' she said.
``We got connected.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Dyson sees it, the advent of the Internet trumps all the
other changes the decade has seen. ``Globalization, the backlash to
globalization, the inevitability of globalization; the diminishing
importance of the nation state, the rise of the tribe, on the one
hand, and the corporation on the other _ the Internet makes a
difference to all of those,'' she said. ``Those changes are, in one
sense, being pushed by the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   While people always learn and adopt new technologies more slowly
than cyberspace pioneers expect, Ms. Dyson thinks the Internet has
unleashed wholly unappreciated changes in society. ``The Internet
permits people to communicate in a more decentralized way'' by
using a tool that is far more accessible than, say, a television
station or newspaper, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The personal computer and the Internet put the means of
production in the hands of individuals,'' Ms. Dyson said.
``Businesses are motivated primarily to make a profit, but
individuals are motivated by other things, too. I think more people
want to do good, and just get ground down. So if you're given a
tool to resist that pressure, the world might be very slightly
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The historian David Hackett Fischer of Brandeis University
thinks the 1990s may be the decade when a centurylong surge in
inflation finally faltered and stopped.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``The Great Wave: Price Revolutions and the Rhythm
of History'' (Oxford University Press, 1996), Fischer suggested
that European history has been shaped by four great waves of
inflation, the first climaxing in the mid-14th century and the most
recent beginning in 1896 and continuing into this decade, with the
1930s a mere pothole in the upward path. It is this last long
inflationary wave that may have begun to break in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a very deep change in the dynamics of price
movements,'' he said. ``This is not the usual flutters, but
something more profound.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer attributes this apparent shift to a worldwide decline in
the rate of population growth coupled with a decline in military
spending after the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   He said the transition from inflation to price equilibrium in
the past has been a time of severe crisis _ and, indeed, he said,
just such a crisis has been unfolding in recent years, with the
shattering changes in the former Soviet Union and economic and
social strains elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Who wins and loses when prices finally stabilize? In the past,
Fischer said, the losers have included the world's farmers, as
commodity prices fell, and the lending classes, which earned very
low interest on their capital. On the other hand, businesses could
borrow cheaply, pensioners were more secure and workers' wages
stretched further, helping to close the gap between rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have thought the world's recent troubles were caused by a
monetary crisis in Thailand that spread to other nations,'' he
concluded. ``But most people have missed the demographic factors
entirely. We have to look beyond economics to history and
demographics to understand what's happening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
