<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4713 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV03     01-01 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING: TROUBLE, A DESK AWAY
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(bl) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Recently, my boss of seven years and I moved from our old
office to a separate company he owns. One of my new co-workers is
constantly complaining, ridiculing my boss (to whom I am devoted)
and speaking loudly during personal calls _ which I can't avoid
hearing because our desks are just 15 feet apart. This woman has
been with the company for five years, and everyone else seems to
think she is great. I am civil toward her, but my patience is
wearing thin. Should I talk to my boss or to the human resources
department about her behavior? Or should I try another approach?
</P>
<P>
   A. You are not in third grade, and your co-worker is not a
schoolyard bully who keeps stealing your lunch money. As such,
tattling should not be part of your plan.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Reynolds, career coach and owner of Covisioning, a
leadership training firm in Phoenix, says you should approach your
colleague directly with your concerns. Going over her head, she
said, will damage your relationship further. ``When you go to the
boss, it's like going to the principal,'' she warned.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Kalman, president of Performance First, a consulting firm
in Branford, Conn., agreed. ``This woman is your peer,'' she said.
``Call her on her behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   But aim to be diplomatic, at least at first. As the new kid on
the block, you don't want to start by picking a fight with a
popular employee.
</P>
<P>
   First, take some deep breaths and try to understand what is
driving her behavior, Ms. Reynolds suggested. Perhaps the woman
feels threatened by your boss' _ and your _ arrival, she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to conventional wisdom, the first line of defense
against change is denial, but Ms. Reynolds disagreed. The first
step, she said, is complaining. ``We often complain when what's
really going on is we're frightened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She suggested that you try initiating a friendly conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell her, `You know, it's been hard for me to move, but I bet
it's really hard for you to have a new boss here,''' she advised.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, your co-worker may be oblivious to the impact of her
behavior, Ms. Kalman said, perhaps because she acts this way all
the time and no one has ever told her so.
</P>
<P>
   Delicately, let her know that you consider her chatter
inappropriate, Ms. Reynolds said. For example, if she rants on the
phone about a problem, go to her and say, ``I hear you're having
trouble in this area, and I'm wondering if I could help.''
</P>
<P>
   If diplomacy fails and you conclude that this woman is, indeed,
trying to drive you mad, be direct _ though still as pleasant as
possible. When a co-worker becomes disruptive, Ms. Kalman said,
``it's time to say: Get a clue,'' though she added that the nice
approach would be to tell her you're finding it difficult to come
into work each day and listen to all her negative energy.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, your co-worker should respect you for not
running to the principal at the first sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
