<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-CHIPS-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIPS ARE HIDDEN IN WASHING MACHINES, MICROWAVES AND EVEN
RESERVOIRS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(ms) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As companies and government agencies race to fix the Year 2000
computer problem, they have discovered to their chagrin that
problems lurk not only in computer rooms and personal computers.
There are also risks in billions of microchips, doing such diverse
things as mixing the fuel in automobile engines, controlling
factories and medical equipment and even automatically flushing
some toilets.
</P>
<P>
   The Year 2000 problem has raised awareness of what has long been
true in the computer industry _ that hidden computers, sometimes
consisting of only a single chip, are far more numerous than the
machines on desktops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Approximately zero percent of computer chips are actually used
in computers,'' said Jim Turley, senior editor of Microprocessor
Report, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Turley's figure, surprising as it might be, is not too far off.
The market research firm Dataquest estimates that 4.6 billion of
these hidden chips, known as embedded microcomponents, were sold in
1997 alone. By contrast, only about 100 million microprocessors
were sold that year to perform computations in computers.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the personal computer microprocessors that get all the
attention. This is partly because personal computer chips like the
Pentium cost tens or hundreds of times more than the chips that
control microwave ovens or Furby, the fuzzy electronic stuffed
animal with an attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the microprocessor is an important consideration for
personal computer buyers. Embedded chips, by contrast, barely make
their presence known. ``You don't say, `I bought a new Whirlpool
washer with a Motorola processor,''' Turley said.
</P>
<P>
   The market for such hidden computer chips has long provided a
refuge for semiconductor companies that lost out to the Intel Corp.
to provide the brains of personal computers. Motorola Inc. is the
largest player in embedded processors, followed by the NEC Corp. of
Japan. Texas Instruments is the leader in one type of chip known as
a digital signal processor, which is used in cellular phones and
consumer electronics devices.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller companies like Integrated Device Technology Inc. and
Quantum Effect Design Inc., both of Santa Clara, Calif., have found
niches for their embedded processors, because such chips tend to be
more specialized than those for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, some of these more specialized computers are
starting to pose a direct challenge to the personal computer. The
biggest attractions at the Comdex computer trade show in November
were so-called information appliances. These include electronic
organizers, digital televisions, digital audio recorders and small
Web-surfing devices.
</P>
<P>
   Some pundits are saying that the world is entering the post-PC
era. The International Data Corp., a market research firm,
estimates that sales of information appliances that can connect to
the Internet, such as video games, smart phones, hand-held
computers and digital set-top boxes, will exceed sales of consumer
personal computers in the United States by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
   There are also growing markets for such hidden computers well
beyond information appliances. Tom Starnes, an analyst at
Dataquest, estimates that the typical American home has about 63
processors, and the number could grow to 280 in five years. These
chips are found in everything from video cassette recorders and
microwave ovens to washing machines, sprinkler controllers and
auto-focus cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The figure includes the 15 or so processors the family car may
have, controlling the fuel mix in the engine, the anti-lock brakes,
the air bags, the remote keyless entry, the radio and the dashboard
displays. Some luxury automobiles have more than 60 processors,
doing such things as raising or lowering the volume of the radio as
the speed of the car varies, or adjusting the speed of the
windshield wipers automatically depending on the intensity of the
rain, Turley said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Boeing 777 jets have more than 1,000 processors, from
a mere handful in older Boeing models, according to Timothy D.
Fehr, the company's vice president for airplane systems. Most of
the processors are involved in delivering entertainment and
telephone service to each seat. And instead of having cables and
hydraulic systems running through the plane to control the flaps
and rudders, the newest planes use a fly-by-wire system, in which
digital signals are sent over wires to processors that activate
local hydraulic systems. This cuts the weight of the plane,
improving range and fuel efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   But if the proliferation of hidden computers has brought
benefits, for the coming year at least it will also bring many
headaches. That is because companies and government agencies are
now having to root out these computers to determine whether they
will malfunction because they cannot handle the transition to the
year 2000, potentially shutting down factories or harming medical
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that only a small percentage of such systems will
malfunction. But with billions in use, even a small percentage can
cause widespread problems.
</P>
<P>
   The ubiquity of these chips, and the fact that many are hidden,
makes it a challenge even to find all these systems in order to
test them.
</P>
<P>
   At the Public Service Electric &AMP; Gas Co., a unit of the Public
Service Enterprise Group and New Jersey's dominant utility, Year
2000 team members walked through 250 locations, from power plants
to substations, hunting down hidden processors, a job that took
about a year.
</P>
<P>
   Just when they thought they had everything, they realized they
had forgotten to check a reservoir the utility had built to put
water into the Delaware River for environmental purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Could it possibly contain hidden processors?
</P>
<P>
   When the team members visited, they found that a technician
walks the dam twice a day with a hand-held device to check
creepage. That device, which contains a processor, needed to be
fixed for the year 2000. At the bottom of the dam was a control
system that monitored how much water was being released. It, too,
was not ready for the year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
