</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE JOB: SURPRISE! EVEN THE BOSS HAS A HEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(editors: first graf should be italicized) 
(bl) 
By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who would have thought it? Bosses, those storied ogres who
stereotypically withhold raises, tear up expense accounts and send
out pink slips on Christmas Eve, can actually have hearts of mush.
The softies among them help finance vacations, give Cupid a hand
and spring to the aid of the distressed. So next time you see a
boss, honk _ or at least smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '80s, I had a one-in-a-million boss who performed an
extraordinary act of kindness,'' writes C.M. Barnhart of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   When it appeared that Ms. Barnhart would not have enough money
to take a long-anticipated vacation in Greece, the boss gave her a
check for one-third of the trip's cost.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't all.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was about to leave on vacation, he handed me a roll of
drachmas for extra spending money,'' Ms. Barnhart writes. ``No
strings; it just pleased him to make sure I would have a great
vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Messineo of Clifton, N.J., recalls how her supervisor
approached her with a brochure in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a present for you,'' the boss said. The flier described
a conference on remedial reading _ Mrs. Messineo's field of
expertise _ to be held in the Southern city where her daughter and
family had settled recently.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Messineo writes: ``I was able to spend five days in a lovely
hotel, attend an informative conference and visit with my loved
ones with all expenses paid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Several years ago I was diagnosed with `incurable' cancer at
its most advanced stages,'' writes Kenny Moore of Totowa, N.J., a
manager of human resources for Keyspan Energy in Brooklyn. So Moore
underwent a year of experimental treatment at the National Cancer
Institute in Bethesda, Md., consisting of aggressive chemotherapy
followed by full-body radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Though he had held his job for just two years, his boss was
unequivocal in his reaction: ``Go do what you need to do. We'll
cover for you when you can't come to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore writes: ``For the next year, I lived the harrowing
experience which has become commonplace for cancer victims. Some
days I was barely able to come to work; other days I could barely
walk.''
</P>
<P>
   The company never wavered in its support, and the treatment
worked. ``Eleven years later, I'm still cancer-free,'' he says. And
still grateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, I've had several opportunities to work
elsewhere,'' he says. ``While the money may have been better, I
have stayed. I continue to feel honored to work for a company whose
corporate values support both the business needs as well as the
human needs of its employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Toni Heidrich of Convent Station, N.J., is a partner in a
15-person accounting firm. Most of the employees are under 30 and
are trying to save money for their future.
</P>
<P>
   When one of Ms. Heidrich's colleagues decided to marry, everyone
in the firm was invited to his wedding. But the event would be out
of state _ not within driving distance.
</P>
<P>
   When the firm's managing partner learned that the cost of air
fare and lodging was going to keeping many employees from
attending, he offered to pay for tickets, accommodations and food
for each employee and a companion.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Heidrich writes, ``Ten people ended up attending and were
happy to be able to share our friend's special day.''
</P>
<P>
   One Friday night in 1982, when Ben Suntag of Pomona, N.Y., was
working for Western Union as an engineer, he received a phone call
from his sister in Los Angeles. Their father had been struck by a
car and was in a coma.
</P>
<P>
   Suntag flew immediately to California to be at his father's
bedside. Early the next week, he talked with his boss, Harry
Halpert, back in New York. Halpert told him to spend as much time
with his father as he needed _ then to fly to the company's office
in San Francisco to take a few pictures. That way, he said, he
could justify reimbursing Suntag's return flight.
</P>
<P>
   When Suntag returned to New York two weeks later, he was
summoned to the office of his boss' boss, John Doherty. Paying for
his one-way fare back home was just not right, Doherty said;
instead, he insisted on paying for the round trip. Moreover, since
Suntag had visited the San Francisco office, he had obviously been
to the West Coast ``on business'' and would receive full salary for
his time away.
</P>
<P>
   Though his father never recovered from his injuries, Suntag
writes, ``there was some happiness in knowing that a big company
like Western Union and two great bosses like Harry Halpert and John
Doherty could make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when Dr. Heiko Spallek came to Philadelphia from the
former East Germany to become an assistant professor at Temple
University's School of Dentistry, one of his most difficult tasks
was overcoming his poor English.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Professor Titus Schleyer, the chairman of the Department
of Dental Informatics. To help Spallek master the language, he
offered some unusual motivational tools: a notebook and stickers
that depicted cartoon characters and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Into the notebook went the phrases that Spallek struggled with
most. When he used a phrase correctly, Schleyer rewarded him with a
sticker. When he mastered the expression, he received a sticker in
the shape of a star.
</P>
<P>
   At the department's Christmas party in 1997, one year and 600
stickers after the training sessions began, Schleyer awarded
Spallek a certificate for successful completion of the ``Dental
Informatics Linguistics Program.''
</P>
<P>
   Spallek says the framed certificate decorates his office wall.
``My boss,'' he writes, ``managed to pull me through a major
challenge in my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
