r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MARKIEWICZ-COLUMN-     01-01 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MARKIEWICZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-OF-A-KIND BROADCASTER JACKSON WILL BE MISSED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a mark of college football announcer Keith Jackson's
greatness that he can rouse the passions of his listeners _ even
when he's just talking over the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   That happened in a recent conference call with reporters when
Jackson was asked what he'll miss most when he retires from ABC
after Monday's Fiesta Bowl from Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the hour before the game,'' he pronounced, sounding
at once wistful and grumpy. ``That's a special time, if the
producers let you alone so you can sit there and enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Warming to the fond recollection of autumn afternoons in Ann
Arbor, Mich., and Columbus, Ohio, Jackson proceeded to discuss the
exhilaration he feels every time he sees the teams charge out of
the tunnel onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   It is like ancient warriors before battle, he suggested, a
moment that ``has always been with mankind.'' Then there are the
bands, he added, and ``the coming-together of the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   After listening to Jackson set the scene from memory, you wonder
how he can leave now. Perhaps more than any other broadcaster of
the day, Jackson is the voice of a sport. More than Vin Scully is
baseball, Pat Summerall is the NFL, or Marv Albert was pro
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's time for me to step down and step aside,''
he stated firmly, sounding sure of his decision, though not quite
sure how to explain it. Jackson offered that his step is a little
slower these days, that he is less patient, and that he has to huff
and puff en route to the announcers' booth.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, he doesn't feel old.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``When you've worked someplace for a half a
century, you need to see if you're doing a good job anymore. I see
things \RI'm doing on Saturday\S on Sunday and Monday that I don't
like. I just think it's time. It's a gut feeling I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Few listeners would agree with Jackson's assessment of his own
performance, since most days he's still as good as it gets in the
sports broadcasting business.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has his plans in place for retirement, however. Very
short-term plans, anyway. He and his wife will travel the country
playing golf next fall _ a time when he'd normally be working. When
he runs out of golf courses, he jokes, he'll commence to fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, he added, ``I don't know what happens. I'm a
blank page. And it's not everybody who gets a chance to be a blank
page. I've never been unemployed. We'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Jackson probably won't do is write a book. One reason,
he said, is ``I have no desire or reason to hurt anybody.'' So many
books these days do, and hurting people is not Jackson's style.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Jackson doesn't have the memories that come with 47
years in the business, covering pro football and basketball as well
as college football.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to pick a favorite game, he cites an Oklahoma-Ohio State
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a game at the Horseshoe,'' he says of the Buckeyes'
ancient stadium. ``Barry Switzer and Woody Hayes. Uwe von Schamann
is the place-kicker for Oklahoma. Ohio State is leading by a point
with 40 seconds to play, roughly.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jackson recalls the game, his deep voice rising and falling
with each statement, it is impossible to not feel as if you're at
the old stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma, Jackson continued, decided to try a 43-yard field goal
to win the game, so Hayes called three timeouts trying to ice the
Sooners kicker. But the cool von Schamann walked around in the
middle of the field during the timeouts ``conducting'' the crowd in
its booing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then,'' Jackson concludes, ``he popped it right up the
highway. I thought it was remarkable seeing him stand up to 90,000
people.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been equally remarkable the way Jackson has performed in
what has become his farewell tour. While others, from stadiums full
of fans to officials, have celebrated him with cheers and with
sentimental gifts, Jackson has downplayed his departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd had my druthers, I'd have kept my mouth shut and just
walked away and said goodbye,'' he said. ``It's been somewhat of a
strain. People have been so generous and kind. I'm not used to
crying that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the impact of his retirement on college football
fans, Jackson is equally humble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never aware of posture,'' he said. ``I just do my ballgame
and go home.''
</P>
<P>
   And better than anybody else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
