 &HT;        PA SENS. ARLEN SPECTER AND RICK SANTORUM SAY FULL SENATE
TRIAL NEEDED   By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Jan 01, -- Pennsylvania Republican Senators Arlen
Specter and Rick Santorum have emerged in agreement that the Senate
should hold a trial to resolve impeachment charges against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the consensus between the more moderate Specter and
conservative Santorum does not reflect one among GOP Senators, some
of whom favor a more swift conclusion to the impeachment process
that would bypass a full trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to proceed with a trial,'' Santorum said.
``That's the best course from the perspective of what is right for
the situation and for history. We set a dangerous precedent if we
dispense with a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter had initially favored waiting until after Clinton left
office to resolve the charges, but changed his mind when the House
voted to impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   Specter, who was overseas and could not be reached for comment,
said on CBS's Face the Nation last week that he favored a
bipartisan, deliberative proceeding, but did not think a vote could
be ``taken today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it does have to go to trial,'' Specter said. ``I don't
think anybody is prepared to vote today.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter, also said that censure is ``really not worth the
tinker's damn...''
</P>
<P>
   Senate majority leader Trent Lott, R-Mississippi, is reportedly
circulating a plan that suggests taking a vote, up or down, on
whether charges against Clinton - even if they are proven true -
are serious enough to warrant his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Several Senators from both sides of the aisle have pushed for
such a plan, saying they wanted a quick resolution and an option to
consider censure.
</P>
<P>
   But Santorum said any movement toward favoring censure is media
hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say any push for a consensus on censure is
media-created,'' Santorum said. ``I don't know that anyone is
pushing for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum said it wasn't constitutional for the Senate to censure
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Censure is punishment for the president,'' Santorum said.
``Our role is whether to convict on charges or not to convict. I
don't think we should be able to punish. Besides, anything short of
trial is thwarting our constitutional responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum, who is mum on whether he would convict Clinton, said
anybody who is ready to vote would ``not make an impartial juror in
a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how anybody can vote before they have heard all
the evidence and testimony,'' Santorum said. ``I don't think the
trial has to be long or drawn out. That all depends on how Clinton
cooperates.''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum said if a trial proceeds it would not jeopardize issues
like Social Security reform, which he has stated as a priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's all possible to get done,'' Santorum said. ``We
can get this impeachment process behind us and move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum said he thinks Clinton's leadership has been key in
efforts to reform Social Security to prevent it from going
bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone else has shown that kind of commitment to
bipartisan Social Security reform,'' Santorum said. ``I do think
that would suffer if Clinton had to leave office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
