<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL BUSINESS DIARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(bl) 
By ALAN KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Online Searches For Offline Work
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is no longer just for technophiles, and neither, it
seems, is online job-hunting. A growing number of services are
catering to job seekers of all types, offering everything from
online classified ads to aptitude evaluation questionnaires and
resume advice.
</P>
<P>
   And a new study suggests that most people searching the World
Wide Web for employment opportunities are not looking for jobs
involving computers and software.
</P>
<P>
   Career Mosaic, a Web employment site, analyzed key terms typed
in by job seekers who conducted 15.1 million searches of its data
base between July and September. The word that came up most often
was ``manager'' (or ``management''); only 3 of the 10 most
frequently used terms _ ``engineer,'' ``computer'' and
``programmer'' _ were specifically technical.
</P>
<P>
   Other search terms in the top 10 were sales (No. 3), marketing
(4), finance (5), accounting (6), assistant (8) and human resources
(10). Over all, the company said, the survey illustrates the Web's
increasingly mainstream place in the workaday world.
</P>
<P>
   Singing Those Retirement Blues
</P>
<P>
   Business publications regularly note how Americans are not
saving enough for retirement. A recent study by Ohio State
University researchers of data collected by the federal government
confirmed the trend, finding that 48 percent of Americans would not
be able to maintain their accustomed living standards, as measured
by current levels of spending, after they retired.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that current spending habits had a lot to
do with the ability to finance retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-one percent of respondents said their household spending
matched or exceeded their income in the previous year. Of that
group, the study found, only one-fourth would have enough income
during retirement to maintain their living standards. By
comparison, three-quarters of the remaining respondents, who spent
less than they made, would have enough for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Of those who said when they intended to retire, 35 percent said
they were aiming for 61 or younger. But only 44 percent of that
group were likely to have enough resources to maintain their living
standards, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published recently in Financial Counseling and
Planning, a journal, was based on data from the 1,387 households
that took part in the 1995 Survey of Consumer Finances, conducted
every three years by the Federal Reserve and the Treasury
Department. It examined participants' spending, saving and
investment patterns and their planned retirement ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
