<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SHOPPING-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING, GOING, GONE ON LINE TO THE HIGHEST BIDDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, Jan. 3.)  
(ms) 
 By JUDITH NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I just bid $180 for a Donna Karan black cashmere sweater I've
never seen. It's supposed to be new, but for all I know it has
spent the last three years locked in a closet with bulimic moths.
Until recently I had assumed that anyone foolish enough to buy
anything through an Internet auction had too much time, money or
both. But today, I find myself eager to shell out $100 for a used
scarf.
</P>
<P>
   How did this happen?
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few months, most of my friends have gone berserk
over Ebay, the online auction house offering everything from
Corvettes to Furbies. Ebay is like a flea market with a potentially
limitless number of booths _ and an all-important time limit on the
bidding. You can send in your maximum bid and hope for the best or
be a jockey and neurotically track the item's progress minute by
minute.
</P>
<P>
   One friend said she knew she had gone overboard when a dealer
sent her an e-mail beginning, ``Hello, Darling.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone I knew was urging me to join the fun. I resisted. Which
wasn't hard. I hate shopping _ that mad-dog look in everyone's
eyes, the doctor's-office feeling of taking off my clothes behind a
curtain. And I especially hate the overabundance of choices: too
many Fendi bags in one place and I hyperventilate. For years I've
strong-armed my best friend, who was approximately my shoe and
dress size, to accompany me on every shopping expedition so she can
try on stuff that might fit me. But recently, she lost weight and I
gained. So it's perhaps not surprising that she was the first one
to suggest I try Ebay. She used the one argument guaranteed to get
me to the Web site: Ebay, she promised, would help me realize my
ultimate goal of never having to leave my apartment.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons why Ebay can make a rabid shopper out
of someone like me. First, the system allows you to limit choices.
Sure, you could get waylaid if you're not careful _ which is how I
found myself craving a blood-red evening dress yet bidding on a
blood-pressure gauge after typing in ``blood'' and ``read'' by
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're careful, Ebay can target the object of your desire
with the precision of a cruise missile. Typing the words ``Chanel''
``shoes,'' ``size 10'' means I never even have to think about
Guccis, about Ferragamos, or about whether Chanel 9's might fit.
For that matter, who knows whether a Chanel 10 in this particular
style will fit: but if it's a great bargain, if it's Chanel and if
I can capture it for me, me, me _ I become possessed.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows what new merchandise tomorrow will bring? That's
why one can't afford not to check in with Ebay once a day. Twice.
OK, 23 times _ but who's counting?
</P>
<P>
   Ebay also has its literary pleasures _ and I don't mean just the
used-book auctions. (A signed first-edition Anita Brookner was mine
for $27!) Many Ebay sellers seem to be frustrated philosophers. My
favorite is a seller of vintage clothing who goes by the name
enoki. Apparently, enoki sees old cheerleader outfits, deb evening
gowns and the like as her chance to comment on the human condition.
A recent typical entry, offering a pair of boys' cowboy boots:
``Back in the 50's, boys were encouraged to be `boys,' complete
with little Western outfits and capguns. Nowadays, Mommy is so
worried about raising a serial killer that she encourages little
Andy to play with A B C blocks and leave the guns to the Marines.''
Take that, J. Peterman.
</P>
<P>
   Also undeniably piquant, even to a full-time nonshopper, is the
covert market for fetishistic goods hidden among the wholesome
designer fashions. I found this out _ quite accidentally, of course
_ when I typed in ``Calvin Klein'' and discovered ads for used
underwear amid the jeans, jackets and eyeglasses. ``Help a college
kid continue with his education'' runs an ad for three pairs of
pre-owned briefs.
</P>
<P>
   On Ebay, my polite and timid department-store persona vanishes.
I am not a lumpy size 10 hoping the dressing room has those very
special skinny mirrors. Invisible and anonymous, I am a bronzed
beach bunny who'll look just fabulous in that vinyl halter
mesh-chain dress.
</P>
<P>
   But of all its advantages over other forms of shopping, the real
selling point is that Ebay allows for _ indeed, encourages _ the
consumer version of road rage. If I go to a normal sale, I am far
too genteel to elbow anyone out of the way for that last Escada
winter-white double-breasted jacket. And real-live auctions leave
me exhausted and anxious _ loathing myself for being so grasping
and loathing everyone else more for being greedier and richer than
I. On line, I am a shopping warrior, able to vanquish every foe
with a click of my mouse.  &UR; You say $80 for that Hermes scarf with
the galloping horsies? Die, Earthlings! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I've read the tales of fraud and disappointment on Ebay. I
understand that the $60 Ralph Lauren square-hoop earrings I just
bought for $15 might not be Lauren at all and that the gently worn
blue Versace jacket I'm furiously bidding on might not even fit.
Maybe there are shills, friends of the sellers' bidding up items.
Maybe I'm the shill. (One time I upped the ante on the highest
bidder _ only to discover that the ID of the previous highest
bidder was mine.)
</P>
<P>
   Who cares? I am hooked.
</P>
<P>
   It was the final evening of bidding for the Donna Karan cashmere
sweater, size L. The auction, which had been going on for six days,
was ending at 1 a.m. Someone could (and usually does) swoop in
during the last few minutes to beat the highest price. I had to be
at a party, and the hostess did not have a computer. I considered
bringing my laptop as I saw another Ebay devotee do during this
busy holiday season. Instead, I asked a friend to bid for me.
</P>
<P>
   At the party, I got into a long obsessional discussion with
another Ebay groupie. His habit was 1939 World's Fair memorabilia.
I confided to him about the sweater. Would I get it? I had
instructed my friend to bid up to $250. But it might not be enough
... Should I call him, just to see how things were going?
</P>
<P>
   Another guest leaned over and gently patted my arm. ``I want you
to know,'' she said, ``you'll be OK without the sweater.''
</P>
<P>
   She was right, of course. I perked up. Who needed yet another
black cashmere sweater? I scorn such nauseating displays of
consumerism in others, and I laugh at the country's obsession with
overpriced designer goods.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, I never had to face the future without this
sweater. The bidding stopped at $220. Let's see _ that's $30 less
than I'd planned to spend. Just enough to start the bidding on that
adorable pair of Prada ankle boots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
