<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4732 &Cx1f; taf-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-AUTOS-ART-$ADV04     01-01 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-AUTOS-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO MAKERS PREDICT STRONG SALES THIS YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Global slowdowns in the auto industry have
consistently started in the United States, which accounts for
nearly a third of worldwide demand. But that pattern, which dates
back to the end of World War II, seems to have been broken in the
last year as plunging sales in Asia and South America have hurt
auto makers around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether sales will stay strong in North
America, and whether the European auto market will remain vigorous
despite recent hints of weakness, particularly in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Most auto executives are still expressing optimism for 1999. But
difficulties in North America or Europe, the world's two biggest
markets in terms of sales, would create serious problems for
multinational auto makers.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's health is important because highly variable auto
sales tend to be a leading indicator of recessions. Auto
manufacturing accounts for about 4 percent of economic output in
the United States, for instance. The General Motors Corp. and the
Ford Motor Co. are the world's two largest companies in terms of
sales and share of global economic output, although the planned
acquisition of the Mobil Corp. by Exxon would produce an even
bigger company if antitrust regulators do not require the combined
enterprise to sell significant parts of their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   For now, auto executives are watching low unemployment rates and
low interest rates in Western industrialized countries and
concluding that 1999 will be a fairly good year. ``If you look at
the world today, there are only two areas that look strong, but
they happen to be the two biggest,'' said John F. Smith Jr., the
chairman and chief executive of General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler AG are predicting a sixth
consecutive year of high sales of around 15 million cars, sport
utility vehicles, pickup trucks and vans in the United States _ a
remarkable streak of level sales in an industry that until the
current boom had never managed more than two successive years of
roughly identical sales.
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives in Europe are slightly less bullish about 1999
than their American counterparts, though they are not gloomy. ``We
will see a possible slowdown but we definitely don't see a
recession in 1999, as far as the United States and Europe are
concerned,'' said Juergen E. Schrempp, the German co-chairman of
DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   But outside the United States and Europe, there is a definite
pall. The domestic Japanese auto market has been moribund since
1990. Auto sales in smaller markets in Southeast Asia and Latin
America have fallen as much as 70 percent, compelling auto makers
to furlough workers and postpone investment plans made as recently
as two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts worry that the optimism in Detroit may be
misplaced, given the troubles overseas. Prosperity at home ``gives
us the mind-set things haven't changed,'' said Paul D. Ballew,
chief economist at J.D. Power &AMP; Associates, the automotive
consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in truth, he added, ``we are in the midst of a global
slump.''
</P>
<P>
   The precise level of worldwide auto sales is hard to calculate
because some developing countries provide statistics late, if at
all. But auto makers release detailed figures for worldwide auto
production, which match up closely with sales. The final worldwide
tally is likely to show a 12.8 percent drop in 1998, and a further
1.5 percent decline in 1999, according to estimates by J.D. Power.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest financial damage has been to Japanese and South
Korean auto makers, which face weak markets at home and were making
the most aggressive efforts to expand in Asia before that region
became the epicenter of global currency and economic problems. The
Hyundai Motor Co. of South Korea has already bought control of the
insolvent Kia Motors Corp., another Korean producer. Now auto
makers around the world are following the struggle of the Nissan
Motor Co., which was forced in November to negotiate a 100 billion
yen ($817 million) loan from the government-run Japan Development
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Asian auto makers are also suffering because they are strongest
in small cars, the segment of the global auto market hurt by an
enormous excess of assembly plants. Auto makers around the world
have the capacity to build 70 million vehicles a year of all sizes
for an international market of 50 million vehicles, and most of the
overcapacity is in small cars.
</P>
<P>
   But while small-car factories are being closed or are running
shorter hours, factories that produce sport utility vehicles and
other light trucks are typically running around the clock and are
still unable to keep up with demand. American auto makers own most
of the world's sport utility vehicle production capacity,
particularly for larger, high-profit models. These models have
become very popular in the United States and, to a lesser extent,
in foreign markets as gasoline prices have fallen in
inflation-adjusted terms.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Ford survived in the early 1980s partly because of
profits from their international operations, while foreign auto
makers used their profits overseas to build up American
subsidiaries. But as Asian and South American markets crumble and
the European market looks a little shaky, the North American market
has turned into a bastion of profits for the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the shoe is on the other foot _ North America is carrying
virtually everybody else,'' said William Clay Ford Jr., Ford's
chairman. ``We are very dependent on North American profits, and
particularly our North American truck profits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
