<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS PEOPLE BRIEFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(bl) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Down for the Count, a Stock Becomes a Net Heavyweight
</P>
<P>
   For George Horowitz, chairman of the Active Apparel Group,
reviving his small clothing company's dead-in-the-cellar share
price often seemed like the name of his line of active wear, ``The
Grind.'' The thinly traded stock wallowed around at $1.25 a share
as recently as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Horowitz, 48, discovered the Internet. When he announced
that his company's retail Web site had started operations, Active
Apparel became an instant darling of the Internet stock-trading
community. Never mind that it had yet to peddle a single pair of
its Everlast boxing trunks electronically. The stock hit $19 by
Tuesday. Horowitz's stake surged from $758,000 to $10.8 million.
Since then, investor ardor has cooled and the stock has slipped to
$8.125, but it still managed a 550 percent gain for the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such big changes are a little unnerving,'' Horowitz said. In
fact, the volatility has taken a toll. Horowitz said he felt ``a
little under the weather from all this running around,'' including
appearances on CNBC and CNN. ``I just hope that when all this
settles down, we hold some of the premium. We should, I think,
because investors are just beginning to realize the value in our
company.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOSEPH KAHN
</P>
<P>
   Ballooning? It's Just So 1870s
</P>
<P>
   Richard Branson, the gung-ho chairman of Virgin Group of Cos.,
presumably did not enjoy seeing a picture of himself _ windswept
and waterlogged _ on the front pages of Britain's newspapers the
day after Christmas. But he was unable to escape the barrage of
publicity that came when he aborted his fourth effort to
circumnavigate the Earth and ditched his hot-air balloon off
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Jean-Jules Verne, great-grandson of Jules
Verne, the author of ``Around the World in 80 Days,'' said he
couldn't take the efforts of Branson and his crewmates, Per
Lindstrand and Steve Fossett, seriously. ``I'm not taken in by the
ICO Global Challenger's team,'' Verne told Le Figaro, the French
newspaper. ``What they are doing is closer to a millionaire's whim
than a genuine scientific inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   Verne, 36, who recently put his famous ancestor's works on
CD-Rom, said Jules wouldn't have been impressed, either. ``He would
be much more enthusiastic about a possible voyage to Mars than by a
competition reserved for people who can afford to indulge in this
sort of craze,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SARAH LYALL
</P>
<P>
   Another Day, Another $100 Million
</P>
<P>
   Another Las Vegas executive has given $100 million to a citadel
of higher learning. Just before Thanksgiving, James E. Rogers,
owner of Sunbelt Communications, doubled an earlier pledge to the
University of Arizona's college of law, to $100 million. Then,
before Christmas, Ralph Engelstad, owner of the Imperial Palace
Hotel and Casino, pledged $100 million to the University of North
Dakota in Grand Forks.
</P>
<P>
   Engelstad said that nearly half of the gift would be used to
build a 12,000-seat hockey arena at the school, where he played
goalie in the early 1950s. The university's president, Ken Baker,
told The Associated Press that he was ``really without words to
adequately express how incredibly grateful we are.''
</P>
<P>
   But Erik Siemers, editor of the school newspaper, The Dakota
Student, had a slightly different take. ``Personally, it's really
exciting,'' Siemers said, noting that hockey is something of a
religion in the state. But, he added, ``Some people might be
skeptical and ask, `How much does the hockey program need?' '' UND
teachers, he said, ``are very low-paid _ very.''
</P>
<P>
   Prepare for Departure. Quickly.
</P>
<P>
   It's the little things that count in making the planes fly on
time. Make that the little things you don't have to count. The
flight attendants on Delta Air Lines' no-frills carrier, Delta
Express, complained they were wasting time totaling up the
beverages and napkins for the next flight before loading them in
galley drawers.
</P>
<P>
   So Paulette Corbin, Delta Express' managing director (and a
former flight attendant), told them to skip the task. Also at their
suggestion, magazine racks were moved from the front to the back of
planes, so browsing passengers would not slow down boarding.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes after the last passenger gets off an airplane, the
crew starts getting it ready for the next load, Ms. Corbin said,
``and 30 minutes later we're flying again.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts did not exactly cheer the launch of Delta
Express two years ago. ``The first article that I remember called
us `Delta Distress,''' Ms. Corbin said. Since then, though, the
carrier has nearly tripled its daily flights, to 170 from 62.
</P>
<P>
   _ By EDWIN McDOWELL
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
