<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-BUDGET-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO SPEND THE LONG-SOUGHT SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rl) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1997, Congress and the Clinton administration
agreed on a five-year plan to balance the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, they watched in surprise as the deficit disappeared
ahead of schedule and the nation entered what should be a long era
of surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Congress and the administration will debate in earnest
for the first time what to do with the fiscal windfall, which the
Congressional Budget Office estimates should total $1.55 trillion
over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   They can use the money to help shore up the Social Security
system. They can use it for tax cuts. They can use it to increase
spending on education, health care, the military and other
politically popular programs. Or they can use it to pay down the
$5.5 trillion national debt accumulated over decades of deficit
spending.
</P>
<P>
   But if the options are clear cut, budget politics this year are
likely to be even more muddled than usual, even if the focus has
shifted from the belt-tightening of the deficit years to dividing
up the spoils generated by a strong economy and excess tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last 18 years the goal of fiscal policy was clear: to
reduce the deficit,'' said Thomas Gallagher, a political economist
at Lehman Bros. in Washington. ``Now there's no clear goal for
fiscal policy. This will be the hardest year to anticipate the
outcome of the policy debate, and a hard year for the markets to
interpret what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the usual ideological and interest group politics
that shape the debate over tax and spending priorities, both
parties will be keeping a close eye on the economy. If growth slows
substantially and unemployment rises, Republicans are likely to
step up calls for a tax cut to give the economy some fiscal
stimulus and Democrats are likely to call for additional spending
on unemployment insurance, job retraining and other social programs
to help ease the impact of any downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a sharp economic downturn, though, the budget debate
will center on Social Security. With the retirement system heading
toward insolvency in 2032, according to the latest government
projections, the administration and congressional leaders are
looking for solutions among a host of ideologically charged and
politically sensitive proposals.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is not just Social Security's long-term health, but the
budget agenda for 1999. In a move that even Republicans concede was
brilliant politics, Clinton demanded early last year that Congress
set aside any surpluses until the nation had dealt with Social
Security _ a formulation that stymied Republican efforts to use the
surpluses to finance tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, too, have been itching to get at the surplus. After
years of being told that social programs had to be curtailed in the
interests of bringing down the deficit, they have a long list of
priorities that they say deserve more money, especially education,
child care and help for people moving off welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Working out agreements that can pass a Republican Congress and
win the president's signature would be difficult enough, given the
ideological difference between the parties. Reaching bipartisan
deals in the aftermath of impeachment proceedings will be even
trickier.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, you have to find a way to accommodate both sets of
goals, or neither gets done,'' said Philip Moseley, a former
Republican chief of staff for the House Ways and Means Committee
who is now a partner at Ernst &AMP; Young. ``It's going to take some
accommodation. What I don't know is whether the political situation
will allow for that.''
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans succeed in freeing up some of the surplus for a
big tax reduction, they will face a fight among themselves about
what kind of cut to pursue. Social conservatives want to
concentrate on tax cuts for families, and have put at the top of
their list a reduction in the so-called marriage penalty. Economic
conservatives are pressing for an across-the-board cut in income
tax rates. In recent years the social conservatives have prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has left open the possibility that he could support a
tax cut once Social Security's problems are solved. But when asked
about uses for the surplus, Clinton's advisers have, in the last
several months, emphasized the need to also shore up Medicare, the
health insurance system for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Given all the crosscurrents at play, Gallagher of Lehman Bros.
said he could see four possible developments. First is what he
calls ``the big deal,'' in which the two parties agree on Social
Security and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Second would be an outcome similar to 1998, in which the two
parties stalemate, spending a bit of the surplus, but basically
allowing it by default to go to reducing the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   The third of his outcomes is no Social Security deal, but a
modest budget package, including some additional spending plus some
reduction in the marriage penalty, the quirk in the tax code that
leads many two-income couples to pay more in taxes than single
people with the same incomes.
</P>
<P>
   And fourth is a sizable tax cut independent of a Social Security
overhaul _ an outcome that would be likely only if the economy
turned down sharply.
</P>
<P>
   There are some signs that the two parties might be able to reach
a compromise on Social Security. But any bipartisanship on that
front could be more than offset by lingering effects from the
impeachment proceedings. And if the two parties are unable to reach
some accommodation on fiscal issues this year, they will have to
wait until after the presidential race of 2000, which both sides
think could hinge on what priorities the nation wants to set for
the new era of fiscal plenty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
