<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE SUN GOES OUT OF THE SUN FLOWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Jan. 3)  
(DW) 
 By TOVAH MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I figured it was safe to visit Moses Pendleton only after
sunflower season was a distant memory. It didn't seem wise to
arrive in midsummer during the throes of this year's sunflower
fiasco. Moses, as he is universally known, doesn't suffer failure
lightly, and he finds helianthus-related humiliations particularly
hard to bear.
</P>
<P>
   Moses Pendletonis a dancer and choreographer. founder of the
groundbreaking Pilobolus troupe and the founder, choreographer and
artistic director of Momix. But 20 years ago, when he first settled
in a cavernous Victorian house in Washington, Conn., where both
Pilobolus and Momix are based, he decided that the place needed to
be spruced up by a garden. A friend advised that sunflowers were
the least labor-intensive option.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hacked out ray-shaped beds from the wilderness, planted
seeds of Mammoth Russian and enjoyed an Instamatic garden,'' Moses
said. Beginner's luck continued for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the blissful days when sunflowers flowed freely.
Gardens planted in variations of a gigantic wheel with spokes or
spirals dense with sunflowers provided a reason for dinner parties
with tables set for 60 at the center of the helix. The gargantuan,
radiant botanical overachievers inspired Momix's 1991 ``Passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before sunflowers hit international stardom as cut flowers,
the biggest blooms found their way into vases throughout the
rambling Victorian house. Three rocking chairs on the porch were
commandeered by sunflower-faced scarecrows. Dried sunflowers
predominated Halloween and Thanksgiving decorations. By Christmas,
sunflower seed heads were pinned to the wallpaper in the living
room and strewn on mantels.
</P>
<P>
   That was 20 years ago, and Moses has ever since been found
planting sunflowers faithfully on the Ides of May. You can set your
watch by it.
</P>
<P>
   He insists on performing the sowing ritual himself, although he
has hired a gardener to tend, thin, weed and fertilize. When things
were going smoothly, every summer morning, he could be found in the
center of his sunflower wheel, getting ``energized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a solarist,'' Moses once said. ``I worship them.'' The
sunflower garden ranked among his proudest triumphs and most vital
muses, until something went awry about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the days when deer, chipmunks and crows were his
primary concern. However, the last couple of years have brought
foes of a more serious nature.
</P>
<P>
   First, it was verticillium wilt, then, it was rhizoctonia,
compounded by other opportunistic viruses. At first, a single plant
here and there curled up its leaves and wilted. Then stems started
succumbing wholesale to a distinct white mold. Before long, his
garden had a 90 percent mortality rate, or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of going down to the garden to become inspired, I went
down to bury the dead,'' Moses moaned.
</P>
<P>
   He tried everything, including altering his planting pattern to
leave infected soil fallow; spacing the plants, so that each had
plenty of breathing room; spraying every 7 to 10 days with a
fungicide; thinning out and burning infected bedfellows; and
sterilizing tools.
</P>
<P>
   Sunflowers are not normally such a challenge. They are often
recommended to beginners as a ``sow and stand back'' operation. But
nature doesn't usually smile on large-scale, single-species gardens
and Moses' property was a classic monoculture.
</P>
<P>
   He has experimented with cultivated varieties other than the
standard Mammoth Russian. But they all fall victim sooner or later,
even the age-old Tarahumara White Shelled sunflower grown by
Southwestern American Indians long before Europeans settled this
country. He draws the line at chemicals so toxic that they require
donning a full-body rubber suit, and he has yet to try steaming the
soil and then covering it with tin foil. He has consulted every
agriculture extension agent and university botanist who will listen
to his plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to call my senator,'' he threatened, in the heat of
triage.
</P>
<P>
   Moses refuses to surrender, although friends have tried to prod
him toward cannas, poppies or any other flashy flower that might
divert his attention. Instead, the sunflower-possessed
choreographer is seeking disease-resistant heirloom varieties and
look-alikes. (So far, the perennial many-armed Helianthus
maximilliani, as well as the closely related Mexican sunflower,
Tithonia rotundifolia, have proved steadfast.)
</P>
<P>
   Moses has faith that a cure will be found. ``The government will
do something about this,'' he said, with the faith of a true
fanatic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
