<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4742 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-GM-ART-$AD     01-01 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-GM-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM KNOCKING AT AUTO SHOW DOOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ General Motors Corp. practically invented the
auto-design extravaganza, piquing the public's interest in the
1950s with its glitzy Motorama shows that included futuristic
concept cars. But in recent years, as its budgets were cut and its
marketers gained prominence over its designers, GM has pretty much
sat in the shadows at the leading auto shows, upstaged by its
crosstown rivals.
</P>
<P>
   This year, GM is planning to make a splash once again. Starting
with the 1999 North American International Auto Show in Detroit,
where press previews begin Jan. 3, and continuing through the other
leading shows this year, GM wants the world to know that a lot is
going on behind the closely guarded doors of its design center.
</P>
<P>
   GM is providing a sampling of some 200 vehicle concepts it has
developed to explore new types of vehicles and design themes it
plans to use for each of its divisions. The company has not put on
such a corporate spread of design studies since the '50s, said
Wayne Cherry, vice president of design at GM.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've selected concepts representing five divisions to show
publicly all at once,'' Cherry said. ``They will show the breadth
and depth of GM's portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the GM concept cars making their debut at the
Detroit show, which opens to the public Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   BUICK CIELO _ Based on the Regal GS and equipped with GM's
venerable supercharged 3.8-liter V6 engine, the Cielo _ Spanish for
``sky'' _ is a a five-passenger, four-door contemporary convertible
built for a family.
</P>
<P>
   The car is laden with technology: The hardtop retracts along
roof rails that extend from the front pillar to the rear deck; the
roof responds to spoken commands, retracting in segments or all the
way. The clamshell doors _ access is easy, because there is no
pillar between front and rear _ also open electronically on
command. And voice recognition is also used to fold down the rear
seats and operate the various entertainment and climate controls.
</P>
<P>
   With its fluid lines, the Cielo's design is reminiscent of the
first Buick concepts created by GM's legendary design chief, Harley
Earl. The car revives a discontinued Buick trademark _
``portholes'' outside the engine compartment _ and has a prominent
Riviera-style grille.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cielo has a very strong design theme that I think we can
use with Buick for the foreseeable future in terms of giving us a
strong identity,'' Cherry said.
</P>
<P>
   CADILLAC EVOQ _ This two-passenger roadster bristles with
technology, but perhaps more significantly it is is ``a medium to
show the visual direction of Cadillacs of the future,'' Cherry
said.
</P>
<P>
   The black Evoq (pronounced evoke) has sharp edges and a
retractable hardtop similar to the Mercedes SLKs. And Cadillac is
using it as a showcase for its latest high-tech devices, including
Night Vision, a system that uses infrared cameras to allow drivers
to ``see'' objects at night that are beyond headlight range; an
on-board computer that can connect to the Internet; a digital audio
system, voice recognition controls and external rear-view cameras
instead of conventional mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   The engine is a supercharged 4.2-liter version of the acclaimed
Northstar V8.
</P>
<P>
   CHEVROLET NOMAD _ Chevy, which has been reviving famous names
like Malibu and Impala, has dusted off this appellation originally
used in the 1954 Motorama and then applied to sporty station wagons
in 1955-57 _ cars that are treasured by collectors today.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Nomad defies categorization. Technically, it is a
performance coupe because of its two doors, its rear-wheel drive
configuration and its 5.7-liter V8. Stylistically, the
five-passenger vehicle looks like a station wagon. But access to
the back seat is through pivoting panels that pull out and back,
somewhat like the doors of a minivan. The rear seats fold flat with
the rear floor. A tailgate pulls down like a pickup truck's, then
slides under the cargo bay. The roof retracts in sections like a
Venetian blind, allowing tall loads to rise above the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   OLDSMOBILE RECON _ GM calls this, like the Nomad, a crossover
vehicle, though it clearly resembles a compact sport utility. With
hard edges even more severe than the Evoq's, this five-passenger,
four-door hatchback has a two-panel sunroof and is loaded with
technology, including an Internet-capable computer.
</P>
<P>
   PONTIAC AZTEK _ A vehicle that seems much like a sport utility,
the Aztek mixes in attributes of a sedan and a minivan. An
extremely sporty four-door, four-passenger hatchback, the bold
Aztek has flip-and-fold rear bucket seats to provide a flat floor _
they can also be removed _ and has innovative storage areas like a
minivan. The instrument cluster resembles that of a motorcycle. The
Aztek is front-wheel drive with traction control and is powered by
a 3.4-liter V6 engine. It features traditional Pontiac styling
touches like air scoops, a split grille and ribbing along the
sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
