<HEADER>
A4744 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SMART-FORD-ART-$A     01-01 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-FORD-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD EAGER TO MAKE A SPLASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When J. Mays took over the top design post at Ford Motor Co. in
October 1997, he boldly promised to put his signature on Ford's
cars at the Detroit auto show in 1999. He would begin, he said, by
making the company's brands more distinct from one another.
</P>
<P>
   Mays, one of today's most watched car designers, will begin
delivering on his promise today with the unveiling of a reborn
Thunderbird evocative of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Ford will showcase that car, along with other concept vehicles
and production models, in an elaborate and huge (about 100,000
square feet on two levels) exhibit that Mays played a prominent
role in designing. Each brand under Ford's control _ Aston Martin,
Ford, Jaguar, Lincoln, Mazda and Mercury _ will have its own
display area intended to set a complementary ambiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our overall theme for the show is separation and amplification
of the individual marques under the Ford umbrella,'' Mays said in
an interview. Ford will also showcase ``aspirational products''
like the Thunderbird. He describes these as ``products you desire
and covet'' and that stimulate an emotional response.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are cars with a point of view, and a point of view that
isn't going to appeal to everyone,'' he said. ``It's much the same
as Harley-Davidson says _ they try to delight the few and therefore
attract the many.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are two products Ford will display:
</P>
<P>
   FORD THUNDERBIRD _ This rear-drive, V8-powered two-seat roadster
uses styling touches from the 1955-57 and 1961-62 T-Birds and uses
pastel colors from those periods. Aluminum provides a modern touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to give people the car they looked at and dreamt
about as children,'' Mays said. ``It's a very light-hearted,
relaxed American look at what a great Sunday afternoon drive could
look like.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thunderbird is scheduled to go into production as a 2000
model, marking the 45th anniversary of the original T-Bird.
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN BLACKWOOD _ Mays describes this luxury pickup truck,
which was shown publicly last week at the Los Angeles auto show, as
the ultimate utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   It looks much like a Lincoln Navigator from front bumper to back
doors, but behind those is a pickup bed lined with stainless steel
and covered by a metal top. The exterior is accented with dark,
trendy Wenge wood _ not an applique _ from Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackwood could easily be produced, and because it would
require few new components it would cost relatively little to
build. Mays said Ford had not decided whether to offer it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
