<HEADER>
A4748 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSOURI-RIVER-ART-85     01-01 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-RIVER-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE WANTS A SAY IN SETTING THE MISSOURI RIVER'S COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(htv) 
 By PAM BELLUCK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEBRASKA CITY, Neb. _ Lewis and Clark would not know the
Missouri River now.
</P>
<P>
   The tumultuous water that taunted their canoes as they forged
the way to the American West is docile now, domesticated.
</P>
<P>
   The ``confused jumble of savage-looking snags'' that Mark Twain
steered his steamboat through is now slick and sterile. And there
is little left of the muddy water that Horace Greeley once said was
like ``thick milk porridge _ you could not discern an egg in a
glass of it.''
</P>
<P>
   For 50 years now, the hand of man has tamed the Missouri River,
damming it and diking it, streamlining and straitjacketing it into
a channel for barges and a generally well-behaved feeding tube for
the fertile farmland on its banks.
</P>
<P>
   But big changes are coming to the Big Muddy, America's longest
river, stretching nearly 2,500 miles from Three Forks, Mont., to
St. Louis, is in the throes of an identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   After the withering drought of the late 1980s and the ferocious
floods of 1993, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, which essentially
controls the river's water flow, decided it needed to re-evaluate
its master plan.
</P>
<P>
   The fracas over the river's future is fierce as
environmentalists, farmers, barge operators, recreation boosters,
hydroelectric utilities, Indian tribes and municipal leaders all
try to make sure the river stays _ or becomes _ what they want it
to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody would dearly love if we could come up with a
recommendation that everyone could agree on,'' said Richard H.
Opper, executive director of the Missouri River Basin Association,
a coalition of the eight river-basin states and two dozen Indian
tribes, which met recently to discuss the river.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle is the Corps, which controls how much water
is released from upstream reservoirs after each year's snow melt _
and when. It has the sometimes Sisyphean task of insuring there is
enough water when and where it is needed, but not so much that it
mutinies its banks.
</P>
<P>
   The Corps has issued a list of options _ different ways to
adjust the ebb and flow of the Missouri _ with the aim of making a
decision later this year.
</P>
<P>
   And that has unleashed a torrent of debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saying for years there are really two things that the
Corps could not propose politically,'' Opper said. ``One was
keeping the current situation the same. The other was any sort of
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Nebraska City, an unpretentious, plain-vanilla Plains
town about 400 miles upriver from where the Missouri dumps into the
Mississippi near St. Louis, most of the conflicts are easy to see.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers like John Crook, growing corn and soybeans on river
bottom land his great grandfather staked out in 1878, want the
Missouri to be reined in further so their crops won't drown.
</P>
<P>
   People like Ray Pinney, who manages the barge terminal here,
want the water to stay swift and deep so towboats and barges can
keep hauling fertilizer up from St. Louis and Kansas City and
taking grain down river at harvest time.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Smith, who represents the environmental group, American
Rivers, in this part of the country, and Gerald Mestl, a biologist
with the Nebraska Game and Parks Commission, want the river to
return, as much as possible, to its natural, free-flowing state.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of management have destroyed miles of natural habitat,
threatening the survival of many species and landing three _ the
pallid sturgeon, the piping plover and the least tern _ on the
endangered species list.
</P>
<P>
   And Nancy Hoch, who heads the economic development corporation
in this town of about 7,000 people, is supportive of farming and
business interests. But like leaders in other cities that once used
the river as an industrial dumping ground, she also understands
environmental concerns. After all, Nebraska City's claim to fame is
as the home of the inventor of Arbor Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strongly that the river does not belong to
anyone,'' said Ms. Hoch. ``It does not belong to the least tern. It
does not belong to barge traffic. We need to balance the river.''
</P>
<P>
   But balance is hard to come by on a river that sculpts the
country's mid-section, draining about one-sixth of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Further north of Nebraska City, a booming hunting, fishing and
boating industry wants to insure the reservoirs don't lose too much
water each year.
</P>
<P>
   And up and down the Missouri are Indian tribes, who have begun
to assert claims to water rights along significant portions of the
river, supported by a turn-of-the-century Supreme Court ruling.
When they ultimately negotiate what water they control, the tribes
say they envision many uses including irrigation, electricity and
exporting water for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many interests in the Missouri River Basin,'' said
Richard Bad Moccasin, executive director of the tribes'
organization, Mni Sose Intertribal Water Rights Coalition (``Mni''
means ``water'' in the Lakota language, and ``Sose,'' Bad Moccasin
said, means ``the way the Missouri used to be _ murky and muddy and
wild and woolly.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't envy the Army Corps,'' he said, ``but, well, they
created the monster _ trying to change that mighty Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 1924EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASPIAN-OIL-ART-2TAKE     01-01 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASPIAN-OIL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASPIAN NATIONS AWAIT A WALL OF MONEY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALAKHANY, Azerbaijan _ A forest of rusting oil derricks, relics
of the last oil boom here a century ago, stretch from this gritty
town toward the shore of the Caspian Sea. They are producing
low-grade crude, worked by laborers who live nearby in hovels. Oil
permeates the soil, and in warm months its stench becomes nearly
unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   A welder who lives at the edge of the sprawling oil field, Kazim
Heydarov, earns a monthly salary of $50 from the state-owned
Azerbaijani oil company. With that and the produce from a small
vegetable garden, he supports his wife and three children.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the oil money starts coming in, the government will pave
our streets,'' Heydarov predicted during a recent break from his
work. ``There will be free medicine and schoolbooks. I'll be making
enough money to move to a nicer place away from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he and his friends would react if the oil wealth did
not filter down to them, Heydarov paused, as if he had never
considered the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money has to be used for our benefit because we're the
people of this country,'' he said finally. ``If it doesn't, of
course we will be very angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Waves of cash are expected to begin pouring into the treasuries
of Azerbaijan and the two other new Caspian nations, Kazakhstan and
Turkmenistan. Even with a slump in crude oil prices, all three
former Soviet republics will probably have more than enough money
to guarantee most citizens a comfortable life.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden riches, however, can be dangerous. Oil money has made
some countries prosperous, but it has helped destroy others. The
three new nations on the shores of the Caspian Sea are ruled by
despots, torn by ethnic rivalries, plagued by corruption and
surrounded by unruly neighbors. Many outsiders doubt their ability
to survive the bonanza ahead. Some fear a decline into
Nigeria-style chaos rather than a rise to Norway-like stability and
affluence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no sign that they will have the capacity to manage
this wealth,'' said Ercan Murat, the chief U.N. representative in
Azerbaijan. ``It will create a lot of problems. It will increase
the already substantial gap between rich and poor, and eventually
it will affect political stability.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point in the coming decade, when oil and gas production
reaches full capacity and pipeline networks are in place, the three
new Caspian nations will be hit by what planners call ``the wall of
money.'' Each will probably take in billions of dollars each year
from energy exports.
</P>
<P>
   Falling oil prices have sobered energy executives and government
officials in Caspian countries. Their resource is large enough,
however, that even with low prices, they can be reasonably sure of
making enough money to lift their countries out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials pledge that they will use this money to
build schools, hospitals and roads. But they concede that no plans
are in place to assure such promises.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Azerbaijan, where the big money is expected to begin
arriving around 2003, newly rich ``oil sharks'' pay cash for luxury
cars but can barely drive them outside the capital because roads
are in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   In Kazakhstan, which also expects to see riches in about five
years, the government has moved its capital from the largest city,
Almaty, to Astana, a remote town on the northern steppe, at a cost
that may reach billions of dollars. Yet almost nothing is being
spent to deal with a virulent strain of tuberculosis that is
sweeping the country, or to combat other diseases ranging from
polio to bubonic plague.
</P>
<P>
   It is less certain when great wealth will come to Turkmenistan,
because someone must first build a pipeline for its natural gas
reserves, and energy companies are still deciding which route would
be most economical. But even with no decision in sight, President
Saparmurat Niyazov has embarked on a billion-dollar building spree,
borrowing money from foreign banks to pay for hotels, palaces and
mosques.
</P>
<P>
   ``The region could become a breeding ground of terrorism, a
hotbed of religious and political extremism and a battleground for
outright war,'' the U.S. deputy secretary of state, Strobe Talbott,
asserted in a speech.
</P>
<P>
   Three specters figure in almost every Caspian nightmare:
corruption, ethnic war and battles over political succession.
</P>
<P>
   The presidents of Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan and Azerbaijan spent
decades in the communist apparatus, rising to pinnacles of power in
a system that rewarded the clever, the devious and the ruthless.
Today they rule in the style of absolute monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   Even critics of the three leaders acknowledge that they have
done remarkably well in balancing pressures from foreign
governments and oil companies. President Heydar Aliyev of
Azerbaijan has proven especially deft, returning from political
oblivion and then emerging as an international deal maker. Yet he
also personifies the region's weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Aliyev, who is 75, has crushed several potential successors,
apparently fearing that they might seek to overthrow him.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about the post-Aliyev era is taboo. Last year, the
police suppressed a magazine that had predicted chaos when he
passes from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   If Aliyev had wanted to encourage the emergence of younger
politicians, October would have been a fine time to do it. He was
running for re-election, and few doubted that even in a free
election he would win handsomely. But foreign diplomats and
election observers proclaimed the campaign deeply unfair, with the
police attacking opposition rallies and with ballot boxes evidently
stuffed to guarantee Aliyev a resounding victory.
</P>
<P>
   In facing the succession issue, as in other ways, Azerbaijan is
a troubling model for the two other Caspian nations awaiting their
riches.
</P>
<P>
   Niyazov, 58, was hospitalized in 1993 for what was described as
an arterial blockage in his lung, and last year he underwent a
quadruple bypass heart operation. Nonetheless, he insists that he
is in perfect health and brooks no talk of successors.
</P>
<P>
   When Niyazov visited Washington in May, journalists asked him
about reports that he represses opposition parties. ``We do not
have any opposition parties,'' he replied. ``You are misinformed.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Kazakhstan's president, Nursultan Nazarbayev, also
58, has called an election for January, apparently hoping to
prolong his mandate before any trouble sets in. He has forbidden
his most potent critic to run against him and has arranged for the
press to give him lavish coverage while virtually ignoring his
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years ago, both Azerbaijan and neighboring Georgia,
through which an oil pipeline is being built, were consumed by
civil wars. They could erupt again.
</P>
<P>
   In Azerbaijan, fighting between government troops and ethnic
Armenians from the Nagorno-Karabakh region ended in early 1994 with
the Armenians triumphant. But within a few years, Azerbaijan will
have enough money to build a powerful army and may be tempted to
try to retake Nagorno-Karabakh. That could prompt a regional
conflict, especially if Armenia's old friend Russia, or its new
friend Iran, decides to come to its aid.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, rebels have seized territory in two regions and
could probably stage insurgencies in two others. Shooting regularly
breaks out along disputed borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most disruptive things that could happen in these
countries are battles over succession and a renewal of ethnic
conflicts,'' said an American oil executive based in Azerbaijan.
``In your worst case they happen together.''
</P>
<P>
   Corruption is blatant in Azerbaijan, where many diplomats and
local citizens say that nearly every public official may be bought,
from lowly customs inspector to august cabinet minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this country anyone can become rich overnight if the
president favors him,'' said Zardoucht Alizadeh, a leader of
Azerbaijan's small Social Democratic Party. ``If I get a permit to
export 100 million barrels of oil, I will be so rich I will never
have to work again. And that is without doing anything, just by
getting one favor from the president.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Ambitious neighbors are watching them enviously. Some powerful
Russians dream of retaking these lands and their energy reserves,
or at least imposing pro-Russian regimes on them.
</P>
<P>
   Iran is working to increase its influence over neighboring
Azerbaijan and Turkmenistan. China thirsts looks longingly at the
reserves just over its western border in Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this array of threats, many people in the new Caspian
nations remain optimistic. They complain about corruption and are
impatient for better housing, schools and medical care. Yet they
believe the promises their leaders have made, and they are eagerly
waiting for the money to pour in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is going to get better,'' predicted Muatlieva
Aksha, a mother who runs a roadside kiosk in Turkmenistan. ``We've
heard government people on TV talking about how much oil and gas we
have. It means that poor people aren't going to be poor any more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
