<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4761 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-RENAISSANCE-7     01-01 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RENAISSANCE-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 CLINTON PREFERS GOLF TO TALK AT RENAISSANCE WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also CONSERVATIVE-RETREAT) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILTON HEAD, S.C. _ President Clinton rang out his most unusual
of years in his usual, if peculiar, way: in very earnest policy
discussion with more than a thousand acquaintances and fans _ and a
few old friends and unimpressed strangers _ assembled at the annual
Renaissance Weekend here.
</P>
<P>
   For more than an hour as midnight approached on Thursday, the
president and Hillary Rodham Clinton fielded questions selected by
the event's organizers. In all the talk about Africa, Social
Security and health care, impeachment and Monica Lewinsky went
unmentioned. At midnight the president kissed his wife, then joined
in a champagne toast and sang along to ``Auld Lang Syne.''
</P>
<P>
   To some guests, the Clintons appeared solemn, far less spirited
and engaged than in the past. Indeed, after a year in which he
admitted adultery before his family and the world, launched his
biggest military assault, and became the second president ever
impeached, Clinton seems in particular need of renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   But if so, he did not seek it in the organized doings here. He
spent more time on the golf course and with his Labrador retriever
on the beach during his three days at this studious gathering, a
kind of ``Big Chill'' retreat for Baby Boomers who didn't inhale.
``This is sort of paradise if you're a C-Span junkie,'' enthused
Bob Richardson, winner of a Nobel Prize in physics for discovering
superfluidity in liquid helium 3.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not attend any of the chin-stroking seminars that,
like bran flakes in a retirement community, are a staple of the
official fare. He passed up the half-day ``academy'' devoted to
``Character: What is it? Does is it count?'' He also skipped ``My
Family's Lessons for Life,'' ``Spiritual Life in a Secular
Society,'' and a session on the meaning of the 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
   In some seminars, Clinton's trying year was an unavoidable, if
delicate, subject for the businessmen, politicians, scientists and
journalists. ``I don't think anyone here is quite so gauche as to
directly address'' Clinton's problems, said Walt Cunningham, the
Apollo 7 astronaut and conservative radio talk show host, though he
said the subject had been debated in a ``genteel way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentility is the reigning principle of this privileged, even
precious conclave, and guests bemoan what they regard as the
baffling failure of political discourse at large to mimic
Renaissance Weekend's lonely model. So far, the only ones to take
up the challenge are the conservatives who set out to mock it by
creating the rival ``Dark Ages'' conference, now known as ``The
Weekend,'' which is focused more tightly on politics.
</P>
<P>
   The throng here leans distinctly to the left, but there are some
notable Republicans, including Rep. Mark Sanford, R-S.C., who voted
to impeach the president. He told The Associated Press that he
intended to avoid any talk of that with Clinton. ``They'd probably
be fairly unproductive conversations, to say the least,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford said he would encourage Clinton to achieve ``a legacy''
by fixing Social Security _ apparently not expecting the president
to be removed any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gave the same impression, appearing as cheerful and
confident in public as ever. But those who spent private time with
him here described him as clearly in need of recreation and
preoccupied with maneuvering in the Senate over his upcoming trial.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a question-and-answer session with young people
Thursday evening, followed by the banquet and exchange later that
night, Clinton did not attend any Renaissance Weekend events. On
Friday, he spent more than four hours on the golf course _ on top
of almost six on Thursday _ before returning to the beachfront
estate he is using here. There, he watched his beloved Arkansas
Razorbacks lose a heartbreaker to Michigan in the Citrus Bowl. With
their daughter, Chelsea, the Clintons flew back to Washington late
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons have been regulars at Renaissance Weekend for 15
years, almost since its founding in 1981. Their detachment this
year contrasted sharply with past appearances, particularly with
the exuberant touch football games and job-seeking of 1992, after
Clinton's first election.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That election transformed the annual event from a fringe,
low-key gathering into an A-list magnet for those who keep track of
such things. (Clinton's rising tide also elevated the weekend's
founder, Philip Lader, to the Court of St. James's, where he is the
U.S. ambassador.)
</P>
<P>
   Participants still gush about the breadth of the discussion and
the vigor of the networking. Frank Luntz, a Republican pollster,
rhapsodized about spending 90 minutes on Thursday walking the beach
with Dr. Ruth Westheimer, the sex expert, and Alan Blinder, the
Princeton economist. ``Al Franken's wife is helping me decorate my
new home!'' he added, referring to the comedian.
</P>
<P>
   Luntz's question was the last one read to Clinton on Thursday
night. After noting that he had got rich helping to write the
Republicans' Contract with America, he asked, ``What advice would
you give to the Republican party? I need the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton replied, according to the White House and participants,
that the Contract with America helped the Republicans in 1994 and
the Democrats in 1996. He called for a partisanship devoted to
debates over worthy subjects like Social Security. And in his only,
oblique reference to his difficult 1998, he said he hoped the
country would ``move away from the politics of personal
destruction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
