<HEADER>
A4767 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKETS-FOREIGN-ART-N     01-01 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETS-FOREIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN STOCKS STILL LAG AFTER A LATE RALLY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Overseas stocks rebounded sharply in the fourth quarter, both in
developed and emerging markets. But in some emerging markets even
100 percent rallies were not enough to make up for the selloffs
that pushed stocks to their lows just as the quarter began. Many of
these markets still ended the year with declines.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Indonesia. Its stock market surged 120.6 percent in
dollar terms in the fourth quarter, according to the
emerging-market indexes of the International Finance Corp., the
private sector financing arm of the World Bank. But for the year,
the stock market is down 29.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombian stock market rose 27.3 percent in the last three
months but is off 43.6 percent for the year. Brazil slipped 0.3
percent and is down 42.6 percent for the year, while the Mexican
market climbed 9.5 percent in the third quarter but is off 39
percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall Latin American markets, which are still being held back
by the doubts about the success of budget reform in Brazil, rose
6.9 percent in the fourth quarter but plunged 38.3 percent for the
year. Asian emerging stock markets jumped 24.6 percent but are down
6.7 percent for the year, according to the I.F.C. data.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea was an exception. Its stock market surged 123.3
percent in the last quarter, and the market is now up 119.1 percent
for the year. South Korea's economy has stabilized more quickly
than a lot of other Asian countries. Interest rates have fallen and
the country's trade deficit has turned around.
</P>
<P>
   But Ron Chapman, head of international equities at the Dreyfus
Corp., said most of the rallies in emerging markets had been driven
by local investors. Foreign investors, he said, are still staying
away.
</P>
<P>
   William P. Sterling, the global strategist for BEA Associates,
an investment management firm, said that ``some of these stock
markets have become penny stock markets, and institutional
investors can't play that.'' He also said investors could not
assume that good fundamentals had precipitated the fourth-quarter
rallies. ``I think that would be misleading,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the world's developed stock markets, the story was more
positive as the fourth-quarter rally, in many cases, wiped out the
losses from the selloff that accelerated with the ruble devaluation
and debt default by the Russians in August. In Europe, according to
the Financial Times/Standard &AMP; Poor's world indexes, Britain,
Belgium, Finland, France and Italy led a rebound that pushed the
European-wide index up 18 percent and left it up 24.8 percent for
the year.
</P>
<P>
   The best performer in Europe was Finland, a market that few
investors pay much attention to. It surged 40.4 percent, buoyed by
two stocks that dominate the market: Nokia, the mobil phone maker,
and Sonera Group, the state-owned telephone company that went
public in November. Since then its stock is up 40.8 percent for the
year. Finland is up 106.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum was Norway, where stocks rose
3.5 percent in the Financial Times index, and Germany, Europe's
largest economy, where stocks rose 12.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Oil-dependent Norway was hurt by the plunge in petroleum prices.
In Germany, the market was held back by weakness in banks, like
Deutsche and Dresdner, industrial companies like Thyssen and energy
companies like RWE.
</P>
<P>
   European emerging markets were mixed. Eastern Europe together
was up 28 percent in the quarter but down 64.8 percent for the
year. Russia surged 66.3 percent, but it was still off a staggering
87.5 percent for the year. Hungary rose 37.2 percent in the last
three months, cutting its annual decline to just 10.8 percent. The
Slovakian market dropped 15.5 percent and plunged 54 percent for
the year.
</P>
<P>
   For next year, Chapman said that Europe would be bedeviled by
the same questions facing the United States: How much will the
economy slow down and what will happen to corporate earnings? He
said that in just the last several months the 1999 growth forecasts
for Continental Europe had dropped to 2 percent or less from almost
3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For American investors, the dollar played a key role in many of
the world's markets.
</P>
<P>
   In some countries, including Indonesia and Japan, much of the
fourth-quarter rebound came from a slide in the value of the dollar
at the end of the year. When the value of the American currency
falls, returns from abroad are worth more when they are translated
back to dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In Indonesia, the dollar's decline accounted for one-third of
the investor's return.
</P>
<P>
   And in Japan, the weaker dollar was about four-fifths of the
quarter's 26.9 percent gain that pushed the stock market into
positive territory for the year with an increase of 5.5 percent.
All of the annual gain was due to a weaker dollar: In yen, the
Japanese market was down 8.5 percent. If many forecasters are
right, the dollar may begin to rally against the Japanese yen this
year, making gains for American investors much harder to come by.
</P>
<P>
   In New Zealand, Australia, Thailand and other countries the
weaker dollar added smaller, but significant, gains to the
quarterly return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incremental returns from the dollar are nothing to sneeze
at,'' said Mark Eisner, a co-head of the index products group at
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
