<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4774 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BRITISH-$ADV03-ART     01-01 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRITISH-$ADV03-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEWEST BRITISH COLONY: NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Blue Room,'' ``Electra'' and ``Cabaret'' with
Alan Cumming, all imported to Broadway from London. ``Shakespeare
in Love,'' ``Elizabeth'' and ``Hilary and Jackie'' on our screens.
``Two Fat Ladies,'' ``Sister Wendy'' and ``Teletubbies'' attracting
cults to PBS. More British names on mastheads. English DJs at Twilo
and Limelight. The oh so post-modern Wallpaper magazine. Alexander
McQueen, the Verve, Ewan MacGregor and the well-tousled Tony Blair,
all giving off glamour rays from afar. In the buzz kingdom of
Manhattan, it's a felicitous time to be British.
</P>
<P>
   And with the ferocity of ... well, wasps, they are colonizing
downtown. They can be seen having breakfast at Les Deux Gamins on
Sheridan Square, spotted at dinner at Da Silvano on Avenue of the
Americas (around the corner from Anna Wintour's town house) or
Balthazar (owned by their countryman Keith McNally) and smelled
chain-smoking in the back room of Piadina on West Ninth Street.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not all. On Thursdays, you'll find them at Don Hill's
bar on Spring Street, where British models like Karen Elson, Kate
Moss and Sophie Dahl, a granddaughter of Roald Dahl, congregate for
'80s revival nights. Other spots include Telephone Bar, Two Eyes,
N.V. and, every Saturday at 10 a.m., Nevada Smith's for soccer on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get all kinds for the games,'' said John Birchall, a
Liverpool-born hairstylist for Cindy Crawford and a Nevada Smith
regular. ``We've seen Vanessa Redgrave and Posh Spice. Sting was in
here once, too, but nobody cared because we were watching the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, when Sting's ``Englishman in New York'' was a hit 10
years ago, it was addressing an alienation that no longer exists
here for the English. These days, downtown is a Little London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans think we all know each other and hang around
together,'' said Vicky Ward, the features editor of The New York
Post, ``and what's shocking is, we sort of do. It's the herd
instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ward said that English people with the gumption to move to
New York, leaving it to their peers to settle down back home, are
downtown types by nature who get a kick out of the novelty of loft
living. Others say they like Greenwich Village because it resembles
London.
</P>
<P>
   Toby Young, a writer, is surrounded on West Fourth Street by
Oxford and Cambridge graduates. ``It's almost like being back at
university,'' said Young, whose father is an English lord, and who
asked for ``The Honorable'' on his credit card to impress American
women. ``In fact, my apartment is about the same size as my room at
Oxford. Well, anyway, it's just a place to sleep between parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Parties and more parties. It's almost like the American
expatriate scene in Paris in the '50s, minus the artistic
sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the Brits who come here tend to be very ambitious,''
Ms. Ward said. ``But many of them know that eventually they'll be
going back to England, so that gives the whole adventure a certain
holiday atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, living in Little London isn't everyone's cup of
Yorkshire tea. ``I find most British men tedious,'' said Patti
Munter, a Jane Street resident, ``because they're all so sure
they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon Doonan, the creative director of Barneys New York, who
moved to the United States from London in the mid-1980s, also finds
the influx unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something so xenophobic about the English,'' he said.
``And there's something so silly about their smug enjoyment of
their horrible food and twee customs. I mean, when the English
colonized the world, they took their tea trays and other annoying
little things with them. Really, the idea of hanging around English
people who are eating English food here seems preposterous to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Everett, James Truman, Gabe Doppelt, Honor Fraser, Stella
Tennant, Joe McKenna, Hamish Bowles, Ms. Wintour, Ms. Moss and
James Murdoch, a son of Rupert, who just bought a town house on
Downing Street and may as well be British. In my neighborhood these
days, I can't run out for a box of tissues without running into
another boldface English person. They're all over the place, and
succeeding as lavishly as orchids in a hothouse.
</P>
<P>
   The British have always sent America their fashionable figures,
from Wilde and Dickens to the Beatles and Bowie, and the visits
have always bolstered their careers. These days, ever more Brits
seem to be coming to New York to get the royal treatment in a
meritocracy that likes to believe it doesn't give a hoot what one's
background is but is nonetheless cowed by accents that sound like
something out of ``Masterpiece Theater.''
</P>
<P>
   So I wondered: if I were to devote a day to being English, would
some of what they have rub off on me? Maybe I could overcome the
age-old inferiority complex Americans feel around the British.
Maybe I could pick up a witticism or two that would singe with
laserlike focus the next time I'm introduced to some supercool
English media pooh-bah who doesn't have the time of day for me.
Maybe, after a good long bath of Britishness, I would be able to
purge myself of feeling so terribly, unstylishly, sincerely
American.
</P>
<P>
   Thackeray, among others, called the English ``a nation of
shopkeepers,'' and so I decided to go shopping. I slipped into my
Katharine Hamnett shirt and a Burberry cashmere turtleneck, then
pedaled my old English bicycle (a black Dunelt _ very Cambridge
tutorial) up to Myers of Keswick on Hudson Street.
</P>
<P>
   Myers of Keswick (it's important that you don't pronounce the w
in Keswick) is a shop with a window photo of Keith Richards, who
sometimes calls in for kippers or steak-and-kidney pie. For an
American, it's a puzzling place. Sausage butty? Marmite? Clotted
cream? When a lovely woman in Birkenstocks, who turned out to be
Stella Tennant, walked in pushing a baby stroller, I seized the
opportunity to ask her how to breakfast like a Briton.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to have marmalade on white toast,'' said Ms. Tennant,
who has a notable aristocratic family in England but lives instead
among the media aristocrats of Greenwich Village. ``And for later,
I recommend you try the Branston pickle.'' She had come in for
Cumberland sausages, Cadbury chocolate powder and other English
foods, which, I suggested, all seemed very high in cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all your American low-fat foods are a bit silly, really,
aren't they,'' Ms. Tennant said, ``because they're all just loaded
with sugar instead of fat.'' Having made me feel like a culinary
alarmist, she pointed her stroller toward the door. ``Well, then,''
she said with a warm smile. ``Have a nice day being English, and do
watch your diet if you must.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Easier said than done. Because a few minutes later, Peter Myers,
who opened Myers of Keswick on July 4, 1985 (``I didn't have
anything better to do that day,'' he said), was feeding me one of
his homemade pork pies. I was still getting over the taste of the
vile Marmite on toast he had just served: Marmite is a yeast
extract that tastes like cheese-flavored shoe polish. While the
cold pork pie beat the Marmite, it wasn't exactly appealing,
either, with aspic congealed on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't like it?'' asked Myers, who has Sweeney Todd
eyebrows and a North Country accent. ``But I made it up so nice for
you.'' He isn't always so welcoming. In the English tradition, he
can be withering to the fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are just so stupid,'' he added. Naomi Campbell, he
said, used to drive up to his store in ``her chauffeur-driven
Jeep'' and charge through his aisles ``like a blinking dervish
while gollaring into a mobile phone to make sure that everyone in
the store knew who she was.''
</P>
<P>
   Just listening to his evisceration of her made me want to
improve my diction and sit up properly. But then, that's the effect
most English people have always had on me. They either tie my
tongue or make me howl like a dog in an attempt to impress, while
they watch with cool moonlike faces.
</P>
<P>
   When I told Myers that I was going to visit Niall Smith, the
antiques dealer, he gave me some Chipolata sausages to deliver.
Stuffed full of pork pie and a bit of bile, I got on my bicycle and
wobbled away.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a stout man whose disheveled blond hair hangs elegantly
in his face, quietly took the sausages from me without making a
fuss. His shop on Bleecker Street smelled of old furniture and was
silent except for one 150-year-old mantel clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``No antiques store should be without a ticking clock,'' said
Smith, who, like Oscar Wilde, is an Irishman who came of age in
London.
</P>
<P>
   If Myers is the stern English butcher, then Smith is the
eccentric dealer. Although he's well known for his Biedermeier
furniture, he declined to talk about the success of his business.
He preferred to describe being followed around in August by a
writer modeling a character on him for a Rupert Everett movie in
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly had a good time talking about that in England,''
said Smith, who uses the same rotary phone he had when he opened
his shop 30 years ago but seems not to find himself eccentric at
all. ``Quentin Crisp is a real eccentric,'' he said. ``He lives
without any money in a one-room flat in the East Village.'' Asked
what he thought about American eccentrics like RuPaul and Sandra
Bernhard, he pursed his lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not eccentric,'' he said. ``Eccentricity is a form of
rebellion. You cannot make a career out of it.'' It seemed a
typically English put-down of success. The thing is, and I didn't
want to argue this with Smith, New York is the place to make a
successful career out of anything that suits you.
</P>
<P>
   It's exactly why the foppish Hamish Bowles at Vogue, loopy
Victoria Bartlett at Interview, and other style-world somebodies
like Candy Pratts-Price, Plum and Lucy Sykes, Melanie Ward and
Doonan have such flashy careers here, too. They are eccentric,
irreverent ironists who are deeply skeptical of American sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   What, if anything, do the English here believe in? The
importance of not being earnest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to declare but my genius,'' Oscar Wilde said
when he arrived for a well-publicized tour of America in 1882 and
was greeted with unchecked enthusiasm. He had not yet written
anything of note. It mattered little. He was English, a confident
dandy dripping with solicitude. ``I know perfectly well why
Americans are so violent,'' he said at one stop. ``It's because
your wallpaper is so ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Could I be more ironic and eccentric, if not in spirit, then at
least in appearance?
</P>
<P>
   At the shop of Paul Smith, the quasi-mod English designer (Fifth
Avenue and 16th Street), I tried on a pink velvet blazer with
embroidered foliage. I resembled an overwrought cupcake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all in the way you wear it,'' said the salesman, Clive
Williams, a young Cockney. ``An English person would never make a
fuss about it. An American will tell people to look at his new
blazer and announce who made it. But to wear this blazer properly,
you have to be understated and not expect any compliments. You have
to be very, very cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. Cool. That's a large part of being successfully English.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't spring for the blazer, but I did buy a pair of
baby-blue socks with birds painted on them. Williams (who said he
gets better drinks here because bartenders like to hear him talk)
told me it's very English to wear loud socks. Then I hopped on my
understated bicycle in my understated Burberry turtleneck and
pedaled understatedly into the dusk with my new loud socks in tow.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   I got off at Tea and Sympathy, a cozy restaurant on Greenwich
Avenue that serves only English food. On Sundays, the line for
roast beef and Yorkshire pudding floods the sidewalk. ``It's a big
hangover crowd,'' Nicky Perry, the owner, told me. ``That's when
the boys miss Sunday dinner at their mums' at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's the case with Rupert Everett, who had just
clicked off his cell phone (the English call them ``mobiles'') and
was sitting alone, reading a magazine. I approached politely to ask
him about living in the Village, and he snubbed me so elegantly
that I felt chilled. ``I really don't want to get into this right
now _ it's just too intrusive,'' he said. ``I enjoy living here,
and this restaurant has all the comforts of home. Is that what you
want to know?''
</P>
<P>
   What hauteur! Surely, had I been British _ cooler, quippier,
waspier _ I would have been able to engage him, or at least fire
off an amusing retort. Instead, I quickly backed away, leaving him
to his Hello magazine and returning to my bangers and mash, which
is Cumberland sausage and mashed potatoes _ heart-attack food that
added to my anxiety with each bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just be an American and wish him well,'' Ms. Perry told me as
I quivered with humiliation. ``I love that about living here. Plus,
you have 24-hour everything, and you can step out onto the street
and yell for a taxi. We English love America because we see
everything you take for granted!''
</P>
<P>
   As I got up to leave Tea and Sympathy, Ms. Perry asked if I was
warm enough. ``Yes,'' I told her. ``My sweater is cashmere, and
it's Burberry. Isn't that so English?'' She shook her head. ``If
you want to be English,'' she said, ``don't be showing off what
you're wearing, mate!'' Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I changed into red tartan pants and a hip black
mackintosh, and I did not take for granted how easy it was to hail
a cab to go to Limelight, where it was ``Made in England'' night.
Inside, two DJs from England were playing Trance, the club music
that's been big in London for a while. The modest crowd on the
dance floor seemed not very English at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, this place was packed with English people,'' said
Jason Hobert, a London party promoter who is thinking about having
Teletubbies and Lulu nights at Limelight later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole vibe between the two countries,'' he said, ``is
working very well right now.''
</P>
<P>
   When I asked how I could be more English myself, he looked me
over. ``I think you're doing very well,'' he said. ``With that
look, you could be a hipster in London, without a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of English person I need to run into more
often.
</P>
<P>
   Later, someone named Fat Tony, a visiting English DJ who was
tipsy but not fat, offered to buy me a drink at the bar. ``What can
I have that's English?'' I asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have a Scotch,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   Now I was the one acting haughty, and it felt, to use an
American word, empowering.
</P>
<P>
   My quest for all the Englishness I could find downtown in a day
ended there. It was midnight, after all, and I was feeling great,
not only about the English in New York, but about myself, too. So
what if I hadn't learned to intimidate anyone elegantly? I had been
told I looked like a hipster from London. That would do.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, I have felt purged of my obsessions with the
English. I've also stopped reading Wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be yourself, no matter what they say,'' Sting sings in ``An
Englishman in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are lyrics to live by, even if they are by a Brit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
