<HEADER>
A4777 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT     01-01 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FORCED-FED FUN
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By FRANK RICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perpetual New Year's Eve anxiety is officially here.
</P>
<P>
   Though we've only just kissed off Dec. 31, 1998, this is one
weekend-after that will bring no relief. The annual societal
pressure that New Year's Eve be the bubbliest, happiest, most
spiritual and yet entertaining night of the whole year _ or else
your life is a sham unworthy even of the cheap champagne you're
getting sick on _ is already rising to a previously unimaginable
pitch for Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   By international mandate, our next New Year's Eve cannot be
anything less than the usual Nirvana _ times 1,000. Anyone who
fails to reach a state of pure millennial ecstasy is less likely to
cross the bridge to the 21st century than to throw himself from it.
</P>
<P>
   How did we get to this sorry pass? I still remember childhood,
when New Year's Eve was all innocent joy, no sweat. You stayed
safely at home, watching Johnny Carson past your bedtime, while all
the parents went out to drink and fight to the sounds of Guy
Lombardo.
</P>
<P>
   No one warned you then that once you reach adulthood, New Year's
Eve becomes a job. You must go to the right party, which is surely
not the party you're invited to, let alone giving. Failing that,
you must partake of the best meal or sex or stupor you've ever
known. You must have fun, conspicuous fun, in the same way that the
upwardly mobile pursue conspicuous consumption. Should you fail,
you will find yourself facing the void at 12:03 a.m., the
temperature will be zero, and there will be no cabs.
</P>
<P>
   What New Year's Eve activity could possibly offer enough fun to
usher in 2000? According to one poll, 75 percent of Americans want
to be traveling next New Year's Eve. Another survey says that 46
percent of the country wants to end up in Times Square. There's a
message in this for New Yorkers: Get out of town.
</P>
<P>
   But where? Every nationality is becoming as pushy and
competitive as we are about New Year's Eve: one tiny island nation
in the Pacific, Kiribati, went so far as to change its time zone so
its parties could upstage those of all its neighbors. With
countless entertainment-packed cruise ships planning to crisscross
the international date line at midnight, any passenger is bound to
have a collision _ if not with another ship or an iceberg, then
surely with a floor show starring Kathie Lee.
</P>
<P>
   For an airborne escape, the names of Harvard and Northwestern
are attached to a $44,950-per-person time-zone-leaping bacchanal by
private jet, stocked with prominent lecturers on the various Asian
cultures that will be providing servants at each luxury hotel along
the way. This is not a option for me without a scholarship, but
even were money no object, there's still the Y2K problem. No matter
how much the Federal Aviation Administration assures us that planes
won't fall out of the sky, are we really certain they won't in
Tonga or Western Samoa? When the computer clock turns '00, the
misrouted luggage and rental-car reservations alone may be enough
to break the spirit of all but the hardiest American families.
</P>
<P>
   Much less scary or costly is a slow boat to Basseterre, St.
Kitts, where, a brochure from my travel agent informs me, there's
``a gingerbread version of Big Ben to strike the hour.'' Somewhat
less glamorous, perhaps, is the special Millennial package offered
by the Ritz-Carlton Hotel in Dearborn, Mich., which, at $450, no
doubt includes all the antifreeze you can drink. A monastic
antidote to excess is offered by the Four Seasons Hotel in London,
where one sought-after suite will resist all celebrations with
blacked-out windows, special soundproofing and the banishment of
clocks and calendars. But if you're in an isolated cell, why not
save a buck and go directly to Dearborn?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure the world will let us black out our windows in any
case. The mob demands we be festive, or else. Perhaps the only
escape is to stay home, pull up the covers and watch TV as we did
as children. But will there be anything to watch? Fox Broadcasting
chairman David Hill told Variety last week that the audience ``is
going to be out rocking and rolling that night,'' and that any
stay-at-homes ``would have to be hooked up to life-support
machines. We wouldn't want 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the dire alternatives, those of us who dread millennial
New Year's Eve are left with little choice but to root for
apocalypse now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
