<HEADER>
A4778 &Cx1f; taf-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-RUSSIA-$ADV04-NY     01-01 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-RUSSIA-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA: IN AN ECONOMY OF SURVIVAL, OPTIMISM HAS A WAN SMILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Monday, Jan. 4) 
(bl) 
By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin left his sickbed to deliver a
surprisingly bullish year-end verdict on Russia's economy. ``Russia
is on the up,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, in fact, is probably the only optimist. From
international economists to the Kremlin's own specialists, the
prognosis is decidedly grim.
</P>
<P>
   The chief question is not whether Russia will turn the corner
this year. It is whether Russia will find some way to muddle
through despite a weakening economy or whether the situation will
tumble precipitously out of control.
</P>
<P>
   This is not just an economic matter. Given its vast store of
nuclear material and often poisonous politics, Russia's struggle to
establish a stable, pro-market system has powerful implications for
the West.
</P>
<P>
   The muddle-through school believes that Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov and his unlikely coalition of Communists and social
democrats are far more realistic than their polemics would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   True, they have lauded the idea of state intervention in the
economy and mocked the specialists at the International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But optimists say the government team will try to limit the
printing of new rubles, contain public spending and do just enough
market reform to pry a few billion dollars from the IMF and the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The movement toward a market economy will continue, they
maintain, but at a slow pace. And Russia will be spared yet another
debilitating government shake-up, like the ones last year that
resulted in the ouster of Sergei Kiriyenko as prime minister and
Anatoly Chubais, one of the nation's most prominent economic
reformers.
</P>
<P>
   The muddle-through theorists even have a name for this policy:
they call it the ``Russification of reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The darker view foresees hyperinflation, a deepening recession
and mounting confusion among the top government ranks, as financial
problems overwhelm Primakov's untested and ideologically
incongruous team.
</P>
<P>
   No one can say for sure how Russia's economy will fare. That
will depend mightily on the government's ability to make unpopular
but necessary decisions about the economy and to make them stick.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the IMF, the U.S. Treasury, most specialists and
the news media to foresee Russia's current economic crisis should
chasten anyone bold enough to hazard a prediction.
</P>
<P>
   It is sobering, however, to see what a ``good year'' signifies
for Russia's policy makers. The nation's gross domestic product
fell almost 6 percent in 1998 and Russia will be fortunate if the
decline is no more than 4 percent or 5 percent this year. (The IMF
projects that economic output will shrink 8.3 percent, and some
critics fear the contraction could be as much as 15 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Inflation, the Russian government hopes, will hover at 30
percent in 1999. (The IMF is predicting 56 percent and other
critics say it could be more.)
</P>
<P>
   The government says the exchange rate this year will be about
21.5 rubles to the dollar, more or less the rate in late December.
Before the currency collapsed in August, the rate was about 6, and
few believe that the ruble will not be devalued further.
</P>
<P>
   With a little luck, and some food and other humanitarian aid
from the West, the nation will suffer only isolated pockets of
hunger. (That, experts say, is a fairly credible expectation,
assuming that the assistance reaches those that need it and is not
stolen.)
</P>
<P>
   The economic crisis gathered force when foreign and domestic
investors began to lose confidence in emerging markets because of
the economic turmoil in Asia. That was a huge problem for Russia,
because it had financed much of its debt through the sale of
government Treasury securities to foreign investors. Its troubles
were compounded by the plunging prices of oil and other natural
resources that Russia exports.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis hit average Russians hard. Many people lost their
savings when the banking system collapsed. After the government
stopped propping up the ruble in August, the price of imports
soared, no small concern considering that the goods most desired by
Russian consumers are made abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Since many Russians are owed months of back wages, the
devaluation of the nation's currency means that the wages they will
eventually receive will be worth only a fraction of what they
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Real incomes dropped 15.6 percent last year, according to
government statistics. The Kremlin's sanguine view is that real
income will continue to drop by 7.5 percent this year and then rise
in 2000, a presidential election year.
</P>
<P>
   There has not been any sustained period of economic growth since
the Soviet Union collapsed in 1991. And as the government tells it,
growth is always just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   There is no easy explanation for the Russians' ability to grin
and bear it. But the question is a vital one _ especially for those
who are worried where the economy is headed.
</P>
<P>
   Russians appear to have become accustomed to many of the
material benefits of a freer economy even as they have become
disillusioned with Russia's corrupt version of market reform.
Russia may not be moving boldly to carry out economic changes, but
at least it has not been moving backward.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have the nation's financial elite been dislodged by the
economic crisis. The so-called oligarchs who dominate the nation's
energy, banking, natural resources and media industries are mostly
still in place, though they are not quite as swaggering as they
used to be.
</P>
<P>
   The key factors to watch will be Yeltsin's faltering health,
which could open the door to early elections, and a change of
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   Much will also depend on whether the Primakov team has the will
to tackle fiscal problems. Primakov has successfully pressed
Parliament to pass important legislation, encouraging foreign
investment in Russia's oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   The list of unaccomplished changes, however, is long and
includes a new tax code, laws that would allow farmers to buy and
sell land and the overhaul of the battered banking system.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the nation's fiscal house in order is also essential.
After defaulting on its domestic debt, the Kremlin can no longer
finance its deficit by selling Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
   Printing money is not the answer. The money supply was increased
20 percent after the August crisis, but the Primakov government
understands that it is flirting with hyperinflation if it covers
the deficit by running the printing presses at full steam.
</P>
<P>
   Assistance from the IMF and the World Bank would help. But the
fund has made it clear that it will not provide more aid until the
government demonstrates its ability to cut spending and collect
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The fund put it accurately, if somewhat inelegantly, in its
latest report on the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, it said, urgently needs a fiscal policy under which most
expenditures ``would be financed by tax revenue, without resort to
arrears, and whose financing would allow inflation to be reasonably
well contained, without price controls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
