<HEADER>
A4780 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UZBEKISTAN-BOOM-ART-N     01-01 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UZBEKISTAN-BOOM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMISTS FORESEE A STUMBLE IN UZBEKISTAN'S STRIDE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl) 
By STEVE LeVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TASHKENT, Uzbekistan _ A striking new look has crept into this
capital of Soviet-era concrete blocks, where a half-dozen swank
hotels, office buildings and a theme park that people call ``Mini
Disneyland'' are open or under construction.
</P>
<P>
   The change is puzzling, because hotel rooms are not scarce here;
guests are. And the potential foreign tenants for prime new office
space, who initially flocked to the country, have been deserting
Uzbekistan's closed economy for two years.
</P>
<P>
   So if not demand, what is behind the flashy building boom? The
answer, diplomats say, is Islam Karimov, Uzbekistan's autocratic
president, whose nation for years has vexed foreign economists by
rejecting most market reforms but nonetheless sustaining jobs and
public services better than any other former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
   Today foreign economists are warning again that unless the
president radically changes course, a crisis is inevitable in this
Central Asian nation of 24 million people. But Karimov is defiant,
on the attack, and by all appearances as popular as ever with his
people. He dismissed subordinates accused of failing to fulfill his
wishes and criticizes foreign critics who refuse to concede that
his way is right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karimov is the kind of man that every international economist
loves to hate,'' said Paul Bergne, a former British ambassador to
Uzbekistan who now teaches the history of the region at Oxford
University. ``It is fair to say that he has been making life hard
for himself, which is to say hard for anyone trying to make
investments in his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you ask Central Asians, Karimov is seen enviously. He
is seen locally differently from how he is seen in international
eyes. People say that Uzbekistan has fewer problems than anywhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Soviet Union broke up seven years ago, the intertwined
economies of its 15 republics crashed with it. Obsolete factories
collapsed, and by 1997 the republics were turning out an average of
just 59 percent of their last Soviet-era production. Four of the
republics, including Russia, suffered civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Uzbekistan, which only reluctantly left the Soviet Union, is an
exception. It has kept a system of strict state control of the
economy and restrictions on conversion of profits to dollars,
allowing no real privatization of industrial enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   But it has retained 85.8 percent of its 1991 production,
according to a study issued in May by the International Monetary
Fund, ``The Uzbek Growth Puzzle.'' The rate in Uzbekistan has even
outpaced the 80 percent in Estonia, considered the former Soviet
Union's economic star.
</P>
<P>
   Today, unlike many of its neighbors, Uzbekistan still pays
salaries mostly on time, maintains its roads, keeps its cities tidy
and delivers electricity and gas to homes.
</P>
<P>
   The state had also kept price controls on major commodities. At
an outdoor Tashkent cafe, 60 cents buys a large bowl of delicious
pilaf with raisins and beef, in addition to a plate of lamb shish
kebab smothered in onions and a warm slab of flat Uzbek bread.
</P>
<P>
   A result of all this is that, despite a climate of fear that
deters almost anyone foreign or local from speaking in other than
glowing terms about him for the record, Karimov seems genuinely
well-respected.
</P>
<P>
   People widely appear to agree with Karimov when he defends his
decision not to plunge into reforms. And they do not much question
the frequent, televised tirades in which, discussing the economy,
he accuses underlings of failing to carry out his programs.
</P>
<P>
   But many foreign economists and some local businessmen assert
that no matter how good things look, the future here is worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining Uzbekistan's successes, for example, the IMF study
said that the economy here did not crash as it did for former
Soviet neighbors that depended on industrial production because
Uzbekistan was mainly an agricultural and mining nation.
</P>
<P>
   While other republics struggled to find products to sell abroad
after the Soviet Union collapsed, the report said, Uzbekistan was
able to bank $2 billion a year from the world's second-largest
volume of cotton exports, and much more from Murantau, considered
the biggest gold mine on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   These advantages ``suggest that Uzbekistan's favorable output
performance did not occur because, but in spite of, its
macroeconomic and structural policies,'' the study concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a bad harvest has reduced Uzbekistan's 1998 cotton
export profits to $1 billion, and its gold earnings have plunged
with world gold prices. Cash and gold reserves _ a key indicator of
economic health _ have halved in the last two years, to $1 billion,
according to Western figures.
</P>
<P>
   Uzbekistan's relatively few private merchants have suffered as
the value of the national currency has fallen by two-thirds since
summer, after the Russian crisis, and strict state controls have
made it harder and harder to operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, they said, `Do your business the way you
want and just pay taxes,' '' a local appliances trader said. ``Now
they say, `Do your business the way we say.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In Tashkent, the construction boom has helped buoy economic
appearances. In the countryside, though, the problems are more
easily visible.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Zanca, who teaches on the region at Northeastern
Illinois University, spent two months last summer in the central
sheep-raising town of Nurota, where he saw people under such
economic pressure that they were returning to old-time ways. The
main cooking fuel was sheep manure cakes called chalma, and donkeys
were ``an increasingly important means of transportation between
villages,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have enough to eat,'' he said, but malnourishment is a
growing winter and spring phenomenon. Unemployment in many villages
runs from 60 percent to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Western banker here summed up the concern. ``The Uzbek
model has been tried in Latin America in the '60s, India in the
'70s,'' he said. ``It doesn't work. Things are starting to come
apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
