<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4781 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     01-01 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LONGHORNS, THERE'S A MAJOR CHANGE IN THE LEADERSHIP ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Ricky Williams stopped by the Cotton Bowl to say
goodbye yesterday. He did it with proper Heisman-like fanfare,
gracing us with yet another 200-yard rushing day, one last peek at
his shy, unassuming smile, even striking an un-Ricky-like,
picture-perfect Heisman pose after his 37-yard, third-quarter
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Happy trails, Ricky. Don't forget to write. See you in Port
Charlotte this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing, though, as Williams, college football's all-time
leading rusher, rumbled toward the exit, an upcoming Hula Bowl stop
and a flirtation with major-league baseball in March before April's
NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky, for a change, wasn't the biggest story of the day as
Texas impressively ate Mississippi State's brunch, 38-11, in a game
that kicked off almost before the roosters crowed.
</P>
<P>
   Not by a long shot, despite what those who voted him the game's
offensive MVP would like you to believe.
</P>
<P>
   You see, as Williams was bidding us all a fond farewell, a
red-haired, freckle-faced Tom Sawyer straight out of ``Mayberry
RFD'' was quietly, firmly, convincingly, saying hello.
</P>
<P>
   Major Applewhite is the new future of Texas football.
</P>
<P>
   From Captain Dreadlocks to Howdy Doody, just like that.
</P>
<P>
   Snap your fingers here, to get the proper idea.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ricky's team when the Longhorns appeared through the fog
created by an overzealous smoke machine yesterday morning, but by
the time the game was over, it belonged, heart and soul, to the kid
freshman who didn't even begin the season as the starting
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think,'' Texas offensive coordinator Greg Davis
concluded afterward, ``that we'll put a few more eggs in his basket
next year.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite? If he hadn't been wearing shoulder pads and his No.
11 burnt orange jersey, you'd have probably mistaken him for the
waterboy, not the leader of a major-college offense.
</P>
<P>
   This is the baby boy who was named after Alabama running back
Major Oglivie, but as his dad would say later, must have been born
to be a Longhorn because he already had the burnt orange hair; the
slightly chubby kid who spent his junior high years playing in the
offensive line; the eager high schooler who regularly asked his dad
to run pass routes when he had no other receivers available; the
determined quarterback who came home after high school dates and
retired to the garage to do jump-rope sets to 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players used to call him `Opie,''' Texas coach Mack Brown
said wryly after Applewhite, Williams and a stingy defense had led
the Longhorns to their eighth victory in their past nine games.
``Now they call him Major. I figure that's progress.''
</P>
<P>
   While Williams was gouging the Bulldogs for 208 yards and two
touchdowns on 30 carries, Applewhite calmly hit 15 of 26 passes for
225 yards and three touchdowns. I'm here to tell you that while
Applewhite's numbers may not be as impressive, they were much more
significant.
</P>
<P>
   Not to take anything away from Williams or the excellent job
that Texas' offensive line did in stopping Mississippi State's
all-out blitz, because one doesn't work without the other. But it
was Applewhite's touchdown strikes to wide receiver Wane McGarity _
first for 59 yards and then for 52 _ that sliced the Bulldogs'
jugular and sent Texas to the locker room with a 14-3 halftime
lead.
</P>
<P>
   And it was Applewhite's 18-yarder to Kwame Cavil that put the
game on ice at 38-3 with 14 seconds left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not give up the deep ball,'' lamented MSU coach
Jackie Sherrill. ``That's what hurt us.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Black-eyed peas and an embarrassing loss by Sherrill _ what a
way to start the year!)''
</P>
<P>
   ``Applewhite did a great job of getting the ball where it's
supposed to be. He throws the deep ball very well. He puts some air
under it and gives his receivers a chance to go get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was when the Longhorns went three-and-out on
their first possession that a worried Davis began to believe that
everything was going to be OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we really talked to our team about was to
not get frustrated when \Rthe MSU\S defense makes plays, because
they're going to make some,'' Davis said. ``First series, we're
three-and-out and Ricky gets hit in the mouth on the second play
and Major comes out, gets on the headset and says, `Coach, we're
fine. We'll get 'em next time.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of poise I knew we'd need.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of poise _ and the kind of quarterback _ that
Brown and Davis will build an offense around next season.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Dreadlocks is over and out.
</P>
<P>
   The Major has the ship now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
