A4785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-PRIVATE-TALES-N     01-01 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PRIVATE-TALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG CHINESE WRITER FINDS SUCCESS WITH SOUL-BARING JOURNALISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Each day An Dun receives a dozen calls from people
desperate to spill their deepest secrets, vying to have their
private lives laid bare and dissected in her popular weekly
newspaper column. Some have become pregnant out of wedlock. Some
have been raped by their bosses. Some have been abandoned by their
husbands. Others have done the ditching themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In conservative Chinese society, such topics are generally taboo
even among close relatives and best friends, and they are certainly
not mainstream media fare. But since 1996, when Ms. An started
recording matter-of-factly the stories of real people caught in
such predicaments, she has wowed the younger generation with her
candor and helped to liberate a nation's skeletons from the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Her first book, ``Absolute Privacy,'' a sometimes moving,
sometimes sordid volume containing the stories of 20 women's love
lives, quickly sold a quarter million copies when it was published
last summer, and most have now passed through dozens of hands. In
student dorms, in airport lounges, on crowded subways, readers
engrossed in dog-eared copies of ``Absolute Privacy'' are
everywhere. Her second book, ``Going Home,'' came out last week,
and like her recent columns, shifts the focus to relationships
between parents and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``My work is popular because nobody has written about these
kinds of things before,'' said Ms. An, a lively straight-talking
29-year-old, dressed for work in a blue silk dress and pearls.
``Chinese people are very reluctant to talk about private matters.
I hope that at least I've raised these topics and made them public
now.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a crusade that has made her a celebrity, engendered more
than a dozen copycat collections of ``real life'' tales, and
brought enough financial success that she now has a retreat in the
coastal city of Dalian, where she escapes to write.
</P>
<P>
   But her work has also come under fire from conservative Chinese,
who regard her tales of unwanted pregnancies, office love affairs
and runaway teens as ``spiritual pollution.'' And she often butts
heads with government censors at her newspaper, the progressive
Beijing Youth Daily. All newspapers in China are owned by a
Communist Party or government branch, in this case, the Communist
Youth League.
</P>
<P>
   In one recent column about a teen-ager who had hidden her
pregnancy from her mother, editors at her newspaper censored almost
a quarter of the text, 300 words. ``The pressure is pretty scary,''
Ms. An said. ``Some senior comrades think it's immoral and
destabilizing to write about the ugly side of life, that it will
give children bad ideas. They want us to hide everything ugly and
tell a fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we have to tell children that there is Adam and
there are snakes, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. An said she wrote her books in part to have greater freedom
to tell her subjects' stories, with all their pathos and unseemly
details. Books require less formal approval than newspapers before
publication.
</P>
<P>
   In her books and in her column, Ms. An tells of chaotic lives
without judgment or advice. Each story is based on extensive
interviews; names and places are changed.
</P>
<P>
   In one, a young college graduate from a simple rural town gets a
coveted government job in Beijing only to be forced to have sex
with her boss, an older married man. After a year, she quits and
finds a job in a foreign-owned company, but remains depressed and
fearful that no man will ever love her defiled body. Ms. An meets
her at a drugstore where she is buying a hymen-repairing kit.
</P>
<P>
   In another, a married journalist has a liaison with a married
mid-level bureaucrat and leaves her husband after she becomes
pregnant by her lover. But the bureaucrat fears the scandal will
hurt his chances of promotion and decides not to leave his
marriage. She aborts the baby and leaves Beijing, heartbroken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to understand more about marriage and family and
people's emotional lives,'' Ms. An said. ``As the economy has
opened, people have become more individualistic. In the past,
people put their feelings last; now they have started to pay more
attention to their feelings and the quality of their relationships,
which is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. An's books and columns are part sociology and part soap
opera, and have been particularly popular among young urban women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everyone I know has read it,'' said Yu Xiao, 31, a
teacher in a black jacket trimmed with fake leopard fur, as she
browsed at Beijing Book City, Beijing's new mega-bookstore. ``We
used to be so closed off about people's private lives but now that
we're more open, people are very interested and are really thinking
about this for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. An, a self-made go-getter who is in many ways an archetypal
new Chinese professional woman, felt compelled to take on her
countrymen's taboos after her own personal life ran afoul of
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   At 24, she fell in love with a married businessman 10 years her
senior, who was separated from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents hated the idea,'' Ms. An said. ``He was older. He
was divorced. He had a son. People just assumed there must be
something wrong with me, like that I was infertile.''
</P>
<P>
   After her parents relented, the two got married, and Ms. An quit
her job as an accountant for a time. But she quickly tired of
hanging around with other nonworking wives of successful
businessmen. Most were well-educated young women and seemed to have
everything, and yet many were miserable. After a year she borrowed
money from her mother to buy new work clothes and to pay car fare
to job interviews, and set about becoming a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Her rarefied year among the ladies who lunch led to her first
newspaper story, ``Canary in a Cage,'' which she sold to Beijing
Youth Daily for a onetime column in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The editors thought we couldn't run more than one like this,''
Ms. An said. ``They were worried my article would teach young
people about bad options. They didn't want to highlight that there
were people leading this kind of life and not contributing to
society.''
</P>
<P>
   But readers loved this kind of story, and at a time when
government subsidies to newspapers were drying up, it drew in
advertisers as well. Ms. An's column became a weekly feature in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where therapists are still a rarity, it is easy to
see why people bare their souls to her, an intent listener with an
open mind and an easy smile. She could be a psychiatrist, though
she prefers to think of her work as anthropology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think Chinese people have become somewhat more
tolerant,'' she said, noting that in the past, people who had been
unfaithful to their spouses were branded as hooligans and
ostracized. But, she added, ``change is very slow, which is why
people talk to me.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``Almost everyone in the West can find someone to
talk to about their inner feelings, but not here. The people who
talk to me have friends and relatives but they dare not speak to
them about this. This way they can stand in the shadows and see
what others think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 1956EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
