<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4786 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COP-ARREST-SPI &LR;      01-01 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COP-ARREST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE OFFICER HELD IN DUI FATALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACK HOPKINS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Two suspected drunk drivers _ one of them an off-duty
police officer from the suburb of Bellevue _ collided Friday in a
grinding, high-speed crash that left one passenger dead and three
others injured.
</P>
<P>
   A Washington State Patrol officer who was riding with the
Bellevue cop when the collision occurred is in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The fatal accident happened at 3:15 a.m., just hours after tough
new drunk driving laws took effect in Washington _ laws for which
the policeman involved in the crash had recently taken training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done a good job of setting an example,'' said an
obviously saddened Bellevue police spokesman Mike Johnson as
investigators checked the crumpled remains of the off-duty
officer's Dodge Strata.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no mystery to any law enforcement officer in the state
about the new laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The new laws lower the blood-alcohol level required for proof of
intoxication from 0.10 to 0.08 percent and provide tougher
penalties for those convicted of drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   Police involvement in the fatal accident stunned area residents
who have fought drunken driving for years and counted law
enforcement officers among their staunchest allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That certainly is dereliction of duty by law enforcement
officers and itsends out the wrong message,'' said state Sen. Adam
Kline, D-Seattle, who helped push through tougher laws against
drunken driving and formerly served as president of the local
chapter of Mothers Against Drunk Driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it demonstrates a point MADD has been trying to make for
years: That driving under the influence is not an offense committed
by a small number of career criminals... Even a generally alert,
conscientious person can fall into that and we need ongoing
vigilance on everybody's part.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellevue police declined to release the name of the officer
involved in the crash, but said he was arrested on suspicion of
vehicular homicide. The 29-year-old policeman suffered a bruised
heart in the crash and was reported in satisfactory condition
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the officer has been a patrolman for about two or
three years and said he is unaware of any previous problems
involving the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a nice guy who is well liked by his peers,'' he said.
``He did a nice job for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellevue police also declined to identify the state trooper
riding in the front passenger seat with the policeman at the time
of the crash. They said only that he was 26 years old and had been
a trooper for about 2 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   The state patrolman suffered head and chest and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The medical examiner's office identified the dead man as Brian
Heath Grooms, 26, of Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Bellevue police said Grooms, a salesman, was a friend of the
state trooper and was in the Seattle area on vacation. He was
riding in the back seat of the Dodge Strata when the crash
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The Bellevue police officer driving the Strata had been drinking
and was traveling southbound at ``a high rate of speed'' when he
lost control of the vehicle, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The policeman's car went spinning across the center line and
collided with a northbound Ford Expedition driven by a 45-year-old
Bellevue man, who was identified only as a Navy officer.
</P>
<P>
   There were two passengers in the Expedition _ the officer's
53-year-old wife and a 78-year-old man in the back seat. The Naval
officer and the elderly man, believed to be the father or
father-in-law of the Navy man, were not injured. The woman was
reported in satisfactory condition and hospitalized with neck and
leg injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alcohol appears to be a contributing factor to the accident,''
said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Blood-alcohol tests were given to both drivers, but police
declined to release the results. He said, however, that both
drivers are believed to have been drunk at the time of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he didn't know if open containers of alcoholic
beverages were found in either car.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy man was cited for driving under the influence and
released. The off-duty Bellevue policeman was arrested on suspicion
of vehicular homicide, a more serious offense that almost always
carries a prison term upon conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they did not know where the off-duty cop, the
trooper and the other man had been in the hours before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Police were called to the scene by a nearby resident who was
awakened by the sound of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I heard a crashing sound and then a horn that was
stuck on `on,' '' Jeff Johnson said. ``We immediately knew that
something was very wrong outside the house and called 911.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he quickly dressed and hurried to the crash site
where he spotted about six people clustered around the Strata,
trying to help the victims of the collision.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed amazement that an officer was involved in an
alcohol-related crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is amazing and sad,'' he said. ``For someone that much in
the know, someone who has seen the results of accidents... If
anybody should know better, it would be officers of the law,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, meanwhile, say it could take quite some time before
police wrap up their investigation and prosecutors make a charging
decision in the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
