<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP SEES MIXED TREND IN GIVING AMONG PROTESTANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the recessionary years of the early 1990s, some major
Protestant denominations faced budget shortfalls and were forced to
downsize, cutting back staff at the national levels.
</P>
<P>
   Such developments reinforced a concern among some church
officials about those denominations' financial futures.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent days, one organization that studies patterns of
giving among Protestants has reported positive news _ although with
limitations.
</P>
<P>
   An annual survey of giving by members of 29 Protestant
denominations has found that what people are putting into the
collection plate, when measured as a percentage of Americans' per
capita income, has grown slightly for three consecutive years after
falling for most of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, by Empty Tomb Inc., a nonprofit organization
dedicated to ``Christian service and research,'' reports that
members of those denominations increased their giving to about 2.6
percent of their disposable income in 1996, the last year for which
statistics are available, from about 2.5 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're cautiously optimistic,'' said Sylvia Ronsvalle,
executive vice president of the organization, which is based in
Champaign, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Ronsvalle said she was concerned that the giving
picture had a downside in that the proportion of members' money
earmarked for purposes outside the local church (that is, money for
seminaries, missionary work, hunger-relief programs and other
causes), had continued to decline, even as overall giving had
risen.
</P>
<P>
   The denominations included in the survey range from mainline
Protestant bodies like the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) and the
United Church of Christ to more conservative, evangelical
denominations, like the Church of the Nazarene and the Southern
Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   On average, members of the denominations gave $538 each in 1996,
out of a per capita income of $20,840, as measured by the Bureau of
Economic Analysis, a branch of the Commerce Department. Of the
total given, $453 went to the local congregation to pay for budget
items ranging from clergy salaries to the cost of utilities and to
such in-house charitable activities as soup kitchens and food
pantries.
</P>
<P>
   Through denominational financial statistics, Empty Tomb has kept
track of giving by Protestants since 1968 and has seen a fairly
steady decline since then, measured against per capita income. In
its surveys, the organization has reported that church members gave
slightly more than 3.1 percent of their disposable income in 1968.
That fell to slightly less than 2.5 percent in 1992 and 1993, the
organization reported.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Ronsvalle, whose husband, John, is president of the
organization, said she was particularly concerned with the gradual
decline in the proportion of giving to ``benevolences,'' causes
beyond the local congregation. By Empty Tomb's calculations, church
members gave about 0.7 percent of their per capita income to such
causes in 1968, but that has fallen to 0.4 percent in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the church were helping church members integrate their
faith, you would expect to see different patterns in the way they
spend money,'' Mrs. Ronsvalle said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 2000EST &QL; 
