<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-ROUGHNECK-NYT &LR;      01-01 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-ROUGHNECK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAMA, DON'T LET YOUR SONS GROW UP TO BE ROUGHNECKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wyo., Mont.) (EDS: With OIL-U.S.) 
(nk) 
 By ALLEN R. MYERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GILLETTE, Wyo. _ As Tim Gimbel sees it from the double-wide
trailer near here where he now spends his days, even working a
drilling rig when it's 25 below beats a layoff. He won't have the
money to build a garage this summer, so his wife, Laura, has at
least two more winters of creeping an icy hundred yards uphill
every morning to fetch her car from a shed as she leaves for her
job as a secretary.
</P>
<P>
   She often asks how soon her husband expects to be called back,
or why he wants to remain a driller in the first place, and whether
there aren't more dependable ways to make a living. ``She's done
everything but put her boots on and kick me out the door,'' Gimbel
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, he joined 600 others, out of 1,000, whom Caza
Drilling, based in Denver, has sent to the unemployment offices
over the last year. As oil prices sank, Caza, whose clients include
George Fancher, went from running 30 rigs to 10 or 12.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Schledwitz, Caza's operations manager, has seen the toll.
It's not just the 21 of his own field people it takes to keep a rig
running, he says, but also his office staff and 20 or so more at
his suppliers and service companies. Oil deposits _ and, thus, the
jobs _ in such a volatile business tend, perversely, to be in
places where other options are few. ``In Wyoming or Montana,
farming and mining are about the only other industries,''
Schledwitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone could see the romance of a grimy, dangerous job
requiring seven straight days of 12-hour shifts, as likely to be 7
p.m. to 7 a.m. as the reverse. Not to mention living away from home
with 10 or 12 others jammed into a single trailer.
</P>
<P>
   But workers speak of oilfield labor, its highs and lows, almost
the way addicts speak of drugs. Dale Shaffer, a Caza driller who
lives in Thermopolis, near Casper, Wyo., said he once tried
breaking his habit with a job indoors, in an oil pump shop. ``I did
that for two years and about went stark raving mad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaffer, 34, began as the lowliest of the roughnecks _ working
the worm's corner, as they say _ digging ditches and doing other
jobs nobody else would touch. As a driller, he supervises a crew of
four, earning $600 to $700 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Besides seeing his checks fall to less than half that on
unemployment, Shaffer has to pay an extra $200 a month to keep his
health insurance. With his wife, Karla, pregnant and due in March,
insurance is essential.
</P>
<P>
   The clothing store where his wife worked as a sales clerk has
laid her off, too, while the closing of other local stores has
killed her job prospects. ``A lot of it is because of the oil
business being so slow,'' Shaffer said. ``People aren't out buying
stuff. There really aren't jobs to be had.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaffer, laid off in mid-December, hopes to help friends who
install carpeting or serve as roustabouts, driving trucks and
delivering oilfield supplies. Having grown up on a Wyoming ranch,
he has worked as a cowboy, too, but that paid only $12,000 a year.
He won't be called back by Caza Drilling for at least three months,
but he isn't complaining since others from his company have been
waiting a year.
</P>
<P>
   Gimbel, 45, might tide himself over by driving a bus to take
miners and train operators to the coal mines. He knows he could
then be called out at any hour of the day or night, but he does not
know the pay. ``They've always got an ad in the newspaper,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gimbel admits he should have known better after seeing his
father auction off his rigs and go out of business in an oil slump
12 years ago. His father's old shop is where Laura Gimbel now
leaves her car. But even now, Gimbel focuses more on the $45,000 or
$50,000 he can earn for a full year's work than on his $240 a week
in unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Shaffer accepts that buying a home, instead of renting one, is
now at least two years off. By then, the costs of his 16-year-old
stepson's college could delay homebuying even more.
</P>
<P>
   But whenever his stepson, Ryan, speaks of tracking his father
into the oilfields right after high school, Shaffer tells him,
``Get your education first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
