</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SYRACUSE-FLORIDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EJECTION LED TO A SYRACUSE-FLORIDA MATCHUP
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Tony George insists he does not dwell on what might have
been. Others do it for him. They say that if the Florida cornerback
and co-captain had shown some restraint, the Gators might well be
in Arizona playing for a national championship instead of settling
for the Orange Bowl Classic here.
</P>
<P>
   George was thrown out of the Gators' pivotal game against
Florida State in late November minutes before it started, allegedly
for punching an FSU coach. Two obscure Seminoles also were tossed,
and Florida State exploited a George-less secondary in a 23-12
victory for a spot in the Fiesta Bowl's national title game on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators dropped to 9-2 and find themselves paired with
Syracuse (8-3) in Saturday night's Orange Bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched several tapes and it's been shown throughout,''
George said of his untimely scuffle. ``No punches were thrown,
especially from my hands. I admit there was a lot of pushing and
shoving on my part and some key name players on their part. But
only I get thrown out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gators suffered two ways from the loss to Florida State. The
importance of their bowl game is dramatically different, but the
difficulty of the opponent may be comparable.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse's victims include Michigan, Virginia Tech and Miami,
and the Orangemen lost by only a point to Tennessee, Florida
State's foe in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen have three particularly distinguished offensive
players _ quarterback Donovan McNabb, wide receiver Kevin Johnson
and fullback Rob Konrad. All are expected to go high in the next
National Football League draft.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb is at the throttle of Syracuse's 42.5-points-a-game
offense. He combines the elusiveness of a halfback with some newly
appreciated passing skills, earned by completing 62.5 percent of
251 passes this season for 2,134 yards and 22 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   To those who label him as basically an option quarterback,
McNabb politely demurs. ``I'm a quarterback first and foremost,''
he said this week. ``Secondly, I can do other things besides just
drop back and throw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson arrived at Syracuse as a quarterback the same year
McNabb did. After an intense battle between the two, Syracuse opted
for McNabb on what Coach Paul Pasqualoni called a ``gut feeling.''
Johnson was crushed, thinking he would have to spend his college
career watching others play.
</P>
<P>
   Then he had a talk with Marvin Harrison, Syracuse's best
receiver at the time, who reminded him that there were not too many
professional quarterbacks his size _ 5 feet 11 inches, 195 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Johnson has committed himself to being a wide
receiver. He caught 60 passes this season for 894 yards and 9
touchdowns, rushed for three more scores and returned two kickoffs
all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Konrad is the first fullback in Syracuse history to wear its No.
44 jersey, which was made famous by the tailbacks Jim Brown, Ernie
Davis and Floyd Little. Konrad's blocking and versatility make him
special in his own way, Pasqualoni said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can be the tailback, the fullback, the receiver, he's great
in protections _ he blocks very, very well for the tailbacks,''
Pasqualoni said. ``So much can happen when Rob is playing.''
</P>
<P>
   As diversified as Syracuse's offense is, Pasqualoni said Florida
raises diversification to a new standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They use three wideouts, four wideouts, five wideouts,'' he
said. ``Then they can go with two tight ends and two wideouts in
the game. Then they can have one tight end in the game with two
wideouts and two backs. It just goes on and on and on. They wear
you out just trying to keep track of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very multiple,'' Pasqualoni said. ``I'd say they're
probably a little more multiple than we are.''
</P>
<P>
   But this has not been a particularly great year offensively for
the Gators. Coach Steve Spurrier says their running game has
suffered, and that is usually when Florida is most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at our losses since I've been here,'' he said. ``When
our running game is pitiful, we lose. The '93 Auburn loss was the
only time we've run the ball well and lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier has used two quarterbacks _ the junior Doug Johnson
starts on Saturday _ and says he is sorry neither one is mobile
enough to scramble for a first down occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Spurrier's complaints, Florida is scoring nearly 32
points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, a distinct edge goes to Florida, which has held the
opposition to an average of 14.1 points, 10.4 better than Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators have a number of potential NFL draftees, headed by
linebacker Jevon Kearse, a 6-foot-5, 250-pounder who projects as a
likely top-10 pick, even as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Orangemen's defense is populated by seven
first-year starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any big all-star names there,'' Pasqualoni said.
``It's jersey No. 7, jersey No. 10, that type of thing. But they
have learned that if they play together and very, very hard,
they'll do well.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
