</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BOWL GAMES LOSING THEIR INCENTIVES
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I never thought I'd see the day when a UCLA football team would
view a trip to the Rose Bowl as settling for something. But the day
has come. UCLA's players are grousing about a mighty tumble that
sent them from an undefeated season and a national championship
showdown with Tennessee to a beauty pageant game Friday against
Wisconsin. After UCLA's stunning loss to Miami last month, guard
Andy Myers said: ``Oh well, we're still going to the Rose Bowl.
Didn't that used to be the big one?''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Rose is simply another one. Between Dec. 19 and Jan. 4,
24 bowl games will have been played. The only game that truly means
something will take place on Monday night when Tennessee and
Florida State meet in the Fiesta Bowl for the national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system we have that brings No. 1 and No. 2 together cries
out to be the only game that matters,'' Mike Tranghese, the Big
East Conference commissioner, said. ``The others get a little
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost? Bowl games are being played that most fans don't even know
existed. Insight.com? Humanitarian? Great as a concept,
questionable as a game. In days of old, leading a team to a bowl
game was certain to save a coach's job. No more. The glut of games
cheapens the accomplishment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Washington made it to the Oahu Bowl with a 6-5 record and lost,
45-25, to Air Force. On Wednesday, the Washington administration
fired Coach Jim Lambright. Ticket sales were slow for Friday's Rose
Bowl; prices went from $75 for last year's game to $110 this year.
UCLA returned 6,300 unsold tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a world of outlets willing to put the games on
television, sponsors willing to sponsor them and teams willing to
go to them,'' said Jim Delany, the Big Ten Conference commissioner.
``They are celebrations for communities, players and sponsors. They
are part of the American sports mosaic.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about Delany's reference to the American sports
mosaic, but this is certainly the way we do business in the United
States. We seem to find a way to commercialize, and often corrupt,
everything. Not just everything, but every inch of everything. The
universities have allowed themselves to become ivy-covered
billboards for corporate sponsors. Nokia. Micron. Federal Express.
Two years ago the Rose Bowl refused to take a corporate sponsor
because its officials thought it would dilute the game's image.
When ABC offered the major bowls a half-billion dollars over the
next seven years if they would sign up for the Bowl Championship
Series, the Rose Bowl jumped.
</P>
<P>
   New Year's Day used to be defined by games: Rose, Cotton,
Orange, Sugar and eventually the Fiesta. In my neighborhood,
families came together for black-eyed peas, greens and cornbread.
College players crashing into one another into the evening provided
reassuring background music for our celebration.
</P>
<P>
   But now the bowls are not a day but a season unto themselves, a
separate industry. They represent a pyramid of realities: at the
top, elite teams compete in the several major bowls, one leading to
a national championship; at the bottom, a glut of teams competes
for varying reasons, revenue obviously, but also exposure and in
many cases to provide a perk for boosters and fans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Tulane, the remarkable accomplishment of an undefeated 12-0
season might have gone unrecognized but for an opportunity to face
nationally known BYU in the Liberty Bowl. Tulane won, 41-27.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA players should be angry; I'm angry, too. Four weeks ago
we were looking forward to a smashing debut of the BCS: explosive
Tennessee with the first-year starter Tee Martin at quarterback
against UCLA with Cade McNown. Florida State is worthy, but so is
Ohio State. John Cooper, coach of the once-beaten Buckeyes, is
pulling for once-beaten Florida State to defeat unbeaten Tennessee
in the Fiesta Bowl so Ohio State might get a share of the national
title. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This tosses us back to the method of selecting a national
champion in major college football. Help may be on the way. ISL
Worldwide, a Switzerland-based sports marketing and licensing
company, is proposing a 16-team major college playoff. The plan
would use the bowls as setup games. The BCS would be expanded from
one game to a 16-team playoff. The semifinals and finals would be
bowl games. The ISL timetable would launch the playoff in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowl Championship Series, with all its flaws, at least
brings us closer to the kind of resolution we often lack in our
civilian lives but routinely get from sports: winners and losers
determined in an objective manner, not by polls, not by politics,
not by pundits and their computers. Instead they are determined by
games: six Friday , one Saturday night and finally the national
title showdown on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The system isn't perfect, but it's moving in the right
direction. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
