<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDDLE-AGES-RETURN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS NATIONS FADE, IS A RETURN TO THE MIDDLE AGES IN THE FUTURE?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it possible that cyberspace and economic globalization are
pushing the modern world back into the Middle Ages?
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 years have passed since the late Hedley Bull, then
professor of international relations at Oxford, suggested the
existing system of nation states might be replaced by ``a modern
and secular equivalent of the kind of universal political
organization that existed in Western Christendom in the Middle
Ages.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then many scholars have sought to explain changes in the
present-day world by making analogies with medieval Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of this neomedievalist case is that as a result of a
variety of pressures, the modern organization of nations, generally
seen as dating from the Treaty of Westphalia, which ended the
Thirty Years War in 1648, is, if not broken down already, then
certainly going through a period of profound weakening.
</P>
<P>
   Once nation states exercised absolute sovereignty over a clearly
defined territory, ``bundling together,'' in the phrase of James
Anderson of the Open University in Britain, responsibility for all
aspects of the ``secular, moral and spiritual'' lives of their
citizens. No higher authority existed than the ruler of such a
state, whether it be king or parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But no longer. Today nation states' traditional responsibilities
are being ``unbundled'' by a combination of forces.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of multinational corporations and global markets limit
their economic influence. Cyberspace and the internet belong to no
one. And increasingly nation states are surrendering sovereignty by
joining together in international organizations, recognizing that
many of their aspirations can be achieved only through concerted
action.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a modern citizen can be subject to many different,
often overlapping authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The life of a resident of the European Union, for instance, is
shaped by the decisions of local authorities, national parliaments,
the faceless Eurocrats of the Brussels Commission and a host of
other international bodies like the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development, numerous U.N. agencies and, since
Friday, Europe's new single central bank with its new single
currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The growing complexity and diffuseness of modern authority
reminds some scholars of the Middle Ages, before nation states were
invented, when the boundaries of kingdoms were often vague and
subject to the fortunes of war and dynastic marriage, and many
different centers of power competed for influence.
</P>
<P>
   As Anderson puts it: ``Political sovereignty was shared between
a wide variety of secular and religious institutions and different
levels of authority _ feudal knights and barons, kings and princes,
guilds and cities, bishops, abbots and the papacy _ rather than
being based on territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen J. Kobrin of the University of Pennsylvania recently
argued in a paper in the Journal of International Affairs:
``Political power and authority were not geographically defined in
medieval Europe and may not be in a digitalized world economy
organized through overlapping electronic networks. Thinking about
the Middle Ages, the last premodern period, might help us imagine
possibilities for a postmodern future.''
</P>
<P>
   Other parallels can be glimpsed between today's world and that
of the Middle Ages, too. Christianity may no longer be the
universal religion, but some, particularly in the United States,
argue that democracy and free markets are close to playing a
similar role as an almost universally accepted ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Matthew, a political scientist at the University of
California at Irvine, has suggested that environmentalism is ready
to become a contemporary version of Christianity because it is a
global cause that transcends national borders.
</P>
<P>
   As the world of self-contained nation states starts to break
down, Kobrin believes, there is a quest under way for ``a center,''
some body with the universally accepted authority medieval popes
once claimed. Not just the United Nations but virtually every
intergovernmental organization in existence today was created since
World War II. ``It's like the medieval longing for the restoration
of the Roman Empire,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Kobrin finds a further parallel between the castles, retainers
and private armies of the medieval nobility and the rise of crime,
gated communities and private security companies in today's world,
showing that the nation state's traditional monopoly of coersive
power is losing strength.
</P>
<P>
   In his account of the collapse of civil authority over much of
West Africa, the writer Robert Kaplan warns that in some regions,
nation states are being ``replaced by a jagged-glass pattern of
city states, shanty states, nebulous and anarchic regionalisms''
suggestive of the Dark Ages that preceded the medieval world after
the fall of Rome.
</P>
<P>
   In his eyes, and others, it seems we're headed back to the
future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
