u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-POLICE-945&AMP;AD     01-01 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLICE-945&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA LIMPS OUT OF BAD YEAR FOR POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ This Christmas-New Year's season
has not been kind to the South African police. But then 1998 was
not a very good year for them in general.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Chauke, the mastermind of blood-soaked armored-car
robberies and South Africa's most-wanted man, was not behind bars
by Christmas, as Bushie Engelbrecht, the country's most famous
detective had, in a rash moment, promised he would be.
</P>
<P>
   At least 25 people died in massacres in KwaZulu-Natal, although
for the first time in almost ritual Christmas bloodshed, most of
the killings looked like family feuds rather than political ones.
</P>
<P>
   The annual report card on the performances of Cabinet ministers
by The Mail &AMP; Guardian, a liberal weekly newspaper, gave Sydney
Mufamadi, the minister in charge of the police, an ``F.''
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 16, 50 brand-new BMW highway patrol cars were handed
over to the police at a ceremony on a race track. On the way home,
the police crashed six of them.
</P>
<P>
   That same week, television networks around the world carried
pictures of a Johannesburg inventor's solution to the carjacking
crisis: a chassis-mounted flamethrower that roasts anyone within 3
feet of the car. A police superintendent bought one.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the Center for the Study of Violence and
Reconciliation published a study showing that 1,081 people had died
in police custody in the previous 18 months. During the worst years
of apartheid, no more than 200 people a year died in custody, noted
a former member of a group that helped apartheid arrestees.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that frustrated police officers, certain
that the courts would release criminals on bail, were killing them
instead. Criminals, for their part, fearing summary execution, were
choosing shootouts over surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after that report was issued, a police sergeant shot
dead two of his colleagues for talking too loud. He then went back
into his room and shot himself. The killings highlighted the issue
of police suicides, of which there are about 150 a year, nine times
the U.S. per capita rate.
</P>
<P>
   The police here, who take home pay of only about $4,000 a year,
are under enormous pressure and get almost no counseling. A
suicide-prevention expert from the University of Natal said
officers, who often live in barracks far from home, were three
times more likely than average citizens to snap violently or commit
suicide when under stress.
</P>
<P>
   At least 269 members of the force were killed in action last
year, about five times the U.S. rate per capita. That is about
three times the number killed in 1990, when black guerrillas were
deliberately targeting police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The daily crime reports in the press showed that many officers
were ambushed and killed by thieves who were after their guns, yet
the public outcry and huge manhunts that usually follow an American
police killing were missing here. Few of the cases are solved.
</P>
<P>
   A survey released in early December said 20 percent of all South
African households were victims of crime in 1997. In line with old
patterns, the rich were more likely to be the victims of burglars
and the poor were more likely to be victims of violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   But 42 percent of all South Africans thought the police were
doing a worse job than they were in 1994, the year the first
all-race elections brought the African National Congress to power.
Only 26 percent said they were doing better. ``Indifferent
officers'' was the chief complaint.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 21 scores of crime victims left flowers, candles and
crosses outside President Nelson Mandela's home, which is in an
expensive, secure Johannesburg neighborhood. The demonstration was
arranged by the opposition Democratic Party, but many of the
participants were relatives of those killed recently.
</P>
<P>
   And a week later, Anne Paton, the 71-year-old widow of Alan
Paton, author of ``Cry the Beloved Country,'' wrote a widely
published essay explaining why she was leaving South Africa after
35 years: Nine of her friends had been murdered in the last four
years, she said, and she had been carjacked at gunpoint, mugged
twice in her own home in midafternoon and terrorized with her own
Girl Guide knife.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably fair to say that the bad news has come faster and
more furiously in the last three months than it usually does, but
the flood of it has been startling. Furthermore, it was given
impetus by the fact that for a while things had seemed to be
getting better.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the police said crime had stabilized, although at high
levels. Meyer Kahn, the chairman of South African Breweries, a
well-run conglomerate with bold affirmative-action policies, had
been acting as chief executive officer of the police for a year and
was unveiling some reorganization plans.
</P>
<P>
   And the police and the Department of Transport had markedly
slowed down the ``taxi wars'' in which owners of fleets competing
for lucrative routes hired hit squads to rake rivals'
passenger-crammed taxis with machine-gun fire.
</P>
<P>
   There had also been a lull in embarrassing high-profile crimes.
In fact, some had been solved: Moses Sithole, a serial killer, had
been convicted of 38 murders. A wealthy couple shot dead at their
dining-room table had not been killed by intruders, as had at first
been thought; their son was arrested. Two ``mugged'' cricketers
from the Pakistani national team turned out to have staged the
incident to cover up their beating by a whorehouse bouncer. A spate
of political killings in the Richmond area of KwaZulu-Natal had
been stopped through Engelbrecht's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The only conclusion that could be drawn was that the travails of
the police, like crime itself, come in waves.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Antoinette Louw, a police specialist for the Institute for
Security Studies, a think tank that studies crime and war, said it
was hard to tell whether the police were doing a better job, or
whether the perceptions about them were worse. The police were once
hated as the functionaries of an apartheid state. Now, as they
struggle to fight crime instead, they are derided as incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   The police made real strides in 1998, Ms. Louw said. Absenteeism
was down. Many carjacking syndicates were cracked, some because the
officers who were sending them stolen cars were arrested. The
entire Illegal Alien Unit was arrested on corruption charges and
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Bank robberies and hijackings seemed to be going down, and
murders were definitely down while rape was definitely up, she
said. But overall it was ``incredibly difficult'' to say that any
trend was established. Pre-1994 statistics were worthless, and
current ones fluctuate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception that crime is still skyrocketing is untrue,''
Ms. Louw said. ``But the police statements that it is stabilizing
are misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   The crisis, she said, is in leadership. While the department has
suffered rapid post-apartheid attrition, many precinct captains
have never even been told how to do their jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 2022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
