<HEADLINE>
JETS WATCH AND WAIT    
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ As the first playoff bye week in Jets history
sailed along Friday, some members of the organization found
themselves in unfamiliar territory.
</P>
<P>
   After all, if you have seldom been there, how do you deal with
playoff tickets? When do you print the guide for the news media?
How do you scout the teams in the playoffs you may never even face?
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, unaccustomed to this sort of thing more than most
teams, are enjoying this bye week before their divisional playoff
game on Jan. 10. They reached this point by capturing a division
title in what has been an unusual season league-wide. After all, it
was merely the second time in league history that there are new
champions in all six divisions.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the Jets do know. By about 3:30 p.m. Sunday they
will have discovered whether they will play Jacksonville (which
meets New England) or face the winner of Saturday's Miami-Buffalo
wild-card game. The Jaguars are heavily favored to beat the
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   So Curtis Martin, will you be watching both games this weekend?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the 1,000-yard running back said. ``Neither game. I'm
not a big football fan.''
</P>
<P>
   But Coach Bill Parcells and those around him will watch. Also,
the Jets have dispatched their highly regarded pro personnel
director, Scott Pioli, to Jacksonville to scout the game between
the Jaguars and Patriots. Meanwhile, Jo Jo Wooden, who works under
Pioli, will be in Miami to scout the Dolphins-Bills game.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has used this week to introduce his club to the Jaguars
on tape. He put his players in pads today after meetings that
included a second day of looking at Jacksonville. They will
practice again on Saturday and then be off until next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm going to feel good about our preparation for this
game,'' Parcells said. ``We had ample time.'' And if the Jets wind
up facing either Miami or Buffalo, the Jets merely have to go back
and get one or two game films. The Jets played both teams in the
past month.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the Jets' offices, Doug Miller was also feeling good
about his playoff preparation. Miller, the assistant director of
public relations, could finally exhale. The thick, magazine-sized
playoff guide was ready this week, even though he had waited until
the team had clinched to put on the final touches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I had it all set the last month and I think I
jinxed us,'' Miller said. ``This year our printing company kept
saying, `We have to get started.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Miller would not hand it over. He kept telling the printer,
``I'll call you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had updated the information all along,'' Miller said, ``but
I didn't start to get ready to put it out until we beat Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Jets return to the Meadowlands for their playoff game,
400 members of the news media will be in the press box as part of a
total of more than 800 people covering the game. That will include
more than 200 people from CBS, which is doing two broadcasts, over
the regular airwaves and on experimental high-definition
television.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1991, the Jets also have sent out
playoff ticket notices. These went out Thanksgiving week, and about
75,000 of the 77,000 season's tickets have been taken. The league
sets the price increase at all playoff sites. For the Jets,
traditionally the lowest-priced seat in the NFL, the $35 ticket
will cost $58 and the $40 seat has gone up to $63.
</P>
<P>
   Next week team officials are going to Miami to scout the hotel
that the American Conference winner stays in for the Super Bowl.
After all, you never know.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets will be sending Mike Kensil, the operations director;
Kevin Coyle, the director of travel; Steve Yarnell, in charge of
security, and Frank Ramos, the public relations director. This is
standard procedure among all the teams who get to the divisional
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say `Super Bowl' are words you're not supposed to say
when you're in the playoffs,'' Ramos said. ``But you can't just
suddenly prepare for the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   It appears that all the Jets' regulars who started the season
will be able to play in the post-season. Aaron Glenn,  &UR;  &LR; who missed
the last three games at left cornerback with a sprained ankle, is
practicing at an increased tempo. ``It looks like he has a real
shot, unless he has a setback,'' Bill Parcells said &UR; . &LR;  Fullback
Keith Byars &UR; ,  &LR; who also did not play the past three games, has had
the cast removed from his broken forearm. The only regular player
sidelined for the year was Marvin Jones &UR; ,  &LR; who suffered a serious
knee injury from a training camp accident. Leon Johnson, a key role
player, had a rib injury that ended his season after Game 14. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
