<HEADLINE>
2 INDUSTRIES UNITE TO PAVE WAY FOR HIGH-SPEED WEB ACCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 4)  
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who has used the Internet at both work and home knows
that those are vastly different experiences. Whatever the metaphor
they choose _ jack rabbit and tortoise, water and molasses, heaven
and hell _ most people who access the Net from home via dial-up
modems miss a big part of what cyberspace ought to be all about:
high-speed, low-hassle access to text, graphics, audio and video.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is that typical modems are simply not
able to do the Internet full justice. And most consumers have no
other economically realistic options for connecting.
</P>
<P>
   But if the telecommunications and cable television industries
have their way, that will start to change in a big way this year,
beginning a process that could bring quick Internet connections
from the office to the living room just as Henry Ford brought the
automobile from the mansion to the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with the advent of truly low-cost personal computers,
the mass deployment of cheap, reliable, high-speed Internet links
for residential consumers could have an impact as deep as Ford's.
After all, it was not until cars became less a novelty for the rich
than a necessity for the rest that it made sense to actually pave
roads.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the broad availability of high-speed cyberspace
connections could foster the development of new sorts of
applications that make today's Internet look like a rutted cart
path.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is the bet that many of the nation's largest
telephone and cable television companies have made or are getting
ready to make. And 1999 will probably be the year that those two
industries, with their vastly different financial, regulatory and
cultural dimensions, join their battle to control the future of how
the nation's consumers enter cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest single opportunity that exists in all of
communications,'' said Howard Anderson, managing director of the
Yankee Group, a high-technology consulting firm in Boston. ``It
will get very serious and this, 1999, is the year that we will see
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable television and telephone industries are trying to use
radically different technologies to deliver huge amounts of data to
homes, but the financial opportunity for each of them is
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most aggressive projections peg the number of homes
that had high-speed Internet access at the end of last year at
something less than 750,000 (a vast majority of those using cable
modems rather than the telephone technology known as asymmetric
digital subscriber line, or ADSL.)
</P>
<P>
   Overall, somewhere around 45 percent of the nation's 100 million
homes have computers, and only about half of those, or around 22.5
million, are online at all.
</P>
<P>
   US West Inc. has been the most aggressive of the Bell local
phone companies in deploying ADSL technology, planning to sign up
as many as 25,000 customers by the end of last year. Michael
Rouleau, a US West vice president for marketing, estimated that
about 10 percent of cyberspace-using homes would pay extra for
high-speed access.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jermoluk, chairman of At Home Corp., the cable-modem
venture backed by many of the nation's large cable system
operators, said his company's business plan was to win 20 percent
of any given market's online homes as customers after four years.
</P>
<P>
   Split the difference at 15 percent and the potential market
today _ at $40 a month a home, which is roughly what both the
telephone and cable companies are charging _ comes to about $1.6
billion. In the communications world, that is not a large number.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson of Yankee Group, however, believes that fully half of
the online homes would pay $40 a month for high-speed Internet
access. If that were true, and if, in a few years, the proportion
of U.S. homes that had computers rose to 60 percent and the
proportion of online homes also rose to 60 percent, then the market
opportunity would be a much more significant $8.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But even that is just the entrance to the potential gold mine.
That $40 a month just covers basic access to cyberspace. What the
telephone and cable companies may try to do is to leverage that
relationship with users to sell them additional services, ranging
from e-mail to clothing shopping to video games.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, standing in the way of such incremental revenue are
some very daunting fixed costs. It generally takes around $700 to
upgrade each phone or cable line to provide high-speed data access.
(Additional options, like offering Internet-based phone service
over a cable line, cost even more.)
</P>
<P>
   So, for instance, because At Home's affiliates serve about 60
million customers, Jermoluk said, it would cost a staggering $42
billion to get all of them online using cable modems. And so the
deployment goes slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Other than competition between each other, however, the biggest
force pushing the cable and telephone companies to deploy
high-speed data systems may not be consumers, but the computer
industry.
</P>
<P>
   In this day of 450-megahertz processors and video cards with as
many transistors as Pentium chips, the biggest bottleneck in the
computer system is the link to other computers. If the connections
do not increase in speed, the prospect of buying a new computer
every year or two becomes less compelling.
</P>
<P>
   That is why companies like Compaq Computer and Microsoft are
perhaps even more eager for widespread high-speed data connections
than even the most intense Internet surfer. For the local phone and
cable companies, the Internet is the future. For the computer
companies it is now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 2028EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
