<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4831 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSOURI-RIVER-ART-85     01-01 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-RIVER-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE WANTS A SAY IN SETTING THE MISSOURI RIVER'S COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING for all needing)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(htv) 
 By PAM BELLUCK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEBRASKA CITY, Neb. _ Lewis and Clark would not know the
Missouri River now.
</P>
<P>
   The tumultuous water that taunted their canoes as they forged
the way to the American West is docile now, domesticated.
</P>
<P>
   The ``confused jumble of savage-looking snags'' that Mark Twain
steered his steamboat through is now slick and sterile. And there
is little left of the muddy water that Horace Greeley once said was
like ``thick milk porridge _ you could not discern an egg in a
glass of it.''
</P>
<P>
   For 50 years now, the hand of man has tamed the Missouri River,
damming it and diking it, streamlining and straitjacketing it into
a channel for barges and a generally well-behaved feeding tube for
the fertile farmland on its banks.
</P>
<P>
   But big changes are coming to the Big Muddy, America's longest
river, stretching nearly 2,500 miles from Three Forks, Mont., to
St. Louis, is in the throes of an identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   After the withering drought of the late 1980s and the ferocious
floods of 1993, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, which essentially
controls the river's water flow, decided it needed to re-evaluate
its master plan.
</P>
<P>
   The fracas over the river's future is fierce as
environmentalists, farmers, barge operators, recreation boosters,
hydroelectric utilities, Indian tribes and municipal leaders all
try to make sure the river stays _ or becomes _ what they want it
to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody would dearly love if we could come up with a
recommendation that everyone could agree on,'' said Richard H.
Opper, executive director of the Missouri River Basin Association,
a coalition of the eight river-basin states and two dozen Indian
tribes, which met recently to discuss the river.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle is the Corps, which controls how much water
is released from upstream reservoirs after each year's snow melt _
and when. It has the sometimes Sisyphean task of insuring there is
enough water when and where it is needed, but not so much that it
mutinies its banks.
</P>
<P>
   The Corps has issued a list of options _ different ways to
adjust the ebb and flow of the Missouri _ with the aim of making a
decision later this year.
</P>
<P>
   And that has unleashed a torrent of debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saying for years there are really two things that the
Corps could not propose politically,'' Opper said. ``One was
keeping the current situation the same. The other was any sort of
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Nebraska City, an unpretentious, plain-vanilla Plains
town about 400 miles upriver from where the Missouri dumps into the
Mississippi near St. Louis, most of the conflicts are easy to see.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers like John Crook, growing corn and soybeans on river
bottom land his great grandfather staked out in 1878, want the
Missouri to be reined in further so their crops won't drown.
</P>
<P>
   People like Ray Pinney, who manages the barge terminal here,
want the water to stay swift and deep so towboats and barges can
keep hauling fertilizer up from St. Louis and Kansas City and
taking grain down river at harvest time.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Smith, who represents the environmental group, American
Rivers, in this part of the country, and Gerald Mestl, a biologist
with the Nebraska Game and Parks Commission, want the river to
return, as much as possible, to its natural, free-flowing state.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of management have destroyed miles of natural habitat,
threatening the survival of many species and landing three _ the
pallid sturgeon, the piping plover and the least tern _ on the
endangered species list.
</P>
<P>
   And Nancy Hoch, who heads the economic development corporation
in this town of about 7,000 people, is supportive of farming and
business interests. But like leaders in other cities that once used
the river as an industrial dumping ground, she also understands
environmental concerns. After all, Nebraska City's claim to fame is
as the home of the inventor of Arbor Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strongly that the river does not belong to
anyone,'' said Ms. Hoch. ``It does not belong to the least tern. It
does not belong to barge traffic. We need to balance the river.''
</P>
<P>
   But balance is hard to come by on a river that sculpts the
country's mid-section, draining about one-sixth of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Further north of Nebraska City, a booming hunting, fishing and
boating industry wants to insure the reservoirs don't lose too much
water each year.
</P>
<P>
   And up and down the Missouri are Indian tribes, who have begun
to assert claims to water rights along significant portions of the
river, supported by a turn-of-the-century Supreme Court ruling.
When they ultimately negotiate what water they control, the tribes
say they envision many uses including irrigation, electricity and
exporting water for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many interests in the Missouri River Basin,'' said
Richard Bad Moccasin, executive director of the tribes'
organization, Mni Sose Intertribal Water Rights Coalition (``Mni''
means ``water'' in the Lakota language, and ``Sose,'' Bad Moccasin
said, means ``the way the Missouri used to be _ murky and muddy and
wild and woolly.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't envy the Army Corps,'' he said, ``but, well, they
created the monster _ trying to change that mighty Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, concerned that the river would overrun some of
the nation's richest farmland _ and eager for a public works
project to employ the veterans of World War II _ the Corps erected
six dams on the Missouri, with reservoirs to hold the snow melt
from South Dakota to Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Further downstream, it narrowed a wide bramble of sandbars and
side-channels into a single, manicured canal, with fast, deep water
to satisfy towboats and barges plying between Sioux City and St.
Louis. Dikes and levees were rigged up too, keeping the river in
check, and holding back the runoff that once muddied its waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people,'' Opper said, ``say it more closely resembles a
plumbing system rather than a natural river.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The voices of those who say that have gotten stronger in recent
years. Environmental groups, distressed that the loss of about half
a million acres of the river's habitat has threatened or endangered
a fifth of the plant and animal species in and around the river,
have been pressing for substantial changes.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the American Rivers group proposed ending all
commercial navigation, saying it pales in economic significance to
the river's environmental and recreational value.
</P>
<P>
   When that was met with anger, the group suggested the Corps
change its policy of releasing a constant amount of water from the
spring through the fall and instead release more water in the
spring and less in the summer. That would create a ``spring rise,''
that would act as a kind of aphrodisiac to fish, and in summer
would encourage the formation of sandbars, where birds like to
nest.
</P>
<P>
   To the navigation industry, that would be a grave threat. It
would ground barges and towboats when the river was low in summer.
While the Missouri's barge traffic has never been heavy and has
diminished in the last 20 years _ the Army Corps says 2 million
tons of cargo a year travel on the Missouri compared with over 100
million tons on the Mississippi _ industry officials say it is
important because it forces railroads to set competitive shipping
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Paul J. Werner, a vice president with American Waterways
Operators, the barge industry trade association, said keeping the
Missouri's water level consistently high is also crucial for
insuring the Mississippi has enough water for navigation.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, for their part, worry a spring rise could cause
flooding or make it impossible to drain fields in time for
planting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's too wet to get a crop planted by the first of June,
you're not farming this year,'' said Crook, who like many farmers
here is reeling from the loss of some crops in recent years because
wet weather has made the river unusually high.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, weather anomalies like that have made the Army Corps'
impending choice even harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The river changes and you need to change with it,'' said John
Remus, a hydraulic engineer with the Army Corps, standing on a bank
near Nebraska City. ``We're not going to be able to be as
high-handed as we once were. We're going to have to listen to other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Opper, who in the last year has managed, with the help of
professional mediators, to get sworn enemies to at least
acknowledge each other's claims to the river, hopes the pressure of
the Corps' upcoming decision and the responsibilities imposed by
the Endangered Species Act will force the groups to reach a
consensus, even though ``it will be a recommendation that nobody is
completely happy with.''
</P>
<P>
   But one recent change on the river has so far not angered too
many people.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps has begun buying up parcels of farmland along the
banks, grafting them onto the river and converting them into
wetlands that re-create a little bit of the old Missouri. The
environmentalists approve, even if they consider it a drop in the
bucket. And most navigators and farmers aren't complaining, since
the wetlands are walled off with rocks so they don't disturb the
flow and depth of the main river channel.
</P>
<P>
   The first of these, Hamburg Bend, created in 1996 just south of
Nebraska City, is a chute carved from land so damaged by the 1993
flood that it became practically impossible to farm.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent tour in a flat-bottomed skiff, as a bald eagle and a
blue heron flapped by, Mestl of the Game and Parks Commission
pointed out the sandbars, slower, shallower water, and tapered,
natural banks that attract wildlife, including the speckled chub,
the plains minnow and the catfish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lewis and Clark called the Missouri a catfish river,'' Mestl
said. And even though the wetlands are small consolation for
environmentalists, he said, at least ``people are starting to catch
fish here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
