<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-WEBSITES-84     01-01 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-WEBSITES-845(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET SPECULATORS TARGET POLITICIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif., Va., Mo., Minn., N.J., Tenn., Mass., Ala.)  (lb) 
 By REBECCA FAIRLEY RANEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has never declared himself a
presidential candidate, at least 39 pieces of prime Internet real
estate have already been claimed in his name. Yet only two of those
addresses for sites on the World Wide Web _ Bush2000.org and
GeorgeWBush.com _ belong to people officially affiliated with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rest were snatched up by a small group of
speculators who have been grabbing politicians' names like mining
claims in the Old West. Their motive is financial, not political.
</P>
<P>
   The speculators, who paid $70 for each domain name, as such
Internet addresses are known, hope to sell their cyberclaims to the
highest bidders _ even if the buyer happens to be a political
opponent of the potential candidate in question.
</P>
<P>
   The leading player in this game is Alex Goldstein, 25, of Los
Angeles, who has spent at least $10,000 on domain names. Goldstein,
a native of Long Island, N.Y., who worked for a few years as a bond
trader in Chicago and now works for an Internet marketing firm in
California, owns nine variations of Bush's name, five for the
magazine publisher Steve Forbes and at least 15 for former House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for any major national political figures who had
left useful names open,'' Goldstein said. Politicians, he said, are
good targets for domain-name investment because they cannot
trademark their names. Speculators who tried to grab corporate
names in recent years found their claims thwarted by lawsuits
claiming trademark infringement.
</P>
<P>
   Obtaining a domain name is otherwise not difficult. A $70
registration fee is paid to Network Solutions Inc., the Herndon,
Va., company that has handled domain registrations for the last
five years under an exclusive contract with the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, who describes himself as nonpartisan, said that
whether the bidders for his names are supporters or opponents of a
candidate is irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally don't really care who controls these names,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 elections, political operatives quickly learned the
value of publishing Web sites under names that would attract an
opponents' supporters. For example, when supporters of Sen. Bob
Dole pointed their browsers to dole96.com, they found content that
ridiculed and belittled their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Like many cyberspace speculators, Goldstein expressed surprise
that so many politicians had failed to learn from the 1996 campaign
and had left themselves open to the potential for opponents to
create sites under Web addresses similar to those of official
campaign sites, which candidates use for everything from
biographical information to text of speeches to fund raising. He
predicted that in six months the going rate for such names would be
five figures for each.
</P>
<P>
   But several political consultants said that while candidates
could be hurt by their ignorance of the ways of the Internet,
speculators like Goldstein could get soaked by their ignorance of
the ways of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hockaday, president of Campaign Solutions, a Republican
consulting firm in Alexandria, Va., that specializes in direct
mail, telemarketing and Internet services, predicted that campaign
managers were ``not going to be held up by highway robbery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Should they be really worried? Not really,'' Hockaday said.
``Should they do better promoting of the official site?
Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 elections, very few campaigns bothered to promote
their Web sites on brochures or television advertisements. But that
may change as candidates face the prospect of a field of
``look-alike'' sites, Hockaday said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the presumed candidates, Bush's name has proved to be the
most popular among the speculators, with at least 39 variations
having been registered. For most of the domain names purchased, no
sites have been built.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential candidates who have been attracting domain-name
speculators are Vice President Al Gore (at least 20 addresses),
Forbes (21) and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. (19).
Eight names each have been registered for possible candidacies by
Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., and former Democratic Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   In those cases, the candidates' own organization had generally
registered only one or two of the domain names. But few political
consultants see the need to buy a block of Web addresses to protect
their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only get troubled over things over which you have
control,'' said Karl Rove, a consultant to Bush, based in Austin,
Texas. ``If people are interested in good information on a
candidate and they find a site that's just a rant about a
candidate, they'll pass it by.''
</P>
<P>
   But advisers to former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander disagreed.
Mel Lukens, a former aide with Alexander's political action
committee in Nashville, strategically purchased six variations of
the name to block opposition sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every positive site,'' Lukens said, ``there's a multitude
of people who want to get negative information out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are also strategic issues to be considered when potential
candidates or their agents register domain names. To secure one
name for a campaign Web site is cautious, for example, but to
register 15 names is tantamount to a declaration of candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do a dance before you're a declared candidate,''
said Michael Cornfield, a professor at The George Washington
University's Graduate School of Political Management who
specializes in online politics. ``You don't want to tip your hand
to the Federal Election Commission and to the other candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, the lack of defensive domain-name
registrations also shows widespread ignorance among political
operatives of the growing importance of the Internet as an
information medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elites in the political consultancy world are television
people,'' Cornfield said. ``They just don't get it.'' The emerging
class of Internet political consultants _ who would invariably
advise candidates to buy blocks of Web addresses _ ``don't have the
access to the inner circles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few people who bought domain names based on potential
candidates in 2000 said they planned to create sites opposing the
candidate whose name they had registered.
</P>
<P>
   Among this group is David Crump of Boston, who runs adult Web
sites for a living and bought three variations on
``AlbertGore2000.'' Crump, a Libertarian, said he might establish
parody sites under the vice president's name that direct traffic to
the Libertarian Party's Web site. Of course, he allowed, if someone
were to offer him money for the names, he would sell them.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Walker, a rent collector in St. Louis, registered four
addresses based on Gephardt's name. Walker, who had volunteered for
the congressman's campaigns in the past, said he would donate the
names to the campaign if anyone asked for them. Walker said he had
never used the Internet but when he heard that people were
registering addresses to build opposition sites against candidates,
he acted to protect Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rodgers, a real-estate broker in Austin, registered the
domain name GeorgeBush2000.com because, he said, ``I don't want
George Bush to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers, who describes himself as ``neither Republican nor
Democrat _ just frustrated,'' said he had no intention of selling
the name.
</P>
<P>
   Still, profit potential is by far the most popular reason for
registering a domain name. Four Web addresses registered under
variations of Gore's name are already hawking political
memorabilia. Vollie Goehring, the systems administrator for the
political consultant to Bush, said he received e-mail daily from
people offering to sell campaign-related domain names.
</P>
<P>
   To Joe Moorman, the domain game is part of the democratic
process. Moorman, a 28-year-old Libertarian programmer in
Birmingham, Ala., owns GeorgeBush2000.org and GeorgeBush2004.com.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he might set up parody sites but that he would be
willing to sell the names, ``especially if I could recoup all those
taxes the politicians keep raising on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Moorman wonders, in the face of all the speculating,
whether the domain-name registration process will remain democratic
for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I fear,'' he said of politicians, ``is that they're going
to try to rewrite the laws _ because they're in control _ and take
them from us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 2039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4838 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENOPAUSE-MAVEN-$ADV0     01-01 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENOPAUSE-MAVEN-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIONEER IN WOMEN'S HEALTH ATTRACTS A DEVOTED FOLLOWING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(rl) 
 By ELIZABETH HAYT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, when the hot flashes hit and her hormones took a nose
dive, Janet Brown, 50, became a self-described raging bull. ``I was
hot, cranky, impossible to live with, angry in my own body and
looking for love in all the wrong places,'' said Ms. Brown, who
owns a high-end designer boutique in Port Washington, N.Y. ``Not
one person could be near me. I could alienate a planet.'' Her
doctor referred her to Dr. Patricia Allen, an obstetrician and
gynecologist with a reputation for taming the most unruly patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Allen came along, otherwise known as the Elmer Gantry of
medicine, and made me lose 25 pounds, take medication and see
specialists for everything to get my body back into good health
after seven years of neglect,'' Ms. Brown said. ``I don't perspire
anymore. I am absolutely the most amiable 50-year-old in the world.
I was born again.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allen's all-encompassing approach to female health care _
she has prescribed hormone-replacement therapy and a personal
trainer in the same breath _ along with her take-charge, ``Queen of
England'' manner, have attracted a fierce following, especially
among New York's power elite.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allen, who was born in a Kentucky farmhouse 51 years ago,
conducts examinations in her Upper East Side office in a Chanel lab
coat and Manolo Blahnik stilettos. Her patients have been known to
receive faxes in their paper gowns. Liz Smith, the gossip
columnist; Joni Evans, the literary agent, and Barbara Taylor
Bradford, the novelist, are among the strong-willed, often
demanding women who submit to Dr. Allen's orders, in part because
they regard her as one of them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to seeing as many as 25 patients a day, Dr. Allen
may also preside over a charity lunch for the New York Presbyterian
Hospital, where she is on staff, and then spend the evening at the
opera. She has been known to make a quick exit from a black-tie
affair to tend to a hospital emergency, only to return to the party
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I met Pat,'' Ms. Bradford said, ``I thought,
`Now who does she remind me of? A cross between Edwina Sandys, the
granddaughter of Sir Winston Churchill, and Pamela Harriman.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allen's active social life notwithstanding, she owes her
reputation to her innovative methods of treatment. ``She's really
out there on the forefront,'' said Dr. David Skinner, chief
executive of the New York Presbyterian Health-Care System.
</P>
<P>
   She has helped shape a new attitude toward menopause, once a
hush-hush event signaling the end of a woman's fertile years, now
perceived as a positive experience. Her interest in the subject
coincided with her own menopause and the publication, in 1991, of
``A Silent Passage,'' a reconsideration of menopause by one of her
patients, Gail Sheehy, who used Dr. Allen as a source.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat was a pioneer,'' Ms. Sheehy said. ``She recognized the
neglect of women in this age group.'' In 1996, Dr. Allen started
the New York Menopause Center at her office on 90th Street, off
Madison Avenue, a cozy setting where Provencal decor and fresh
flowers mix with the latest ultrasound and scanning equipment. She
has assembled a network of doctors _ surgeons, urologists,
psychiatrists, a cardiologist, dermatologist, endocrinologist and
nutritionist _for the women under her care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women need a consolidated way to get things done,'' Dr. Allen
said. ``They don't want to go someplace for a bone-density test, go
someplace else to be counseled and then come back to me. They want
one visit.''
</P>
<P>
   This one-stop shopping is a hit with her patients. ``I had a
checkup with Pat to get a routine bone-density test because I'm on
hormone-replacement therapy,'' said Ms. Evans, the literary agent.
``She found a fibroid, an orange going to grapefruit size. If Pat
hadn't found it, it would have been a tree in a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allen's care is not limited to gynecology. ``When I walk in,
she says, `Remember to take off your socks so I can see your toes
because women over 45 tend to get melanomas between the toes and on
the ankles,' '' Ms. Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allen has also been known to dispense nonmedical advice,
suggesting a different hairstyle, or marriage counseling. Last
spring, when interviewing a new patient, Dr. Allen discovered that
the woman's marriage was in crisis. Dr. Allen called the patient's
husband, then recommended a family therapist.
</P>
<P>
   In an age of impersonal managed health care, Dr. Allen's
professional style harks back to her roots, in Columbia, Ky. The
eldest of six children _ her father was a tenant farmer, her mother
a schoolteacher _ Dr. Allen was delivered by a local practitioner.
``He and another local doctor not only did obstetrics and
gynecology, but pediatrics, geriatrics and general surgery as
well,'' she said. ``They were the emergency room doctor and the
psychiatrist.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allen strives to be a small-town doctor in the big city.
After making a referral to a surgeon, she may accompany the patient
to the consultation, a cup of coffee in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had me in the hospital for a D and C,' '' said Ms. Smith,
the columnist. ``She encouraged all my friends to come and see me.
She came to see me before the operation and twice afterward. She
explained everything. She did all my tests twice. She must really
be a joy for a hypochondriac.''
</P>
<P>
   And she is not the kind of obstetrician who shows up at the
hospital when the patient is screaming for pain relief at the end
of labor. Dr. Allen sits with mothers-to-be from the moment they
are admitted to the hospital. In six years, she has not missed a
delivery, she said, though she insists that her patients give her
enough advance warning to do her hair before a delivery, even a
midnight one. And she is never without her lucky 22-karat gold
angel earrings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear the clicking of her heels coming down the hallway in
the hospital,'' said Linda Wells, the editor of Allure magazine
whose two sons were delivered by Dr. Allen. It was Ms. Wells who,
as a token of appreciation, gave her doctor the Chanel lab coat.
``She bullies you if you gain too much weight in the first three to
four months of pregnancy,'' Ms. Wells said. ``I know one person
whom she sent to Weight Watchers. I don't think Weight Watchers
accepts people who are pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Ms. Wells wondered how to keep her condition a secret
until she got back her amniocentesis results, Dr. Allen had an
answer for that, too. ``She said: `Just get your hair done,' '' Ms.
Wells recalled. `` `It'll draw attention away from your belly.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
