<SLUG> BC-CADBURY-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS CADBURY LOOKING FOR AN EXIT FROM THE BEVERAGE BUSINESS? 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By agreeing to sell nearly all its international beverage
business to the Coca-Cola Co., Cadbury Schweppes PLC made it clear
last month that it was leaving the global soft-drink field to
Coca-Cola and Pepsico Inc.
</P>
<P>
   What is less clear is Cadbury's strategy for its remaining
soft-drink business, which will now be concentrated in its most
profitable market, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some popular brands like Dr Pepper, Cadbury lags far
behind Coca-Cola and Pepsico in market share, which was part of the
company's justification for selling its international business.
While it says the sale will allow it to focus better on the U.S.
market, one major bottler contends that the deal signals the
British company's intention to leave the soft-drink business
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe this is the first step in determining what some
kind of exit strategy might be for Cadbury,'' said Jim Turner, one
of the biggest independent bottlers of Dr Pepper and 7-Up, another
Cadbury brand. The Coca-Cola deal, he said, ``certainly opens up a
lot of questions in terms of Cadbury's long-term plans in the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury executives say they are committed to staying in the
American soft-drink market. ``Dr. Pepper/Seven-Up is an important
component of the Cadbury Schweppes family, and there are no plans
to sell it,'' said Philippa Dworkin, a spokeswoman for Dr.
Pepper/Seven-Up, based in Plano, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While its geographical sweep will be much smaller (Cadbury is
keeping its soft-drink brands in France and South Africa, as well
as the United States), the company is retaining the most profitable
part of the business. Indeed, about 65 percent of Cadbury's
beverage profits came from its operations in the United States in
1997, according to the company's annual report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see North American beverages as very different from the
rest of the world,'' said John F. Brock, Cadbury's managing
director for global beverages. ``We have a 15 percent share here,
compared to a 3 share outside the U.S. We have a terrific set of
brands, led by Dr Pepper, and an increasingly secure route to
market.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cadbury and Coca-Cola executives announced the $1.85
billion sale on Dec. 11, it was presented as a deal that was in the
best interests of both. Without a cohesive distribution network,
Cadbury could not develop its own brands overseas as well as
Coca-Cola would be able to, both companies said. Coca-Cola wanted
those brands _ to round out its portfolio, or, perhaps, to keep
them away from archrival Pepsico.
</P>
<P>
   (Pepsico, which has bottling agreements with Cadbury in Canada,
Chile, Eastern Europe and other places, greeted the news warily,
saying it will have to ``take a long, hard look'' at every aspect
of the arrangement.)
</P>
<P>
   Michael Branca, a beverage analyst with Lehman Brothers, said
the deal with Coke was an effort to create value for Cadbury's
brands. At the same time, he expects a sizable portion of the
deal's proceeds to be spent on buying back shares, benefiting
shareholders _ many of whom never liked the idea of getting
involved in the American soft-drink market in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Since the deal was announced, American depository receipts of
Cadbury _ each representing four shares of the British company _
have risen 12 percent. The stock closed on Thursday at $69.125,
near the 52-week high of $70.125 it touched on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury's brands, which also include Crush, Hires and A &AMP; W,
have long plied a treacherous path between Coca-Cola and Pepsi,
with some bottled by each giant and the rest handled by independent
bottlers, a famously Balkanized lot. In the past, Cadbury brands
have been unceremoniously dropped from Coke and Pepsi delivery
trucks; when Coke and Pepsi decided to acquire their own root-beer
brands not long ago, neither giant wanted to continue distributing
Hires and A &AMP; W.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Cadbury signed an agreement with Pepsico to continue
bottling and distributing the brands it currently handles, which is
thought to extend a certain amount of security to 7-Up. In
February, Cadbury signed another agreement with Coca-Cola
Enterprises, Coke's biggest bottler, to distribute Dr Pepper
through 2005. Coca-Cola Enterprises handles about 19 percent of Dr
Pepper's total volume.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those agreements, Cadbury's route to market would be
more secure if the company had its own distribution system to rely
on. Yet it seems unlikely that Cadbury will pour money into
building up that distribution immediately.
</P>
<P>
   In February, after much foot-dragging, Cadbury spent about $300
million for a 40 percent stake in the American Bottling Company,
formed by the merger of two Midwestern bottlers. Cadbury's partner
is Carlyle Group, a Washington investment firm. At the time, the
company said the new bottler would absorb others, continuing a
consolidation of the so-called third tier. To date, more than 10
months after the company was formed, only one bottler has been
added to the fold _ hardly an impressive pace.
</P>
<P>
   But Brock, the Cadbury executive, said some money would be spent
on consolidating Cadbury's bottling operations. ``It's a fairly
modest investment to get the independent system consolidated,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, there are also acquisitions to be made in the
candy business, using the money from the Coke deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the confectionery side, we see the global opportunity
higher than in soft drinks,'' Brock said. ``The top six players
make up only about 50 percent of the business. It's far more
fragmented.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Pirko, a beverage-industry consultant, says Cadbury's
decision to sell its overseas brands to Coca-Cola was indeed the
right move. ``It moves them back to their position of strength,
which is confectionery,'' he said. ``It gives them an opportunity
to go after what they do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Some other analysts say that certain Cadbury Schweppes
executives are more comfortable in the confectionery business,
where the company is a major global player and the fourth-largest
chocolate maker, than in the soft-drink business.
</P>
<P>
   Without the international beverage operations, Cadbury will be
tilted more toward confectioneries, whose sales totaled about $3.7
billion in 1997. Beverage sales minus the brands being sold will be
closer to $2 billion, with profits of $470 million. Confectionery
profits in 1997 were about $479 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intuition tells me that they are going to invest more in
the confectionary side than the soft-drink side,'' Turner said,
``and they will also try to consolidate some of the bottling
operations in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner speculated that such a consolidation could be a precursor
to spinning off the bottling and beverage operations as a separate
company. And, he noted, both Coca-Cola and Pepsico would love to
own Dr Pepper, a perennial moneymaker for both companies' bottlers,
should the Federal Trade Commission, which has blocked previous
efforts by both companies to acquire Dr Pepper and 7-Up, become
more accommodating.
</P>
<P>
   One problem that might impede any possible sale is the
performance of 7-Up, which has been losing market share in many
areas to Sprite the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they wanted to sell, they might not get full value
because they haven't turned 7-Up around,'' said Emanuel Goldman, a
global consumer-products analyst for Merrill Lynch. ``And if you
can do that, why do you want to get out of the business?''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman says, the decision to concentrate on the United States
soft-drink business signals that Cadbury will battle Coca-Cola and
Pepsi. ``There isn't a graceful exit,'' he said. ``They wouldn't
have put this bottling thing together if that's what they were
looking for. That means they plan to stick around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
