u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-OUTBACK-BOWL-NYT &LR;      01-01 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OUTBACK-BOWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WHAT MIGHT BE HIS LAST COLLEGE GAME, COUCH STIFLED BY PENN
STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Story for use by NYT News Service subscribers.) 
(ms) 
 BY JODY ROYCE    
 NYT Regional Newspapers    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ If it was Tim Couch's final game at Kentucky, it
was not the best way to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State kept the Wildcats' standout quarterback from
finishing what he began. The Nittany Lions (9-3) did enough on both
sides of the ball to post their second Outback Bowl victory in two
appearances in four years, beating Kentucky, 26-14, Friday at
Raymond James Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Nittany Lions shut out Kentucky for the final
three quarters. Offensively, they came back from an 11-point
deficit to give 72-year-old Coach Joe Paterno his 19th career bowl
victory, a National Collegiate Athletic Association record.
</P>
<P>
   Couch completed 30 of 48 passes for 336 yards and both
touchdowns for Kentucky (7-5). But the 6-foot-5-inch junior was
picked off twice by Penn State's Anthony King in the first half and
went 10 for 19 for just 106 yards in the second half. Penn State,
which had a team-record tying 47 sacks going into the game, also
sacked him six times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was brilliant,'' Kentucky coach Hal Mumme said of Couch.
``We wouldn't be playing in a New Year's Day bowl game without him
or several other key players''
</P>
<P>
   Mumme added: ``I'd like to have him for another year. He has to
make a very big life-changing decision in a short period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch said he would make a decision Wednesday or Thursday as to
whether he will stay for his senior season. The deadline for
underclassmen to file for the National Football League draft is
next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm 50-50 as to living the dream of being an NFL
quarterback or staying with my teammates,'' Couch said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats benefited from a missed field goal to score the
game's first points. Couch capped a 66-yard drive in six plays by
throwing a 37-yard scoring strike to Lance Mickelsen over the
middle. Mickelsen worked his way free from Penn State safety Shawn
Lee before making a leaping catch in the end zone wth 7 minutes 17
seconds gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions countered with the first of Travis Forney's four field
goals, an Outback Bowl record and a school record for bowl games.
After coming up short on a 51-yard effort on the previous
possession, Forney hit a 43-yarder 2:18 later after freshman
tailback Eric McCoo ran 25 yards from midfield.
</P>
<P>
   Couch then guided Kentucky to its second touchdown. A 40-yard
connection to Kevin Coleman was wiped out by a holding call, but
Couch went back to Coleman for 22 yards and a first down at the
Kentucky 46.
</P>
<P>
   Couch completed his next three passes _ 8 yards to Derek Homer,
30 to Mickelsen and the last 16 on a screen to Anthony White, who
eluded a Penn State defender at the 8 before trotting in for a 14-3
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to get discouraged, but the defense kept their
poise and discipline,'' said Paterno. Of Kentucky, he said:``You
don't get any better than what they did early.''
</P>
<P>
   After a shanked punt, the Lions used the big play to cut into
their deficit. On second-and-16, Kevin Thompson scrambled out of
the pocket and hit an open Joe Nastasi for a 56-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Forney booted a 26-yard field goal with 63 seconds left in the
second to trim the Wildcats' halftime lead to 14-13.
</P>
<P>
   Things began to fall apart early for the Wildcats in the third
quarter. On the second play of the second half, Couch was sacked
for an 8-yard loss by Courtney Brown, who was named the game's most
outstanding player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've been held scoreless in a half for two
years,'' Couch said. ``We hurt ourselves a lot with penalties. They
made some good adjustments in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   That forced a punt and the Lions turned that into a 21-yard
Forney field goal 7:09 into the third period, putting them ahead
for good at 16-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cut the defensive package a bit,'' Paterno said. ``Toward
the end they beat us with the back out of the backfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Couch's 30 completions, 14 went to running backs and only two
went to his favorite receiver, Craig Yeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a lot of good adjustments,'' Couch said. ``It's been
a while since I saw that many different defensive looks. They were
well-disguised.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats drove to a potential go-ahead field goal with 3:54
left, but Seth Hanson's 29-yard try was blocked by all-American
linebacker LaVar Arrington. It may have been Kentucky's last chance
to win.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State used two big plays by McCoo to set up Forney's fourth
field goal. Right after Kentucky's missed kick, McCoo broke loose
for 30 yards. He later took a screen pass from Kevin Thompson and
scampered 21 yards to put Penn State in field-goal range. Forney's
25-yard kick with 13 seconds left in the third quarter made it
19-14.
</P>
<P>
   To open the fourth, Kentucky had second-and-1 at its 35 and did
not gain another yard. Arrington stopped Derek Homer on fourth
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't question going for it, but I question the call,''
Mumme said. ``I'd go for it again, but I would have made a better
call.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions sealed the victory win with 11:03 left on a
19-yard reverse Chafie Fields for the final touchdown. Fields
eluded four would-be tacklers at the Kentucky 6.
</P>
<P>
   (Jody Royce is a sports writer for the Sarasota Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
<P>
   (Story Filed By The HERALD TRIBUNE, SARASOTA, FLORIDA.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
