<HEADLINE>
PATAKI, STARTING 2ND TERM, SAYS NEW YORK CAN LEAD NATION
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ George Elmer Pataki began his second term as
governor Friday by declaring that his success in scaling back
government had rekindled New York's spirit, saying that the strides
of the last four years showed that the state was ready to lead the
nation into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We the people of New York must light the way to a brighter
future,'' Pataki said in a 14-minute inaugural address that often
had the feel of a civic-minded pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, 53, a Republican who rose from a childhood on a
Peekskill farm to become the state's 53rd governor, outlined no new
proposals in the speech and did not refer to his ambitions beyond
Albany, which have been the subject of growing speculation since he
easily won re-election in November.
</P>
<P>
   But the tirelessly upbeat oratory suggested he was honing a
theme he plans to expound while traveling the country: that his
brand of Republicanism _ fiscally conservative, with little
emphasis on divisive social issues _ had worked in New York, and
would work elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We charted a bold new course for this state,'' he said, ``a
course driven by our determination to see that government remains
the people's servant and not their master.''
</P>
<P>
   As he often does, he referred to his idol, Theodore Roosevelt,
who was inaugurated governor of New York 100 years ago Friday.
Pataki noted that both he and Roosevelt stood ``at the edge of a
new century, which is spread out before us like an undiscovered
land of promise.'' Roosevelt also was the last New York Republican
to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has declined to say whether he will run for president
next year, insisting only that he has not ruled it out and saying
that as leader of a large state, he wants to help set his party's
agenda. In recent weeks, he has uncharacteristically lashed out at
the Republicans in Congress. He has asserted that they have damaged
the party by neglecting core issues, like cutting taxes, in their
zeal to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential bid could prove daunting for Pataki, because
while his support for abortion rights and views on other social
issues play well in New York, they put him in conflict with the
conservatives who hold sway in Republican presidential primaries in
other states.
</P>
<P>
   Though he did not detail his agenda for his second term Friday,
he plans to use his State of the State Message on Wednesday and his
budget message later this month to announce new proposals. They
will include a budget that is to be considerably more austere than
his election-year one, which raised spending at more than the rate
of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   At the ceremony in the Convention Center in Albany, Pataki took
the oath of office from the state's chief judge, Judith Kaye, while
a 19-gun salute resounded in the piercing cold outside.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Earlier, Judge Kaye swore in the new lieutenant governor, Mary
Donohue, a former judge and prosecutor from upstate New York, who
was recruited by Pataki to replace Betsy McCaughey Ross. Pataki had
a long falling-out with Ms. McCaughey Ross. After he removed her
from the re-election ticket, she became a Democrat, lost the party
primary and ran against Pataki in the general election on the
Liberal Party line.
</P>
<P>
   The state Comptroller H. Carl McCall and the new attorney
general, Eliot Spitzer, also took their oaths of office Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Besides starting his second term, Pataki is now the most
prominent Republican in the state, replacing his mentor, U.S. Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, who was defeated for re-election in November. In
1994, D'Amato had anointed Pataki, then an obscure state senator,
as the party's nominee for governor.
</P>
<P>
   The D'Amato defeat capped a disappointing election for the
Republicans. Dennis Vacco was ousted as attorney general by
Spitzer, a wealthy former state prosecutor from Manhattan, and the
party failed to pick up seats in the Legislature, despite spending
heavily. That showing blunted Pataki's victory over the Democratic
nominee, New York City Council Speaker Peter Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato sat in the front row during the inaugural ceremony, two
rows in front of New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a Republican
who spurned Pataki and endorsed the three-term Democratic
incumbent, Mario Cuomo, in 1994, only to return to the fold in last
fall's election and campaign for Pataki. Giuliani also has national
aspirations, but publicly, he and Pataki say they get along.
Privately, there is no affection between their camps.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's relatively short address Friday had little in common
with his first in 1995, when he cited his upset victory over Cuomo
as evidence that the public was angry with the state's condition.
He attacked a ``paid and pampered bureaucracy,'' pledging a smaller
government, new work requirements for welfare recipients and tough
criminal justice laws, including the death penalty, which Cuomo had
blocked. He returned briefly to these issues Friday when he noted
that he had followed through on his promises.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the speech was not the only difference. The
inauguration this year was short and restrained, with none of the
exuberance of 1995, when the Republicans held a weekend of parties
to celebrate winning the governor's mansion for the first time in
24 years. About 2,100 people attended the swearing in Friday, down
from 13,000 in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
