<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CUSTOMERS IN CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Jan. 2:
</P>
<P>
   Online shopping jumped dramatically this holiday season, and
when preliminary estimates indicated that 1998 Christmas sales more
than tripled the previous year's figures, investors flocked to buy
shares in Internet retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices _ fueled by dreams of mass marketing online _
soared even though actual sales on the Internet are still tiny
compared with sales in the bricks-and-mortar world. Even a tripling
of sales is not terribly surprising given how limited online
retailing has been.
</P>
<P>
   One extremely optimistic forecast pegs total Internet-based
retail sales in 1998 at about $13 billion, a trivial amount when
compared with $2.6 trillion in annual retail sales in the United
States, and a fraction of the $118 billion transacted annually in
Wal-Mart stores alone. It may be several years before e-tailing
comes close to the volume of sales done through mail-order
catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   But growth in e-commerce is certain, and even traditional
retailers sense they cannot ignore the Internet for long. Next
year, some of their customers might just decide to stay home and
click on that little shopping-cart icon. Speed and convenience are
the obvious lures _ no more waiting in the checkout line or on hold
for a customer service agent to take your catalog order (though
back orders can be a big problem in cyberspace, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, though, some surveys suggest that traditional
retailers may be best positioned to take advantage of online growth
if they are nimble. Companies with stores, catalogs and Web sites _
multichannel retailers _ account for nearly 60 percent of all
Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that many customers will research products online,
then phone in their orders or even visit the store. Fears about
sending a credit-card number over the Internet may be a factor. But
a lot of consumers obviously think that talking to a sales clerk is
an indispensable part of the hassle. At least for now, most of them
prefer a live human to an electronic mouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
