<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PLAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUTIE AND DOLPHINS SPARRING BEFORE PLAYOFF BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This weekend the American Football Conference playoffs are about
quarterbacks: who will play, who won't play and who should have
kept his mouth shut.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Bills play the Dolphins in Miami in the early game
Saturday, and the New England Patriots are at Jacksonville on
Sunday. That matchup is the one the National Football League
probably did not expect.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will be without three-time Pro Bowler Drew Bledsoe
because his finger that was fractured six weeks ago has not healed.
So instead of having Bledsoe, the sixth-rated quarterback in the
conference, New England will go with Scott Zolak, making his first
playoff start in eight pro seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of knew what was going to happen,'' Zolak said, ``but
as far as the mindset of the team, they know who the quarterback is
and that's what we're going to rally around.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against Zolak, but Bledsoe's absence is a terrible blow
for the Patriots, who might not be able to exploit a mediocre
Jaguar defense. Jacksonville will probably stack the line of
scrimmage with seven or eight men for much of the game, trying to
stop the rookie running back Robert Edwards and daring Zolak to
beat them.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars have their own problems at quarterback. Mark Brunell
has practiced all week despite a troubling high ankle sprain and
will probably start. The question is: how long will Brunell be able
to go?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll watch him closely as the game goes on,'' said Coach Tom
Coughlin.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of attention for the Miami-Buffalo game will also be
on the quarterbacks. The ``S'' word _ as in short, as in 5 feet 9
inches tall _ has come up again in relation to Buffalo's Doug
Flutie, perhaps the best story in the league this year.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie and Miami Coach Jimmy Johnson do not have a lot of love
for each other because Flutie feels that Johnson has taken some
cheap shots at him over the years regarding his height. Now
Dolphins cornerback Sam Madison has poked fun at Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie this week said there was no way Miami cornerbacks could
cover Buffalo's wide receivers, in particular Eric Moulds, who has
been explosive this season.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie also said Madison and the other starting corner, Terrell
Buckley, do a lot of clutching and grabbing while in coverage but
are rarely called for pass interference. The Dolphins have the
sixth-ranked pass defense, and Madison and Buckley combined have 16
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the week, Flutie's words were posted on a bulletin
board in Miami's locker room. Madison seemed particularly perturbed
by the assertion that Miami defensive backs could not cover Buffalo
receivers with single coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's 5-foot-5 and can't see over the line unless he
scrambles, that does make me mad for him to say something like
that,'' Madison said. ``That really touched a nerve with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to get him out of the pocket,'' Madison added,
``because he's too short to see over the defensive line. We're
going to be ready for that and get him on the ground and shove some
Flutie Flakes down his throat.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie did not back down from his comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just having fun with the guys,'' he said. ``I feel we
have talented receivers and, I mean, you always look in your reads
to go to the guy, try to find the guy that is matched up one-on-one
who doesn't have help over the top, who doesn't have inside help,
you try to find those matchups. And I feel very confident that we
have quality receivers and they can get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie was asked if he realized that his comments would probably
irk the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``What, are they going to play harder?'' Flutie responded. ``I
think if that makes someone play harder, then why didn't they play
that way last week or the week before? It is playoff time. I hope
you can play as hard as you can possibly play.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley was amused by Madison's anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks at it as an insult, but being a veteran, I'm going to
wait until I get out there Saturday,'' Buckley said. ``You don't
want to spend your energy getting mad now, or you might be tired by
the time the game begins.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami quarterback Dan Marino has stayed out of the fray because
he has more important things to worry about, like beating the Bills
in the postseason. Marino is 0-3 against Buffalo in the playoffs,
and it's easy to understand by the numbers. Marino has completed
only 49.4 percent of his passes against the Bills in the playoffs
and has a quarterback rating of 64.1. He has also thrown for six
touchdowns and has had seven interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Marino has struggled is because the all-pro defensive
end Bruce Smith gets fired up to play him and does well against the
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wouldn't be extra motivated against Marino?'' Smith said.
``He's a great player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
