A4852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-DEATH-PENALTY-RU     01-01 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DEATH-PENALTY-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CURIOUS RULINGS ON CAPITAL PUNISHMENT  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Jan. 2:
</P>
<P>
   In a sound ruling last week, New York state's highest court
struck down most of the plea-bargaining provisions of the state's
four-year-old death penalty statute. These provisions, the Court of
Appeals found, unconstitutionally penalized defendants in capital
cases for exercising their Sixth Amendment right to a jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was a portion of the statute that specifically
prohibited the death penalty whenever the defendant in a capital
case reached a plea agreement. That gave New York the dubious
distinction of being the only death penalty state with a law that
encouraged defendants to plead guilty rather than risk a death
sentence by going to trial.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling will not necessarily block plea negotiations. The
main immediate impact will be to push those negotiations into the
early phase of the case, before the prosecution files notice of its
intention to seek the death penalty. That makes all the more
troubling the court's other death-penalty-related action last week,
slashing the compensation for assigned counsel in capital cases,
with the deepest cuts reserved for work done in the pre-death
notice phase.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the lead counsel in capital cases will be paid $100
an hour before the prosecution decides to seek the death penalty,
compared with $175 now. Assisting lawyers will also be paid
considerably less.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Judge Judith Kaye and her colleagues may have succumbed to
death penalty politics. Gov. George Pataki has called the original
fees ``exorbitant.'' But the court should have been more concerned
by the warnings of New York bar leaders that the new fee schedule
could make it difficult to attract qualified counsel. This has
happened in other death penalty states that have skimped on fees.
The capital case fees that offended the governor were lower than
the fees the state regularly pays private lawyers for work on bond
issues and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the ruling was curious. Just a few days after a
constitutional ruling elevating the importance of early work in a
capital case, the court chose to pay lawyers less for doing that
work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 2049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
