<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: RIDING HORSEBACK IN MONTANA TO FISH FOR TROUT
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GREG THOMAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAILEY, Idaho _ With temperatures seasonably wintry out here, it
seems as good a time as any to unhook and release a fish story
about a particularly satisfying adventure in Montana trout country.
At the least, it will help address my cabin fever.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer I ventured on horseback into the
grizzly-bear-riddled Bob Marshall Wilderness in northwest Montana
with Jack and Karen Hooker, who run Whitetail Outfitters in the
village of Ovando. I wanted to concentrate on the Bob Marshall
Wilderness trout, cutthroats that range up to 20 inches and seem
particularly eager to inhale any dry fly cast in their direction.
</P>
<P>
   But my horse, Snip, didn't help matters. Snip shook my saddle
bag loose during the first two miles of trail riding. I dismounted,
shored up loose ties and found myself displaced to the back of the
pack.
</P>
<P>
   Late on the second day of our five-day trip, with my buttocks
feeling saddle sore and screaming revolt, we reached Basin Creek,
which drains into the South Fork Flathead River. There, I found
myself wading knee-deep in crystal-clear water on one of the most
remote fly-fishing waters in North America, 32 miles deep in the
wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Basin Creek and the South Fork Flathead's waters are a mix of
long, shallow runs highlighted by deep, alluring pools. The water
takes on an aqua-green color and shimmers beautifully in the
morning and evening light.
</P>
<P>
   Peering into the clear currents, you can spot trout finning at
the bottom in 10-foot-deep pools, hovering above the rocks as if
suspended in space. Most of those fish have never seen an
artificial fly and likely never will.
</P>
<P>
   Trout aren't the only attraction. Lots of bears, both blacks and
grizzlies, feed along the river's gravel bars. Elk, moose, mountain
goats and even some bighorn sheep feed on the higher slopes. Mule
deer, nearly as tame as a dog or cat, wander into camp in the
mornings and evenings, feeding on lush green meadow grass.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the South Fork Flathead and to view its varied
wildlife, an angler has two options: hike in on foot, under full
burden of a heavy backpack, or ride on the back of a horse with a
packstring along to carry food and gear. My suggestion, having
hiked into wilderness areas in the past, losing gallons of sweat in
the process, is this: take the horse.
</P>
<P>
   Each day during our rides, which ranged from 8 to 18 miles, we
wandered through dense stands of lodgepole pine trees, ancient,
old-growth forests that held a cathedral quality. In the afternoons
we lounged in wonderful little glades and meadows, eating our
lunch, bartering with each other for extra candy bars, soaking in
the healing summer sun, wandering to small, spring-fed streams that
run as clear and tasty as any water in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Life was laid-back and I loved it, but it was the fish that I
was after. And I found them.
</P>
<P>
   The fishing was easy; when I placed a dry fly over any of the
deep pools, little, eager cutthroats would fire up from the bottom
to inhale any offering without inspection. After pursuing trout on
challenging tailwaters and spring creeks for 11 years, those
wilderness trout were a welcome treat. During the trip, I caught
numerous native west-slope cutthroat on large, bushy dry flies that
floated like corks.
</P>
<P>
   One particular evening, on Basin Creek, I wandered away from our
group and found the mother of all trout holes. The surface was
covered with small olive mayflies and it was frothing with rising
fish.
</P>
<P>
   From that hole, in maybe an hour, I caught about 20 trout, most
rating 9 inches, with a couple of monsters that stretched 16 inches
or more. Each native cutthroat was beautiful, their bellies the
color of orange peels, their gill plates splashed a rosy red, and
their chins streaked with the red slashes from which they gain
their name.
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone want to fish for anything else? Could a man
survive a winter in the wilderness? I was about ready to answer
that question when rain started pelting my face. Instead of braving
the weather, I returned to camp, where a savory slab of chicken,
along with peas, hot rolls and peach cobbler, waited.
</P>
<P>
   Don't hike! Take the horse!
</P>
<P>
   While fishing the South Fork Flathead and its tributary streams
was memorable, if not truly outstanding, perhaps the best part of
the trip was listening to Jack Hooker's stories. If you had been
nestled around the Danaher Valley horse camp last August, staring
contentedly into a large bonfire, you would have heard, among other
entertaining and unedited narratives, many tales about grizzly
bears.
</P>
<P>
   That was fine, engaging conversation for most of our group.
However, one member, Brad, couldn't stand it. He'd seen ``Night of
the Grizzlies'' on the big screen. He'd read gruesome tales about
grizzlies pulling helpless campers from their sleeping bags. His
fear of grizzlies was deeply imbedded and it showed. When Jack told
his stories, Brad's eyes opened proportionately wider and his jaw
dropped lower, his skin turning paler with each word. By the end of
the trip, a crackle from the bonfire might send Brad dashing for
the nearest tree.
</P>
<P>
   On the last day of our scheduled pack trip, we loaded horses one
final time and wandered away from the South Fork Flathead and its
cutthroat trout.
</P>
<P>
   Then and there, I decided to extend my stay and enjoy an extra
night in the wilderness on one of western Montana's most remarkable
rivers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
