<HEADLINE>
MUCKLER GETS TOUGH OVER TOUGH GUYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Colo.)  (mk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Late last season, shortly after he became coach of
the Rangers, John Muckler ignited a shouting match with coach Mike
Milbury of the Islanders after Milbury called a timeout with a big
lead late in a game. The confrontation took place with both men
behind their respective benches. Late Thursday night, Muckler
verbally confronted another counterpart, Bob Hartley, the rookie
coach of the Colorado Avalanche. It happened as both teams and
their coaches crossed the ice after the final buzzer in a 6-3
Rangers victory.
</P>
<P>
   Muckler was angry that Hartley played Scott Parker and Jeff
Odgers, two of his tough guys, against Wayne Gretzky's line late in
the game. ``It was a minor-league move,'' Muckler said of Hartley's
choice of personnel. ``I just took it as a cheap shot, which it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Muckler said Parker made gratuitous contact with Gretzky, who
had two assists. Asked if he had punched Hartley, Muckler said he
had not. But the two appeared to come very close to physical
contact before players and officials got between them.
</P>
<P>
   Hartley at first joked that Muckler was wishing him a happy new
year. In a more serious vein, Hartley said he had been trying to
give ice time to some players who rarely get it. Earlier in the
game, Parker had fought Darren Langdon of the Rangers and Odgers
had fought Rumun Ndur of the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why double-shift Petr Forsberg instead of giving a kid some
time?'' Hartley said, referring to his best player.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Brown, a spokesman for the National Hockey League, said
the league had nothing to announce regarding the incident and that
he did not know as of late Friday if it would be investigated by
league headquarters. Speaking in general terms, Brown said that
some incidents of this nature are penalized through fines, not
suspensions, and that the fines are not announced.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the second for the Rangers in three games of a
four-game road trip that began in Carolina last Saturday and will
end on Saturday night with a visit to the Blues, weather
permitting. The Rangers traveled here Friday from Denver and the
Blues were coming from Nashville, Tenn., despite daunting weather
conditions. Snow, fog, sleet and freezing rain caused many flights
to St. Louis to be canceled. The Rangers arrived several hours late
and called off plans to practice here in the late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The scorers for the Rangers on Thursday were Mike Knuble,
Mathieu Schneider, Petr Nedved, Marc Savard, John MacLean and Adam
Graves. Schneider, Nedved and Graves scored on the power play, and
Nedved's came with a two-man advantage. Each team scored on its
first shot of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Muckler juggled his lines somewhat, switching the centers Savard
and Gretzky. Savard skated with MacLean and Kevin Stevens, while
Gretzky was between Graves and Todd Harvey. Several Rangers said
they were bolstered by a morning meeting at which Muckler and the
team captain, Brian Leetch, spoke out.
</P>
<P>
   Graves, who leads the Rangers with 16 goals, said: ``Obviously
there were some things to be said, and Brian hit the nail on the
butt. When he speaks, everyone listens, because it comes not only
with intelligence, but from the heart. He was right on the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky called the meeting ``positive and kind of upbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider said, ``We talked about relaxing and trying to be more
creative and not worrying about making mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Richter, who returned as starting goalie after Dan Cloutier
filled in for him in Phoenix, said Muckler's words also were
important. ``With all the traveling and a lot of fatigue, it's easy
to get off track,'' Richter said. ``Your mind can wander. Muck is
very good about reminding us that every game is critical. If you
don't say it right, it can end up falling on deaf ears, but Muck
keeps the attention of the players. He lets you know what he
expects and what's going to happen if it doesn't take place.''
</P>
<P>
   Muckler said he was concerned about the team's ``fragile''
confidence after it lost 3-1 in Phoenix on Wednesday night. ``We
had an exceptionally good meeting,'' Muckler said. ``Some of the
players were maybe losing confidence in themselves, questioning
themselves.'' The defeat in Phoenix, Muckler said, was ``the rock
bottom,'' and he called it ``a game we could have won and should
have won.''
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, the Rangers faced a Coyotes team playing without the
forwards Jeremy Roenick and Keith Tkachuk, both of whom are
injured. In Denver, the Avalanche was without the center Joe Sakic
and the goalie Patrick Roy, both of whom were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' confidence and spirits seemed high after Thursday's
game. In the dressing room, the players watched on television and
some counted along as the screen showed the ball dropping in Times
Square to signal the new year. ``1999!'' shouted MacLean, 34 years
old, ``and I'm still playing!''
</P>
<P>
   Langdon, who is from Newfoundland, advised everyone that it had
already been a new year for 30 minutes in Newfoundland because of
its peculiar time zone, east of the East Coast. It's an avant garde
kind of place, that Newfoundland, ahead of the times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
