<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GETTING SCHOOL CONSTRUCTION RIGHT 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Jan. 2:
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Board of Education's new report on its 1,100
schools consists of 71,000 pages of disheartening news. Conditions
are still generally poor, and in the best-case scenario they will
only be ``fair'' after five more years of intensive effort.
</P>
<P>
   Many schools are also overcrowded, and the city will not be able
to take advantage of new state aid for smaller classes and
pre-kindergarten programs unless it gets more classroom space.
</P>
<P>
   The board is thus proposing a five-year, $11 billion rebuilding
plan. Putting that package together will require help from the
city, state and national governments. One huge barrier is
dissatisfaction with the School Construction Authority's record of
delays and shoddy construction.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report on the construction authority's work on Public
School 131 in Brooklyn, where falling bricks killed a 16-year-old
girl, is disturbing. The general contractor, who failed to
construct protective sidewalk sheds or use even the most basic
safety precautions, was prequalified for the job under a system so
meaningless that no applicant was ever rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The project officer was married to the top aide to Gov. George
Pataki's appointee to the construction authority's board of
trustees. An official inquiry found that although the officer
behaved erratically and tolerated unprofessional behavior by the
workers, his supervisors rated his performance as ``good.''
</P>
<P>
   The SCA is run by three trustees, appointed by the governor,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew. Giuliani
argues that it would perform better if he had full control. The
Democrats in Albany and the teachers' union want trustees of their
own. But the last thing the construction authority needs is a
diversionary power struggle. Despite its terrible performance at PS
131, the authority may actually be figuring out how to do its job.
Milo Riverso, the latest chief executive, is getting good grades
for completing projects more quickly. The caliber of the
professional workers seems to be improving.
</P>
<P>
   What the SCA most needs is better procedures for screening
contractors and more qualified project officers with smaller work
loads. Riverso says that these are his goals. The Legislature can
help by changing the burdensome rules it has imposed on the
authority, like the requirement that much of the building design be
done in-house rather than by outside contractors. The lawmakers
must also renew the authority's exemption to the ridiculous Wicks
law, which requires separate contractors for different pieces of
each public construction project.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has asked the Legislature to transfer his power to
appoint a trustee to Giuliani, an unusual offer to relinquish
authority. The governor's eagerness to get out of the construction
authority may have something to do with the fact that there is a
disturbing amount of evidence connecting the PS 131 tragedy to the
patronage needs of members of the Conservative Party, with which
the governor is aligned. But rather than changing the law, Pataki
can cede his powers simply by appointing a new trustee of
Giuliani's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Giuliani will have controlling authority, since he
can count on Crew. This page has supported his argument that
government works best when there are clear lines of responsibility.
His task now is to grasp those lines, tell the Legislature and
public what practical internal changes the SCA needs to operate
efficiently, and then direct his attention to making sure it has
the resources and the will to do things right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 2056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
