<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4859 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-SEMINOLES-     01-01 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-SEMINOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BACKUP SOARS WITH AN EGO AS BIG AS THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ It is the red hair shorn close that earned him
the nickname Rooster. But a cocky strut was there long before
Marcus Outzen wandered onto the field during Florida State's 10th
game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It was there last spring when the quarterback, bummed that his
name was listed near the bottom of the Seminoles' depth chart,
busted into Bobby Bowden's office for an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   He was a red-shirt sophomore, an option quarterback in high
school, whom Bowden brought to Tallahassee, frankly, to be a
backup. The kid was talking transfer. The coach was taken aback.
</P>
<P>
   Outzen was neither a super talent, nor had he waited his turn as
better Seminole quarterbacks had done in the past. The coach
conceded that yes, Dan Kendra and Chris Weinke, were ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I told him to stay around, to give spring practice his
best effort. Then, we'll talk transfer. You never know what's going
to happen,'' Bowden told him.
</P>
<P>
   What happened was Kendra injured his knee out in Florida State's
spring game, underwent surgery and ceded the job to Weinke. While
Weinke, a 26-year-old former baseball minor-leaguer, ran off an 8-1
record, Outzen watched as his backup. When Weinke suffered a
herniated disk in his neck in the first half against Virginia, the
20-year-old Outzen suddenly became the most unlikely quarterback to
play for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   He will lead No. 2 Florida State (11-1) against top-ranked
Tennessee (12-0) here Monday night at the Fiesta Bowl. He has gone
from third-team to title dream only eight months after having
enough cheek to challenge a coach who won the national championship
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't used to sitting on the bench. No one here is used to
sitting on the bench,'' Outzen said, not seeing anything at all
wrong with the tete-a-tete between him and Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the realist, Bowden says he is worried. He lost six years,
10 starts and a howitzer for an arm at quarterback when Weinke went
down. The kid he convinced to stay around? He has completed 36
passes and started two games, but besides liking Outzen's
``swagger,'' Bowden says, dadgummit, he doesn't know what he has
behind center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a blue-collar quarterback,'' said Bowden, comparing him
to former National Football League yeomen Billy Kilmer and Joe
Kapp. ``His ball wobbles. It flutters, but it gets there.''
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback, however, is not worried. For Christmas, he
bought his father, Eric, the Fiesta Bowl poster, which declared
Tennessee and Florida State were playing for the inaugural Bowl
Championship Series national championship. He promised him he was
going to win it. He knows there is little on his abbreviated
resume, but he tries to crow about what he can.
</P>
<P>
   Outzen is a business communications major who is bright enough
to accumulate a 3.4 grade-point average, the highest on the team,
and he is astute enough to hone his message. He likes talking about
the Florida game, only his second career start and it was against
the Seminoles' most-hated rival. He was 13 of 22 for 167 passing
yards and threw his first collegiate touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, nothing against Tennessee, but down where we are in
Florida, playing the Gators is a championship in itself. I went
into it with the goal of staying calm, and I did,'' he said of the
17 unanswered points he engineered to beat Florida, 23-12, a feat
more remarkable because he had two first-half fumbles, one in the
end zone for a safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I've had a whole month or practicing with the first
team,'' Outzen said. ``Our game plan is broader. Never in a million
years did I think that I'd be in a game like this. But anyone would
be wrong to believe I don't know what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   His all-American wide receiver, Peter Warrick, believes in the
Rooster. Back in the summer, Weinke organized throwing drills for
the quarterbacks and receivers. Warrick says a different Outzen was
there each day. ``He was more quiet. Just there putting his work
in,'' Warrick said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the second half of the Florida game that the
receiver saw what he believes was the birth of a championship
quarterback. Outzen had just picked up a third and long on a
hard-nosed scramble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got nailed, really hit and he came back to the huddle
pumped up and yelled `Come on, fellas, let's go down and . . .' you
know,'' Warrick said, letting a smile tip off his quarterback's
colorful language, ``he said something real fired up. It was
something Chris would have done. And from then on, I knew we'd be
all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden might have thought he was getting a future backup when
Outzen came out of Fort Walton Beach (Fla.) High School, but Mickey
Andrews, the Seminoles' defensive coordinator who recruited him,
knew better. He watched Outzen, 6 feet 2 inches and 220 pounds, run
the option all the way to the state championship. Outzen was quick,
overpowering and, tough enough to play on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strong safety,'' Andrews said, admitting that in the back of
his mind he had hoped to convert him.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, the Seminole offense has a fledgling quarterback
leading it into the second-most important game in its history. In a
role reversal from the summer workouts, Weinke is here in the
shadows on the sidelines, his season done. His 19 touchdowns and
2,487 yards started Florida State's title run. How does he feel
about Outzen finishing it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here as a supporter. He knows I'm five yards behind him
every day to help him with any questions he has,'' Weinke said.
</P>
<P>
   Has Outzen asked any? The fallen quarterback smiles sheepishly.
``Not one,'' Weinke said. ``He's a really confident guy.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
