<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS' DEFENSE MEETS ITS GOALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mississippi State coach Jackie Sherrill said he felt
his team needed to score at least 28 points to keep up with the
high-powered Texas offense in the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs didn't come close.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Texas defense proved just as significant as Ricky
Williams' running and Major Applewhite's passing in the Longhorns'
38-11 victory against the Bulldogs yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they expected our defense to be as tough as it
was,'' Texas linebacker Dusty Renfro said. ``All week long we had
to listen to how good their offense was and how good their defense
was. We knew we had to outplay their defense and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   For extra inspiration, Renfro wore No. 60 yesterday instead of
his usual 46. The switch was in honor of Mike Campbell, the former
assistant under Darrell Royal who designed the defenses that helped
the Longhorns win national championships in 1963 and 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell died in June, and Renfro wanted the spirit of those
great defenses to carry the Longhorns yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we accomplished that,'' Renfro said.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Aaron Babino, who was named the defensive player of
the game, said, ``Our goal was to shut them down under 17 points,
and we did that. We just got out there and got after them.''
</P>
<P>
   Babino, who stepped into the Longhorns' starting lineup late in
the season when Anthony Hicks went down with a knee injury, led the
Longhorns with nine tackles, including three for losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns, using a variety of blitzes, held the Bulldogs to
87 yards rushing while Mississippi State quarterbacks Wayne Madkin
and Matt Wyatt were a combined 16-for-40 passing for 205 yards.
They were sacked three times, and Madkin threw an interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept pounding and pounding and pounding,'' Babino
said. ``We knew eventually they would give up.''
</P>
<P>
   The defensive performance was the latest indication of the
improvement the Longhorns have shown since giving up 49 points to
UCLA and 48 to Kansas State on consecutive Saturdays in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the season we were using a new defense, and there
were new things we had to adjust to,'' Babino said. ``One or two
people would blow an assignment on every play, and you can't have
that. We corrected that because the coaches stressed guys who make
mistakes wouldn't play. Now we have our assignments down, and
things are working out.''
</P>
<P>
   They've worked out to the point where the Longhorns believe
their defense will be a significant factor in a serious challenge
for a national title next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it,'' Babino said. ``I feel with our defense,
next year we'll be able to compete with anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
