<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-YACHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AUSTRALIA, A TRIBUTE TO LOST SAILORS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOBART, Australia _ A thousand yachtsmen and an estimated 4,000
more visitors and summer tourists gathered here at Constitution
Dock Friday afternoon to pray for those affected so traumatically
when a fierce storm ripped apart the fleet in the 54th
Sydney-to-Hobart yacht race.
</P>
<P>
   As the families and fellow crew members of the six lost sailors
cast a red rose and a bed of daisies into the still waters, the
muted bells of St. David's Cathedral tolled their own tribute, and
many wept as they remembered other seamen who had perished in
previous storms.
</P>
<P>
   For 54 years, Constitution Dock in this capital city of the
island state of Tasmania has been a haven and temporary home for
thousands of yachtsmen and women who have competed in the annual
ocean race.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, with a gentle sea breeze blowing up the Derwent River on
a warm and sunny afternoon, Monsignor Phillip Green, chaplain of
the Royal Yacht Club of Tasmania, delivered the ``Yachties
Farewell.'' It was not only a paean to the lost sailors _ the
British Olympic Star Class sailor Glyn Charles from the Sword of
Orion; Bruce Guy and Phil Skeggs on Business Post Naiad; and Jim
Lawler, Mike Bannister and John Dean, swept off the veteran cutter
Winston Churchill _ but to the enduring affection between Hobart
and the sport of yacht racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We who live by the sea and depend on it,'' said Green,
speaking from a table draped by a green and gold sail, ``know, like
the yachties, its beauty, but also its power.''
</P>
<P>
   In a eulogy, Commodore Hugo van Kretschmar of the Cruising Yacht
Club of Australia, the club that has organized and conducted the
Sydney-to-Hobart race every Christmas since 1945, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We will miss you; we will remember you always; we will learn
from the tragic circumstances of your passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``May the everlasting voyage you have now embarked on be blessed
with calm seas and gentle breezes. May you never have to reef or
change a headsail in the night. May your bunk always be warm and
dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the international fleet of 115 yachts that set sail from
Sydney Dec. 26, only 44 completed the 725-mile course. Seventy-one
boats retired, many seeking shelter before encountering the worst
of the storm. Seven yachts were abandoned, and 55 sailors were
saved in the largest search-and-rescue operation in the history of
an Australian ocean yacht race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
