<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT OIL COMPANIES SUFFER DURING WEAK MARKET
</P>
<P>
   Independent oil producers in the United States and the small
companies that provide services to them have been hurt by low
prices and foreign competition more than giants such as Exxon and
Mobil have. Enshrined in fable for his enterprise and daring, the
oilman in jeans and boots is giving way to the oilman in a suit.
</P>
<P>
   Except for huge oilfields far offshore or in Alaska's wilds,
major oil companies consider most of the United States too
expensive or played out to bother with.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, the contract drillers and oil-service
companies, which do everything from making drill bits to flying the
helicopters used to transport offshore workers, are expected to
post their second consecutive quarter of falling earnings. As oil
prices languish at the lowest levels in more than a decade,
contractors are taking rigs out of service as rents slide.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA READIES DEBT PLAN
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government will soon announce how it plans to cover
the debts of the nation's second-biggest financial company, which
it closed in October, and the news for foreign bankers is likely to
be bad. China closed the financial arm of the company, Guangdong
International Trust and Investment Corp., because it could not
repay more than $2 billion of foreign debt. All told, GITIC, as the
company is known, owes an estimated $10 billion to foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
   PREPARING FOR EURO'S MARKET DEBUT
</P>
<P>
   One day after 11 European countries christened the euro as their
new currency, financial institutions across the Continent began the
enormous job of reprogramming their electronic networks before
markets reopened for business Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   SURGE IN HONG KONG REAL ESTATE
</P>
<P>
   People in Hong Kong, from first-time buyers to the big
development companies, have been trying to decide whether the
strong housing sales of November were a sign that the worst
recession in a generation was nearly over, or whether the market
only found a false bottom and would continue to drop if the economy
kept contracting. Sales have been driven, in part, by falling
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   INSURERS EXPECT SMALL GAINS
</P>
<P>
   The nation's property and casualty insurers are expected to
report slim profit gains for the fourth quarter because competition
has kept a lid on premiums. The group, including Allstate, CNA
Financial and St. Paul Cos., is expected to report an average
earnings increase of only 1 percent for the quarter, far below the
28 percent gain for all of 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
