<HEADLINE>
LACK OF PASSING GAME SPELLED TROUBLE FOR MISSISSIPPI STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mississippi State running back James Johnson gave his
team 105 yards in the first half, and he provided some hope for a
Bulldogs rally yesterday in the Southwestern Bell Cotton Bowl
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   When the Texas defense figured out how to stop him however,
Mississippi State's day was over, 38-11.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had 1 yard in the third quarter, and his team was forced
to throw in an attempt to trim a 35-point deficit.
</P>
<P>
   After a first half of outgaining Texas running back Ricky
Williams, Johnson could only watch as Williams got stronger en
route to 203 yards rushing, 45 yards receiving and one Heisman
Trophy pose.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson finished with 22 carries and 112 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half, you look at Ricky and you look at James,
you saw two very good backs on the field,'' Mississippi State coach
Jackie Sherrill said. ``In the first half, we did quite well at
certain things. But when you're not throwing the football, you're
not going to run it as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the performance by Johnson in the first half, the
Bulldogs dug a 14-3 hole.
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill pulled starting quarterback Wayne Madkin late in the
second quarter after the redshirt freshman went 3 of 12 with one
interception and 29 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Madkin was back in to start the third quarter, but the offensive
troubles grew.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State's first two drives of the second half went
three plays and a punt. The Bulldogs' third possession included two
sacks and a punt after only four plays.
</P>
<P>
   Texas scored three touchdowns to make it 24-3 with 6:30 left in
the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame it all on the passing game, but that certainly
had a lot to do with it,'' Mississippi State center Eric Allen
said. ``Texas did a good job in the third quarter of making their
reads and getting to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Buried at their own 19-yard line in the closing seconds of the
third quarter, Mississippi State called Johnson's number on
fourth-and-1.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson ran into Texas senior linebacker Dusty Renfro behind he
line of scrimmage for a 1-yard loss. Texas put the game away, 38-3,
one play later on an 18-yard pass from Major Applewhite to Kwame
Cavil.
</P>
<P>
   Renfro was wearing No. 60 in honor of former Texas defensive
coach Mike Campbell, who died on June 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could feel the spirit moving through our defense,'' Renfro
said. ``We wanted to show people that Texas not only has a great
offense, but a great defense, too. We knew that running the ball is
the strength of their team. We wanted to take that away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
