<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-DRUGS-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS HOPE FOR ANOTHER VIAGRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The successful introduction last year of Pfizer Inc.'s Viagra,
the impotence pill, delivered huge returns to investors who bought
shares in the company. The windfall _ Pfizer's stock zoomed about
69 percent in the year _ has encouraged investors to study the
current pipelines of the world's largest pharmaceutical companies,
hoping to spot the next boom drug.
</P>
<P>
   They, as well as analysts, are betting that at least one of the
medications scheduled for introduction this year will also produce
impressive gains.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting the next blockbuster drug is never easy, because
pharmaceutical executives are loath to forecast the sales of their
wares. But some compounds clearly have a better chance than others
of achieving $1 billion in annual sales, the benchmark for a
blockbuster drug.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agree that top-selling drugs share two traits: They
have to be prescribed by more than one type of doctor, ideally a
general practitioner and a specialist, and treat a condition that
is sorely lacking in new remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Viagra prescribed by several types of doctors,
including urologists and psychiatrists, but it was offered in pill
form, making it a popular alternative to the invasive shots of
other impotence medications.
</P>
<P>
   That formula for a winning drug should work this year as well,
but with one major twist. Many of last year's hot new remedies _
Viagra and Detrol, Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn Inc.'s pill for incontinence
_ were so-called lifestyle drugs, designed to relieve afflictions
that damage self-esteem. This year's top-selling new medications
are expected to treat several chronic or life-threatening
conditions, including diabetes and organ-transplant rejection.
</P>
<P>
   The two most anticipated introductions this year are Monsanto
Co.'s Celebrex, which Pfizer is helping to market, and Vioxx by
Merck &AMP; Co. Both drugs will treat the pain and inflammation of
arthritis and are expected to be free of the gastrointestinal side
effects of other medications.
</P>
<P>
   This market is projected to be enormous, rivaling the $7.4
billion in anti-depressant sales. About 13,000 Americans take
nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs each year, according to Merck.
Yet these drugs are not always safe; according to arthritis experts
at Stanford University, they cause 20,000 hospitalizations and
2,600 deaths each year.
</P>
<P>
   While the first product to market usually gets the largest
market share _ in this case, that will most likely be Celebrex _
both drugs are expected to record strong sales. Analysts predict
that Celebrex will have $3 billion in annual sales and Vioxx $2
billion by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peak sales of these drugs may not happen quickly,'' said
Neil Sweig, a pharmaceuticals analyst with Southeast Research
Partners. ``It could take four to five years after the drugs are
introduced in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   As a supplement to the search for blockbusters, and in an effort
to maintain annual earnings gains of 16 percent or more, many
pharmaceutical companies are introducing drugs for markets that
have been profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the industry's cash machines are ulcer drugs,
which can easily bring in annual sales of $1.5 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products Corp. and Johnson &AMP; Johnson are expected
to roll out their respective ulcer drugs, Protonix and Aciphex.
Even though the ulcer market already has several players, including
Astra AB's Prilosec, with $2.3 billion in annual sales, both new
entrants are expected to be very successful. Analysts expect
Protonix to bring in an annual $400 million in 2002, when Aciphex
is expected to have sales of $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   The market for diabetes drugs, which has long been competitive,
should be vicious by the end of the year. SmithKline Beecham PLC is
expected to release Avandia, a drug that may siphon sales from the
three leading medications, Glucophage by Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.,
Glucotrol XL by Pfizer and Warner-Lambert Co.'s Rezulin.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect that Avandia will have annual sales of $755
million and that the sum could be higher if patients decided to
switch from the leading medications.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo Wellcome PLC will introduce Ziagen to treat HIV infection.
Analysts expect the drug to have $450 million in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products is set to introduce Rapamune for
organ-transplant rejection, a use that should generate some $750
million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Schering-Plough Corp. and Zonagen, a tiny Texas biotechnology
company, are expected to begin marketing Vasomax, a competitor to
Pfizer's Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Viagra, which analysts predict will have $1 billion in
sales during its first year on the market, Vasomax is not expected
to surpass $500 million in annual sales during its first four years
on the market. But it may usher in this year's crop of drugs to
address everything from age spots to facial hair on women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really just beginning this phase of lifestyle drugs,''
said Viren Mehta, a partner at Mehta Partners, a biopharmaceutical
investment research company in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 2105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4871 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     01-01 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO HANDLE SNAKE, COWBOYS MUST ALSO SHINE ON OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jake Plummer deserved better. But a fair shake for the Snake
this week was apparently too much to ask, at least around here.
</P>
<P>
   In the retelling of Plummer's magical moment of November against
the Cowboys, there was once again a media memory lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Nine-Toed Deion was at cornerback that day in Tempe _ not
for the entire second half, but for the Cardinals' final two
drives. Plummer rang up nearly 150 yards passing on those two
possessions, which included one touchdown, then a journey to the
5-yard line in the waning seconds.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Kevin Smith's end-zone play is still up for loud
debate, at least in the desert precincts.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Snake's miracle rally (after Arizona was down,
28-0), came up short, Plummer's performance certainly didn't. And
it shouldn't be cheapened by inaccurate local information that Jake
did it without having to deal with Deion.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Deion also started for the Cowboys the next week
against Seattle, and in the second quarter limped off the field
looking like a guy who had just stepped on a landmine. Nine-Toed
has not been seen in action since.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, call it justice for Plummer that today's wild-card
round playoff game is against the Cowboys. There is no question he
has some unfinished business from November, and since it's now a
sudden-elimination postseason format, Plummer will cause
uncomfortable moments for the local team and the local fans at
Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would prefer,'' a smiling Cowboys defensive coordinator Dave
Campo said, ``that the outcome doesn't depend on stopping him for
one last drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Those kind of compliments are usually reserved for an
Elway-type, but Plummer is a young quarterback with a proven resume
for manufacturing last-second victories.
</P>
<P>
   How Plummer goes today, so goes the outcome. He is the focal
point for the Cardinals, making their first playoff appearance in
16 seasons. He is obviously the focal point for the Cowboys, who
missed the playoffs last season. To a Jerry Jones, that seemed like
a 16-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom on Plummer brings us to the usual football
tune about the best defense being a dominant offense. Let there
also be no argument on that count _ the less Plummer is on the
field, the better off the Cowboys. How sensible.
</P>
<P>
   But until more evidence is available, the Cowboys' offense
cannot be trusted to provide the clock management that chains
Plummer to the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   In the entire month of December, exactly one quarter of
high-octane offense has been on display, and that was last weekend
against Washington. If that positive trend expands this afternoon,
the Cowboys will win. If not, they could still win the hard way,
meaning a stout defensive performance. In fact, the December
reading on the Cowboys shows the defense is much more likely to
give a good account today, as opposed to the offense.
</P>
<P>
   This can be said even though pressure on opposing QBs is almost
nil, containment of scramblers like Plummer doesn't exist, and
coverage of Plummer's receivers is questionable since it will not
be determined until game time whether Deion will sit yet another
one out
</P>
<P>
   But with a reworked secondary, and with Campo using the normal
assortment of smoke and mirrors, the defense shut down hot passing
games in two of the regular season's final three games _ Kansas
City and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Mathis and Kevin Smith have settled in at cornerback,
while Campo has a better assortment of nickel-coverage defenders
than the last time Plummer faced the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   It is a secondary that lives on the edge with no pass rush ``but
we now know who we are defensively,'' said Campo, ``and without
Deion we've managed to move on and establish some continuity.''
</P>
<P>
   At times against Plummer in November, the Cowboys had to use
Kenny Wheaton and Charlie Williams at the corners. Deion and Kevin
Smith were injured, and Mathis didn't suit up for the game due to a
broken arm. In the following games against Seattle and Minnesota,
the cornerback combos even included Terry Billups, from the
practice squad, being teamed with Williams, who is a safety by
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overcoming adversity is part of it,'' shrugged Campo. ``But
where we are today is much better than it was there for a while
after we lost Deion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have had limited success running the ball, and if
that holds today, then Plummer is the warhead that must be defused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like pressure, containment and coverage,'' said Campo,
``but the most important is containment. On the perimeter,
\RPlummer\S does his most damage. Given the chance to be creative,
he will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Snake-handling is a postseason must today for the Cowboys. And
they have the bite-marks from November as a reminder. /
</P>
</TEXT>
