<SLUG> BC-NY-TIMESSQUARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEDATE MERRYMAKING IN TIMES SQUARE 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New Year's Eve here was a cold, crowded and _ at one
point _ smoky, but largely peaceful trial run for the
century-ending celebration planned for next year, according to
police officials, who arrested only a handful of the half-million
revelers who squeezed into Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The 5,000 police officers who patrolled the party _ one of the
largest police details in history _ made fewer arrests than the
year before, 23 versus 30, officials said. Most of those arrested
were people who took the spirit of celebration too far and were
charged with disorderly conduct, the police said, but there were
also two arrests for robbery and three for assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went super,'' said Lt. Stephen Biegel. ``The majority of
the crowd acted orderly and had a great time. It bodes well for
next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The most spectacular disruption of the night occurred as the
crowd filed home and confetti that had blown onto a rooftop of a
four-story building caught fire, sending flames and smoke into the
frigid night air at 12:42 a.m. They said the fire probably started
when someone in a nearby building dropped a cigarette onto the
confetti-covered roof.
</P>
<P>
   Despite public warnings, a number of people tried to bring the
bar with them to Times Square for the celebration; the police
issued 72 summonses to people with open containers of alcohol, a
jump from the 19 issued the year before. Alcohol or illegal drugs
were confiscated from an additional 140 people, the police said,
and 27 people were given summonses for possession of marijuana, up
one from the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Another discordant note in midtown was the stabbing of a hot dog
vendor, Sayed Hussein, 34, outside Pennsylvania Station as groups
of vendors vied for the business of revelers streaming in for the
train ride home. The police charged Felah Hussein, 20, a fellow
vendor who is not related to the victim, in the 3 a.m. assault. The
stabbing was one of a rash of violent incidents, including three
killings, that marred the new year before it was five hours old.
</P>
<P>
   Sharone Glenn, 17, the son of Nathaniel Boyd, a professional
boxing manager, was fatally shot in the head at 3:40 a.m. after a
dispute in the Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The two other slaying victims, both of whom were killed before
dawn, also were men under the age of 30. One man, who was not
identified by the police by Friday night, was found shot to death
in the Morrisania section of the Bronx. The second, identified as
Bromley Walcott, 21, was beaten with a brick during a fight at a
party in Laurelton, N.Y., in Queens County. He later died of his
injuries at Franklin Hospital Medical Center, in Valley Stream,
N.Y., the police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
