<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI-PATAKI RIFT STALLS HOUSING FOR MENTALLY-ILL HOMELESS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By MIKE WINERIP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Gov. George Pataki are at
odds over the second phase of a housing program for mentally ill
homeless people in the city, arguing over the scope of the program
and the size of the state's contribution.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has left plans to expand the program in limbo, with
neither city nor state officials willing to estimate when
construction might begin.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the program, known as ``New York/New York,''
has been widely credited with moving almost 4,000 mentally ill
people off the streets of the city. That phase began in 1990, when
Mario Cuomo was governor and David Dinkins was mayor, and provided
3,814 housing units. The state paid for two-thirds of the building
cost and the city the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration has proposed 1,350 units of housing
for the second phase, with the state underwriting 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, a strong proponent of the program, last year earmarked
$51 million for the city's share and asked Pataki to provide double
that amount _ $100 million _ for the state's share, the rate of
support Cuomo provided. That would have paid for 2,500 units. City
officials hoped the $40 million appropriated by the state last
spring would be the first installment of the state's contribution.
</P>
<P>
   But as negotiations have progressed, state officials have made
it clear they do not want to go beyond that $40 million, and the
city has reduced its request in recent months to 1,750 units from
2,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``For months, the city's been begging the state to help out
more,'' said James Brennan, a Democrat from Brooklyn who heads the
state Assembly's committee on mental health. ``But the state won't
budge.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Giuliani would say little publicly about Pataki, who
controls the state purse strings. But in off-the-record interviews,
they made it clear they were very discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neal Cohen, the city's mental health commissioner, would say
only that he hoped the two sides could work things out. ``We've
been playing catchup with decades of deinstitutionalization,'' he
said. ``We can't afford to set the clock back now.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials said the governor was concerned about
controlling social welfare spending. Roger Klingman, a spokesman
for the state Office of Mental Health, said that rather than
financing new housing programs, the governor had emphasized
``managing the beds we already have.'' He would not comment on the
talks except to say, ``We will continue to negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the nonprofit agencies that provide the housing for
the homeless complain that the Pataki administration is not
sufficiently interested in the mentally ill or the problems they
can cause on city streets. There has been a marked drop in
financing levels for such housing under Pataki statewide.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Pataki administration has provided no new
financing to build supervised housing for the mentally ill in the
last two years, and in its first two years of its term it
essentially finished projects Cuomo had started.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the money the state has appropriated in recent years
has gone toward rent subsidies that can be used in any apartment
building, providing housing for mentally ill people with the least
serious problems. The type of housing built under the first New
York/New York agreement includes counselors who provide 24-hour
supervision, including monitoring whether residents take their
medication.
</P>
<P>
   The rent subsidy program costs the state $9,000 a year per
person; supervised housing with counselors costs $30,000 a year per
person.
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown in negotiations comes as the state is striving to
discharge the last 6,500 patients at state psychiatric hospitals,
many with more complex problems than the patients released in the
1980s at the height of deinstitutionalization.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them also have criminal records. In 1986, 16 percent of
state psychiatric patients had a criminal conviction; by 1996, that
had climbed to 24 percent. Mental health professionals say that the
more troubled a patient, the more he or she needs supervised
housing programs.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say that Manhattan State Psychiatric Center now
has a majority of patients with a criminal history. In 1993,
according to state documents, 7 percent of new admissions at the
center were from jails and prisons. By 1997, 70 percent of new
admissions were, and today almost all admissions come from
correctional institutions.
</P>
<P>
   By 2002, the Pataki administration has said it hopes to reduce
the state's mental hospital census by 2,000 patients.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say they do not discharge patients unless there
is appropriate housing for them. Klingman says that most of the
patients with criminal backgrounds committed misdemeanors and are
therefore not dangerous to the community.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Culhane, a professor at the University of Pennsylvania
who has worked with the Giuliani administration in monitoring the
city's homeless shelters, said the 1990 agreement was a major
factor in reducing the shelter population. When the agreement was
signed, there were 9,300 single adults in city shelters, a record;
that was reduced to 6,100 by 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other city in the country experienced this kind of drop _
that was New York/New York working,'' Culhane said. ``During that
same period, Philadelphia's shelter population actually climbed 35
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   But beginning in 1995, as most of the New York/New York beds
were filled, the adult shelter population began creeping up again,
and now stands at 7,200. Culhane estimates that 3,000 of the adults
are mentally ill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
