<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4882 &Cx1f; taf-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-EURO-$ADV04-ART-     01-01 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-EURO-$ADV04-ART-895(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EURO DEBUTS IN 11 EUROPEAN NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Europe made history on Friday, but there
will not be much time for self-congratulation.
</P>
<P>
   After years of political squabbling, arduous negotiations and
painful economic preparation, 11 European nations opened for
business on Friday with a new common currency: the euro.
</P>
<P>
   It is a political and economic achievement that seemed
impossible and even quixotic as recently as three years ago. Yet
suddenly the euro is here. And in a testimony to the euro's
remarkably smooth start, the economic debates within Europe have
already moved on to other topics.
</P>
<P>
   Almost no one worries about whether the euro can establish its
credibility as a strong currency in world markets. Now the big
issue is whether the euro will be a bit too strong, so highly
valued that it hinders European growth by making exports more
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, almost nobody fears an imminent resurgence of
inflation _ not even the famously austere German central bank, the
Bundesbank. Now the debate is whether Europe faces a danger from
deflation and declining prices.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, European business is reinventing itself both at home
and in the global marketplace. Much of that is a simple response to
global competition, but the euro is accelerating the change by
bringing Europe closer to the ideal of a single market as big as
that of North America.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the stock exchanges in Frankfurt and London, European
bourses are moving rapidly toward becoming cross-border equities
markets. Corporations, which traditionally financed themselves
through their own reserves or through bank loans, are now raising
billions in global stock and bond offerings. Junk bonds and
American-style leveraged buyouts are on the increase. Banks and
insurance companies are searching for mergers and partnerships
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   And Europe's bewildering patchwork of consumer pricing _ where
the price of a Volkswagen Golf or a bottle of Chanel perfume can be
25 percent higher in Paris than in Madrid, Spain _ is under new
challenge as the euro strips away the camouflage of currency
differences.
</P>
<P>
   The euro will still seem like a phantom currency to many
consumers for some time. The new bills and coins will not enter
circulation until Jan. 1, 2002, and companies are allowed to keep
doing business in their national currencies until then.
</P>
<P>
   But as an economic entity, the euro is now more real than the
German marks or French francs that people keep in their wallets.
European monetary policy and interest rates are under the control
of the new European Central Bank. And when European finance
ministers locked in the exchange rates between their national
currencies and the euro on New Year's Eve, the old currencies
became nothing more than different ways to print euros.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Friday, the securities exchanges in all member
countries are conducting their business in euros. All interbank
transfers, even those within the same country, will be in euros.
Consumers now have the choice of keeping their bank accounts in
euros or their national currencies. During the next year, many
stores and companies plan to convert credit-card and other
electronic transactions into euros.
</P>
<P>
   As Europeans enter this new era, the ground beneath them is
shifting. Economists and government officials are much more worried
about an economic slowdown this year than they were just six months
ago. Having argued somewhat smugly that Europe would be only mildly
affected by the financial crises sweeping through Asia, Russia and
Latin America, government officials now admit they are troubled.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists have cut their aggregate growth estimates for
the 11 countries in Euroland from more than 3 percent to about 2.5
percent or lower. In Germany, which accounts for nearly a quarter
of the region's economic activity, some economists predict that
growth will drop from about 3 percent in 1998 to just 1.7 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing companies are considerably more pessimistic.
German engineering and machine-tool companies have slashed their
predictions for export growth from 7 percent to 4 percent. Chemical
companies such as BASF and Hoechst are all reeling from lower
prices and lower demand, mostly as a result of the problems in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the United States, Europe is flooded with low-cost
imports as a result of currency devaluations from Asia and Latin
America. While Europe still has a big trade surplus with the rest
of the world, a rising tide of imports is cutting into local
growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together with the U.S., Euroland is turning into the global
importer of last resort,'' wrote Holger Schmieding, European
economist for Merrill Lynch in London, in a recent report. He
predicts that the shift in trade will reduce Europe's growth by
about one-half of a percentage point, and bring it down to about 2
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   That would not be catastrophic. Most economists expect that the
United States, which has grown faster than Europe since the early
1990s, will not do much better.
</P>
<P>
   But even a modest slowdown will put more pressure on the
fledgling European Central Bank, with Wim Duisenberg as its
president. Formerly the president of the central bank of the
Netherlands, Duisenberg has cast himself as an unflinching hawk on
monetary policy whose only interest is preventing inflation.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Long after the Federal Reserve Board began cutting U.S. interest
rates last fall, hoping to head off a possible recession,
Duisenberg argued against similar measures in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But as the signs of a European slowdown continued to multiply,
Duisenberg and his mentors at the Bundesbank changed course and
surprised almost everybody last month by cutting nearly all
benchmark rates to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether that will be enough to shield
Europe against the chill winds from Asia or Latin America. But the
rate cut is bigger than it looks, because it came on top of even
more radical reductions in European countries like Italy, Spain and
Ireland, which have traditionally had higher inflation and interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Because countries adopting the same currency have to have the
same general level of inflation and interest rates, central banks
in these poorer periphery countries had already slashed their rates
to 4 percent from more than 6 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, baseline interest rates are now mostly at 3 percent
from Madrid to Frankfurt for the first time in European history. As
recently as a year ago, most economists assumed that this process
of convergence would head in the opposite direction, with countries
like Germany nudging their rates up to about 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The lower interest rates could lead to economic tensions within
Europe. For Ireland, Spain and Portugal, which were already growing
much more rapidly than their bigger and wealthier neighbors, the
latest cuts simply add more rocket fuel to the mixture and could
ignite inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   But that hardly settles the matter. With last fall's election
victory in Germany by Gerhard Schroeder and the Social Democratic
Party, most countries in Europe are now controlled by
left-of-center governments that are more interested in reducing
unemployment than in adhering to orthodox inflation-fighting
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those political leaders are hinting at a readiness to
run higher budget deficits, especially if European unemployment
rises beyond its current level of about 10 percent. If budget
deficits do begin to swell, Duisenberg will be under pressure to
counterattack with tighter monetary policy _ an unpopular job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
