<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION OFFERS A NEW PLAN THROUGH THE NEWS MEDIA
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association owners finally got a glimpse
of the union's latest proposal Friday. The only problem was that
they found out about the players' compromises through the news
media.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the union gave the media a sample of the
concessions it hopes may end the lockout, now in its 186th day,
league officials had not seen a copy of the proposal. What is
amounting to the final preliminary fight before next week's
expected last round of bargaining, neither the union nor the league
is budging.
</P>
<P>
   The players have requested a meeting to formally submit their
proposal, and the league has said only that it would forward it to
its labor relations committee with no guarantee of a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no comment on a proposal that has not been made to the
NBA,'' Jeffrey Mishkin, the league's chief legal officer, said
Friday. ``They can give us their proposal by any means they choose.
If they want to deliver it in person, fine. If want to mail it or
fax it, great. When they deliver it to us, we'll respond to it, but
not until then.''
</P>
<P>
   The league's stance was hardened on Thursday when Jeffrey
Kessler, the union's chief outside counsel, telephoned Mishkin to
request a meeting at which the proposal would be presented. When
Mishkin said he would forward it to the committee and its members
would then decide whether to schedule a meeting, Kessler called
back to say the union would not formally submit the proposal until
a meeting was scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked when he said we weren't going to meet,'' Kessler
said. ``It's not their offer, but there is definitely going to be
some movement in their direction. I just hope we get a chance to
present it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest skirmish, the lawyers were merely the conduits for
David Stern, the league's commissioner, and Billy Hunter, the
union's executive director. Both seem entrenched in their positions
and have only until Thursday to resuscitate the season, at which
time Stern and his deputy, Russ Granik, are expected to recommend
canceling the season if a new collective bargaining agreement has
not been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter portrayed the union's revised offer Thursday as
``unprecedented,'' saying that the players had agreed to an
absolute limit on maximum salaries.
</P>
<P>
   The players have proposed that the most a player with 10 years
or more experience could earn would be $15 million a year, though
only three players currently average higher than that salary. The
league wants that number to be $12.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   The union has also lowered its desired revenue percentage in the
critical fourth year of a proposed six-year deal to 55 percent. The
league wants the figure to be 53 percent in that year.
</P>
<P>
   A laundry list of other economic issues needs to be sorted
through before the two sides work on putting together an
abbreviated season of 40 to 50 games that could start no sooner
than the last week of January.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get a deal, it's simply because David Stern
doesn't want to do a deal,'' Hunter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
