<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR FAULTS GORE ON ETHICS BEFORE RACE BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)  (lb) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who took formal steps on
Wednesday to run for president, wasted no time Friday in signaling
that he would make Vice President Al Gore's fund-raising techniques
a major part of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, speaking to a gathering of conservative activists here
in his first appearance since filing papers on Wednesday to start a
presidential exploratory committee, said that the vice president
was a part of what McCain said were broad-based ethical lapses of
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you proud when monks and nuns abandon their vows of
poverty and pay tens of thousands of dollars to have spiritual
communion with the vice president?'' McCain said, referring to a
fund-raiser at a Buddhist temple that Gore attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you proud of an administration that spends all of its time
worrying about `controlling legal authorities' but cannot abide a
controlling ethical authority?'' McCain added, referring to a
phrase Gore used to deflect criticism of his fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has not formally declared his candidacy but is already
perceived as the front-runner for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who said he would not leave the Senate to run for
president, is the first Republican to take formal steps toward the
2000 nomination, but others are expected to follow shortly.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief sidewalk news conference before his speech, McCain
discussed some of his apparent political liabilities. He was asked
whether he looked forward to the personal scrutiny that goes with
being a presidential candidate, particularly at a time when the
private lives of politicians are being exposed. McCain long ago
acknowledged that he had an affair during his first marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't,'' he said. ``And it's well known that I've had a
very colorful life and career, so that's obviously something that
obviously we have to seriously consider. At the same time, you have
to appreciate that that goes with the territory.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain hedged when asked how he thought the Senate should deal
with articles of impeachment against President Clinton. He said he
had not yet spoken with Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the
Republican leader, who has proposed a speedy Senate trial that
would be over by Jan. 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 2125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
