u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-ACCIDENTS-NYT &LR;      01-01 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ACCIDENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7 KILLED, 7 HURT IN NEW YORK-AREA CAR WRECKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.C.)  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In three and a half hours on New Year's Eve, seven
lives were lost and others were forever altered in car wrecks in
the New York metropolitan region, and in each case police said a
drunken driver might have been to blame.
</P>
<P>
   The three accidents in New York and Connecticut, between 9 p.m.
Thursday and 12:30 a.m. Friday, also left seven people hurt, at
least one of them with life-threatening injuries. In two of the
crashes, drivers were arrested on drunken-driving charges; in the
other, a driver was killed, but police said they were awaiting a
toxicology report and that they suspected alcohol played a part.
</P>
<P>
   In the deadliest crash, an Army private was killed with his wife
and her child almost in the blink of an eye shortly after midnight
as he drove on Interstate 95 in Connecticut on his way to North
Carolina. State police said the private, Charles Flaherty, 20, was
driving with his wife, Josephine, 22, and her 3-year-old daughter,
when their car was hit head on by a car driving the wrong way in
the southbound lane in Stratford.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of that car, Silverstre Bonilla, 41, also died at the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they were awaiting results from an autopsy, but
Sgt. Daniel Semosky of the Connecticut State Police in Bridgeport
said, ``Thinking about the time of day and what he was doing, we
are checking for drugs and alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Flaherty had enlisted in the Army six months ago and was
stationed at Fort Bragg, N.C. He was with the 82nd Airborne
Division.
</P>
<P>
   In another crash, 20 minutes before midnight on the Long Island
Expressway, three young people were killed when an off-duty New
York City corrections officer, Edwin Rodriguez, rammed into their
car as it traveled east in Holtsville, police said. Police said
Rodriguez had been drinking.
</P>
<P>
   The Chevrolet Chevette that police said was hit by Rodriguez
soon exploded. The driver, Angelette Coffey, 19, managed to flee,
police said, but three passengers were killed. They were identified
as Matthew Marcotrigiano, 21, of Wading River, N.Y., and Norma
Vestal, 17, and Lee Trent, 16, both of Riverhead, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Coffey was listed Friday in stable condition at Stony Brook
Hospital, as was Rodriguez. He was charged with driving while
intoxicated, and will be under watch by a police officer until he
is released from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The first accident of the three-hour period occurred at about 9
p.m. in Hollis, Queens, as Pernell Hanton drove his 1988 Chevrolet
Corsica filled with children and another adult west on 109th
Avenue. Police said Paul Wachter, who was driving alone in his 1991
Chevrolet Blazer north along Farmers Boulevard, collided with
Hanton's car with such force that everyone in the Corsica was
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Wachter, who police said was from Westbury, N.Y., was taken to
Queens General Hospital, but was soon released and charged with
driving while intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   Hanton was taken to Mary Immaculate Hospital in Queens, where he
was listed in very critical condition, police said. They added that
a 9-year-old girl, Lanelle Hanton, was also in critical condition
in the hospital's intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   Three other passengers were hospitalized: Laquaisa Simpkins, 11,
Maudine Hanton, 14, and Aytasha Hanton, 25. A relative said that
Laquaisa, Maudine and Lanelle were all daughters of Hanton.
Aytasha's relationship to the others could not be learned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
