<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENNESSEE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Tennessee's Wilson exudes leadership, dismisses pain
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TEMPE, Ariz. _ It only hurts when he rolls over in bed. Or when he
turns the wrong way. Or when he inadvertently tries to lift
something at the wrong angle.
</P>
<P>
   It hurts a whole lot more when instinct dictates that he lean
that battered right shoulder into a running back or receiver to
deliver the appropriate hit, but Al Wilson doesn't want anyone to
dwell on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had time to rehab it,'' he said. ``It's not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   John Chavis knows better, of course. Tennessee's defensive
coordinator marvels at what Wilson has been able to do in a season
that has been almost equal parts elation and agony. With each hit,
with each time the heart and soul of the Volunteers' defense gets
up slowly, Chavis feels the pain, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts to know that even though he's playing so well, he's
not at his best because of that shoulder,'' Chavis said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, the senior middle linebacker of the nation's No.
1-ranked team, prefers not to ponder the might-have-beens.
Tennessee is 12-0 for the first time in school history. A national
championship is just 60 minutes away in Monday night's Fiesta Bowl
matchup with Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   That's what matters, he will tell you.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wilson conceded there have been a few dark moments along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely depressing,'' he said the other day. ``But
it was something I just had to push on through.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, he has done just that, and in remarkable style. He
missed the Auburn game with the shoulder injury, and the Kentucky
and Vanderbilt games when a groin strain further complicated
matters. Still, he managed to earn consensus All-Southeastern
Conference honors and a first-team All-American spot from the
American Football Coaches Association and the Football Writers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   He also impressed some more important observers along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see him play injured the whole year like he did was a great
inspiration for our team,'' Tennessee wide receiver Peerless Price
said. ``Even when he couldn't play, we all wanted to win for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always upbeat and cheering. He was into what the
offense was doing. Seeing the way he handled things gave us a lot
of motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who weighed the merits of NFL money after last season
before deciding to stay in school, takes his role seriously.
Forcing three fumbles in the watershed victory over Florida was an
obvious way to lead, as were the four sacks, six tackles for
losses, two fumble recoveries and an interception he managed in the
nine games he was able to play.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining quality control in the less public moments, however,
is part of the job, too.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the season, for instance, Vols coach Phillip Fulmer
spent 20 minutes delivering a motivational speech. When Fulmer was
done, Wilson stepped up and uttered two words:
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the message that stuck, becoming a team motto.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm a so-called leader, I have to be vocally into it,'' he
said. ``I have to take charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I feel like a guy is slipping a little bit, I might say,
`Let's pick it up, baby.' And those guys take it to heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State coach Bobby Bowden evidently has taken Wilson's
efforts to heart as well. Sizing up Monday's Fiesta Bowl
national-championship matchup, Bowden cited two Tennessee players
he feared.
</P>
<P>
   One was quarterback Tee Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The other: ``No. 27.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nice, but one guy can't win the game,'' Wilson said. ''
I can go out and have a great football game, but I can't focus all
the attention on myself. I can't cause 10 turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean he won't try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen guys with as much ability who never, ever got
anything done with it,'' Chavis said. ``His will to win and desire
to be the best are what set him apart.''
</P>
<P>
   That drive has helped carry Tennessee from preseason
afterthought to the cusp of a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to set an example for the young guys down the road, when
it's their turn to be leaders,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   That turn will come soon enough. For 60 more minutes on Monday
night, Al Wilson will offer a final primer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
