<HEADER>
A4894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-COLUMN-HNS     01-01 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Price boasts of Peerless Tennessee
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Tennessee receiver Peerless Price finally had to
say what his body language and facial expressions have said all
week.
</P>
<P>
   He has none _ a peer, that is. At least not in the Florida State
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   It was refreshing to see such resolution on New Year's Day, for
Price to say what he really thought and remind the world there's
something of a tradition at Tennessee, too.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was all that televised college football Friday. Maybe
Price realized that while so many other big games were being
played, there were three days of only talking about football left
before Monday night's national-championship Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the desert weather, which Price said has been
playing with his mind as much as all the hype the Seminoles have
been getting here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 70 degrees in the daytime and 30 degrees at night, that's
the weirdest thing I've ever seen,'' Price said. ``Where I'm from,
when it's cold it's cold and when it's hot it's hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Price is from is Tennessee, where they've been known to
catch a few passes. Much of the hypesters for Monday night's game
seem to have forgotten and Price no longer could just sit there and
take it, as he has throughout a month's worth of functions,
banquets and news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   He tried, sure. He crossed his arms, squirmed in his chair and
tried not to roll his eyes and scream every time the focus of this
Fiesta Bowl was put on the No. 2 Seminoles rather than the No. 1
Vols.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good team and a good defense,'' Price said of the
'Noles. ``They've accomplished a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the way to giving the Seminoles all the necessary
compliments and pats on the back before Monday night's
national-championship game, something finally got the better of
Price.
</P>
<P>
   A tough, smart stare crossed Price's face when another reference
to the Seminoles' defense was made Friday. Someone talked about the
physical way the Seminoles traditionally have treated opposing
receivers. Someone mentioned the confidence the FSU corners have
shown this week. Someone mentioned the Seminoles' long line of
secondary standouts _ players such as Deion Sanders and Terrell
Buckley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of it hearing what they're going to do in the
ballgame,'' Price said. ``I'm tired of hearing about everything
they've done and this and that. Let's just play and find out.
They're the No. 1-ranked secondary in the country? I haven't seen
it. We think we can beat them in the passing game.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be the most significant matchup of Monday's
national-championship game. FSU's run defense will be huge, of
course. Tennessee's pursuit against the speedy Seminoles will be
important. Decision-making by both quarterbacks, as always, will
have to be good.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe nothing will determine the champion more than what
FSU's No. 1-ranked defensive secondary will do against Tennessee's
hugely explosive group of receivers led by Price. It also will be
the most hotly contested of the matchups, because both sides
represent past heroes that built these traditions of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you sign with Tennessee you expect to be the next in
line,'' Price said. ``You expect to have success against anyone you
play. I've heard (from former Tennessee players) and they've all
told me not to take anything; not to back down, to uphold the
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Players such as Willie Gault, Tim McGee, Joey Kent and Marcus
Nash were but a few of the great Tennessee receivers over the
years. Many of them have called Price in recent days and told him
to attack the Seminoles at their strength. They have told Price to
show Tennessee pride and prove it on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the (FSU) secondary is going to be at a
disadvantage,'' Price said. ``They're good, but they're not unlike
what we've already seen this year. We can make plays against them.
They talk trash, but we hear it all in our own conference. And it's
better trash talk in the SEC because there are more good teams and
better players in our conference than the (Atlantic Coast
Conference).''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the emotional temperature for Monday night's game began
to rise Friday. Price certainly realized the skill and tradition
the Vols will face.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles' secondary of Dexter Jackson, Derrick Gibson, Tay
Cody and Mario Edwards did indeed lead the nation. It limited six
teams to 100 yards of passing or less, a remarkable statistic in
this age of college football. It is the latest star-studded group
of athletes charged with upholding a terrific Florida State
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   But Price and the Vols receivers have a tradition to uphold,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've played a lot of great football over there,'' Price
said of Florida State. ``People kind of have forgotten what we're
capable of doing over here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
