<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HOOTERS-HARDTIMES-     01-01 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOOTERS-HARDTIMES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT MANHATTAN HOOTERS, SHORT SHORTS ARE ORANGE, INK IS RED
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo was sent Thursday (as NY-HOOTERS) to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By LESLIE EATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As if more evidence were needed that Manhattan is not
really part of America, consider this: The Hooters here is
bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Hooters, for those who have never ventured west of Hoboken, is a
popular and fast-growing chain of restaurants known almost entirely
for their waitresses, whom the company calls Hooters Girls. This is
not because they look like owls.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than a year ago, the first Hooters in Manhattan
opened in a prime tourist area, on 56th Street between Seventh
Avenue and Broadway, a block away from the Hard Rock Cafe and
Planet Hollywood. There was a bit of a splash at the time; David
Letterman featured the new restaurant on his show, ordering chicken
wings to go for his studio audience one night.
</P>
<P>
   But in November, the restaurant filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection, which means all the people to whom it owes more than $1
million are on hold while the management tries to figure out how to
stop the red ink. The restaurant is not closed, but it is in
financial peril, losing something like $30,000 a month, according
to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what went wrong? Richard Yudenfriend, the local
businessman who owns this particular Hooters restaurant, is
tight-lipped, to say the least. ``We intend to be around for a long
time, and are hopeful this is a temporary situation,'' he said last
week, adding only that he did not think the Hooters ``concept,'' as
they say in the restaurant business, was wrong for New York.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that is the case is arguable, considering the scantily
clad _ or not clad at all _ competition nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, New York can be a tough town for anyone who wants to
open a restaurant, no matter what the concept. Persnickety
customers, temperamental chefs, high rents, lots of regulations,
nettlesome neighbors and loads of competition make restaurants
among the most frequent visitors to the bankruptcy court at Bowling
Green.
</P>
<P>
   As for chain restaurants, which offer middle-of-the-road food at
middling prices, New York probably has fewer per capita than any
other big city in the United States, industry experts say. Even
some of the more expensive theme restaurants, like the Hard Rock
Cafe and Planet Hollywood, have been faring poorly here.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Hooters, court documents and interviews with
people involved in the restaurant tell a tale that hits all of
those New York hot buttons: sex, food, money and real estate (not
necessarily in that order).
</P>
<P>
   Start with sex _ Hooters does. It has fought off government
efforts to force it to hire male waiters, arguing that feminine,
er, pulchritude is crucial to its business plan. This seems to be
working elsewhere: the chain now has 232 restaurants, including 18
that opened in the last year. It is the sixth largest ``casual
dining'' chain in the country, according to Technomic Inc., a
leading restaurant consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   Hooters Girls wear scooped-neck tank tops, push-up bras, very
short orange shorts, white socks and sneakers (and flesh-toned
tights, but don't tell the guys). The company describes the ideal
Hooters Girl as a ``cheerleader, surfer girl next door,'' though
the ones featured in the company's calendars look more like Miss
February.
</P>
<P>
   The waitresses at the Hooters in Manhattan, however, do not.
They are pretty and pleasant, but more Jones Beach than
``Baywatch.'' At lunchtime recently, a table of young men clearly
enjoyed flirting with their waitress. (Hooters Girls make most of
their money from tips, and are encouraged to sit down with
customers and chat.) But the smirking men became slack-jawed only
when one of the many televisions ran a video of very buxom babes in
bikinis.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, men who are mainly interested in seeing female flesh
can see a lot more of it at Flash Dancers (Topless Entertainment),
say, or Legz Diamond's (All Nude), both of which are mere blocks
away down Broadway. But Edward Droste, one of the men who founded
Hooters in Florida in the 1980s, said such joints are not
competitors. ``Hooters has never crossed over into that kind of
arena,'' he said, adding that the restaurant is ``a little safe
haven.''
</P>
<P>
   The place looks like a combination fern bar and fraternity
house: the blond paneled walls are covered with beer signs, pinup
posters and fake traffic signs bearing slogans like ``Double
Curves.''
</P>
<P>
   As befits a restaurant whose slogan is, ``Delightfully tacky,
yet unrefined,'' the menu is written in a hokey, jokey style, as if
the author were simultaneously channeling Hugh Hefner and Walt
Disney. It boasts about the food, especially the ``nearly world
famous'' chicken wings.
</P>
<P>
   But customers do not seem convinced. In a recent survey for the
magazine Restaurants and Institutions, consumers ranked Hooters
78th out of 90 chains in quality of food. As for what New Yorkers
think, well, here's the 1999 Zagat Survey review: `` `Look but
don't touch' applies both to the skimpily costumed staff and to the
fried chain grub at the recent cholesterol-and-Lycra import; it's
`everything you've heard and less.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, food is not likely to be the primary draw for the men
who frequent Hooters _ and they are almost entirely men. Michael
McNeil, vice president for marketing at Hooters of America, based
in Atlanta, reports that nationally, 70 percent of the customers at
Hooters are men, though it depends on the location and time of day.
(Some Hooters have a children's menu.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, almost all of the customers appear to be local men
in their 20s rather than tourists. On a recent evening, they
streamed into the place, paying a $3 cover charge to watch the
waitresses compete in a bikini contest.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch, however, things seem a lot slower. While nearby
restaurants like the Brooklyn Diner and the Redeye Grill were
jammed on a recent Thursday, only 50 or so people rattled around in
Hooters, which seats 250.
</P>
<P>
   That presents a particular problem for such a place, restaurant
experts suggest, because its costs are high and its revenues are
relatively low. Most of its entrees go for less than $10, and it
serves only beer and wine, not hard liquor, which is more
profitable. In court papers, Yudenfriend estimated that the
restaurant would take in about $140,000 in December.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there is a big nut to cover: The rent is almost
$30,000 a month. And, because it is a franchise _ locally owned but
part of a chain _ the restaurant must also pay about $10,000 a
month in royalties to the mother ship in Atlanta. And all of that
is before the payroll, food, taxes, insurance and interest payments
on its loans. Total costs for December, Yudenfriend estimated,
would be almost $173,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most franchises are still a volume business,'' said Jeffrey
Bradach, a professor at Harvard Business School who has written a
book called ``Franchise Organizations'' (Harvard Business School
Press, 1998), which focuses on restaurants. ``Because they don't
have huge margins, they need people moving through the doors every
hour of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most important thing for a franchise, Bradach said, is
to match the concept of the restaurant to the demographics of the
area.
</P>
<P>
   Child-towing tourists do not seem to be flocking to Hooters. As
for the locals, well, New York's service economy is unusually
mixed, in terms of men and women working together, said Mitchell
Moss, director of the Urban Research Center at New York University.
``I don't want to be harsh,'' he said, ``but there are too many
successful women in New York for men to be public about this. No
professional male can come home and say, `I went to Hooters.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hooters executives say that the biggest problem for the
Manhattan restaurant has been its location. The entrance and awning
are in a little courtyard on the north side of 56th Street, and its
signs are not very visible to anyone driving down Broadway or
Seventh Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The interior of the restaurant needed a lot of work, said
Droste, the Hooters founder, and ``the operator got very much
involved.'' As a result, he said, Yudenfriend may not have
concentrated on ``the promotional aspect we are famous for.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Yudenfriend's backers, however, suggest that he did not
get as much support from the home office as he might have expected,
given that the Manhattan restaurant was supposed to be Hooters'
marquee property. While Yudenfriend did have experience running a
Hooters _ he took over the one on Staten Island in 1996 _ Manhattan
is clearly a different market (for starters, the local Corvette
club is not likely to hold meetings in the parking lot).
</P>
<P>
   He has suffered some recent setbacks, according to papers his
lawyer filed in court early last month. A manager resigned
unexpectedly, the document says, and `` Yudenfriend was mugged
outside the Manhattan restaurant in the early morning of Dec. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hooters of America does pull Yudenfriend's franchise, as it
has threatened to do, that will not be the end of the restaurant
chain's efforts here, McNeil said, adding, ``Ultimately, we believe
Manhattan needs, wants and deserves a Hooters restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   But desire may not be enough. Expanding a chain from Atlanta to
Birmingham is one thing, said Ron Paul, president of Technomic, the
restaurant consulting firm. But New York City, he said, is
something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be offended, but we tell clients that it's like going
into an international location, in terms of culture, real estate,
laws,'' Paul said. ``It's very high risk to go into Manhattan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
