u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FLORIDAST.-HNS &LR;      01-01 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLORIDA </SLUG>
 ST.-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Florida State's Edwards maximizes final chance
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TEMPE, Ariz. _ Mario Edwards took a moment to soak it all in.
</P>
<P>
   The late-morning desert sunshine. The green grass below. The
colorful banners adorning Sun Devil Stadium as Monday night's
Fiesta Bowl game draws near.
</P>
<P>
   All of that was nice, the Florida State cornerback said, but the
cause of the smile on his face was something entirely different.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most satisfying thing for me this year was just making it
back,'' he said. ``I told my mom and my brother that if I ever got
another chance, I'd make the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Edwards had to wonder if that chance would come.
Worst of all, he knew he had no one to blame but himself if it
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   He was kicked out of school shortly before the 1997 opener after
a woman alleged that he had slapped and choked her. The incident
came on the heels of an arrest that same summer when he failed to
appear in court to answer petty theft charges from his use of a
cellular phone he found on a bus.
</P>
<P>
   Not a pretty picture, by any means.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I let a lot of people down,'' he says. ``When you're
young, you're going to make mistakes. The main thing is to learn
from them, and I think I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleading no contest in the phone matter, he got probation and
community service. The woman, in turn, never actually pressed
charges, but FSU's student judicial committee still suspended
Edwards for two semesters.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, then, he was in Tallahassee while the Seminoles
traveled to New Orleans to play Ohio State in the Sugar Bowl. The
road to Tempe would begin with a modest goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I was thinking about,'' Edwards said, ``was doing whatever
I could to get back to Florida State.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, he passed 10 hours of classes at Tallahassee
Community College in the spring. He added eight more in the summer
to regain his eligibility, convincing coach Bobby Bowden to give
him another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Omitted from the 1998 media guide and depth chart, Edwards
nevertheless reclaimed his starting job early in the season and has
been a big part of the Seminoles' No. 1-rated defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incident made me a better person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to be a decent player, too. In the course of
redeeming himself, he set a school record with four interceptions
against Wake Forest and narrowly missed a fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe they kept throwing at me,'' he said with a
smile. ``It wasn't Christmas yet, but it felt like it.''
</P>
<P>
   After helping the Seminoles bottle up Florida in the game that
proved to be the springboard for this national title run, Edwards
faces yet another challenge Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's Tee Martin has emerged as a credible passing threat
in the season's second half. Wide receiver Peerless Price (10
touchdowns) has been the Vols' big-play man in complementing a
strong running game. In what is expected to be a low-scoring game,
a big play in the passing game _ either way _ could make the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good, but I think our defense has proven that we can
stop anyone,'' Edwards said. ``Our secondary was a problem the last
couple of years, but I think we're a strength now.''
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight beckons. Even as it does, though, this participant
on college football's biggest stage already has plenty to
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't realize how much you miss something until it's taken
away,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Edwards understands. In case you didn't know, it's written
all over his face.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
