<HEADER>
A4900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANFRAN-CITYHALL-ART-     01-01 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANFRAN-CITYHALL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO'S CITY HALL AS GOLDEN AS ITS BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BILL STAGGS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Not since the 1920s has the sunlight glinted so
brightly from San Francisco's City Hall dome, a shapely structure
taller than the 90-foot dome of the capitol in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The gold leaf shining when the building opened in 1915 simply
washed away over those first two decades, undone by wet winters and
questionable early-century technology.
</P>
<P>
   But the glow is back on the landmark building and its dome,
which were closed for more than three years of renovation.
Beginning at noon on Tuesday, San Franciscans will once again be
able to step inside their Beaux-Arts seat of government to dispute
a water bill, pay taxes, get married or buy a dog license.
</P>
<P>
   The $500,000 spent on regilding the dome is a fraction of the
$293 million total cost of the project. The building received $207
million in structural improvements, made necessary by a deadly
earthquake in 1989, and another $85 million went into fixtures and
paint, furniture and lights, and computer and communication systems
ready for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation cost $100 million more than originally planned,
and controversy swirled for years over what City Hall should be _ a
functional, workaday civic hub, or an imposing public space in the
European tradition. San Franciscans will see both.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown drew public and political ire when he
proposed to reshape the ground floor as a near-regal setting for
welcoming dignitaries and throwing elaborate parties. Local
politicians reined him in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayor Brown wanted more ceremonial space,'' said Susan Leal,
the city treasurer and former city supervisor, noting that the
mayor wanted only 700 of 1,300 workers to return when the building
reopened, with the other 600 working in space rented in commercial
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Board of Supervisors insisted that every department
with citizen interaction should be back in the building,'' Ms. Leal
said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 city workers will have returned by Tuesday, and
300 municipal court employees have moved to a new building across
the street.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor could not be reached for comment on the renovation.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the carping and political skirmishes, the results of
the renovation seem likely to please even the most demanding
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Temko, one of San Francisco's most respected architecture
critics, praised the renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' Temko said. ``I love the gold, the old oak
furniture, the elegant spaces, the restored light courts with their
skylights. But the real triumph is in the strengthening of the
building seismically and structurally.''
</P>
<P>
   The building's seismic undoing came in an the fall of 1989, with
the Loma Prieta earthquake. That rolling temblor killed more than
50 people, stopped a World Series game before it started and
destroyed or damaged buildings throughout the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall was one of the quake's more visible victims, safe
enough for interim habitation but clearly cracked. Corridors shrank
with the installation of temporary bracing, and the elegant dome
inspired more fear than awe. After the earthquake, people raced
across the patterned limestone of the rotunda floor on their way to
the grand staircase.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Irons, a city architect and the project manager for the
renovation, told visitors that the real beauty of the building lies
in what is not seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ultimate goal has been to make City Hall look as though no
architect had been involved in the rebuilding,'' Irons said.
</P>
<P>
   Working from the original blueprints, contractors stripped away
acres of Vermont marble to get at the steel core, then installed
giant rubber and steel shock absorbers under each of nearly 600
beams and columns at the base of the building. The result: a steel
building clad in its original marble, limestone and Sierra granite,
and resting on high-tech cushions that will keep it from moving
when the next ``big one'' comes.
</P>
<P>
   The building's status as a national landmark dictated that every
lamp and railing and bit of carved wood had to be kept as it was,
refinished or repaired.
</P>
<P>
   Gladys Hansen, the city's archivist emeritus and director of the
Museum of the City of San Francisco, said San Francisco needed
something new to brag about. ``We've lived too long on the
reputation of our bridges,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
