<SLUG> BC-1999-COHEN-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORECASTERS SEE BLUE-CHIPS CONTINUING TO RALLY  
(FOR RELEASE ON MONDAY, JAN.4.)
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abby Joseph Cohen did not flinch in August when the stock market
sank. Instead, Ms. Cohen, the chief investment strategist at
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., telephoned her clients and told them the same
thing she told them a year earlier when the market seemed to be in
free fall: ``Stay the course.''
</P>
<P>
   It has become a familiar refrain for Ms. Cohen, who has remained
steadfast in her bullishness even when others have turned bearish.
And what should investors expect this year?
</P>
<P>
   ``When we do a retrospective of 1999 we'll be saying, `It wasn't
so bad after all,''' she said in a telephone interview late last
year. ``We see profits continuing to grow in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   After combing through an array of charts and graphs, her
statistical crystal ball, Ms. Cohen predicted an unprecedented
fifth consecutive year of solid gains for blue-chip stocks, even
though profit growth will continue to moderate. By the end of the
year, she said, the Dow Jones industrial average could reach 9,850
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index could climb to 1,275.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ms. Cohen said that the Dow, one of the most widely
followed market barometers, would end the year at 9,300. (It ended
at 9,181.43.) She also predicted that the S&AMP;P 500, which most index
funds track, would finish the year at 1,200. (It ended at
1,229.23.)
</P>
<P>
   She has not been alone in forecasting a prolonged bull market.
Edward M. Kerschner, the chief investment strategist at Paine
Webber, has also had relatively accurate predictions, bucking the
trend toward pessimism when the Asian economic crisis appeared. He,
too, was projecting modest gains for stocks this year, noting that
the big shift of cash into equities (spurred by baby boomers) could
continue for the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Another prescient Wall Street forecaster is Laszlo Birinyi, a
former Salomon Brothers technician, who now heads his own research
and money management firm in Greenwich, Conn. By following the
amount of cash rushing into certain stocks, Birinyi has been able
to discern trends in buying sentiment _ trends that have made him
an unrepentant bull, even during sharp downturns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still very positive,'' Birinyi said, adding that the
blue chips would continue to lead the rallies. ``When the market
goes down, people continue to buy stocks, you see investors
manifesting their views about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who see nothing impressive in the actions of these
bulls, consider this: Almost every other Wall Street strategist has
forecast that the sharp increase in stock prices that began in
October 1990, with the Dow at 2,365.10, would surely collapse into
a bear market. Valuations, they said, were too high. They said it
in 1995. 1996. 1997. And 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997, for example, Barton M. Biggs, the chief global
strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said: ``If this has been
a year of moonlight and roses, next year, I expect, is going to be
sackcloth and ashes. In other words, the huge brutal hug of a bear
market will squeeze some.''
</P>
<P>
   The same year Ralph J. Acampora, the widely followed technician
at Prudential Securities, predicted a Dow 10,000 by 1998, and then
had a change of heart in August, after the Dow passed 9,300,
declaring himself a bear and warning that the Dow could fall 20
percent. ``It was the toughest call I've ever made, but I didn't
flip-flop,'' Acampora said. ``I market-time, that's my job. I saved
my clients a lot of agony.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, concerns about a global economic crisis caused the Dow
to fall 19 percent from its all-time high in August and September,
before it roared back in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   During the downturn, Ms. Cohen was resolute. She moved swiftly
to calm investors' fears, calling the decline a short-term ``market
event'' and not a real threat to the economy or the thriving bull
market in equities.
</P>
<P>
   That most strategists would expect a sharp and prolonged
downturn is only natural. Few other bull markets have roared so
fast for so long. And if one listens to Ms. Cohen, that run is not
over yet. ``Where our forecast ends, there is no recession in
sight,'' she said. ``The U.S. economy is strong. I believe in
business cycles; I just don't think this cycle is ending in the
next 12 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cohen said she expected more of the same this year: steady
earnings growth, with profits up about 5 percent from a year
earlier; a steady economy, and stable interest rates _ a recipe for
the strong rise of share prices.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Ms. Cohen said that investors should be comforted by
the nation's economy, which she likened to a ``supertanker'': It
wasn't the fastest or most colorful ship at sea, but it was the
strongest and the steadiest. This year's metaphor? ``Supertanker
revisited,'' she said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Investors will be much more comfortable this year, she
contended, having worked off a great deal of anxiety during the
downturn in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   How exactly does Ms. Cohen forecast what will happen 3, 6 or 12
months out? Ms. Cohen said she had developed statistical and
intellectual models, models that weigh economic trends, cash flows
into mutual funds, corporate earnings and other variables that
could propel or eventually upset the apple cart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing we do is deciding which of the things
we look at are the most important, the critical variable,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, every Wall Street strategist has a model, but Ms.
Cohen said she sweated all the details. She creates her own
measurement of corporate earnings growth, and tries to identify the
variables that may eventually undermine her projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do is a combination of science and art,'' she said.
``Many investors believe if they only have the numbers they can get
all the answers, but there are also critical variables.''
</P>
<P>
   Such variables, she says, could include earnings, the global
economy, wage growth _ almost any statistic or trend in business
and the economy. The real trick, she says, is in learning how to
use those details to construct a forecast.
</P>
<P>
   An important and early lesson came when Ms. Cohen was working at
the Federal Reserve Board in the 1970s. Some of the best
econometricians had devised an enormously successful forecasting
model that suddenly did not work. Ms. Cohen helped try to find out
why. The reason, she and other staff members later determined, was
that the forecast was based on a particular inflationary
environment, and when that environment changed, the model failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great lessons I learned is that you can have
sophisticated models and they might not work,'' she said. ``I view
our work as: Let's try this disciplined scientific approach, and
then let's try intellectual approaches as to why it won't work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
