<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-MERGE-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BIG MERGERS ARE ON THE HORIZON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You would think that after last year's more than $2.4 trillion
in announced mergers worldwide _ the largest on record _ corporate
executives might take 1999 off. Think again.
</P>
<P>
   With the stock market for the most part continuing its upward
march, investors can expect even more mergers in the next 12
months. But unlike last year, when mergers were concentrated
primarily in the telecommunications, banking and insurance
industries, the frenzy this year will spread to other industries as
well, merger professionals say.
</P>
<P>
   Even more international combinations are expected in the months
ahead, along with a shift in activity to include industrial
companies as well as increased activity in the burgeoning
high-technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you assume a reasonably stable market environment for a
good part of the year, it will be good for the merger market,''
said Stephen Volk, a senior partner at the New York law firm of
Shearman &AMP; Sterling. ``Chief-executive confidence is quite high
now, and it is a major predictor of deals getting done.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of what has driven the megamerger boom in the United States
is the effort by corporations to fend off competition from larger
rivals by combining. As a result, regional companies will continue
to turn their attention away from their home market in the hopes of
quickly establishing a national, if not international, presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing becomes important,'' said Steven Wolitzer, head of
global mergers and acquisitions at Lehman Brothers. ``The ability
to build your business first becomes important to really create the
winners. It's a mad scramble to get there quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Witness the flurry of activity after Nationsbank bought and
merged into BankAmerica in a $60 billion stock deal or after SBC
Communications announced its intent to acquire Ameritech for $62
billion in stock, a deal the Federal Communications Commission is
reviewing.
</P>
<P>
   Investors can expect even more activity, particularly in
pharmaceuticals, health care, utilities and energy _ the latter
recently evidenced by the $80 billion planned merger of Exxon and
Mobil.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our themes has been the everyday nature of this
activity,'' said Mac Heller, co-chief operating officer of the
investment banking division and head of global mergers and
acquisitions at Goldman, Sachs. ``Yes, the numbers are spectacular,
but it is no more spectacular to have a $70 billion deal in 1998
than it was to have a $10 billion deal in 1984.''
</P>
<P>
   More U.S. executives are expected to turn their attention to
foreign concerns. That's in part because more European companies
have set their sights on the United States as well as on their
next-door neighbors, in an effort to extend beyond national borders
_ a trend that will only grow as Europe moves closer to a common
market.
</P>
<P>
   A unified Europe ``requires companies to look at themselves and
become larger and more competitive,'' said John Studzinski, head of
European investment banking at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``There
will be more profound consolidation in the midsize sector.''
</P>
<P>
   The courtship has already begun, for companies of all sizes.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a spate of recently announced pharmaceutical
combinations in Europe, including the $35 billion planned
acquisition of Astra of Sweden by the London-based Zeneca Group,
and the agreement to combine the drug and agricultural units of
Hoechst of Germany and Rhone-Poulenc of France.
</P>
<P>
   And while European companies have always been attracted to U.S.
targets, they are finally going after them in a big way. In
December for instance, Scottish Power announced its intent to
acquire Pacificorp, which operates in the Pacific Northwest and is
one of the United States' biggest power companies, for $7.9
billion. If approved it would be the first purchase of a U.S.
utility by a foreign company. And Deutsche Bank said it would buy
Bankers Trust for $10.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Such cross-border combinations will be anything but easy to pull
off as companies grapple with inconsistent accounting, legal and
regulatory rules in the home countries. And there are sure to be
social and political ramifications as foreign workers and their
bosses alike become accustomed to the American-style corporate
reorganizations of the 1980s, which turned many companies into
leaner operations _ but only after major cost-cutting and huge
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Technology will continue to be an active area for mergers, too,
but these combinations present their own complications, industry
experts say. For one thing, technology stocks are quite volatile,
and anyone seeking a merger partner is subject to unpredictable
downside risk because of the often short life span of technology
products. That is why activity in the industry has mostly consisted
of weaker companies being acquired by stronger concerns. This is
likely to change as the industry matures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
