<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-TENN-HOLDSCLAW-NY     01-01 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-TENN-HOLDSCLAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LADY VOLS' HOLDSCLAW, A HOMECOMING OF SORTS AT THE GARDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She knows it would make for a nice, romantic story,
but Chamique Holdsclaw cannot tell a lie. She did not grow up
dreaming about playing basketball in Madison Square Garden, did not
go to Knicks games often as a child and will not feel jitters,
tingles or any other manifestation of awe when she steps onto the
famed court for the first time in her career.
</P>
<P>
   Although she is excited about playing in the Garden, Holdsclaw
has been too many places and done too many things to be overwhelmed
by the setting. So the heralded senior from Astoria, Queens, said
there will be no pressure to put on a show for the hometown crowd
when Tennessee plays Rutgers on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I play the worst game of my life, life goes on,'' said
Holdsclaw, who will play in New York for only the second time since
joining the Lady Vols nearly four years ago. ``I know what I can
do, everybody knows what I can do, they know what this team can do.
So it's no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's no stretch to assume that, pressure or not, Holdsclaw
will put on a show, one that will leave the more than 11,000 fans
who have already purchased tickets begging for the Liberty to find
a way to snag the three-time all-American in the next Women's
National Basketball Association draft.
</P>
<P>
   The game between second-ranked Tennessee (10-1) and 15th-ranked
Rutgers (10-2) will be the first women's collegiate basketball game
at the Garden since December 1981. It is fitting that the event is
being billed as ``Holdsclaw's Homecoming,'' for Holdsclaw is the
reason for the game.
</P>
<P>
   While recruiting the former Christ the King High School star,
Tennessee coach Pat Summitt promised she would schedule at least
one game in New York before Holdsclaw graduated. Last year, Summitt
fulfilled that promise when Tennessee rolled over host Manhattan by
50 points en route to posting its 39-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   But while the game, played before a sparse crowd in a middling
gymnasium, satisfied Holdsclaw, it was not enough for Summitt.
Holdsclaw had traveled south to help her win three national titles,
and the coach wanted to do something big for her star. So she began
attempting to secure a date at the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chamique truly deserves to play at the Garden,'' said Summitt,
whose teams have won 110 of 125 games since Holdsclaw joined the
program. ``For what she's meant to women's basketball, to our
program, to the kids here in New York City. She's been a terrific
role model. And what better place for Chamique to play in her
senior season?''
</P>
<P>
   Summitt likes Holdsclaw's casual approach toward playing in the
Garden _ such an attitude is more conducive to her star playing
well against Rutgers _ and admits that the biggest thrill may
belong to Holdsclaw's nearly 100 friends and family members who
will be in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she came south to Tennessee, a lot of people probably
thought they would never see her play again,'' Summitt said. ``It's
like she was going to the end of the earth. So a lot of the people
that care about her will enjoy getting to see her play again.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who sees Holdsclaw play enjoys it. At 6 feet 2 inches,
she is the torchbearer for a new type of women's player. With the
size of a forward and the skill and athleticism of a guard, she can
dominate from any spot on the court.
</P>
<P>
   After a few seasons of watching Holdsclaw bring the ball upcourt
like a point guard, sink mid-range jumpers like a small forward,
rebound like a power forward and post up like a center, the people
who put together Tennessee's media guide decided to list her as a
``guard/forward/center.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She can play and defend any position on the court,'' said Nell
Fortner, who coached Holdsclaw the past two summers on the United
States National team and will coach the Olympic team in 2000.
``She's 6-2 and runs the floor like a gazelle. She works the
baseline of a zone offense beautifully. She's very fluid and very
sound fundamentally. She can get a shot whenever she wants to.''
</P>
<P>
   Already Tennessee's career rebounding leader with 1,114,
Holdsclaw needs to average only 10 points a game the rest of the
season to surpass Allan Houston's career scoring mark of 2,801
points. She enters Sunday's game averaging 21.9 points and 8.7
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw's most impressive number, however, is seven, for the
seven consecutive championships she has won dating back to high
school. She led Christ the King to four state championships and one
mythical national title in USA Today. She has never ended her
season with a loss.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1997, she spread her name throughout the rest
of the basketball-playing world by leading the United States
National team to a silver medal in the World Qualifying Tournament.
The only collegiate player on the team, she averaged team highs in
scoring (13.1) and rebounding (6.5). Last summer, she again joined
a group of professionals in helping the United States win the gold
medal at the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Fortner, who watched the Lady Vols practice Saturday at the New
York Athletic Club, said Holdsclaw is a strong candidate for the
next Olympic team, one of the top two or three players in the
history of women's college basketball, and a future star in the
WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   While Holdsclaw tempered her enthusiasm about playing in the
Garden tomorrow, she admitted that playing there on a regular basis
as a member of the Liberty would get her blood rushing. ``I would
love to play here in New York,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And New York would love to have her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
