u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-MILLENNIUM &LR;      01-01 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MILLENNIUM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IS GUAM AVAILABLE?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Jan. 2:
</P>
<P>
   All 700 hotel rooms in Tonga are booked for next New Year's Eve.
This is unhappy news for people who had toyed with the idea of
being right on the spot when the new millennium crosses the
international date line. Many New York City residents, having heard
that 46 percent of all American pleasure travelers would like to
celebrate the great event in Times Square, have undoubtedly also
started thinking that Tonga would be a very nice place to be. Too
late.
</P>
<P>
   This week's spate of reports on hotels and cruises that are
booked for Dec. 31, 1999, have created a sort of pre-millennial
panic among those of us who have failed to plan. Not a minute to
waste _ the Imperial Ball in Vienna is almost sold out, and Machu
Picchu is going fast. People who have not ventured outside on New
Year's Eve since they graduated from college are suddenly worrying
about being excluded from the festivities at the Great Pyramid. New
Yorkers who would rather be flayed than spend the evening in Times
Square with several hundred thousand strangers somehow find the
idea more attractive when the number threatens to be 17 million.
</P>
<P>
   Millennial anxiety disorder (is somebody going to name it MAD?)
will become worse as the date draws nearer and we are forced to
confront additional examples of the great time in store for people
who thought ahead, like Edward Woodyard. Woodyard, a writer who
lives in the New York suburbs, reserved his family's room at the
Marriott Hotel overlooking Times Square in 1983. The move was
particularly prescient since the hotel had not yet been built. Yes,
friends laughed at Woodyard 16 years ago, but now they are sending
him Christmas cards congratulating him on his good fortune and
dropping hints about their availability.
</P>
<P>
   The next public opinion poll will probably reveal that 37
percent of all Americans think the best place to be on New Year's
Eve is in the Woodyard suite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
