<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 12/31/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) PHOENIX -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- CONSERVATIVE-RETREAT-2, 1-1
-- Sen. John McCain, who is putting together a committee to assess
his chances as a Republican presidential candidate, talks to
reporters at a gathering of conservatives on Friday. The gathering
was dubbed the Dark Ages when it began three years ago, but the
organizers, conscious of the signals that the name sent, dropped
the parody this year in an attempt to give themselves an identity
that is not Clinton-dependent. (Jeff Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) PHOENIX -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- CONSERVATIVE-RETREAT, 1-1 --
Conservatives gather on Friday at an annual conference to assess
their movement. Among the participants were Marc Rotterman of the
John Locke Foundation and Arianna Huffington, right, a columnist.
The gathering was dubbed the Dark Ages when it began three years
ago, but the organizers, conscious of the signals that the name
sent, dropped the parody this year in an attempt to give themselves
an identity that is not Clinton-dependent. (Jeff Topping/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- MILITARY-BUDGET-2, 1-1 --
Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, looks on
as President Clinton addresses reporters about operations in
Bosnia-Herzegovina in December 1997. Heeding warnings from the
nation's military chiefs, including the need to address increased
operations from Bosnia to Iraq, President Clinton has decided to
propose the first real increase in the Pentagon's budget in nearly
a decade and the largest since the Cold War buildup of the
mid-1980s, administration and defense officials said. At center is
former White House Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles. (Todd
Cichonowicz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) ABOARD USS ENTERPRISE -- Jan. 1, 1999 --
MILITARY-BUDGET, 1-1 -- Sailors aboard the USS Enterprise prepared
the flight deck for night flight operations during Operation Desert
Fox on Dec. 17, as the aircraft carrier sailed in the Persian Gulf.
Heeding warnings from the nation's military chiefs including the
need to address increased operations from Bosnia to Iraq, President
Clinton has decided to propose the first real increase in the
Pentagon's budget in nearly a decade and the largest since the Cold
War buildup of the mid-1980s, administration and defense officials
said. (Todd Cichonowicz/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BALAKHANY, Azerbaijan -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- CASPIAN-OIL-3,
1-1 -- Seven-year old Bonufsla and her friends play around an oil
field which is now rarely in use. Throughout the Caspian region,
both the promise and the looming dangers of the Caspian oil bonanza
are palpable. Many promises of a better society are being made by
regional leaders. But they acknowledge that no plans are in place
to assure such hopes. (Staton R. Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SEATTLE -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- HUNGER-PROGRAM-FISH, 1-1 --
Tuck Donnelly, of Northwest Food Strategies, standing near a
shipment of fish, was instrumental in getting the government to
change the fishing regulation so food banks could obtain fish that
otherwise would have been thrown overboard. Now the fish are
stored, processed, and shipped from Alaska to Seattle where they
are distributed to food banks and homeless shelters. (Larry
Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEBRASKA CITY, Neb. -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- MISSOURI-RIVER-3,
1-1 -- A fertilizer loading station in Nebraska City sits near the
Missouri River. Big changes are coming to America's longest river.
The fracas over its future is fierce as environmentalists, farmers,
barge operators, recreation boosters, hydroelectric utilities,
Indian tribes and municipal leaders are all trying to make sure the
river stays-- or becomes -- what they want it to be. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- METHADONE-POLICY, 1-1 -- Pam
Carlo takes her methadone dose at a treatment center in New York.
Methadone is a bridge to a new life, but there are many other
rivers to cross. All of which goes a long way toward explaining why
methadone has long been caught in the cross-currents of social
policy, though never more so than right now in New York. (Nancy
Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEAR NEBRASKA CITY, Neb. -- Jan. 1, 1999 --
MISSOURI-RIVER-2, 1-1 -- Gerald Mestl sails a boat near an area
known as the Hamburg Bend mitigation project on the Missouri River
near Nebraska City. Mestl, a biologist with the Nebraska Game and
Parks Commission, wants the Missouri River to be returned to its
natural state. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 3 --
MENOPAUSE-MAVEN, 1-1 -- Dr. Patricia Allen, an obstetrician and
gynecologist, in her office recently. Allen's all-encompassing
approach to female health care along with her take-charge, ``Queen
of England'' manner, have attracted a fierce following, especially
among New York's power elite. (Carol Halebian/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Jan. 1, 1999 --ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 3 --
NY-BRITISH, 1-1 -- Myers of Keswick serves pork pie along with
other British favorites. The alienation felt by British ex-pats,
made into a hit song by the performer Sting 10 years ago in a song
called ``Englishman in New York,'' is no longer the case. These
days, downtown New York is also known by some as ``Little London.''
(Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 3 --
PRINCE-WILLIAM-FANS, 1-1 -- Dana Lautin, 15, has her room filled
with reminders of Britain's Prince William, the 16-year-old heir to
England's throne. Prince William crept into the consciousness of
American girls, many of them not yet teen- agers, shortly after the
death of his mother, Diana, the Princess of Wales. His stoic
suffering touched their hearts. (Marilyn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SAN FRANCISCO -- Jan. 1, 1999 --SANFRAN-CITYHALL-2, 1-1
-- San Francisco's city hall will open next Tuesday after being
closed for three years during renovations. Along with re-guilding
the dome, over $200 million were spent to bring the structure to
current standards for resisting earthquakes. (Peter DaSilva/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SAN FRANCISCO -- Jan. 1, 1999 --SANFRAN-CITYHALL-1, 1-1
-- Workers labor to move furniture up the main staircase in San
Francisco's city hall. After being closed for more than three years
for renovation, San Francisco's Beaux-Arts seat of government will
open to the public next Tuesday. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEAR NEBRASKA CITY, NE. -- Jan. 1, 1999 --
SUB-MISSOURI-RIVER, 1-1 -- An aerial view of a channel next to the
Missouri River, left, built by the Army Corps of Engineers. The
channel is designed to allow water in, but only at a depth shallow
enough to help foster an environment for fish and wildlife. (Fred
R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BAKU, Azerbaijan -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- CASPIAN-OIL-3, 1-1 --
A pensioner sweeps the street for tips in order to supplement her
income. Luxury cars like Mercedes, passing at right, are becoming a
common site in the Azerbaijani capital. Throughout the Caspian
region, both the promise and the looming dangers of the Caspian oil
bonanza are palpable. (Staton R. Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BAKU, Azerbaijan -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- CASPIAN-OIL-2, 1-1 --
An aerial view near Baku showing rotting oil storage tanks at right
and a oil field only partially used. Throughout the Caspian region,
both the promise and the looming dangers of the Caspian oil bonanza
are palpable. (Staton R. Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BALAKHANI, Azerbaijan -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- CASPIAN-OIL, 1-1
-- An oil worker with the state oil company of Azerbaijan at an
off-shore oil rig in the Caspian Sea. The rig, as well as many
others nearby, produce low-grade crude. Throughout the Caspian
region, both the promise and the looming dangers of the Caspian oil
bonanza are palpable. (Staton R. Winter/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ALBANY, N.Y. -- Jan. 1, 1999 -- NY-INAUG , 1-1 -- George
Pataki is sworn in for his second term as governor of New York
early Friday by Judge Judith Kaye. This year's inauguration was a
scaled-back version of Pataki's lavish inaugural four years ago
when he became the first Republican in 20 years to become New
York's governor. Looking on are his children Emily and George Owen.
(David Jennings/New York Times Photo)
</P>
