<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4919 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COTTONBOWL-HNS &LR;      01-01 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COTTONBOWL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas erases bitter memories
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DALLAS _ For Texas fans, Friday's Southwestern Bell Cotton Bowl was
as good as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades of bad memories that have haunted the Longhorns were
erased in a 38-11 triumph over Mississippi State, the biggest
margin of victory for Texas in its 20 Cotton Bowl appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that 46-3 loss to Miami in the 1991 Cotton Bowl? Forget
it. Or how about those seven consecutive victories by longtime
Texas nemesis Jackie Sherrill? Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   It was a damp and dreary day in Dallas, but it was almost
perfect as far as the Longhorns (9-3) were concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous finish to a great year for us,'' said UT
coach Mack Brown. ``I think we have become one of the best teams in
the country, and I hope the rankings will reflect it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first season of the Brown era and the final season for
Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams and receiver Wane McGarity
ended in style in front of 72,611 wet spectators. Williams rushed
for 203 yards and two touchdowns, and McGarity had TD catches of 59
and 52 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was voted the Offensive Player of the Game, and Texas
linebacker Aaron Babino, who led the team with nine tackles, was
the Defensive Player of the Game.
</P>
<P>
   It also was a day that showed the promise of a bright future in
a baby-faced redshirt freshman who played like a seasoned veteran.
Texas quarterback Major Applewhite completed 15 of 26 passes for
225 yards and three TDs without an interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big step for our team,'' Applewhite said. ``If I had
to put a word on this season, it would be historic. It has been
historical and magical. This is a great moment for Texas football,
especially going 9-3 coming off of last year's 4-7 season.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas, which entered the game ranked No. 20 in the nation,
dominated the 25th-ranked Bulldogs (8-5) in every phase of the
game. The UT defense, which started the year as the team's weak
point, held MSU to 87 yards rushing and kept the Bulldogs out of
the end zone until late in the fourth quarter, long after the
outcome had been decided.
</P>
<P>
   It also was a day when the Longhorns ended their long drought
against teams coached by Sherrill, who had defeated Texas in seven
consecutive meetings _ five with Texas A&AMP;M and two with MSU.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I just need to soothe and heal some feelings of our
players,'' Sherrill said. ``The only thing I didn't like was (the
UT fans) singing at the end, saying, `Poor Aggies.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill was mistaken. The fans were chanting, ``Poor Jackie.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas led 14-3 at halftime, thanks to McGarity's two long TD
receptions. But the game was decided in the third quarter when UT
outscored MSU 24-0 while Williams rushed for 104 yards and scored
both of his touchdowns _ on a 37-yard run and a two-yard plunge.
</P>
<P>
   McGarity set the tone of the day with two big plays in the first
half when the Longhorns burned Mississippi State's blitz.
</P>
<P>
   On a first-and-10 at the Texas 41, Applewhite found McGarity
open on a deep post pattern. McGarity caught the pass in full
stride at the MSU 20 and was two steps ahead of MSU cornerback
Kendall Roberson, who was expecting deep help from safety Anthony
Derricks. But Derricks was a step too late to get McGarity, who
sprinted to the end zone to make it 7-0 with 2:17 to go in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   McGarity burned the Bulldogs again in the second quarter,
turning a short pass into a 52-yard TD.
</P>
<P>
   On second-and-13 at the Texas 48, he caught a quick out for what
looked like a five-yard gain. But McGarity broke the attempted
tackle of cornerback Kendall Roberson, turned inside and scooted
past two other MSU defenders for clear sailing to the end zone,
giving the Longhorns a 14-0 lead with 5:11 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play a defense that takes lot of chances with blitzing,''
McGarity said. ``We took advantage of that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Applewhite was making all the right decisions, MSU
freshman quarterback Wayne Madkin was struggling. Madkin, who was
replaced by Matt Wyatt in the second and fourth quarters, finished
4-of-16 passing for 49 yards and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said all along that the freshman quarterback who played the
best would give his team the best chance to win,'' Sherrill said.
``Wayne struggled with his third-down conversions today, and Major
had a great game. But Major also has a lot of help around him out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt was in the game both times MSU scored _ on a 39-yard field
goal by Brian Hazelwood late in the second quarter and a five-yard
TD pass to Lahitia Grant with 5:07 to play.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas was in control from start to finish. The Longhorns did
not have turnover on a day when they amassed 463 yards of offense.
</P>
<P>
   And with Applewhite and McGarity beating the MSU blitz in the
first half when the Bulldogs were stacking the line of scrimmage,
things opened up for Williams in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the two TDs by Williams, Texas also scored
third-quarter points on a 47-yard field goal by Kris Stockton and
an 18-yard TD pass from Applewhite to Kwame Cavil after the defense
held MSU on a fourth-and-one play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mississippi State wanted to intimidate us,'' said UT guard Ben
Adams. ``They started the game doing a lot of talking, but we
decided we would just shut our mouths and go right at them. In the
second half, we just came out and mashed them. When you have our
310-pound guys going against their 250-pound defensive linemen, it
happens that way eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday marked the last game for 23 Texas seniors, including
seven starters on offense and two on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first day I arrived on campus, I heard about the
great history Texas has at the Cotton Bowl,'' Adams said. ``To
finally get back here in our last game and to win like this is
something all the seniors will cherish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
