<SLUG> BC-NY-MILLENNIUM-VIEWS-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BRINK OF MILLENNIUM, IT'S JUST ANOTHER DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nothing ages faster than the ephemera of New Year's
Eve. The discarded funny hats by dawn seem like ancient relics, the
sequined gowns as odd as the discarded styles of some justifiably
forgotten decade.
</P>
<P>
   But even as friends put their heads on each other's shoulders
and fell asleep on the subway, and others talked too fast so they
could stay awake for just a few more minutes, the world moved
ahead. The night before became nothing more than another night
before.
</P>
<P>
   At the brink of day on Friday, if you asked just about anybody
what they thought of being on the brink of a new century and
millennium, they said it seemed pretty much like any other year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the next 100 years will be any different than
the 100 years that came before,'' said John Bajrami, 41, who was
fishing on the Coney Island Pier.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bajrami appeared to change tacks. He said he thought that
technology would do amazing things, but that there would continue
to be fewer and fewer fish. Once, he supported himself by selling
fish he caught. His catch on Friday: ``three lousy herring.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the kind of thing one heard again and again Friday.
People profess not to care about time's passage, and then give
clear evidence that they see their own lives as a voyage through
time. Some think the world will become a crazier place as the
millennium nears. Some foresee awesome improvements.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the pier stood Ron Rogers, a 28-year-old
unemployed actor. He held a video camera, and was waiting for
sunrise. It was cold and clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``After such a terrible year, I wanted to see the first
sunrise,'' he said. ``Things still look pure. I feel some type of
hope.'' The millennium?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is so worried that the world is going to end. The
question is: What if it doesn't? What will you have done with your
life?''
</P>
<P>
   On the beach were five Buddhists, who had come to pray. They
brought wine and food to give to their ancestors. ``I am looking
back on my life and where I have been,'' said Man Hee, a
34-year-old artist who lives in Greenwich Village. ``I'm also
looking ahead to where I'm going.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two blocks away, on 15th Street, more than a half-dozen
fire trucks could be seen. Victor Estrada, 58, watched his
apartment burn. He told of his cat, Simon, going under the bed. An
asthmatic, Estrada could not breathe. He dived through a window and
got out down the fire escape, leaving the cat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about me or where I live,'' Estrada said. ``Man,
what do I say to my cat?''
</P>
<P>
   Four blocks to the east, there is a luncheonette called The
Islander. It is the kind of place where waitresses remember exactly
what customers want. Jokes are familiar enough that they no longer
need punch lines.
</P>
<P>
   A customer told Wanda Feliciano, a waitress, about the fire. She
hurried to the phone to call a friend who lived there. The friend
was fine.
</P>
<P>
   A subway conductor shuffled in, rubbing his eyes. ``What a
train,'' he said. ``Everybody who could have vomited did.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Feliciano preferred to talk about her hopes for the new
year. ``The new year has got to bring peace,'' she said. ``We've
got to get rid of all the bombs and stop destroying people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this year they'll find a cure for AIDS and cancer and
all those diseases,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and one more thing. ``I hate this job,'' she said, smiling
mischievously at her boss.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the counter were two discarded glittery top hats, as old as
time.
</P>
<P>
   In Times Square, little bits of confetti remained, though the
mountains of it had disappeared. The shattered glass of a cheap
wine bottle was next to a champagne magnum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a lot of unexpected things happening this
year,'' said Kenny Lever, 21, a student at Dowling College.
</P>
<P>
   In 1899, Rutherford discovered alpha and beta waves, Freud wrote
``The Interpretation of Dreams'' and the Philippines demanded
independence from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And 1999? ``Last night marked the beginning of an era,'' said
Kristy Bemis, 20, a college student from Utah in the Times Square
subway station. ``But we don't know what era.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Pommelle, who was in the same station, stressed the
uncertainty. ``I'll be honest with you,'' he said. ``No one knows
where we're headed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, people seemed anxious to keep on keeping on. A visit to
the Cub Room, a restaurant in SoHo, found a number of employees who
had worked until 3 or 4 a.m. at Thursday night's celebration, and
were back at work Friday by 9 a.m. Perhaps a bit bleary-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got three hours of sleep, and I feel great,'' said Cicely
Brooks, 21, a waitress who had had ridden four trains between the
restaurant and her home in the Bronx within a six-hour span.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got one hour, and I feel wonderful,'' said Billy Johnson, a
36-year-old waiter.
</P>
<P>
   Their boss, Gary Koenigsberg, was less Pollyanna-ish. ``It's
obviously not the most fun day of the year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it beats living in Central Park in Friday's frigid weather.
At the park's lagoon, where Holden Caulfield in ``The Catcher in
the Rye'' worried about what would happen to the ducks in the cold
weather, a homeless man threw them bread.
</P>
<P>
   He said that his name was Khanbais Wadu and that he and his
friends lived on a hill they called Holy Rock. He was waiting for a
church group to bring him a sandwich and juice. He said he had
hoped to hitch a ride to Florida with somebody coming here for the
celebration, but he had slept through it.
</P>
<P>
   Wadu said 1999 was going to be a year of abundant opportunity.
``It's like a threshold of a different beginning,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
