</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-INAUG-EXCERPT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM GOV. PATAKI'S INAUGURAL SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: With NY-INAUG) 
(rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following are excerpts from the second inaugural address that
Gov. George Pataki gave Friday in Albany:
</P>
<P>
   On the Spirit of the State
</P>
<P>
   There's a spirit in New York today, and it runs strong.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same spirit of courage that prompted Colonial farmers
to lay down their plows and take up arms to confront and conquer
the forces of tyranny on a farm near Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same spirit of hope that inspired immigrants, like my
grandparents, to leave their homelands and endure the seas, knowing
that the shadow of adversity would give way to a light that glows
from a beacon hand in New York Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same spirit of liberty that drove New Yorkers like
Susan B. Anthony and Frederick Douglass to dedicate their lives to
the pursuit of justice. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, seeking to renew that spirit, we charted a bold
new course for this state, a course driven by our determination to
see that government remains the people's servant and not their
master. Now we must commit ourselves to taking the next bold step
in the direction of New York's destiny, which _ as one New Yorker
expressed it _ was to create an atmosphere that is ``responsive to
every need of the people, and to the highest demands of that spirit
which drives us onward and upward.''
</P>
<P>
   That New Yorker was Gov. Theodore Roosevelt, and he spoke those
words 100 years ago to this very day as he delivered his inaugural
address to the people of this great state.
</P>
<P>
   On the Future
</P>
<P>
   As we march boldly into the next century, we will confront new
challenges and new opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Our ability to meet those challenges and seize those
opportunities requires only that we believe in ourselves and the
capacity for greatness that lies within each and every New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   If we have the courage to believe that, and we do, then New York
is going to lead America, not just into a new millennium, but into
a new age of discovery, innovation and prosperity, into a future
brighter than even the most glorious days of our past.
</P>
<P>
   That is New York's destiny. Today, we renew our claim to it.
</P>
<P>
   A Statement of Beliefs
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, we said: ``Cut taxes and return economic freedom
to working families and they will strengthen our economy.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, we said: ``Rein in the long arm of government,
and the men and women of our business community will create jobs.''
. . .
</P>
<P>
   In four years, we have done well. We have rekindled the spirit
of New York. And for that we can be proud. But the progress that
guides our destiny has only just begun.
</P>
<P>
   Six days from now, I will ask the Legislature to build on that
progress by reaffirming our allegiance to deeply held, core
principles.
</P>
<P>
   We believe in people, not bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   We believe in raising hopes, not taxes.
</P>
<P>
   We believe in protecting the rights of victims, not the rights
of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   We believe in big opportunities, not big government. . . .
</P>
<P>
   With a century of opportunity on the horizon, we the people of
New York must light the way to a brighter future for the nation and
the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
