<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS PROVES AWARDS TRAVELS NOT TOO DISTRACTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Ricky Williams admitted that his postseason revelry
might have left him out of shape going into preparations for the
Cotton Bowl. There was a trip to New York to pick up the Heisman
Trophy and another to Orlando, Fla., for a televised awards show.
</P>
<P>
   But he was his old self when the game started, rushing for 203
yards and two touchdowns in the Texas Longhorns' 38-11 victory
against Mississippi State yesterday. His performance earned him the
offensive player-of-the- game award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard on a radio show he was fat and out of shape,''
Longhorns coach Mack Brown said. ``I thought he looked pretty good
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Williams, ``Coming in here, I was hoping my pants still
fit. Luckily they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams also caught five passes for 45 yards, prompting someone
to ask Brown if there was anything his senior running back couldn't
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't come back next year; we already checked on that,''
Brown said. ``He can't sing either. I asked him to sing at a pep
rally and that was a mistake.'' Heisman winners Williams was the
seventh Heisman Trophy winner to play in the Cotton Bowl but only
the third to be on the winning side. Doak Walker led SMU to a 19-3
victory against Oregon in 1949, and Doug Flutie helped Boston
College defeat Houston, 45-28, in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Navy quarterback Roger Staubach, Texas running back Earl
Campbell, Auburn running back Bo Jackson and Notre Dame wide
receiver Tim Brown all lost in the Cotton Bowl. Offensive plan
Texas offensive coordinator Greg Davis said the Longhorns' plan
yesterday was to come out passing and open things up for Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We threw 20 passes in the first half because we wanted to
establish the fact we were two-dimensional and slow down their
blitzes,'' Davis said. ``We felt if we could do that, we could turn
the big boy loose behind that offensive line.'' Political football
Two former cheerleaders turned U.S. senators _ Sen. Trent Lott,
R-Miss., and Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas _ participated in
the coin toss yesterday. Lott, now the head yell leader for the
anti-Clinton forces in Washington, was a cheerleader for the
University of Mississippi in the 1962 Cotton Bowl, and Hutchison
was a cheerleader for the University of Texas in the 1964 Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said they had a bet on the game, a bulldog puppy against a
Longhorn steer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best part of a steer,'' Hutchison said. ``I want the whole
steer,'' Lott said. ``She's already trying to welch on the bet.'']
Walker honored Gov. George W. Bush declared yesterday Doak Walker
Day in Texas in honor of the former SMU Heisman Trophy winner who
died on Sept. 27. Yesterday marked the 50th anniversary of Walker's
final appearance in the Cotton Bowl, and it also would have been
his 72nd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's four children _ Russ, Scott, Kris Walcott and Laurie
Hunt _ attended the game and served as grand marshals of Thursday's
Cotton Bowl parade. The Cotton Bowl also painted Walker's No. 37 on
both 37-yard lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I crossed the 37-yard line I thought of him,'' said
Williams. Briefly Williams rushed for 104 yards in the third
quarter, marking the fifth time this season he's rushed for at
least 100 yards in a quarter. His 203 yards rushing are the most
ever by a Longhorns player in a bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   Major Applewhite's 225 yards passing are the third-most by a
Longhorns player in a bowl game. He has thrown for at least 200
yards in 10 consecutive games, a school record.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns' 24 points in the third quarter are a Cotton Bowl
record.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns are 10-9-1 in the Cotton Bowl and 18-18-2 in bowls
overall. This was their first Cotton Bowl victory since beating
Alabama in 1982, and they are the first Texas team to win here
since Texas A&AMP;M defeated Notre Dame in 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
