<HEADLINE>
1990S MANTRA: BULL MARKET WILL CARRY ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(ms) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The economy will probably cool and corporate profits will
probably slow, but stocks will stay in the stratosphere. That is
the dichotomy that market strategists believe is in store for
investors in the United States stock market this year.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of disconnect _ falling profit growth but rising stock
prices _ is familiar. After all, it was in the midst of last year's
disastrous third quarter, when corporate profits at America's
largest companies wound up falling an average of 3.2 percent, that
stocks shook off the bear-market blues and started soaring again.
The big-capitalization shares that make up both the Dow Jones
industrial average and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index took
off on Oct. 8 and by the end of the year had risen 18.7 percent and
28 percent, respectively, from their lows.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, the Dow Jones rose 16 percent and the S&AMP;P returned
nearly 26.7 percent. The biggest mover of them all was the Nasdaq
composite index, which gained a monumental 39.6 percent, largely on
the fortunes of technology stocks like Dell Computer, Intel and
Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Although the market has recovered nicely from its brush with the
bear last fall, corporate earnings have not rebounded nearly as
much. The final calculations for the fourth quarter will not be
tallied until February, but expectations are that full-year
earnings for S&AMP;P 500 companies averaged 5 percent, according to
Charles Hill, research director for the First Call Corporation,
which tracks earnings estimates. Many analysts and economists are
guessing that the rate of growth will be lower this year, an
average of 4.2 percent for stocks in the S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings this tepid are obviously not enough on their own to
keep stock prices at or near current levels. But many strategists
think stock prices will remain high this year. After all, it is
that kind of market: Internet stocks such as Amazon.com and Ebay
Inc. have scant earnings, but they are the hottest issues around.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, something other than earnings has been propelling
equity prices for years. Consider this: Earnings for stocks in the
S&AMP;P 500 have been flat since early 1997, but during that time the
index has risen nearly 67 percent, from 737.01 to 1,229.01. Since
1995, the S&AMP;P has almost doubled, while average earnings are
expected to have advanced only 28 percent for the period.
</P>
<P>
   The factors other than earnings that have driven stocks to
historically high valuations will keep them aloft this year,
strategists say. The most significant factors are barrels of cash
on the sidelines earmarked for stocks, a continued explosion in the
growth of the nation's money supply and more corporate megamergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Astonishingly, after yet another good year in stocks, the
outlook going into next year is still pretty favorable,'' Byron R.
Wien, chief domestic investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter in New York, said late last year. ``My view is we'll have
another up year _ not a 20 percent year, but maybe a 10 percent
year'' for the S&AMP;P stocks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, most market predictions are barely worth the paper
they're printed on. But Wien has proved fairly prescient on stock
movements recently. A year ago he predicted, among other things,
that technology stocks would re-emerge as market leaders and that
the Dow would roar to 9,000 in the spring, only to fall to 7,000
later in the year. Although he was wrong about the reason for the
decline in the Dow _ he thought inflation and rising interest rates
would be the culprits _ his numbers were pretty close. The Dow was
at 9,211.84 on May 13 and fell to 7,539.07 on Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Wien thinks stocks will rise again this year for two reasons.
One is that central banks around the world are expanding their
money supply, and that is usually good for equities. Even more
important, ``It doesn't look like we're going to have a
recession,'' he said. ``The economy didn't do as badly in the third
and fourth quarter as everybody thought it would.'' As a result, he
predicts that average earnings of companies on the S&AMP;P could rise 7
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Still, all is not rosy on the economic front. The nation's trade
deficit will almost certainly worsen as Asian economies begin to
recover and flood American shores with cheap products. Furthermore,
the ability of corporations to raise prices in the new deflationary
world is nonexistent, a factor that pushes down profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   This is unlikely to change. James Paulsen, chief investment
officer at Norwest Investment Management in Minneapolis says that
both the supply of goods and the capacity to make them have been
growing faster than demand for the last four years. This imbalance
cannot go on forever without some unhappy consequences, like plant
closings and ensuing layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, sluggish profit growth is likely to decrease
capital spending, which has been the jet propellant behind many
stocks recently. And as layoffs rise, consumer confidence may fall,
putting pressure on stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But as the bulls correctly point out, stocks have climbed this
wall of worry before, and admirably. So another good, if not great,
year for stocks may be in the cards.
</P>
<P>
   A big push for stocks will very likely come from the billions of
dollars currently sitting on the sidelines waiting to be invested,
according to Christine A. Callies, equity strategist at Credit
Suisse First Boston. She said that the year-over-year growth of
assets held in retail money market mutual funds hit 24.8 percent in
October, the most recent data available and the highest rate since
1990. ``There was one growth rate of 23 percent in 1996, but it's
quite rare,'' Ms. Callies said. ``This year, the growth rate really
started to sprint over the course of the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Callies thinks that this money is headed for equities.
``Because employment is reasonably good and wages are rising, we
doubt that this money is being piled up to support consumer life
styles,'' she said. ``This appears to be recycled from other
sources and stored there with intent of putting it to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Another force that will continue to be positive for stocks is
merger mania. Edward M. Kerschner, chief strategist at Paine
Webber, expects that record levels of merger and acquisition
activity seen in 1998 will extend into 1999. Kerschner pointed to
some factors that would drive deals this year: Mergers will appeal
to companies trying to gain economies of scale and scope _ for
example, by offering consumers one-stop shopping _ and to those
looking to acquire new technology or assets that would be
impossible to build quickly. Corporate combinations are also the
answer for companies that want to expand internationally, move into
higher-margin businesses or respond to deregulation, according to
Kerschner. All in all, a pretty compelling case for lots more
mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   But while some aspects of the market may look familiar in 1999,
there will also be significant differences. For example, index-fund
investing may no longer produce results superior to those obtained
by seasoned stock pickers.
</P>
<P>
   It may be just a straw in the wind, but according to Lipper
Inc., the mutual-fund research firm in Summit, N.J., funds in two
of the most popular stock fund categories were beating the return
of the S&AMP;P 500 index during the last months of 1998. From the end
of October to mid-December, the average capital appreciation fund
gained 8.86 percent and the average growth fund returned 7.69
percent. The S&AMP;P returned 7.63 percent during the period.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the market may shift to reward stock picking over
basket picking, a reverse of the trend throughout the decade.
</P>
<P>
   And even though high-priced growth stocks, particularly those in
the technology sector, have been the place to be in recent months,
more defensive issues might be the favorites this year. Strategists
who question the market's ability to make 1999 the fifth
consecutive year of returns of 20 percent or more suggest that
investors focus on high-yielding stocks of good-quality companies,
such as utilities, consumer goods manufacturers or integrated oil
concerns. With inflation nowhere to be seen and the possibility of
future credit loosening by the Federal Reserve Board, shares in
these kinds of companies would seem to be a safe but profitable
place for investors to stash some cash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
