u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-BUDGET-1STLD     01-01 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-BUDGET-1STLD-ART-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO PROPOSE INCREASED DEFENSE SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs to clarify 7th graf, removing reference to percentage
increase.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(htv) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Heeding warnings from the nation's military chiefs,
President Clinton has decided to propose the first real increase in
the Pentagon's budget in nearly a decade and the largest since the
Cold War buildup of the mid-1980s, administration and defense
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposal, only the first step in a drawn-out process
with Congress, would reverse years of dwindling defense resources
after the collapse of the Soviet Union. It would address growing
strains, the officials said, caused by aging weapons and increasing
operations overseas, from Bosnia to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal represents a significant political shift for
Clinton. A Democrat who has often had an uneasy relationship with
the military, he came into office in the wake of the Cold War,
focused more on his domestic initiatives than on defense.
</P>
<P>
   But in the face of growing complaints about military readiness,
both from within the military and from Republicans, he was
persuaded to seek an increase of more than $4 billion in the
defense budget for fiscal 2000 and about $100 billion over the next
six years. That is the first increase, discounting inflation, since
1991, when spending spiked slightly for the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to announce the increase in his weekly radio
address on Saturday, and the early word of his plans appeared to be
an effort to blunt new criticism. It is unclear, however, how he
would pay for his proposals, setting the stage for what is sure to
be an intense fight with the new Congress over defense spending.
</P>
<P>
   In the budget he will submit to Congress in a month, Clinton
plans to propose increasing spending for the Department of Defense
to nearly $269 billion, the officials said, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also agreed to let the department keep another $8
billion freed up as a result of lower-than-expected inflation and
fuel prices, money that normally would be returned to the Treasury,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the Pentagon would have $12 billion in new funds
to spend on everything from new equipment to spare parts to raises
for the nation's military personnel in the fiscal year that begins
in October.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next six years, Clinton's budget would propose
additional spending of slightly more than $100 billion. That would
represent the most significant rise in military spending since the
buildup by President Reagan in the early 1980s, although it is only
two-thirds of what the military chiefs had said they would want in
an ideal world.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry
H. Shelton, and the chiefs of the Army, Air Force, Navy and Marine
Corps are scheduled to appear before the Senate's Committee on
Armed Services.
</P>
<P>
   When they last testified before the committee in September, they
faced unusually hostile questioning over the military's readiness
problems from Republicans who accused them of having sugar-coated
issues like pilot shortages and training cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, the Arizona Republican who is considering a
presidential run in 2000, said then that the chiefs were ``not
candid to this member in the problems and challenges that we
faced.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite strict spending caps set by the Balanced Budget Act of
1997, many Republicans have called for much larger increases in the
Pentagon's budget, accusing Clinton of having let the military
become ``hollow'' and the generals and admirals of not blowing the
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James M. Inhofe, R.-Okla., who leads the Senate's
subcommittee on military readiness, reacted strongly when asked
about Clinton's plan to increase spending now, saying the president
was belatedly trying to head off Republican criticism that he has
skimped on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's personally responsible for the defamation of our defense
system and our hollow forces,'' the senator said. ``The president
is going to try to make it look like he's a pro-defense president.
It's an outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials dismiss the accusations. In interviews
this week, they said Clinton's proposals reflected the reality of
today's military. The armed services are doing more _ from flying
over Kosovo to bombing Iraq _ while the jets, ships and other
equipment bought during Reagan's buildup have become old and need
replacements or at least spare parts.
</P>
<P>
   The officials refused to say exactly how Clinton would propose
paying for the increase in defense spending. He has already vowed
not to spend the recent federal surplus until he and Congress agree
on a way to shore up the Social Security system, which is lurching
toward insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   And the Balanced Budget Act has placed strict caps on total
discretionary spending, requiring that any increases be offset by
reductions elsewhere. Clinton could propose to pay for new defense
spending by cutting other domestic programs, although he has not
done so in the past and seems unlikely to now.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the administration is expected to find or create new
pots of money that could be used for new increases. One
administration official said Clinton would call for increases in
both defense and domestic programs when he outlines his budget
priorities, beginning with the State of the Union address later
this month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For much of the last year, Defense Secretary William Cohen and
the service chiefs have been steadily trying to build a case for an
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Even though no threat on the scale of the Soviet Union has
emerged to challenge U.S. supremacy, they have argued that the
declining or flat budgets since the Reagan years have left the
country spending less on defense as a portion of the total federal
budget _ now just under 15 percent _ than at any time since World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   When Cohen asked the chiefs to list their budget priorities,
they came back with requests for personnel and equipment that
totaled $148 billion over the next six years. Cohen cut the
requests back to $112 billion. Negotiations with Clinton's budget
aides have since whittled that down to roughly $100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still short of what we needed,'' one uniformed officer
grumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, most Pentagon officials interviewed this week
sounded pleased. One senior officer said that $12 billion in the
coming fiscal year and more than $100 billion over six years would
go a long way toward shoring up the areas of the budget under the
most strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their most critical needs could be covered with something over
$100 billion,'' the officer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
