A4938 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-FIRST-BOS &LR;      01-01 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-FIRST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIRST BABY OF '99 DEBUTS IN BOSTON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pregnant women have been known to schedule their
surgical deliveries for New Year's Eve to get a chance at having
the first baby of the year. Others try to slow their labor as
midnight approaches, even getting a helping hand from the
obstetrician to start a new life on an auspicious note.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Heidi Slayton, whose daughter Alanna dropped
into this world at Brigham and Women's Hospital just as the New
Year's ball dropped over Times Square, making her perhaps the first
baby born in the United States in 1999. Only a 12:01 a.m. New
Year's baby born in Jacksonville, Fla., has so far emerged to
compare to Slayton's achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think anything about it. I just gave birth.
... I couldn't hold her in,'' said Heidi Slayton, 29, of
Dorchester, now a mother of five, at a press conference  &UR; yesterday &LR; 
with her husband, Wayne. ``I know (the dropping ball) was on TV,
but I could not describe it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Alanna's extraordinary timing _ judged to be two seconds
into the new year by hospital officials _ made the Slaytons the
star players in the closest thing to a New Year's Day bowl game for
hospitals as Brigham and Women's grabbed Boston's first baby
bragging rights for the third time in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had joked a lot with her due date being Dec. 30'' about
having a New Year's baby, ``but I never thought it would happen,''
said Dr. Dorothy Dowling, the Slaytons' obstetrician.
</P>
<P>
   Obstetricians and other delivery room personnel freely admit to
a friendly competition among hospitals over delivering the year's
first baby. Though few would speed up or slow down a delivery to
win, they are quite aware of one another as the magic hour
approaches, sometimes calling other Boston hospitals to scope out
the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Massachusetts General Hospital, whose first baby of
the new year lagged the Slaytons' baby by 40 minutes, put on a
brave face at their showing, noting the hospital has not delivered
the New Year's baby since officials revived its maternity ward
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is that we have healthy babies and healthy
moms and families,'' said Mass. General spokeswoman Georgia Peirce.
But she said hospital staff are quite aware of the coup a New
Year's first would bring ``because it's kind of an annual event
that everyone waits for.''
</P>
<P>
   And Peirce marveled at the apparently efficient timing that
Mass. General is up against in the Boston New Year's baby
competition, noting that Brigham and Women's had marked the exact
second that the Slaytons' child emerged from the womb. ``I'm not
sure we have a synchronized timer or a photo finish,'' said Peirce,
whose hospital tracks births down only to the minute.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, first baby of the year is not exactly an official
record. Government statistics include no such category, leaving it
to the news media to keep track, and there are few rules governing
first-baby claims.
</P>
<P>
   In the Slaytons' case, Dowling had to estimate the time because
of a slight difference between the hospital room's clock and the
official New Year's clock in New York City. Ultimately, she timed
the baby's birth based on the falling ball in Times Square and the
room clock's second hand.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Brigham and Women's officials did not claim that
Alanna Naomi Slayton was America's first 1999 baby; that fell to
reporters. But Friday, officials at Baptist Medical Center in
Jacksonville, Fla., seemed to concede Brigham's supremacy, revising
the birth time of their first baby from one second after midnight
to 12:01 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   But the imprecision in the Slaytons' case is small stuff
compared to other deliveries where parents are determined to have a
New Year's baby even though they lose a tax deduction for the
preceding year if the baby is born after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Jenelle Macaskill recalls that she ``stopped pushing'' at around
11:30 p.m. on New Year's Eve 1996 when she realized she had a
chance to deliver a New Year's baby at Melrose-Wakefield Hospital.
Little Collin Macaskill entered this world at 20 seconds past the
stroke of midnight as a nurse conveyed news of the blessed event by
telephone to a reporter from a Boston TV station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started up as a joke,'' recalled Macaskill, who was almost
three weeks overdue and desperate to deliver on New Year's Eve. But
as midnight approached, both she and her doctor worked together to
produce the first baby in the state of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When Collin's head emerged just before midnight, Macaskill said
her doctor ``held the head for a couple of minutes. That's why he
was out exactly at midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Other parents plan ahead to get a New Year's baby by scheduling
caesarean section deliveries on New Year's Eve. Dr. Toni Beth
Walzer of Brigham and Women's delivered the first baby in Richmond,
Va., a few years ago by performing a caesarean section just after
midnight, which is ``sort of cheating,'' she told the Globe in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the Slaytons more or less let nature take its
course. Heidi Slayton was given medication to induce stronger
contractions during her labor as well as an epidural to ease the
pain, but Alanna decided when to come out.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 10, I turned to Dr. Dowling and said, `We're shooting for
midnight,' '' recalled Heidi, but the labor was going so slowly
that it seemed unrealistic. Then, with a sudden spurt, Alanna, at 7
pounds 3 ounces, 20 inches, emerged, to the applause of hospital
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she came fully out, that's when we heard the crowd shout,
`Happy New Year,' '' said Wayne Slayton, 29, a youth counselor for
the city of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the baby sweepstakes is a numbers game, and Brigham
and Women's has a distinct advantage because it delivers by far the
most babies, accounting for more than 10 percent of the births in
the entire state in 1996. This is the fourth time in the last eight
years for which records are available that Brigham and Women's has
landed Boston's first baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deliver more than 10,000 babies. There's a good chance our
number will come up,'' said Brigham and Women's spokeswoman
Christine A. Baratta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
