<SLUG> BC-OBITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON TAYLOR, 78, MOVIE ACTOR AND DIRECTOR  
 EDWARD MERVOSH, 57, BUSINESS JOURNALIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Pa.)  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Don Taylor, a film actor of the 1940s and '50s who later turned
to directing, died on Tuesday at the UCLA Medical Center in Los
Angeles. He was 78 and lived in Santa Monica, Calif.
 &HT;    The cause was heart failure, his family said.
 &HT;    Taylor, who was born in Pittsburgh, began acting while attending
Penn State University, appearing in college presentations and more
than 80 summer stock productions. In his senior year, while playing
the lead in ``The Taming of the Shrew,'' he attracted the attention
of two Penn State alumni, Julius and Phil Epstein, the
screenwriters of ``Casablanca,'' who invited him to Hollywood.
 &HT;    He hitchhiked to California after graduation, and after several
unsuccessful screen tests was eventually signed to a seven-year
contract by MGM. While serving in the Air Force in World War II he
was recruited by Irving ``Swifty'' Lazar for a lead role in Moss
Hart's production of ``Winged Victory'' for the armed forces, and
later reprised his role in the film version.
 &HT;    After his discharge, he starred in the movie ``Naked City'' and
then won the role of Elizabeth Taylor's bridegroom in ``Father of
the Bride.'' He appeared in numerous war movies, including
``Battleground,'' with Ricardo Montalban and James Whitmore;
``Flying Leathernecks,'' with John Wayne; ``Submarine Command'' and
``Stalag 17,'' with William Holden, and ``Destination Gobi,'' with
Richard Widmark.
 &HT;    After moving behind the camera in the late 1950s, Taylor
directed 15 movies, among them ``Escape From the Planet of the
Apes,'' ``Tom Sawyer,'' ``The Island of Dr. Moreau,'' ``Damien:
Omen II,'' ``The Final Countdown'' and ``Echoes of a Summer,'' as
well as more than 400 television dramas.
 &HT;    He was also a writer, and was nominated for an Emmy award for
his script for an NBC television show, ``The Night They Tore Down
Riley's Bar.''
 &HT;    He is survived by his wife, Hazel Court Taylor, an actress; two
daughters, Avery Taylor Moore of San Francisco and Anne Taylor
Fleming of Los Angeles; a son, Jonathan of Los Angeles; a
stepdaughter, Sally Walsh of Los Angeles; a sister, Janet Tuttle of
Cape May, N.J., and a granddaughter.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edward Mervosh, 57, business journalist
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Edward Mervosh, an economist and business journalist,
died on Tuesday at St. Clare's Hospital in Manhattan. He was 57.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure, according to his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Mervosh was an economist for the Research Institute of America,
Chase Manhattan Bank and the American Importers Association before
joining Business Week in 1971 as a contributing editor.
</P>
<P>
   At Business Week, he was associate economics editor, a senior
economics correspondent and a European economics correspondent
based in Brussels, Belgium, before being named economics editor in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the magazine in 1985, he worked as a senior editor
and columnist for U.S. News &AMP; World Report. He was also a
correspondent and commentator for the Financial News Network and
CBS before becoming editor in chief of International Business in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Mervosh left a position as a managing director for the Economist
Group in 1995 and co-founded Global Business, an Internet business
publication. Last year he joined KPMG Peat Marwick as a managing
editor for an online banking publication.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his companion, Patty Swain, of Manhattan; his
daughter, Heather Carson of San Diego; a sister, Joyce Stromman of
Cleveland, and an aunt, Nelda Perkins of Pittsburgh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
