<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-BANKING-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKING: FINANCIAL INSTITUTIONS GO ONE-STOP-SHOPPING ROUTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Monday, Jan. 4) 
(bl) 
By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Banking is dead. Long live banking.
</P>
<P>
   If a slew of big bank mergers over the last few years was not
reminder enough, then the losses banks took in 1998 by lending to
risky hedge funds like Long-Term Capital Management and by trading
in exotic overseas markets may be proof enough that banking as we
once knew it is firmly passe.
</P>
<P>
   In its place, America now has a high-octane form of banking that
our grandparents would not recognize. Many banks now proffer a
financial cornucopia that includes credit cards, stocks, bonds,
mutual funds, mortgages, auto loans, brokerage services and
insurance. And the really big banks also offer investment banking
advice, private banking and asset management services, derivatives
and large corporate loans.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, banks, brokerage firms, mutual fund companies and
insurers are so eager to invade one another's turf that those neat
little categories they inhabit do not adequately describe all of
the services they engage in or want to provide. All of this goes to
show that as banking ceases to be a useful way to describe a broad
range of America's money-changers, a handy replacement term for
what all of them are doing seems to be financial services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said before that banking is dead and we should bury it,''
said Richard M. Kovacevich, the chief executive of Wells Fargo &AMP;
Co., a bank _ oops, financial services concern _ formed last year
through Norwest Corp.'s acquisition of Wells Fargo. ``A lot of
these businesses were segmented, not because that's the way
consumers wanted it, but because that's what the regulations
mandated. And those regulations are breaking down now.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is still not much of a consensus on the wisdom
of combining the staid workings of plain vanilla banking with the
riskier mechanics of investment banking _ especially when the nest
eggs of individual depositors could be at stake. And there is not a
consensus on how adequately these new high-fliers will meet the
financial needs of low-income communities.
</P>
<P>
   But financial services are clearly heading in the direction of
once-unheard of combinations. Over the next year, and in years to
come, the financial services industry will continue to evolve,
albeit in fits and starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convergence between commercial and investment banking is
sure to be one of the great themes in 1999,'' a group of Merrill
Lynch analysts noted in a recent research report. ``However, few
companies, to date, have effectively blended a securities and
commercial banking model.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a continuing tale in 1999 and beyond will be how well
some of the big financial services mergers play out. The two
book-end deals in this regard are last year's combination of
Citicorp and Travelers Group Inc. to form Citigroup and the German
banking giant Deutsche Bank AG's planned acquisition of Bankers
Trust Corp. Citigroup has already had plenty of trouble knitting
together its unwieldy investment and corporate banking operations,
while many analysts and industry observers see the Deutsche Bank
deal as doomed from the start given the problems the German company
has encountered trying to break into investment banking in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   All of America's big, multinational banks could face substantial
headaches if ill-considered loans go sour in a slowing domestic
economy. Financial turmoil abroad, perhaps the most significant
business development of last year, also promises to pose continuing
hurdles for big banks.
</P>
<P>
   On the consumer side of the ledger, another landmark deal last
year was Nationsbank's acquisition of BankAmerica to form a new
national behemoth named, surprise, surprise, BankAmerica. The new
BankAmerica Corp. is the first truly coast-to-coast national bank,
complete with a brokerage operation and an appetite to enter other
lines of business. Its size and diversity will increase the
pressure on smaller banks to eat or be eaten in the merger game.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller banks, those that rely heavily on traditional
deposit-taking and lending, face tough sledding this year. While
the Year 2000 computer problem is a well-known bugaboo, there are
other problems lurking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to be in a world where interest rates are going lower,
and that's not a friendly environment for a deposit-taking bank,''
said David Berry, an analyst with Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods Inc.
``That's because they can't bring deposit rates much lower than
they already are and they will have to charge less for the money
they are lending out because interest rates are dropping. That
means profits are going to go lower, too.''
</P>
<P>
   To make up for declining profits on loans, traditional banks can
be expected to try to get more fees from products like checking and
savings accounts. While consumers can expect to encounter sticker
shock if banks get more fee-happy, banks no longer have as much
wiggle room to charge fees because competition has grown more
intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the real issue is going to be revenue generation,''
said H. Rodgin Cohen, a banking lawyer with the New York law firm
of Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell. ``And competition remains extremely intense
so there's going to be a lot of pressure on banks to figure out
where earnings are going to come from.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, many big insurers, like Metropolitan Life
Insurance Co., are converting to stock ownership so they have more
ways to pay for growth as the financial services industry
consolidates. Mutual fund titans like Fidelity Investments have to
worry about how easy it will be to keep growing and are already
offering financial services beyond fund management. Midsized
brokerage firms like Paine Webber will have to struggle to remain
competitive with giants like Merrill Lynch, while securities firms
of all sizes are concerned about the possible setback from a
slowing economy and continuing economic uncertainty abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, uncertainty about the big economic picture will loom
over financial services firms this year and may produce unpleasant
earnings surprises at some companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be like popcorn,'' Berry said. ``There will be just
enough popping to keep you on edge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 2227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
