u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      01-01 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cowboys pit experience vs. Cardinals' resilience
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IRVING _ The Arizona Cardinals had one last chance to get into
field-goal position and win the game without going into overtime.
The postseason depended on another fourth-quarter rally, and though
less than 20 seconds remained, quarterback Jake Plummer didn't
disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   With one pass, Plummer put the Cardinals in Chris Jacke's range,
then watched Jacke's 52-yard field goal soar through the uprights
as time expired, pushing Arizona past the San Diego Chargers on
Sunday and giving the Cardinals the NFC's final wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals will need to draw on that stick-to-itiveness when
they face the Dallas Cowboys at 3:05 today at Texas Stadium in a
first-round playoff game. The Cowboys have won the last nine times
the Cardinals have come to Dallas and taken 16 of the last 17
matchups overall.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Cardinals are making their first postseason
appearance since 1982, the Cowboys are accustomed to elimination
games. Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman owns three Super Bowl rings,
a testament to his poise under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But Plummer is quickly earning his own reputation. A master of
the comeback, he guided the Cards to seven victories by three
points or less this season, an NFL record.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been in a lot of games they had to win to get into the
playoffs, and I'm sure it felt like a playoff game to them,''
Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer led the first fourth-quarter rally in Week 3, when the
Cardinals scored 17 points for a 17-3 victory over Philadelphia.
The Cardinals later scored in the final minutes to beat St. Louis,
Detroit, Washington, Philadelphia again (in overtime) and San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   And they almost added Dallas to that list of victims when
Plummer threw for 314 second-half yards and saw what would have
been a game-tying touchdown pass fall incomplete in the end zone on
the final play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You love that situation,'' Plummer said of last-second
heroics. ``We've been in it too many times, but we're never going
to give up. We've got a new team out there. We've got a new
attitude and a new ballclub that goes out and gives everything
every single game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same playoff-type mentality for which Aikman is known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the finality of a playoff game,'' said Aikman, who is
11-2 in the postseason. ``You have to get the job done. There are
no excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   But as much as the Cardinals have been winning under pressure,
they haven't done it in the postseason. Few of them were even in
grade school in 1975, the last time the Cardinals went to the
playoffs in a non-strike season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact the Cowboys have a lot of experience could work in
their favor, but I hope it won't make any difference,'' said
Plummer, who signed a $29 million contract extension less than two
weeks ago. ``It will be a fun first-time experience. We'll just try
to stay cool.''
</P>
<P>
   When the season began, Plummer and his offensive line struggled
against the blitz. The fleet-footed quarterback often stumbled,
throwing more interceptions (20) than touchdowns (17). But his
performance against Dallas in that last meeting Nov. 15 showed the
Cowboys he's maturing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake is a good young player,'' Aikman said. ``He's very
athletic and does a good job giving them a spark. He will be a
great player at some point. He'll get better as his supporting cast
gets better.''
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, his support isn't bad. Frank Sanders led the
NFC with 89 receptions and was fifth with 1,145 receiving yards.
Rob Moore had 892 yards in receptions, and fullback Larry Centers
caught 69 passes for 559 yards. In all, the Cardinals ranked eighth
in the NFL with 217.6 yards passing per game.
</P>
<P>
   Their ground game, behind Adrian Murrell, averaged 101.7 yards
per contest. Murrell had his third consecutive 1,000-yard season,
carrying 274 times for 1,042 yards and eight touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've become more resilient,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   As have the Cowboys, who surprised many with their 10-6
turnaround after last year's 6-10 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough the way the whole season went last year,'' Aikman
said. ``It was a relief for all of us when it was over. We had been
accustomed to being in the playoffs. I'm proud of the way we
handled all the adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll be counting on that experience today.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them (the Cardinals) haven't been in the playoffs, so
they'll be excited,'' Dallas defensive back Kevin Smith said.
``Most of us have been in the playoffs and know how to handle it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
