<HEADLINE>
FISET'S GOAL IS TO PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ It's not exactly the sort of thing one can
make a New Year's resolution about, but Kings goalie Stephane Fiset
definitely is hoping 1999 will bring with it better health than did
1998.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time this season, he has been deemed fit to play
after rehabilitating a groin injury, though Coach Larry Robinson
said Friday that Fiset will serve tonight as Jamie Storr's backup
when the Kings play host to the Colorado Avalanche. With Fiset
healthy, the Kings assigned Manny Legace to the Long Beach Ice
Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie's playing good right now,'' Fiset said of Storr, who has
allowed two goals or less in each of the last five games, four of
them victories by the Kings (12-21-3). ``The most important thing
is to win some games. Everybody knows I like to play against
Colorado. But it doesn't matter who plays. We need some wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado traded Fiset to the Kings in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still have so many guys I played with, and they're all
good friends,'' Fiset said. ``I have good memories there. It's
always fun to play against them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he had chosen to play Storr tonight rather than Fiset,
Coach Larry Robinson said, ``He's playing well. He deserves to be
in there. What's the old saying? If it ain't broke, don't fix it.
Right now, there's no justification for changing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   STILL SORE
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Doug Bodger is expected to miss his second game since
suffering cervical and shoulder strains and bruises when checked
into the boards from behind by Dallas Drake during the Kings' 4-2
victory at Phoenix on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Drake received a four-game suspension from the NHL for the play,
prompting Bodger to say, ``If it doesn't get any better, I may miss
more games than him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodger added, ``It's not getting any better. It feels good in
the evening and in the afternoon. But when I wake up in the
morning, it's not good. I thought I was going to skate (Friday),
but there's no sense going out there feeling like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson made it clear he was puzzled Drake didn't receive a
longer suspension, considering defenseman Rob Blake received a
three-game sentence last month for a slash to the arm that didn't
even cause Vancouver's Harry York to miss a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to make his decisions,'' Robinson said, referring to
NHL vice president Colin Campbell, the judge and jury in cases of
supplementary discipline. ``My feeling is, it's a little different
if you slash somebody on the arm. In (Bodger's) case, you're
talking about (a hit that could have resulted in) paralysis if he'd
been hit the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   SAKIC QUESTIONABLE
</P>
<P>
   Colorado center Joe Sakic, who has missed the last seven games
with a sprained right shoulder, may return to the lineup tonight.
If he does, he'll probably center a line with Peter Forsberg and
rookie Milan Hejduk.
</P>
<P>
   Sakic (12 goals, 32 points) took part in the pregame skate
before Colorado's 6-3 loss to the New York Rangers on Thursday
night, but opted not to play because he said he wasn't 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure we don't take a hit and take a setback,''
Sakic said.
</P>
<P>
   COACHING CONFRONTATION
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Colorado's game Thursday, Rangers coach John
Muckler confronted Avalanche coach Bob Hartley and criticized him
for playing tough guys Scott Parker and Jeff Odgers against Wayne
Gretzky's line at the end of the game.
</P>
<P>
   `That's a minor-league move,` Muckler told the Rocky Mountain
News. `I don't mind if the game's within reach, but it's over with.
I just took it as a cheap shot, which it was.`
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Muckler said to him, Hartley replied, ``He wished me
a happy New Year.''
</P>
<P>
   More seriously, he said, `Why double-shift a guy like Peter
Forsberg when we have a game in two days and I can keep a kid like
Scotty who needs to play on the ice?`
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky said, `I don't think he tried to goon it up. (But) let's
put it this way: The matchup got a little interesting in the last
eight minutes. John took exception to that.`
</P>
<P>
   LOOSE PUCKS
</P>
<P>
   Winger Eric Lacroix has been cleared to play (though not
activated), three weeks after suffering a fractured sternum in a
3-0 victory over Vancouver. Winger Sandy Moger, who has played only
once since Oct. 30 because of a strained lower back, also is close
to being ready to play. The Kings have only one roster spot open,
and wingers Steve McKenna and Russ Courtnall also are expected back
in the next few weeks, which will create some decisions for General
Manager Dave Taylor. ... Winger Dan Bylsma's wife, Mary Beth, is
scheduled to enter the hospital at 10 tonight to give birth to the
couple's first child. The plan is for doctors to induce labor.
Bylsma will join his wife at the hospital after the game. Asked if
he'd be distracted if he's in the lineup tonight, Bylsma said,
``When you're out there on the ice, it's tough to think about
anything other than the people coming at you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
