<HEADER>
A4947 &Cx1f; taf-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-COMMODITIES-600&AMP;     01-01 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-COMMODITIES-600&AMP;ADD-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMODITIES: BAD NEWS FOR DEVELOPING COUNTRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oil is about $12 a barrel, near its lowest level in 12 years.
Copper is 66 cents a pound, its lowest price in 11 years. Aluminum
is $1,241 a metric ton, the least expensive it has been in almost
five years, and, like other commodities, still falling in price.
The major commodity indexes are at or near their lowest levels in
more than two decades. And analysts are not predicting a turnaround
soon.
</P>
<P>
   That's great for consumers. Gasoline prices, adjusted for
inflation, are the lowest they have been since the 1950s. Those low
prices are even better than a tax cut at stimulating spending,
economists say, and they have been a major contributor to the
continuing decline in inflation here and in other developed
economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt, the collapse of commodity prices provided an
important spur to U.S. disinflation,'' said John Lipsky, chief
economist at Chase Manhattan Bank. He is forecasting an inflation
rate of just 1 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   But low commodity prices are bad for much of the developing
world _ for Russia, Chile, Mexico, Indonesia, Malaysia and Zambia.
And they are not so good for some major developed nations,
including Australia, New Zealand and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   These countries depend on commodity sales to spur economic
growth, and many of them also count on the revenue to pay for a
major portion of their government spending. The price declines mean
they have less of both.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and Latin America will be especially hard hit. About 60
percent of Russia's export earnings are from oil, natural gas and
precious and base metals. And a major portion of the revenue for
the Russian budget comes from these sales and taxes on them. In
Latin America, 50 percent of Venezuela's government revenue, 30
percent of Mexico's and 25 percent of Ecuador's come from oil.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse in commodity prices since October 1997 has been
dramatic and has been one of the major ways the Asian financial
crisis, which began in Thailand in July 1997, has spread around the
world. The collapse of the economies in Asia, whose people had been
major consumers of oil, copper, timber, cotton, textiles and other
commodities, sent prices tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Since autumn 1997, prices have plunged 45 percent for oil, 44
percent for natural gas and 30 percent for copper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no optimism about the demand for industrial commodities
in the first half of 1999,'' said William O'Neill, director of
futures research at Merrill Lynch. And, he added, the recovery will
be ``a long, slow process.''
</P>
<P>
   Neal Shear, head of commodities trading at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, is even more pessimistic. He said commodity prices will be
``in a flat to lower trend'' this year. His reason: He does not
expect demand to recover.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks the economies in Europe will be flat and growth in the
United States will slow, and he adds, ``Asia will not recover in
1999.''
</P>
<P>
   He also worries that there is a chance commodities may fall
further if market psychology leads to the kind of overselling that
often occurs when prices are on a long decline.
</P>
<P>
   What also could help delay a recovery in commodity prices is a
rebound in the strength of the dollar, which fell 7.1 percent
against the German mark and 12.8 percent against the Japanese yen
last year. Most of those declines came in the last five months of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Major commodities, like oil, are priced in dollars. This means,
for one thing, that when the dollar weakens against the yen, oil
prices in yen are lower for the Japanese. If the dollar rebounds,
commodity prices are likely to rise for those spending yen and
other Asian currencies, slowing the revival of demand in Asia that
is ultimately crucial to any commodity rebound.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The cutting of interest rates by the Federal Reserve, in an
effort to stabilize financial markets and prevent the American
economy from falling into a recession, helped weaken the dollar at
the end last year. The unwinding of special hedge fund trades
involving the yen, as investors panicked in the wake of the
collapse of Long-Term Capital Management, also sent the dollar
sharply lower against the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
   But the dollar has not lost value against all foreign
currencies, which means commodity prices will get less of a boost
than might be apparent from looking only at the mark and the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar has remained strong against the currencies of two of
America's biggest trading partners, Canada and Mexico. Overall, the
trade-weighted dollar _ computed by measuring the strength of the
American currency in relation to currencies of the country's chief
trading partners _ still rose last year. According to the Federal
Reserve Bank of Dallas, the trade-weighted dollar was up almost 1
percent through October.
</P>
<P>
   And although most analysts expect further rate cuts by the Fed,
some economists expect the dollar to stay at current levels or
rally this year. One reason is that the United States will still be
attractive to investors because it will be performing well in
comparison to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is full of dollar bears right now,'' said Karen
Parker, the currency strategist at Chase Securities. ``But the U.S.
economy is in a relatively good position. Asia is not recovering,
Japan is in a recession and the recovery in Europe is more fragile
than some think.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that is the case, then a rebound in commodity prices will
not get an assist from the dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
