<SLUG> BC-1999-MANAGEMENT-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIVING TO KEEP A LOOSE HOLD ON A TIGHT SHIP
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Mass., Pa.) 
(For release Monday, Jan. 4) 
 (nk) 
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Managing people is hard. And it's going to get even harder.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what the average boss is up against these days. Rapid
growth and mergers and acquisitions are roiling corporate America,
creating management headaches that must be handled with some
old-fashioned command-and-control leadership. After all, to wring
out inefficiencies and cut costs, companies have to make sure
things are done a certain way. And that means lots of memorandums,
policies and rules.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, managers are increasingly expected to
accommodate the particular work styles of their employees.
Otherwise, they are reminded over and over, their valued workers
may leave for a competitor that better understands the intangible
side of running a business.
</P>
<P>
   In an age of so-called talent shortages, on top of an overall
employee shortage, many productive workers see themselves
increasingly as free agents who can take advantage of the seller's
market for their skills.
</P>
<P>
   It is a point that Scott Adams, creator of the Dilbert cartoon
strip, tries to capture in his latest book, ``The Joy of Work'':
``The balance of power has changed. Now it's even safe to make
insulting jokes at the expense of your boss. You'll be amazed at
how much whimsical insolence your boss is willing to tolerate. Take
full advantage of this situation while it lasts.''
</P>
<P>
   These pressures on managers _ to run a tight ship but keep
things loose _ are reflected on the shelves of business sections of
most bookstores, where textbook-like volumes about growth
strategies share space with people-management offerings, like
``Contented Cows Give Better Milk,'' ``Your People Are Your
Product'' and ``Work &AMP; Rewards in the Virtual Workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right recipe for managing is not easy. ``It is a
moving target,'' said Adrian W. Zackheim, publisher of the News
Corp.'s Harper Business book unit. ``I think that most of what's
going on in the world degrades the command-and-control model, but
it certainly isn't dead. There are a lot of forces dragging it this
way and that.''
</P>
<P>
   Effective management is not only a moving target; it is also a
bar that is being raised.
</P>
<P>
   The message of one of the most successful business books of the
year, ``Working With Emotional Intelligence,'' by Daniel Goleman,
offers one illustration. Goleman, who has a doctorate in psychology
from Harvard, writes that certain IQ levels and technical skills
have become ``threshold capabilities,'' or entry-level requirements
for executive positions. The most successful leaders generally also
have emotional intelligence, he writes, such as self-awareness,
empathy and social skills.
</P>
<P>
   Goleman studied 188 companies and determined that among the
ingredients for excellent performance, emotional intelligence was
twice as important as IQ and technical skills. He writes that these
skills can be learned, although doing so takes a great deal of time
and commitment.
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of employers _ especially in Silicon Valley
_ are taking such broader approaches to management, in large part
to stem the job-hopping tide.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Peter Cappelli, a professor of management at the
Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania, ``At many
companies, the gap is huge between what they are saying and
doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
