<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NBA union heads withhold final counterproposal
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The NBA and the National Basketball Players Association have put a
new spin on the phrase, ``New Year's resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides hope to have a happy resolution to the 186-day
lockout, looking to hammer out a new collective-bargaining
agreement before NBA commissioner David Stern's Jan. 7 deadline.
Stern said unless he thinks there is significant progress toward an
agreement, he will recommend canceling the season at the Board of
Governors meeting on that date.
</P>
<P>
   But neither side seems to have progressed beyond the silly games
they have played throughout the lockout. The players have worked up
their ``final'' collective-bargaining offer, but have refused to
present it to the owners.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because the owners refuse to sit down with the players for
a negotiating session. And with no sessions scheduled, union
attorney Jeffrey Kessler (again) accused the NBA of stalling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to delay the process of meeting so they can
keep trying to put pressure on the players,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, said Jeffrey Mishkin, the NBA's chief legal officer.
Mishkin said meeting would be pointless because the league's final
offer, presented Sunday, stands and will not be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The union can call us names and characterize it any way they
want,'' said Mishkin, adding that as soon as the owners receive the
union's proposal, it will be presented to the negotiating committee
and then to the Board of Governors for a vote. ``They may find our
offer unsatisfactory, but it is our final offer.''
</P>
<P>
   So the union will keep its offer to itself _ for now, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process will start on their timing, and when they're ready
we'll give them our proposal,'' Kessler said. ``We are doing what
we think will most further the process to increase the chances of
getting a deal done, not to decrease the chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern probably will return to New York from Aspen, Colo., on
Sunday; union executive director Billy Hunter, who spent New Year's
Eve in Philadelphia, likely will return to New York today.
</P>
<P>
   The sides have until Thursday to reach an agreement, and many
think an agreement could be close because the union's new proposal
contains one of the biggest concessions the owners have sought, a
cap on the salary any player can receive. It includes a demand for
55 percent of revenues in the fourth year of the agreement, close
to the league's offer of 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if only the owners can get a look at the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way a deal can be made is to get the people in the
room, and they'll conclude that,'' Kessler said. ``I don't think
the owners want to lose the season any more than the players do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about pride and it isn't about relationships. This
is about the process, and when you're trying to engage in a final
negotiation to bring a deal home, both sides have to get there,
work out the details and do the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the owners have a New Year's resolution to get serious
and negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sideshows continue. Keith Van Horn became the latest
player to demand a union vote on the owners' proposal, even though
Hunter has refused to put the offer up before the rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn's stance is noteworthy considering he is represented by
agent David Falk, whom Stern accuses of working behind the scenes
to block efforts to reach an agreement that would limit what his
superstar clients could earn.
</P>
<P>
   Falk represents high-priced players such as Michael Jordan,
union president Patrick Ewing, union vice presidents Alonzo
Mourning and Dikembe Mutombo as well as future high-earners Allen
Iverson and Stephon Marbury as well as Van Horn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think we should have a vote,'' Van Horn said.
``Even though you have 19 guys representing the players, it may not
necessarily be accurate or representative of how the other guys
feel. And if 65 to 70 percent of the players want to play and feel
that the deal is satisfactory, you have to take that into
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a vote, I really couldn't tell you which way I
would go right now. But the owners' proposal is pretty good. I
think it is as close to a fair deal as we're going to get.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
