<HEADLINE>
HIGHER DEDUCTIBLES SET FOR HURRICANE DAMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Ala., La.)   (For release Monday, Jan. 4)  
(lb) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a hurricane battered his home on the Mississippi coast,
Eugene Arnold got a big surprise that may prove instructive to tens
of thousands of coastal residents as they renew their homeowners
insurance this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Arnold had just paid his annual premium of $2,700,
he discovered that he would have to pay the first $11,400 in
damages out of his own pocket. His deductible, it turned out, was
not the $1,000 he had been carrying for years, but 2 percent of the
$570,000 policy on his sprawling Mediterranean-style home near
Pascagoula.
</P>
<P>
   Higher deductibles for wind damage started quietly going into
effect all along the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic last year. And
by the end of this year, industry experts say, there will be few _
if any _ eastern and southern coastal states without them. Higher
deductibles have also been introduced for coverage in earthquake
zones.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, who runs several franchised weight-loss centers, said he
had no quarrel with insurers' setting deductibles and premiums as
they chose. His complaint is that he was not adequately informed of
the change.
</P>
<P>
   Other homeowners in Mississippi, Alabama and Louisiana as well
as in Puerto Rico _ all of which were hit hard by Hurricane Georges
in September _ said the higher deductibles came as a shock to them,
too. Many complained to insurance regulators. Some, like Arnold,
joined in a class-action suit demanding that their original, lower
deductibles be used in calculating their Hurricane Georges claims.
</P>
<P>
   The higher deductibles, which amount to a reduction in coverage,
are another manifestation of the ways in which insurers have been
cutting back on the protection they provide for coastal residents
as well as increasing prices.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance companies blame increasing costs. Not only have
hurricanes become more frequent and more powerful, they say, but
more houses and condominiums have been built along the shoreline,
creating more valuable targets for storms. So when the wind gets
roaring, the actuaries say, expensive claims are sure to follow.
</P>
<P>
   As business people committed to maintaining profits, the
insurers say, they saw only two ways they could continue to offer
coverage: raise premiums drastically and risk driving customers to
competitors that might seek less profit, or raise deductibles so
that customers would shoulder more of the costs of damages.
</P>
<P>
   The giants in the business, State Farm Mutual Automobile
Insurance Co. and Allstate Corp., went for the higher deductibles _
combined, in some cases, with rate increases of more than 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it, but insurance companies aren't like they
used to be,'' said George Dale, the insurance commissioner in
Mississippi. ``They don't have the social soul they once had. Now
they are only concerned with their bottom lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale, who is an elected official, had gotten himself into a bit
of a pickle. Months before Hurricane Georges struck, he approved
the 2 percent deductible for three insurers, including State Farm
and Allstate, the two biggest in Mississippi, and USF&AMP;G, a unit of
St. Paul Cos. But he received many complaints after the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   So he backtracked a bit, urging the insurers to treat the damage
from Hurricane Georges as if their policies had been written with
the old deductibles, which for most people had been $250 or $500.
</P>
<P>
   USF&AMP;G said fine, but State Farm and Allstate refused. Dale
ordered independent auditors to look at the financial records of
both companies to determine whether the increases were warranted
and whether policyholders were adequately notified of the higher
deductibles.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the uproars in their states, Dale and the
insurance commissioners in Alabama and Louisiana have begun working
together, hoping their combined voices will give them greater
leverage in trying to steady premiums and deductibles and make sure
that insurers do not simply abandon the coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm and Allstate have sharply curtailed sales of new
policies in Florida and Nationwide Financial Services Inc. has done
the same all along the Atlantic and Gulf coasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to remember that they are in business to make money,''
Dale said. ``We can't order them to write insurance here if they
don't want to.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Robert Hunter, the insurance director for the Consumer
Federation of America, said that the fair thing with deductibles
was to permit customers to choose what level they want, recognizing
that lower deductibles will mean higher premiums.
</P>
<P>
   That's what South Carolina's officials said when State Farm
tried to impose deductibles as high as 5 percent of the value of
the policy on homeowners there in November. So State Farm said its
customers could decide on either a $500 deductible or one of as
much as 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In December, State Farm said it would begin letting
policyholders in Mississippi choose between a $500 deductible _
with premiums increased by 15 percent _ or the 2 percent deductible
that has drawn such protests.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Mintel, a lawyer for State Farm, said the company
expected to eventually offer the same alternatives in other coastal
states.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Hurricane Georges hit, Arnold said, a friend
mentioned the 2 percent deductible. Arnold said he was sure he was
not one of the unfortunates who would be digging into his pockets.
Still, he decided to check his State Farm policy. And there it was,
he said, on a page summarizing his coverage, under the deductibles
section, the words ``hurricane'' and ``2 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no dollar figure, though, and Arnold said, ``You don't
pay much attention to something like that.'' His State Farm agent
should have told him about the change, Arnold contends, and there
should have been newspaper and television advertisements announcing
it.
</P>
<P>
   There were, in fact, some newspaper reports about the deductible
change. But Arnold said he did not see them.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mintel said State Farm sent out three notices to customers
on the changes, including the information on the summary page in
each policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my book, three separate mailings are quite a lot of
notification,'' she said. ``But the fact that so many people are
expressing surprise makes you kind of relook at how you
communicate.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, at least in Mississippi, it is going to be up to a
state court to determine whether there was a failure to
communicate. Or, as often happens, the two sides might decide it
makes more sense to reach a compromise on their own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
