<HEADLINE>
TURNING FINANCIAL DIALECTS INTO A COMMON LANGUAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Monday, Jan. 4) 
 (nk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life would be simpler if all companies, whether in Thailand,
Tanzania or Tennessee, spoke the same financial language.
</P>
<P>
   But each country now sets its own accounting rules, and what may
look like profits at a bank in Kuala Lumpur may turn into losses at
a bank in Kansas City with the same numbers but using American
accounting rules.
</P>
<P>
   The International Accounting Standards Committee, a group of
accountants and executives from around the world, has set out to
change that. And, after more than two decades of work, the
committee is ready to present a core set of 15 universal accounting
standards.
</P>
<P>
   This year, world securities regulators, including the Securities
and Exchange Commission in the United States, will review the
proposed rules and decide whether they are strong enough to
recommend to all countries. These would not be the first
international rules to be devised, but the goal is to have one set
that applies worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the year,'' said James L. Cochrane, the chief
economist at the New York Stock Exchange. ``Investors and analysts
are crying out for a common language, a common set of accounting
principles.''
</P>
<P>
   But a growing number of critics, many of them in this country,
say that the global rules written by the London-based committee are
weak and full of loopholes. The critics, including members of the
Financial Accounting Standards Board, which sets accounting rules
in the United States, have also raised questions about the inner
workings of the committee, which has been holding its meetings in
private and has some members with close ties to companies that
would follow the rules.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of the proposed international rules, Patricia A.
McConnell, an analyst at Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. and the International
Accounting Standards Committee's vice chairwoman, said that they
``look and smell'' like the American rules. ``They are far superior
to most things you would get outside of the U.S.,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And Trevor S. Harris, a professor of accounting at Columbia
University and a consultant for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said
that while the U.S. accounting rules are more detailed, the broad
differences between the American and the proposed global rules are
small. ``In my mind there are few differences that are significant
from an investor's point of view,'' Harris said. ``Sometimes the
extra detail does not lead to more informative information.''
</P>
<P>
   Many financial experts and executives are clamoring for a
worldwide set of accounting rules. They contend that universal
rules are necessary in a world where investors regularly struggle
to compare companies that operate across several time zones and
under very different governments.
</P>
<P>
   Some countries, like South Korea, Poland and Russia, now have
few accounting rules or do not enforce the rules they have, leaving
executives to decide on their own what investors should and should
not know.
</P>
<P>
   While such countries may seem distant enough not to worry most
of this nation's investors, even now anyone can go on the Internet
and invest in foreign companies in countries that lack
well-enforced accounting rules.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of countries have already adopted existing international
rules as an alternative to writing their own, and the World Bank,
which provides loans to poor countries, recommends the existing
standards as a condition of its loan agreements. But the aim of the
new effort is full global standardization.
</P>
<P>
   Global rules have widespread appeal in Europe, where 11
countries are now using a common currency, the euro, but have not
yet knitted together their accounting rules.
</P>
<P>
   Many European countries now allow foreign companies wanting to
sell stock on their exchanges to use the existing international
rules rather than to conform to their own. One of these is Britain,
and many companies that would like to sell their stock on the
American exchanges, where strict American rules apply, have gone to
the London Stock Exchange instead.
</P>
<P>
   Cochrane at the New York Stock Exchange said that many foreign
companies now turn away from American markets because they do not
want to reconcile their financial statements to United States
accounting rules, as required by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   American regulators say they understand the need for having one
set of accounting rules, and they have agreed to review the
international committee's rules and decide whether to allow their
use in this country.
</P>
<P>
   And in a recent speech to the World Congress of Accountants, the
president of the World Bank, James D. Wolfensohn, said: ``In a
world that is growing more and more like a single economic
household, it makes no sense to be speaking in different voices. We
urgently need a unified global language of business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
