<SLUG> BC-FBC-MISSISSIPPI-STATE-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSISSIPPI STATE PAYS FOR GAMBLING BLITZES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mississippi State's defense packed the line of
scrimmage and made no secret of its intention to blitz in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Texas quarterback Major Applewhite made the Bulldogs pay with
two touchdown passes to Wane McGarity for a 14-3 halftime lead.
Applewhite finished the first half with 11 completions for 163
yards.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been even worse for Mississippi State, but left
tackle John Hilliard made a shoestring tackle on Kwame Cavil after
a reception early in the second quarter. Applewhite threw the
screen pass over blitzing defenders, and Cavil caught it at the
Texas 42-yard line with a wide-open field in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question he did a great job, but you can't give
Major all the credit because he had some help,'' Mississippi State
coach Jackie Sherrill said. ``He did a great job of getting the
ball where it was supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs can also blame aggressive play for the first
Longhorns touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Texas faced a third-and-six when Mississippi State attacked too
early at the line of scrimmage and received an offside penalty.
Texas converted on third-and-1 and scored a touchdown four plays
later. Hobbling Bulldogs Mississippi State senior return specialist
Kevin Prentiss had one punt return for 28 yards before leaving the
game because of a pinched nerve in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Prentiss was one of four Bulldogs players to suffer first-half
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman tailback Dicenzo Miller left the game because of a
dislocated left shoulder. Backup quarterback Matt Wyatt twisted his
hip on the Bulldogs' final drive of the first half. Wyatt returned
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Starting guard Kenwoynne Smith suffered a right-leg injury early
in the first quarter. Near miss The Bulldogs missed by inches on
what might have been their best touchdown chance early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   On second-and-22 from the Texas 47-yard line, quarterback Wayne
Madkin rolled right and overthrew Kevin Cooper on a lob pass near
the right sideline. The closest Texas defender was nearly 10 yards
away.
HE STILL WOULDN'T LIKE IT
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill's seven-game winning streak against the Longhorns,
dating back to 1984, ended.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State is winless in four bowl appearances during the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that many teams have been able to beat Texas
seven times in a row,'' Sherrill said. ``Only thing I didn't like
was the crowd singing `Poor Aggies' at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans were actually chanting ``Poor Jackie.''
IN PRAISE OF BACKUP
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs were 3-of-14 on third-down conversions, which is
one reason Sherrill said he pulled starting quarterback Madkin from
the game in favor of Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wyatt played well,'' Sherrill said. ``You have to give Matt a
lot of credit because, mentally, he stayed in the game the whole
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
