<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROSE-GAMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYNE LEADS WISCONSIN PAST UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Thanks for playing, UCLA Bruins. We have some
lovely parting gifts for you.
</P>
<P>
   It was little comfort for UCLA that it ended its season in the
Rose Bowl, which is typically its year-end mecca. After spending
the season chasing the national championship, the Rose was a
consolation prize.
</P>
<P>
   And it was a paltry prize at that. Just like in the
season-ending loss at Miami that squashed their championship hopes,
the Bruins' defense was AWOL. Wisconsin ran its way to a 38-31
victory yesterday before 93,872. The Badgers finished 11-1 and
continued a solid postseason for the Big Ten Conference. UCLA is
10-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing for our season to end this way,'' UCLA
quarterback Cade McNown said. ``We weren't as crisp as we need to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin junior running back Ron Dayne, who announced before
Christmas that he would return for his senior season, is first in
line for the 1999 Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot, 10-inch, 253-pound Dayne gobbled up 246 yards and a
Rose Bowl record-tying four touchdowns on 27 carries for the
Badgers. Wisconsin rushed for 343 yards against UCLA's defense,
which has had all the characteristics of LA smog this season. The
Bruins finished the season allowing 28 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first couple of plays, I knew our offensive line was
going to be opening holes,'' Dayne said, whose rushing total was
one short of the Rose Bowl record. ``I went up to my linemen before
the game and told them it's time to do what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne, who played despite a torn muscle in his shoulder,
approached the record for most rushing yards in a bowl game. The
record had been 280 by Texas Tech's James Gray in the 1989
All-American Bowl. His four TDs tied the Rose Bowl record held by
USC's Sam Cunningham in 1973 and UCLA's Eric Ball in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel one man beat us or one play cost us the game,''
UCLA coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's offense, which had left defenses breathless all season,
was again potent. But the Bruins' offensive line had trouble
holding Wisconsin. Check that. UCLA held fine. Four times,
including twice on the first series.
</P>
<P>
   And while that meant there was more yards for the offense to
gain, it also made it easier for the Badgers to pressure McNown.
The senior finished with 340 yards and two touchdowns, completing
19 of 34 pass attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, Wisconsin had few answers for the Bruins'
breathtaking pass offense. The Badgers, who entered the game with
the nation's fourth-ranked defense (270 yards per game), had not
seen the likes of UCLA's attack in the Big Ten Conference. UCLA
threw for 418 yards, making the Badgers look like they couldn't
cover statues.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers' pressure produced two key plays. Early in the
fourth quarter, facing a third-and-nine, McNown was pressured into
throwing an interception. Freshman corner back Jamar Fletcher
returned it 46 yards for a touchdown that made it 38-28.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get pressure on the quarterback like we did, it makes
my job easier,'' Fletcher said. ``On that play, I was in man
coverage and the ball just came right to me. From there, it was
just daylight.''
</P>
<P>
   And UCLA's final chance ended when reserve defensive tackle
Wendell Bryant sacked McNown with 59 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers took control late in the first half. Matt
Davenport's 40-yard field goal gave Wisconsin the lead for good,
24-21, 17 seconds before halftime. Dayne scored on a 22-yard run to
make it 31-21 early in the third quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
