</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE NFL, CASE FOR THE DEFENSE IS WEAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ This is not your father's football league.
</P>
<P>
   No Steel Curtain. No Doomsday. No Purple People Eaters.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever first said, ``Defense wins championships,'' never heard
of the West Coast offense or five-wide receiver sets. The timeworn
credo about defense slowly began losing significance with the
breakup of the 1985 Bears. It finally faded for good last season
when the Denver Broncos won the Super Bowl despite finishing last
in the National Football League in average rushing yards allowed
per attempt.
</P>
<P>
   As the league begins postseason play today, the game is much
more about touchdowns, not tackles; post patterns, not prevent
defenses. Denver showed us last season that a playmaking
quarterback, a strong rushing attack and gamebreaking wide
receivers can overcome even the ugliest of defensive blemishes.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Cowboys and Cardinals will exchange touchdowns at
Texas Stadium today in a wild-card game that underscores the NFL's
offensive-minded landscape, which has benefited from rule changes
which have led to more pass-interference penalties and more liberal
pass blocking. Both clubs rank considerably higher on offense than
on defense (Dallas 8 to 18 out of 30, Arizona 13 to 21). Troy
Aikman, Emmitt Smith, and Michael Irvin fuel the Cowboys' title
hopes. Jake Plummer is the hope for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   And the top teams in both conferences share this unbalanced
makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's defense (13th overall, 19th against the pass) is far
from championship caliber. But the Vikings are the NFC favorites
because of a Randall Cunningham-Randy Moss-led offensive attack
that helped set an NFL record with 556 points in 16 games. For
that, Vikings offensive coordinator Brian Billick has emerged as
one of the hot candidates to fill one of the seven head coaching
vacancies and has already interviewed with the Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Denver leans toward offense as much as the Vikings. The Broncos
defense, ranked 11th overall and 26th against the pass, hardly
resembles the Orange Crush of the late 1970s. But with 2,000-yard
rusher Terrell Davis and veteran quarterback John Elway, the
Broncos won 13 consecutive games to start the season and are
favored to become the first repeat AFC champion in five years. Like
Billick, Broncos quarterbacks coach/offensive coordinator Gary
Kubiak interviewed for the Cleveland job as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a fallacy to think that you just go out there
and outscore people all the time,'' Aikman said. ``But in this
league, it is hard to expect a defense to hold teams down to 10, 13
points. And if they do, and on offense if you don't score 21, I
don't know how many teams expect to win if they can't score 21
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the salary cap, I think the league is watered
down,'' he continued. ``You've got to pick and choose where the
money goes. The decision has been made in today's game that the
offensive players are going to get that money. It becomes very
difficult to have a good defense and try to provide the team with
some offensive guys that can score for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones clinged to that philosophy when he
hired an ``offensive guy,'' to replace Barry Switzer as head coach
last winter. Feeling that his defense would, ``always be able to
hem them in,'' Jones employed former Pittsburgh Steelers offensive
coordinator Chan Gailey to resurrect an offensive unit whose
starters account for the major portion of the Cowboys payroll.
</P>
<P>
   With Aikman as the career postseason leader in passing
percentage, Smith as the second-leading postseason rusher, and
Irvin as the second-leading postseason receiver, the Cowboys are
confident that they have the pieces in place to claim an
unprecedented sixth Super Bowl title.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, 11 other teams think they have the firepower to
share the same confidence. The pass word is ... Aikman In this
landscape of offensive-minded football, the Cowboys have the one
player whose singular efforts can lead them on an extended playoff
run: Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   He is 11-2 as a starter in the playoffs. He has completed a
postseason record 66.3 percent of his passes. His postseason passer
rating of 96.0 trails only Packers great Bart Starr (104.8).
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we have a healthy Troy Aikman, I'll always feel we
have a chance,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The players around Aikman are not as good as they were in 1992,
1993, and perhaps even 1995. And so Aikman may have to make
game-saving plays by scrambling in the pocket or by throwing on the
run. But do not expect Aikman to try to win games by himself. He'll
stand tall in the pocket and let his receivers carry out their
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Scrambling quarterbacks Brett Favre of Green Bay and Steve Young
of San Francisco do things one way. Aikman, the only active
quarterback with three Super Bowl titles, does things another way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing you want to do is go out and think you've got
to carry the football team or pick up more than your share of the
load,'' Aikman said. ``I don't think that mentality really works.''
The big bang theory Big passing plays have as much of an effect on
a game as a sack or a tackle for loss. The Vikings (14-1) achieved
the league's best record with more pass plays of 25 yards or longer
(44) than sacks (38). Playoff qualifiers San Francisco and New
England finished tied for second in the regular season with 39 pass
plays of 25 yards or longer.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were next with 37 such plays, led by Irvin, whose 12
receptions of 25 yards or longer was seven behind league leaders
Moss of Minnesota and Eric Moulds of Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make big plays, you are not going to have to fight
every way down the field to score,'' Gailey said. ``Big plays pick
up the whole team, they help morale. When you get one, it changes
field position. If you get two or three big plays you can turn the
ball game around.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the Cowboys trail offensive powerhouses Minnesota and
Denver is that Irvin has emerged as the club's only consistent
big-play threat. Irvin had 74 receptions for 1,057 yards and one
touchdown. The Cowboys player with the second-most receptions,
Billy Davis, finished with 39 catches for 691 yards and three
touchdowns. Patrick Jeffers, filling in for the injured Ernie
Mills, had 18 receptions for 330 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFC, Minnesota's Randy Moss and Cris Carter each finished
with at least 1,000 yards receiving. The same is true for Atlanta's
Tony Martin and Terance Mathis, as well as San Francisco's Jerry
Rice and Terrell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   All of these receivers have made their biggest plays after
catching the ball. In terms of receiving yards made after the
catch, the Green Bay receivers are first in the NFL with 1,855
yards, followed by San Francisco (1,854), the Jets (1,798),
Minnesota (1,638), Atlanta (1,478), and Arizona (1,448).
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys receivers are 10th among the 12 playoff teams with
1,281 yards made after the catch, and 21st overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big plays kill the defense,'' Irvin said. ``Have we made
enough? I don't know. The object for us in the playoffs is to make
big plays on offense and prevent them on defense. You can't go
wrong with that combination.'' Power ball The power running game
remains the last link to the glory days of the 1960s and 1970s. You
keep the other team from scoring by keeping the ball yourself. You
do that with a ball control running back who chews up the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, with Smith, have such capabilities, although they
have struggled at times this season. They finished the season with
the league's eighth-ranked rushing attack, averaging 125.9 yards
per game.
</P>
<P>
   A late, three-game slide that included a 58-yard rushing game
against Minnesota, an eight-yard rushing game in New Orleans, and a
51-yard rushing game in Kansas City knocked the Cowboys average
down from 144.4 yards per game to 125.9 and their ranking from
second in the NFL to eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But for the season, the Cowboys still ran for more yards than
Minnesota (2,014 to 1,936). With Smith leading the way with 1,332
yards, the Cowboys ran the ball as well as any team, except for
top-ranked San Francisco (159 yards per game) and Denver (154.3
yards per game).
</P>
<P>
   ``The best defense is keeping the ball yourself and trying to
wear the other team down,'' Smith said. ``You can't win in this
league if you don't run the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Though grinding out 10- and 12-play drives with the running game
will be key in the playoffs, the Cowboys have shown an ability to
break big plays via the rush.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six NFC teams, only the 49ers have more runs longer than
10 yards (74) than the Cowboys (57). Smith is third among playoff
running backs with 40 carries this season for 10 or more yards
behind Denver's Terrell Davis (50) and Atlanta's Jamal Anderson
(45).
</P>
<P>
   Smith, Irvin and Aikman know success is impossible without an
efficient offensive line. The Cowboys have two Pro Bowlers in left
guard Nate Newton and left tackle Larry Allen, and a 1997 Pro
Bowler in right tackle Erik Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offensive line drives our football team, and most any
team,'' Aikman said. ``If you are getting good play up front, the
rest will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Even victory without great play from the defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
