<HEADER>
A5048 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-REPORT-TEX     01-01 1870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEFENSE WINS TITLES' KEPT ALIVE BY A CONSPIRACY OF OLD-TIMERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Mike Fisher 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Defense wins championships,'' said one expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got that right,'' said the other expert. ``You can't lose
if the other team can't score.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Darn right,'' chimed in a third expert, apparently confident
that the simple regurgitation of an ancient football platitude was
enough to make it so. ``Defense wins championships!''
</P>
<P>
   So the Pro Player Stadium security guard, the TV cameraman and
the Miami cab driver had it all figured out _ and lest you think
I'm patronizing blue-collar football fans, let it be known that
such a conversation would seem no less banal to me had it been
conducted by, say, Bill Parcells, Jimmy Johnson and Mike Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of dominating on defense being the only way to win a
title likely came from two now passe facts:
</P>
<P>
   1) Back in the days when the ball was fatter and late-season
games were all played outdoors, offensive finesse was generally
inappropriate; and
</P>
<P>
   2) Coaches are liars.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of coast-to-coast football (all teams aren't in
the Rust Belt anymore, you know), indoor football (the two best
teams in the NFC play under domes in Minnesota and Atlanta) and a
streamlined ball, three-yards-and-a-cloud-of-dust offense still has
its place. But its place isn't at the focus of an offense, where
rules changes _ from blockers being able to extend their arms to
receivers being able to run untouched beyond 5 yards of the line of
scrimmage _ have made playing offense easier than playing defense.
</P>
<P>
   Want to get better fast? Which is easier, finding a cover corner
or a dangerous receiver? Which is easier, finding a pass-rusher or
a hog who can hang onto to him? If you want to get better fast,
score.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the top-ranked offensive teams during the NFL regular
season: 1) San Francisco, 2) Minnesota, 3) Denver, 4) the Jets, 5)
Green Bay, 6) Buffalo, 7) Atlanta, 8) Dallas. Guess what? They're
all in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Now look at the two top-ranked defensive clubs: 1) San Diego and
2) Tampa Bay. Guess what? They're playing golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense wins championships'' is a lie now. And it might have
always been. Most prospective football players want to be stars.
They want to score touchdowns. They want to experience glory. They
want to meet cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   The conspiracy that exists between old-timers will prevent this
from ever blossoming beyond theory-dom. But I believe the ``defense
wins championships'' credo was created in part because it was the
only way coaches could trick 11 of their guys to take on the
crummiest jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Is Denver's defense great? Not at great as its offense. Is
Minnesota's defense great? Same story. Meanwhile, ask Jimmy Johnson
about his defense, and he'll say, ``Other people around the league
believe we have the best defense in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   But how far are the Dolphins going unless Dan Marino and company
start putting up 28 a game?
</P>
<P>
   I've said it before, I'll say it forever, and this Super Bowl
Tournament is destined to prove me right: Every single little
aspect of a football team is a building block in a house of cards.
Every single draft pick, every single play called, every single
block delivered, every single word spoken, maybe even the detergent
the team equipment managers use to launder the locker-room towels,
are part of the equation. Remove one card, and the whole thing
might come crashing down.
</P>
<P>
   See, there are no how-to-win formulas, only bumper stickers
disguised as formulas. It's all like something out of the
best-selling book, ``The Seven Habits of Highly Effective People'',
in which author Stephen Covey instructs us to ``Seek First To
Understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, that's how you become effective? Seeking to understand?
</P>
<P>
   No kidding, Sherlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta control the clock.'' ``It takes depth.'' ``You gotta
grind it out.'' ``Home teams win.'' ``Experience wins.'' ``Defense
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosh, they all sound great. But there is only one great truth,
and it establishes that scoring 35 points a game is as valuable a
game-winning gift as allowing 16 points a game. That one great
truth:
</P>
<P>
   ``Champions'' win championships.
AFC PLAYOFF BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback situation in Jacksonville has such a history
that it'll probably never devolve into a quarterback controversy.
Hanging inside Mark Brunell's locker at Jaguars headquarters is the
cover of the 1987 ``Santa Maria (Calif.) Times'' 1987 Pigskin
Preview. The cover photo shows Brunell, the senior star at St.
Joseph High School, standing alongside Jamie Martin, the senior
star from rival Arroyo Grande High. It might not have been so clear
back then, but it's clear now: Brunell is the standout; Martin is
the (injured) backup. And the Jags hope elevated third-stringer
Jonathan Quinn never enters the picture. ... The Patriots have lost
two of their last three, and visit Jacksonville preparing to start
Scott Zolak at QB. Don't expect sympathy from the Jaguars, who have
labored in recent weeks without Brunell, who wants to play in order
to give Jacksonville a chance to avenge the Jags' three losses to
the Patriots in the last four seasons. ``We owe them something,''
Brunell says. ... Miami is 7-1 at home this year, allowing just
10.6 points per game at Pro Player Stadium. ... Buffalo is laying
the groundwork to get some help from the officials in their meeting
with the Dolphins. ``If the officials throw their flags, it's big
for us,'' says QB Doug Flutie, adding that Miami cornerbacks
Terrell Buckley and Sam Madison can be expected to be ``tugging and
pulling as usual. You can't cover Eric Moulds one-on-one. You can't
cover Andre Reed one-on-one.'' ... Buffalo's Thurman Thomas is tied
with Emmitt Smith for most postseason touchdowns (20) and points
(120) in NFL history ... Folks in Denver are suggesting offensive
coordinator Gary Kubiak, who has already interviewed in Cleveland,
might be attracted to the top job in San Diego, where he'd work
under Bobby Beathard and over Ryan Leaf. . ... A little-noticed
fact: While Miami's defense earned headlines for leading the NFL in
not allowing points, the Jets were within one point of permitting
the same number. Meanwhile, New York scored more than 400 points
for only the second time in franchise history. That's balance.
NFC BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   Earning a bye this week is huge for the Vikings, who expect four
injured starters to return for their playoff debut next weekend.
Linebackers Dixon Edwards and Ed McDaniel and tackle Korey Stringer
have been ailing but will be ready to go next week. Most important,
though, is the expected return of Pro Bowl receiver Jake Reed, a
forgotten man in the Randy Moss frenzy. Without Reed, Minnesota has
often used a standard-set offense. With him, they return to a
three-receiver set as much as 50 percent of the time. ... The
Vikings are the first dome team ever to earn home-field advantage
throughout the playoffs. ... Kicker Ryan Longwell is the first
Packer since Paul Hornung in 1960-61 to post consecutive 100-point
seasons. ... Coach Dan Reeves, recovering from quadruple bypass
surgery, nevertheless visited his Falcons last Sunday morning for a
pregame pep talk. Here's hoping his team pays more attention to his
advice than he pays to his doctor's. ... The 49ers have defeated
only two teams with winning records: the Jets in Week 1 and Atlanta
in Week 3. ... Cardinals coach Vince Tobin is smart enough to
understand the subtle problem with winning close games. ``That's
not the way you like to play football games because eventually it's
going to catch up with you and bite you,'' Tobin says. ``You've got
to be able to put games away early when you have the opportunity.''
... Key to the Packers' five-game wining streak against the 49ers?
Green Bay always jumps out in front. In those five meetings, the
Packers have surged to early leads of 21-0, 6-0, 21-0, 10-0 and
16-0. ... You'll hear all about it during Super Bowl Week, so hear
it now: Yes, Vikings third-string QB Jay Fiedler is related to
Arthur Fiedler of the Boston Pops. Jay's grandfather is Arthur's
third cousin.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYOFF QUICK HITS
NUMBERS GAME
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970 merger, five teams have finished the regular
season with one loss or fewer. Minnesota, 15-1, is hoping to become
the fifth of the group to win the Super Bowl: Team Record Finish
1972 Miam Dolphins 14-0 won Super Bowl 1976 Oakland Raiders 13-1
won Super Bowl 1984 San Francisco 49ers 15-1 won Super Bowl 1985
Chicago Bears 15-1 won Super Bowl 1998 Minnesota Vikings 15-1 To be
determined Trivial pursuit There is no doubting the greatness of
Dan Marino and John Elway, the two still-productive stars from the
vaunted Class of '83 quarterback crop. But weirdly, Denver's Elway
and Miami's Marino haven't fared especially well against the other
top quarterbacks in their class. Lifetime against Todd Blackledge,
Tony Eason, Ken O'Brien and Jim Kelly, Elway is 7-7 and Marino is
19-21.
CHECK OUT
</P>
<P>
   A possible Chan Gailey-vs.-Dan Reeves second-round playoff
matchup. Don't get the wrong idea; Gailey's team cannot afford for
him to be anything less than 100 percent committed to the Cowboys'
cause: the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   But can you blame him if has room in his heart, his head, and
maybe in his vision, for an occasional consideration of Atlanta's
Reeves?
</P>
<P>
   You know the well-chronicled Gailey-Reeves relationship: Reeves
was everybody's All-American in Americus, Ga., and was an idol and
mentor to a young Gailey, who got his first lesson in how to coach
a team when he played for a Reeves-coached Little League baseball
team.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship is a Cowboys' win away from going through a
transformation. If Dallas wins its first-round game, Gailey's team
advances to Atlanta for a second-round meeting with Reeves'
Falcons. Considering their brotherly relationship, Reeves' recent
bypass surgery and the high stakes, story lines will be almost
endless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played them two years ago when I was in Pittsburgh,'' says
Gailey, but, of course, that was different. Gailey was the
Steelers' offensive coordinator. Reeves had left the Broncos and
then the Giants to take over a sad-sack program. ``We barely beat
them. They had the nucleus of a good football team, but they needed
to add some other people around them. That's what Dan's done. If
ever there was a perfect guy for a perfect situation, Dan in
Atlanta is it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Reeves' Falcons started 1-7. The pre-Gailey Cowboys
finished 6-10. Does Gailey see similarities in the turnarounds?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things we do that are similar,'' Gailey says.
``There's an emphasis on the run, although they're more of a power
running game and with Emmitt \RSmith\S, we let the back sort of
pick his holes. But spreading out the passing game, that's the
same. A few trick plays and solid defense, we both rely on that. So
there are some parallels you can draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gailey could've never dreamed of this. Could he have?
</P>
<P>
   ``Right when I got here,'' Gailey says, ``there were questions
asked of both Dan and me about the possibility of a Dallas-Atlanta
\Rplayoff game\S. We both kind of laughed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
