<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYNE NEEDS WILLIAMS-TYPE FINALE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ 1,928. That's the number of yards Ricky
Williams needed to break Tony Dorsett's career rushing record of
6,082.
</P>
<P>
   1,717. That's the number of yards Ron Dayne needs to break
Williams' career rushing record of 6,279.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky, don't lose that number.
</P>
<P>
   When he announced he was returning for his senior season, Dayne
immediately put Williams' ``unbreakable'' record in danger.
Yesterday at the Rose Bowl, Dayne put himself at the top of the
1999 Heisman Trophy list with 246 yards in the Badgers' 38-31 Rose
Bowl victory against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne tied a Rose Bowl record with four touchdowns and he came
within a yard of the Rose single-game rushing record. That is how
Heisman Trophy campaigns begin. Fortunately for Williams, yardage
in bowl games doesn't count in NCAA career statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-10, 253-pound Dayne has averaged 5.7 yards a carry in
three seasons. That means if he maintains that pace, he'll need 302
carries to pass Williams. Dayne has averaged 270 carries in his
first three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne is capable of a huge season. He set an NCAA freshman
record with 2,109 total yards _ and he didn't become a starter
until the fifth game. However, Dayne's rushing totals have declined
each season _ from 1,863 to 1,421 to 1,279 yards this season. He
played in the Rose Bowl despite a torn muscle in his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Williams benefited from the emergence of Texas' passing game
under quarterback Major Applewhite. Opposing defenses had to worry
about the pass ``and'' Williams. Those conundrums keep defensive
coordinators from sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a passing threat, Dayne needs to be more durable.
Williams played nearly every significant play for Texas. Yesterday
in the Rose Bowl, Dayne carried on the Badgers' first three plays,
gaining 24 yards. Then, strangely, he sat for the next two plays.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne, though, is a load. His thighs make Earl Campbell's look
like a runway model's. It's been said that being hit by Dayne is
like being run over by a small car. And he's got speed; he scored
Wisconsin's first touchdown on 38-yard off-tackle burst where he
was untouched.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Williams made the right choice of not entering the
NFL draft after his junior season. He risked serious injury and
gambled that the Longhorns would improve under first-yard coach
Mack Brown. All bets were winners: He broke Dorsett's record, won
the Heisman, helped the Longhorns to a 9-3 season and a Cotton Bowl
victory. Dayne hopes to create similar memories in Madison this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was 37th in career rushing yards before this season;
Dayne is 19th. Dayne's three-year total of 4,563 yards is the
third-highest for players after their junior year, behind the 5,259
rushing yards Herschel Walker had for Georgia and the 4,589
Marshall Faulk compiled for San Diego State. Both Walker and Faulk
passed up their senior seasons to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne said his decision to return ``wasn't about the money.''
Maybe, for once, that's true. Dayne wants to be close to his
13-month-old daughter, Jada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a lot of fun in college and I wasn't ready to leave
my daughter yet,'' Dayne said. ``Her mother is staying for her
senior year and I wanted to see my daughter and her mother.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dayne knew he was unlikely to be a first-round NFL draft
pick. If he duplicates Williams' season, that should change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he made the right decision,'' Wisconsin coach Barry
Alvarez said. ``I think it will help him in the long run. It will
pay huge dividends, and obviously it will make us a better football
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy that deflects attention. Awards and records and all
those things have no meaning for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Those echo words uttered about Williams by Texas coach Mack
Brown. Williams applied that attitude to fashion one of the most
exalted seasons in college football history. Dayne appears poised
to follow his footsteps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
