<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-PLUMMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAKE PLUMMER HAS A MAGIC TOUCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are a believer in Jake Plummer, you see he is part Fran
Tarkenton and part Joe Montana and part Michael Jordan and part
Bret Maverick, the impudent rascal gambler played by James Garner
on the old ``Maverick'' TV western.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a go-getter,'' Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a believer in Jake Plummer, you marveled at his
last-minute football escapades at Arizona State and you saw this
pro career coming: Last week in a must-win situation against San
Diego, for the ninth time in 26 career games, second-year man
Plummer quarterbacked the Cardinals to a fourth-quarter comeback.
It's three consecutive weeks now that Plummer and the Cardinals
have won on the final play of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find a way to get it done,'' Plummer said. ``There is
something special about this team.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are a believer in Jake Plummer, you are Cardinals
management, which rewarded him with a four-year, $29.7 million
contract extension featuring an NFL-record $15 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been concerned too much about money,'' Plummer
said. ``I'm not going to let that change the way I play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are a believer in Jake Plummer, you are tackle Lomas
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seven seconds left,'' Brown recalls saying in the
huddle last Sunday, Arizona needing a win over San Diego to qualify
for the playoffs. ``Seven seconds is too many.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are a believer in Jake Plummer, you are all-time
offensive guru Bill Walsh, who said before the season, ``He will
need some help from his teammates, but if the Cardinals turn it
around in 1998 _ and that's not as far-fetched as it seems _ I
wouldn't be surprised if Jake Plummer is the league's most valuable
player. He's that good.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are not a believer in Jake Plummer. ... well, you haven't
been paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Plummer's 1998 numbers (a 75.0 QB rating, with 17
touchdowns to 20 interceptions) are less than impressive. But the
Cardinals boast a historic number with a maturing Plummer under
center: Arizona is an unprecedented 7-1 this year in games decided
by three points or less _ and Plummer's talent, leadership and
panache is the reason for it. Never was that more the case than
last Sunday when Plummer led his team to a game-winning field goal
in the final seven seconds that put the Cardinals in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake Plummer is a guy,'' said Cardinals cornerback Aeneas
Williams, ``who creates an aura.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who challenge the Cowboys in an NFL wild-card
game today, have long had a aura _ an unsavory one. There remain
questions about how ready this team and this franchise are for the
big time. They haven't defeated the Cowboys at Texas Stadium since
1989. They haven't beaten a team with a winning record all season.
They haven't participated in a nonstrike playoff game in the past
two decades and haven't won a postseason game since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   But the questions about Plummer's readiness are fading. It's
ridiculous to compare him to basketball legend Jordan, though
that's not stopping overzealous Cardinals officials. It's also
premature to compare him to Tarkenton, the smallish Minnesota
Vikings legend who was a scrambler before scrambling was cool. And
it's premature to compare him to a very unusual Joe, Montana, the
former San Francisco 49ers quarterback who has Plummer's same
slight build, knack for last-moment magic and jersey No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   But it's only off the field where Plummer seems to be an
ordinary Joe. Plummer, 24, is heralded in Arizona as an unassuming
team-first guy, a kid from Idaho who apparently favors a bowl
haircut, who spent his college years tooling around in the desert
in a Mazda without air conditioning, who purchased his first suit
in 1996 only because his mom convinced him it would be unbecoming
to attend the Heisman Trophy ceremony in New York wearing khaki
pants.
</P>
<P>
   And when asked what sort of suit he bought for the occasion,
Plummer responded:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. The top matches the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer was only a second-round pick of the Cardinals last year,
and started th 1997 season inactive for the first six weeks as the
third-stringer behind Kent Graham and Stoney Case. But Arizona
coach Vince Tobin says the 6-foot-2, 197-pound quarterback's
intangible assets were overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always players who have special leadership qualities
that can't be measured,'' Tobin said. ``Jake showed that starting
four years at ASU. We saw those same qualities last year as a
rookie. And we only expect him to keep improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in losses, Plummer has established his ability to overcome.
The most statistically stunning example of such savvy came in a
35-28 loss to the Cowboys on Nov. 15, when the Cardinals trailed
28-7 at halftime but stormed back to a near-win as Plummer threw
for 314 of his 465 yards in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had times this year,'' said Cowboys defensive coordinator
Dave Campo: ``when he's walked on water.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds backup quarterback Dave Brown, reflecting on the times when
Plummer comebacks fall short: ``Some guys have it, and some guys
don't. But what impresses me most is that he feels like he should
do it every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week at Sun Devil Stadium, after Plummer had engineered
another unlikely buzzer-beating victory, fireworks exploded. Many
of the 51,000 in attendance rushed the field. And as Plummer
trotted into the locker-room tunnel, tapping his heart and blowing
kisses to his faithful, banners were lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the eighth day, God created Jake,'' read one.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Plummer 3:16,'' read another.
</P>
<P>
   And the most simple, and most telling:
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
