A5055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-ANNIVERSARY-1STL     01-01 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ANNIVERSARY-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-ART-740(2TAKES)NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CITY OF CASTRO'S TRIUMPH, MOST STILL BACK HIM
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS grafs 3-7 to add comments from Castro's speech.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Cuba _ It has been 40 years since Fidel Castro marched
into this seaside colonial city at the head of a column of rebels
and declared the end of the Batista dictatorship from the balcony
of city hall. For residents here, it has been 40 years of
socialism, economic sacrifice and endless maneuvering in a cold war
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But as the city prepared Friday for Castro's return Friday night
to give a speech commemorating the anniversary of the revolution,
it was hard to find anyone on the streets here who would openly
criticize the 72-year-old Cuban leader or his policies.
</P>
<P>
   The town was dressed in propaganda. Cuban flags flew from
balconies, and signs celebrating the ``triumph of the revolution''
could be seen in all the shop windows. ``To be Cuban is a privilege
and a pact with Fidel,'' said one sign.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech here, Castro described the moment of victory on
Jan. 1, 1959, saying that ``I felt for a moment a strange sense of
emptiness'' to leave behind the ``hard, pure and healthy'' life of
a guerrilla to take over the leadership of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I lead are not the same people of that January
first,'' he said, noting that 7 million of Cuba's 11 million
inhabitants were born after the revolution. He said he was ``not
exactly the same man of that day, either.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he still thought the same way and predicted that the
capitalist system would fall. Referring to financial speculators,
he said, ``They have turned the planet into a giant casino.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews earlier, several working-class people and veterans
of the rebel army said they still supported Castro's long
experiment with socialism, despite the economic hardships they have
had to endure. Even with the economy in tatters, many said they
have more opportunity now than they did before 1959, when a good
education was out of reach for most poor people, especially those
with black skin. Castro's supporters also blame the U.S. trade
embargo and not the Castro government for their economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blockade is a crime against Cuba _ Cubans never deserved
this,'' said Ibrahim Salazar, a 63-year-old retired bus driver, who
was waiting with friends near the main plaza where workers were
setting the stage for Castro's speech.
</P>
<P>
   He wore a frayed T-shirt commemorating the revolution's 30th
anniversary. Salazar said he believed the revolution's major goals,
like free education and health care, had been met. His son had
become an engineer, something unthinkable for poor people 40 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't lose faith,'' he said. ``We have problems, but we are
going to conquer them.''
</P>
<P>
   But others, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
country's economic fabric had been slowly unraveling since 1991,
when the Soviet Union stopped subsidizing the economy with more
than $4 billion in aid. Since then, Cuba has become a country where
doctors make less than $30 a month and must moonlight as cab
drivers for tourists to make ends meet and where some educated
women with professional skills choose prostitution at resort hotels
as a way out of poverty. The average monthly salary is 207 pesos,
or about $10.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a country that more than 1 million people have fled
since Castro took over. Just last year, more than 450,000 applied
for visas to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sort of Titanic,'' said a one resident of Santiago,
who spoke on condition of anonymity because he feared arrest.
``Everyone is trying to get a boat to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The system doesn't work. At this moment money is the
principle problem for everyone here. You need money to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   After four decades of Castro's socialist experiment, Cuba has
become a paradox. With free education and health care, it has the
highest literacy rate and the lowest infant mortality rate in Latin
America. The average life expectancy is now 75.3 years, far above
the 60 years in 1959. The number of university graduates per capita
has quadrupled, and Cuban doctors have broken new ground in
biotechnology and vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Castro has failed to break the island's dependency on the
sugar crop and tourism for most of its hard-currency earnings _
twin factors that were blamed before the revolution for making Cuba
an economic vassal of the United States. And the country is no more
democratic than it was under Fulgencio Batista, the dictator who
fled on Jan. 1, 1959.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Since the fall of the Soviet Union, Castro has reluctantly
undertaken some market-oriented reforms. He has legalized the
dollar and allowed some small-scale private business: farmers'
markets, plumbing enterprises, hairdressers, language schools. He
has also decentralized some of the state-owned industries.
</P>
<P>
   But professionals like doctors, who continue to work are not
doing it for the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The living is not much, but we manage,'' said Dr. Juan
Fernandez, a general practitioner, who says he makes about $30 a
month. ``I like my profession, and I'm dedicated to my work.''
</P>
<P>
   To his supporters here in Santiago, Castro remains the best hope
for the working-class people in Cuba. Even if he is an autocrat,
several said, he is their autocrat, looking out for their
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Part of his appeal is rooted in history and nostalgia. Some of
the older residents remember the New Year's Day morning in 1959
when Castro and his troops marched into town and announced the end
of Batista's rule. There was jubilation in the streets, people
singing and cheering for the end of the regime, which had used
increasingly repressive measures in an effort to stanch the
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lived through many assassinations, many tortures, and
the life was impossible here,'' recalled Rafael Guillen, an
accountant. ``When Fidel came, it was as if we had been in great
pain and someone had given us a painkiller.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The new generation who didn't live through it cannot
understand it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Others continue to support Castro because he has advanced
equality for blacks and women. Fermin Reynoso, a 40-year-old
driver, who is black, said that before Castro's takeover, blacks of
his father's generation never had a chance of rising in society.
Racism was pervasive then, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But under Castro, Reynoso could have a military career. He
served for nine years, fighting in Angola and Ethiopia, and retired
as a lieutenant. Now he has a relatively good job, and his children
have a chance at a college degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The socialist system has given a lot of opportunities to all
the blacks here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rolando Segui, 83, is typical of many of the older people here
who still support Castro. Like his father before him, Segui was a
butcher in the 1950s. There was no chance of going to college, he
said, nor of becoming something other than a butcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to become a butcher because there was no other work,''
he said. ``I never had the opportunity to study.''
</P>
<P>
   He joined Castro's rebellion, the July 26 Movement, because he
was appalled at the political assassinations that Batista's
operatives were carrying out in the streets of Santiago,
eliminating young people on unproven charges that they sympathized
with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   After Castro's victory, Segui was rewarded with government jobs,
first as a health inspector and later a housing inspector. He
retired 10 years ago. Segui says he is still optimistic about the
future. The abject poverty, illiteracy and sickness he witnessed in
his youth no longer exists. Most important, he said, his
grandchildren have a chance of rising in society.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we fought for,'' he said. ``If you want to be a
doctor, and you have the capacity to be a doctor, you can be a
doctor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
