<HEADER>
A5061 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COTTON-COLUMN-HNS     01-01 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COTTON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas' defense comes full circle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS _ True, Major Applewhite was a college freshman with the
face of an eighth-grader. But everyone knew the kid had a serious
arm, Jackie Sherrill included. Nobody wanted Major more than Jackie
did.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ricky Williams, he returned to Texas as the odds-on
Heisman Trophy favorite. You couldn't screw up an offense with
Williams anchoring it. And the 'Horns had a bit of speed at
receiver, too. Wane McGarity runs faster, cleaner pass routes
despite a bionic knee than almost everybody in the country, the NFL
types included.
</P>
<P>
   That UT would generate 38 points in a Southwestern Bell Cotton
Bowl rout of Mississippi State on Friday should have shocked not a
soul.
</P>
<P>
   As Sherrill himself said, ``They've got a few weapons over
there, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Longhorns' defense had been allowed in recent years to
lose its teeth, horns and perhaps other significant manly body
parts. Mack Brown's milquetoast predecessor, the fired John
Mackovic, gave the strong impression defense bored him.
</P>
<P>
   This is how it would come to pass that a program made famous by
the hard-nosed likes of D.X. Bible and Darrell K Royal could reach
the point where it could conjure up a way to lose a home game to
UCLA 66-3.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and his defensive coordinator, the crusty old Carl Reese,
found out quickly last spring what they were up against.
</P>
<P>
   ``After our first contact drill,'' Reese said, ``I went home and
threw up.''
</P>
<P>
   Then things turned really ugly. Inevitably, the season came
around and New Mexico State _ New Mexico State! _ rammed the ball
down the 'Horns' gullets. Reese called Brown on the sideline and
conceded he was open to suggestions, that he had run out of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Next, picking up where they had left off in Austin, the Bruins
moved the ball so willfully at Texas' expense Reese said he didn't
have the slightest idea where to point fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really couldn't tell who was supposed to be covering
who,'' he said. ``UCLA's receivers were so open I didn't know who
to yell at.''
</P>
<P>
   At halftime that night in the Rose Bowl, Brown had had enough.
Furious _ and furious doesn't come easily for him _ he told his
starters they step up and show something or there would be a
different lineup on the field in their place the following week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drew a line in the dirt for them,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   And through a good portion of the defensive playbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``We greatly simplified what we were trying to do,'' Mack said.
``We weren't executing all that other stuff anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, something registered. With the lone senior in the
bunch, Dusty Renfro, taking the requisite lead, Reese's pieces
began to come together in fits and spurts. Oklahoma would be held
to three points. More remarkably, the vaunted Nebraska running game
would be squeezed lifeless as UT ended the 'Huskers' home winning
streak at 47.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there have been the occasional setbacks, such as the
relapse against Texas Tech, but the culmination of the 'Horns'
refurbished spirit was on display for all to see at Fair Park on
Friday, a thick early fog notwithstanding. Old nemesis Sherrill
probably didn't recognize the team of erstwhile ``powderpuffs'' _
Reese's word _ he had whipped up on seven times in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Late third quarter. Fourth-and-one. Texas leading 31-3.
Desperate, Jackie goes for the first down at his 19. Middle
linebacker Renfro, wearing the No. 60 Tommy Nobis made
unforgettable to honor the memory of Nobis' renowned defensive
coordinator, the late Mike Campbell, pile-drives James Johnson into
reverse for a one-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the 'Horns are in the end zone again. It's 38-3.
It's over. Final score: Texas 38, Sherrill 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poooor Jackie,'' the Orangebloods in the stadium could chant.
Boy, had they waited a long time to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the spirit of the '60s in me today,'' Renfro said.
``And that play is the one I'll remember the most. We've come a
long way.''
</P>
<P>
   So did he believe he was leaving the Texas defense in good
hands?
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' Renfro said. ``I just wish I had three more
years of eligibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Every other Longhorns starter returns. Come spring, Reese will
reinsert the fancy gimmicks he had scrapped out of frustration
weeks ago. He is plotting improvements. He expects his defense to
progress to a higher plane in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not there yet,'' he argues. ``We've got a bunch to
improve on.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt. After all, the Bulldogs did rush for a whopping 87
yards. And Wayne Madkin, Applewhite's freshman counterpart at
quarterback for MSU, was permitted to complete 25 percent of his
passes before Sherrill, showing pity, sent in Matt Wyatt. Shame,
shame, Carl.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of losing Williams to the NFL can't be overestimated.
A player of Ricky's special stature makes everybody several notches
better simply by association Without him, Applewhite figures to
take a step backward before he takes another, uh, major step
forward. And Brown surely will have days when he doesn't look
nearly as smart as he appears right now, with the 9-3 'Horns, in
his words ``back in the national picture.''
</P>
<P>
   But defense, like love, tends to conquer all. If Renfro can be
replaced _ spiritually perhaps more importantly than physically _
Mack will have the knife with which he can win. It's nice to see
Texas being Texas again.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, Mike Campbell should be smiling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
