<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5062 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COTTON-WILLIAMS-H     01-01 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COTTON-WILLIAMS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Williams goes out in style for UT
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DALLAS _ Throughout all four years of his brilliant college career,
Ricky Williams had humbly handed the football to an official
whenever he scored a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams decided he would make a one-time exception in his
final college game. When he scored on a 37-yard run in the third
quarter of Texas' 38-11 Cotton Bowl victory over Mississippi State
on Friday, it was time to thrill his teammates and the fans by
hamming it up a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   Williams stood in the end zone and broke into the Heisman Trophy
pose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something the guys have tried to get me to do all year,''
he said. ``I didn't want to do it until after I won the award. I
knew when I did it today we were far enough ahead (21-3) that the
penalty wouldn't hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas was penalized 15 yards on the kickoff, but it wasn't for
taunting by Williams. The whistle came on the extra point when a UT
player was flagged for a personal foul. After all, what official
could blame a guy for showing off once in a career of amazing
moments?
</P>
<P>
   Williams ended his record-setting career with another
record-setting day, rushing for 203 yards on 30 carries and scoring
two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most rushing yards ever for a UT player in a bowl and
the third-most in the 63-year history of the Cotton Bowl. Williams
also had 45 yards receiving on five catches to give him a Cotton
Bowl record 248 tandem yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were all the questions about whether you can play with
focus after winning the Heisman Trophy because of all the
distractions,'' said Texas coach Mack Brown. ``There was even a
rumor that Ricky had gotten fat, but I thought he looked pretty
good today.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Williams surprised many people by opting to return
for his senior year when he likely would have been a first-round
draft choice in the NFL. But it turned into a dream season for the
talented running back. He won the Heisman and became Division I's
career rushing leader with 6,279 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely was worth it,'' Williams said. ``I'm a much
stronger and smarter football player after this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing that made Friday's game special for Williams was
the fact it came on Doak Walker Day in Texas. Walker, who won the
1948 Heisman at SMU, died in September at 71.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was so special on Doak Walker Day for Ricky to
play so well on Doak's birthday in the house that Doak built,''
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who would have turned 72 on Friday, also played in the
Cotton Bowl in his Heisman season 50 years ago. To honor him, his
No. 37 was painted at the 37-yard line on each side of the field
for Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Walker had become friends in the last year before
Walker's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely was on my mind,'' Williams said. ``I was looking
for his number every time I crossed the 37-yard line. I wanted to
give him a great birthday present. Then I found out one of my
touchdowns was 37 yards, which I thought was kind of neat.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching Williams reach every goal he set out to achieve
this season, Brown was asked if there was anything he can't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. He can't come back next year,'' quipped Brown. ``We
already have checked.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he can't sing. I asked him at a pep rally to sing, and
that was an awful mistake. Those are the only two things I know he
can't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I learned that Ricky Williams is a lot more than a great
football player. He's a young man that does things right and does
things with a lot of class. When you challenge him with something,
he steps up to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State safety Anthony Derricks admitted after that
game that he never had faced an opponent like Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky certainly deserves the Heisman,'' Derricks said. ``He is
the best running back I have ever played against. I've played
against some great ones, but he's the best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
