<HEADER>
A5063 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PHILHARMONIC-REVIE     01-01 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PHILHARMONIC-REVIEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. PHILHARMONIC: A NEW YEAR'S EVE GALA WITH A BIT OF NEWNESS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By   ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You'll get no complaints here about the waltzes of
Johann Strauss Jr., which are absolutely perfect pieces. No less a
formidable composer than Brahms was an enormous admirer of the
waltz king's work, and having tried his own hand at waltz writing,
he knew it wasn't as easy as it looked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, why is it that when something festive is wanted for a New
Year's Eve Gala program, symphony orchestras seldom come up with
anything other than Strauss? Surely there are other candidates,
some of them American. My choice would be Leroy Anderson, the
overlooked master of the short, skillfully rendered orchestral
novelty piece. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But credit Kurt Masur and the New York Philharmonic with the
good idea of adding Richard Strauss (no relation) to their New
Year's Eve Gala of Johann Strauss on Thursday night, specifically,
excerpts from the former's ``Rosenkavalier.'' Three splendid
singers were on hand as soloists: the sopranos Deborah Voigt and
Heidi Grant Murphy, and, in her New York Philharmonic debut, the
Austrian mezzo-soprano Angelika Kirchschlager.
</P>
<P>
   Actually ``Der Rosenkavalier'' is a most appropriate piece for
reflecting on the past and preparing for the future. In the
love-at-first-sight duets for Sophie and Octavian, we experience
the impetuous ecstasy of adolescence. And in the Marschallin's
teary yet graceful exit from her affair with young Octavian, which
she knew was bound to end but not, as she says in her most moving
line, so quickly, we learn to cherish the present while we can, but
not cling when the time comes to let go. Pretty good advice for New
Year's Eve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As has been the custom, Avery Fisher Hall was decked with swaths
of gold, orange, aquamarine, purple and rose-red fabrics, some of
them stretched across the entire hall like crepe paper streamers.
The women in the orchestra wore festive dresses, a refreshing
change from the requisite formal black. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Murphy was replacing on short notice the soprano Noemi
Nadelmann. But this young American soprano is a veteran Sophie, and
her luminous, creamy voice sounded lovely in the transfixing ``Rose
Duet,'' as it is often called. Ms. Kirchschlager, with her rich,
dusky-toned mezzo-soprano voice, projected young count Octavian's
hormonal passions, but also his awed confusion in the face of
Sophie's disarming beauty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then Ms. Voigt joined the duo for the opera's great final trio
and showed again that she can rein in her powerhouse voice to sing
with affecting tenderness. Ms. Murphy and Ms. Kirchschlager also
performed the subsequent duet that concludes the opera, which left
Ms. Voigt somewhat underutilized in the program's first half. She
might, for instance, have been asked to sing something else by
Richard Strauss (an orchestral song, an operatic scene) in place of
the rather ineffective arrangement of waltzes from ``Der
Rosenkavalier'' with which Masur began the concert. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A conductor has to be careful in this opera not to overly milk
the music's opulent lyricism. But Masur went too much to the other
extreme: his tempos were somewhat brisk; phrases were clipped, and
some of the most heavenly moments had no time to register. You
would have thought Masur was determined above all to end the
program, which was being televised live, at the scheduled 10 p.m.
Still, he drew lush, attentive and texturally transparent playing
from the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The works by Johann Strauss that Masur turned to in the second
half included the popular ``Pizzicato-Polka'' (actually composed by
Johann with his brother Josef), the witty ``Perpetuum Mobile,'' the
exotic Egyptian March and, of course, the Blue Danube Waltz, all
winningly done.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's soloists returned, having changed into more
glamorous gowns (which I believe they would want acknowledged), to
sing one additional work each. Ms. Kirchschlager brought ardor and
elegance to ``Wiener Blut,'' though Masur let the orchestra
overpower her somewhat; Ms. Murphy sang ``Draussen in Sievering''
liltingly, and Ms. Voigt poured out her voice excitingly in the
``Csardas'' from ``Die Fledermaus,'' which was something to hear:
imagine Sieglinde trying to cheer up Siegmund with a little
Hungarian number.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were encores, of course: more dances and polkas, for which
Masur dapperly wore a Fred Astaire top hat, and the audience
clapped along to a rousing march. The guest vocalists returned for
the inevitable ``Auld Lang Syne,'' and those concertgoers not
staying for the fancy post-concert dinner, a benefit for the
orchestra's pension fund, bundled up to face the chilly weather. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 2339EST &QL; 
