<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ROSE-BOWL-NYT     01-01 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROSE-BOWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYNE'S 4 TOUCHDOWNS AND 246 YARDS HUMBLE UCLA 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By KEN GURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Now UCLA will not have to wonder about the
national championship that could have been.
</P>
<P>
   Not after Friday, when Wisconsin beat the Bruins, 38-31, in the
85th Rose Bowl. The Badgers were powered by four touchdowns from
the running back Ron Dayne and a clinching 46-yard interception
return for a touchdown by a freshman cornerback, Jamar Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   The victory provided the Badgers with a measure of pride after
being disrespected nationwide, most notably by CBS analyst Craig
James, who called them ``the worst team ever to play in the Rose
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what does that make UCLA? After being abused for 689 yards
by Miami in the Dec. 5 loss that canceled their Fiesta Bowl
invitation to play for the national championship, the Bruins (10-2)
allowed Wisconsin 497 yards, including 246 by Dayne, 1 yard short
of the Rose Bowl record.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin (11-1) ended the season with the most victories in
school history, but UCLA quarterback Cade McNown, a Heisman Trophy
finalist, passed easily through its top-rated defense.The Badgers,
however, came up with big plays repeatedly in the fourth quarter to
make Dayne's remarkable performance hold up. The clincher was
freshman Wendell Bryant's sack of McNown on fourth-and-3 at the
Wisconsin 47 with 59 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA made too many careless mistakes in a game the Bruins were
supposedly motivated to win as redemption for their loss to Miami.
Instead, the Bruins offense kept putting points on the board, but
the defense was no match for the opposing running game, namely
Dayne.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder UCLA coach Bob Toledo teased earlier in the week that
the Bruins' defense practiced defending Dayne by tackling pickup
trucks. By the second quarter it seemed to be a contest as to who
would collapse first _ Dayne from running up and down the Rose Bowl
field or the Bruins defense from chasing him.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-10-inch, 253-pound back had 173 yards and three
touchdowns by halftime. His favorite direction was right, behind
368-pound tackle Aaron Gibson, one of the biggest players in
college football.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers were supposed to be too small, too slow and not
athletic enough to compete with the Bruins, who were favored by 10
points. But both teams were good enough to be seeking their 11th
victory this season, and the first half was an entertaining
offensive dogfight, with Wisconsin leading, 24-21, and outgaining
UCLA in yardage, 333-305.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had had their sights set on Monday's Fiesta Bowl
until their debacle in Miami in the last game of the season, and
the Badgers were picked for the Rose Bowl as tri-champions of the
Big 10 Conference because they had not played in the bowl for the
longest time.
</P>
<P>
   The game was supposed to be a test of UCLA's defense, after
Miami's Edgerrin Jones had run wild for 299 yards, as well as a
test of Wisconsin's defense, ranked No. 1 in the nation. As the
score indicated, both defenses will want to burn the game films.
</P>
<P>
   With UCLA's maligned group further hampered by injuries,
Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez set the tone immediately, calling
Dayne's number on Wisconsin's first three plays of the game. Dayne
churned out gains of 10, 7 and 7 yards, carrying Bruins defenders
on his back until he could be gang tackled. That drive fizzled when
the Badgers started mixing in pass plays, but they went back to the
big man on their next possession.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne's brute strength, though, had nothing to do with his first
touchdown run. On first down, he took a simple handoff, jumped
outside to the left and no Bruin put a hand on him as he powered
down the sideline 54 yards for his longest rush of the season on
way to a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's offense, at least, accepted the challenge. A seven-play
drive that included McNown completions of 22 and 16 yards ended
with a 38-yard touchdown catch-and-run by tailback Jermaine Lewis,
who slipped up the middle, took McNown's flip to the right, eluded
linebacker Donnel Thompson's tackle and sprinted down the sideline
behind a perfect block from wide receiver Brian Poli-Dixon to tie
it at 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   quarterback Mike Samuel set up Dayne's second touchdown with a
52-yard run down the sideline on an option play. Two plays later
Dayne patiently followed the blocks of Casey Rabach and Eric Grams
around right end for a 7-yard score that led to a 14-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo came right back with a perfectly executed gimmick play
featuring Freddie Mitchell. On second-and-6 from his 39, McNown
rolled left and shoveled to Mitchell on a reverse. Mitchell pulled
up and launched a bomb that Durell Price ran under, catching the
ball at the 20 and running in for the 61-yard touchdown and a 14-14
tie.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA took a 21-14 lead on McNown's arm, a 41-yard post-pattern
to Danny Farmer, who beat freshman Jamar Fletcher, then used his
volleyball jumping skills to reach back for the pass McNown
underthrew.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne's third score, a 5-yard touchdown capping a drive that
included runs of 20 and 36 yards, tied it at 21-21.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Davenport's 40-yard field goal with 17 seconds left in the
half gave Wisconsin a 24-21 lead, and the Bruins narrowly escaped
disaster when they could not handle Vitaly Pisetskys squib kickoff.
But Randy Hakes recovered for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne appeared refreshed after halftime, carrying four times on
his team's first series of the third quarter. His final rush was
his fourth touchdown, a 22-yarder to help give the Badgers a 31-21
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins could have climbed right back but for a devastating
communication mixup between McNown and a freshman running back,
DeShaun Foster. A 44-yard completion to Farmer set up the Bruins at
the Wisconsin 6 . Even after McNown called a timeout, confusion
reigned on the ensuing audible as McNown pitched to Foster, who was
expecting a handoff and the ball bounced off his chest, recovered
by the Badgers.
</P>
<P>
   Although playing in their home stadium, the Bruins were
overwhelmed by the noise the predominantly Wisconsin crowd produced
when they neared the end zone. McNown was forced to burn a second
time out the next time the Bruins reached the red zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
