<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-INAUG-SCENE-NYT &LR;      01-01 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-INAUG-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE PAGEANTRY, MUCH SPECULATION ABOUT PATAKI'S PRESIDENTIAL
PLANS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also NY-INAUG, NY-INAUG-EXCERPT) 
(DW) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ George E. Pataki's inaugural celebration four
years ago had the trappings of a coronation _ a pageant replete
with marching bands, celebrities, a laser show, confetti and a
black-tie gala for 13,000 guests.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, as Pataki was sworn in for a second term, he and his
supporters shunned the sort of lavishness and pomp that made his
first inaugural party one of the most extravagant in the state's
history.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's 1999 swearing-in was celebrated at a modest reception
in a ballroom at the Omni Hotel in downtown Albany, where about 300
people gathered to sample plates of chicken and beef, dance to the
music of a six-piece jazz band and chat from 1 p.m. to 3 p.m. The
nearest thing approaching extravagance was a 180-pound cake baked
in the shape of the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   So why was there so much temperance this time around?
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's aides explained that his re-election victory did not
call for the kind of three-day bash thrown back in January 1995,
after he defeated Mario M. Cuomo, a three-term Democrat, and became
New York's first Republican Governor in more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   That may very well be. But Pataki also drew a lot of political
and legal heat as a result of the way his aides financed his 1995
inaugural. That time, his advisers created two private committees
to raise money for the inaugural and transition.
</P>
<P>
   The aides refused to disclose who made donations to the
committees, even after Democrats sued, seeking the information.
When Pataki's aides released the list of donors to comply with a
court order, it showed that many donations were from corporations
doing business with the state.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's inauguration came a few weeks after Pataki announced
that he would spend part of his second term traveling around the
country, speaking out on issues that he has said are important to
New York state and the nation. That announcement reignited
speculation that Pataki was flirting with the notion of running for
national office. The governor and his aides have said that his
travel plans do not reflect any ambitions beyond Albany. But both
supporters and detractors who watched him being sworn in Friday
could not resist offering their thoughts about the governor's
national prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is heading in the right direction under this
governor,'' said Thomas Libous, a Republican state senator from
Binghamton. ``If people around the nation see the kind of
leadership he has provided here, he'll definitely be a national
contender.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of his most ardent Democratic rivals conceded that the
folksy image Pataki has carefully tailored may play well
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Weprin, a Democratic assemblyman from Queens, said he found
the governor's speech rather humdrum and filled with platitudes but
few specifics. But he grudgingly acknowledged that what he found
dull might attract a scandal-weary electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had to pick a flavor to describe this governor, it
would be vanilla,'' Weprin said. ``But the thing is that many
people like vanilla. If he has any chance as a presidential
candidate, it's because people like his folksy image. He's got this
Jimmy Stewart style.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
