<HEADLINE>
OFFENSIVE LINE SHOULDERS BLAME FOR UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER   
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ UCLA's offensive line is considered the best
in the Pac-10, but the Bruins met their match in Wisconsin's
defensive line, led by All-American Tom Burke.
</P>
<P>
   For UCLA, the collision in the trenches was a draw, at best.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins averaged a mere 3.2 yards per rush, they were called
for several drive-killing holding penalties and they struggled to
protect quarterback Cade McNown, who was sacked three times _
including the final play _ and pressured throughout the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had allowed just 10 sacks all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an offensive line, we take a lot of the blame,'' guard Andy
Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The line was not to blame for every sack or hurry, however. On
several plays, McNown had time to throw but couldn't find an open
receiver. Without Brian Poli-Dixon, who missed most of the game
with a hamstring injury, the Bruins had few downfield options other
than Danny Farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The receivers had some trouble getting off the corners,''
Meyers said, ``but we had the most trouble on rollout plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Going, going . . . Did junior offensive tackle Kris Farris play
his last game for UCLA?
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Farris said he would make a decision about jumping to
the NFL after facing Burke, one of the best lineman in the nation.
When the Rose Bowl ended, Farris talked like someone who had played
his last college game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make a decision over the weekend, but I think I played
the game of my life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he added: ``I was very nervous all week because this game
was going to set up any decision I made, and I'm !ital!very
pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   There's little doubt among his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he's been talking, he's gone,'' one Bruin said.
</P>
<P>
   High Price: Sylmar native Durell Price played one of the best
games of his career with three catches for 102 yards and a
touchdown on a trick pass by receiver Freddie Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the second read,'' Price said. ``If the cornerbacks went
with Farmer, which was likely, he was going to me. They forgot
about the little old fullback.''
</P>
<P>
   A candidate? According to published reports out of Seattle, UCLA
offensive coordinator Al Borges is a secondary candidate for the
vacant Washington coaching position.
</P>
<P>
   Borges is well-respected but lacks two important qualities: He
does not have head-coaching experience, and he does not have ties
to the Washington program.
</P>
<P>
   According to a source, Borges spoke briefly with ex-Washington
coach Don James several weeks ago but has not been contacted by the
Husky administration. James is an unofficial member of the search
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Borges declined to comment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
