</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GAY-PARTY-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY CHARITY EVENT SEEN AS SENDING WRONG MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The news that organizers had canceled the Morning
Party on Fire Island did not surprise Michael Ruggiero. He has
attended the annual AIDS fund-raising event and social gathering
for the last three years, and while he described it as ``a very
spiritual thing,'' he also recognized that ``it was meant to die.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the positive emotion of standing on the beach,
dancing and remembering those lost to AIDS. But he also
acknowledged the illegal drug use and unsafe sex that have brought
the event increased scrutiny, including that from the police
officers who were standing by last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It progressively got more restrained, so it wasn't like a
party,'' said Ruggiero, 37, sipping coffee on Friday at the Big
Cup, a coffee shop in the Chelsea section of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the lack of restraint at the Morning Party _ at
1998's event, for instance, a man overdosed and died before the
party began _ and the bad publicity that resulted, that prompted
the Gay Men's Health Crisis to cancel what had been an event
memorializing AIDS victims as well as the organization's
second-largest fund-raiser after its AIDS Walk.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the United States' leading AIDS service group, the GMHC
had come under intense pressure from gay critics, who derided the
organization as hypocritical for sponsoring a fund-raising event
where illegal drug use and unsafe sex flourished.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with about 20 men on Friday in Chelsea revealed a
widely held sense that the GMHC was correct to cancel the event,
which many said had come to send the wrong message. Several men
also said the publicity might provoke discussion about what they
called the prevalence of drugs in a growing number of similar
parties around the nation, known as ``circuit parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Rawhide, a gay nightclub, the party from New Year's
Eve was still under way at noon Friday. Shirtless and playing a
video game, Dan Reaume, 36, called the Morning Party a hypocritical
event for a gay elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the pretentious crowd,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another man, who identified himself only as Jim, stood nearby,
drinking a beer and smoking a cigarette. He said he attended the
Morning Party in 1996 and predicted it would continue without GMHC
sponsorship. ``There's enough money at Fire Island until something
stronger happens,'' said Jim, who is 33. But even if the party goes
on, he said, the spirit and the purpose of it was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hypocritical,'' he said. ``They were fund raising for
AIDS, and the behavior at the party was contributing to it at the
same time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Walking arm-in-arm up Eighth Avenue in Chelsea, Henry Hodges and
Craig Hibbard, both 34, said they were startled that the party had
been canceled, though not surprised. Hodges said GMHC's decision
might force a healthy discussion of what he called excessive drug
use in the gay club scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of taken for granted that if you're gay, it's all
about drugs and partying,'' he said. Hodges said the prevalence of
drugs is rarely questioned or condemned and that some regulars in
the nightclub scene consider it a ``God-given right to do all the
drugs you want without interference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to question the whole way the scene is set up,''
Hodges said of the circuit-party phenomenon. ``It could be
healthier.''
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, another couple, Carlos Otero and Larry
Isaacson, disagreed about the party. Otero, 32, said, ``Everybody
knows it's a drug party.'' He said he attended two years ago and
enjoyed himself, but he questioned a health organization's fund
raising at such an event. ``What's the message?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Isaacson, however, said he regretted the party's demise and
called it ``an introduction to a charity for a lot of people who
otherwise wouldn't be attracted to charitable events.'' He said
that the party's growth paralleled the GMHC's growth and that the
organization should not be held responsible for the poor behavior
of some guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that some people who couldn't control
themselves or act appropriately have basically forced the GMHC to
cancel the event,'' said Isaacson, 35. ``A few people have ruined
it for everybody else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
