<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS TO PLAY JAGUARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Nick Cafardo 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ A week of practice ended with the usual rhetoric:
``We had a great week out there,'' was the common theme. Sentiments
that are shallow until they're transferred to performance in
Sunday's wild-card game against the Jacksonville Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot going on around Foxborough these days.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of a coach being fired. Talk of leaders rising up. Talk of
a team that normally plays well after adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we responded really well,'' said Chad Eaton. ``I
think everybody went out there this week all business and prepared
like we were supposed to for a game of this magnitude. We're going
to put out a game we're going to be proud of (Sunday). I think
everybody wants that more than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   There are players who said things they regretted, who want to
prove something.
</P>
<P>
   There are players who are pro-Pete, who want to make sure
there's no doubt whom their coach is next year.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Jefferson, Henry Thomas, Ferric Collons, and Eaton all
spoke up to the team this week, showing signs of leadership that
the coach appreciated and made note of at his daily press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that (saving Carroll's job) is going to be a big
motivator,'' said Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   There's motivation for Willie McGinest, who has missed seven
games with a groin pull, to play hard, especially against Tony
Boselli.
</P>
<P>
   There's motivation for Scott Zolak to win the respect and
admiration of the fans by winning a playoff game as a starting
quarterback. There's also personal gain at stake, as Zolak is an
unrestricted free agent and his value could be enhanced with a
solid performance.
</P>
<P>
   There's motivation for Jefferson, who has to assume the No. 1
receiver duties in his hometown with family watching.
</P>
<P>
   There's motivation for Ty Law to keep showing he's worthy of
being considered one of the best cornerbacks in football. Though he
has a year remaining on his contract, it becomes more evident every
day that Law soon will command Deion Sanders money (about $5
million a year).
</P>
<P>
   There's motivation for Robert Edwards, who would like nothing
better than to outgain fellow rookie Fred Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   There's motivation for Vernon Crawford, who crunched
Jacksonville return man Reggie Barlow in the first quarter of a
26-20 win last season, dislodged the ball, and recovered the fumble
at the Jaguars' 27-yard line. That led to a 13-0 first-quarter
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go down there, I don't want it to be a one-time
thing,'' said Crawford. ``I feel I can make it happen again.
Offensively, defensively, and special teams, we all have to go
above and beyond this week.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the theory espoused by big-play receiver Troy Brown, who
has been limited by a severely sprained left ankle. He has gone
virtually unnoticed since returning to the lineup Dec. 6 at
Pittsburgh, catching only two passes for 42 yards. He's returned
four punts during that time, the longest for 14 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wake up in the morning and feel great, and then I wake up
the next day I don't feel so great,'' said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need complete rest in the offseason, but I don't have time
for that right now. I have to go out there and go all out. This is
playoff time, and hopefully they're depending on me to make some
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said it's do or die, and he's ``not ready to go home
yet.'' Brown said he's ready to break a play, whether it's a punt
or a big reception. He said everybody needs to have that attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he hopes Zolak can find him. He said the plays are
still the same, but he didn't line up much with the regular offense
(maybe three third-down plays).
</P>
<P>
   It was a motivating week. A hectic week.
</P>
<P>
   A lot was said, good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about what we do on the field now,'' said Eaton.
</P>
</TEXT>
