<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-McDONALD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Vt.)  
 JOHN McDONALD, WROTE MEMOIR OF GM'S ALFRED P. SLOAN  
(rl) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John D. McDonald, who with Alfred P. Sloan Jr. wrote ``My Years
With General Motors,'' a classic volume on business strategy that
has been used as a college text for 35 years, died Dec. 23 of
respiratory failure, his daughter Joan McDonald Miller said Friday.
He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald was visiting his other daughter, Christie, at her
vacation home in Berkshire, Vt., when he died, Mrs. Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald was a dedicated Trotskyite in the 1930s but became a
chronicler of capitalism when Fortune magazine hired him as a staff
writer in 1945. He wrote about a wide range of subjects for the
magazine, including business strategies, fly-fishing and horse
racing.
</P>
<P>
   His best-known work was the 1964 memoir of Sloan, the visionary
executive who ran GM from 1923 to 1956. McDonald was listed as the
editor of the book, which was based partly on tape-recorded
interviews with Sloan, but he actually wrote it, Jason Epstein, the
editor who acquired it for Doubleday, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before he died, McDonald was shopping a 70,000-word
manuscript, ``A Ghost's Memoir,'' in which he told how GM tried to
suppress the book because the company believed it could be used by
the Justice Department to launch an antitrust case against it.
</P>
<P>
   For five years McDonald and Sloan worked to hone the book's
story of how Sloan melded a gaggle of car companies and parts
makers into the biggest industrial corporation in the world. But on
March 4, 1959, according to a recent article in Forbes by Dan
Seligman, who helped McDonald research the book, Sloan told
McDonald, ``John, we are not publishing.'' McDonald then began a
five-year struggle to get the book published.
</P>
<P>
   Seligman, a contributing editor at Forbes, said Friday that
McDonald ``was a terribly serious guy, so even when he wrote about
fishing and horse racing there was a real scholarly tone to his
work.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's other business books included ``Strategy in Poker,
Business and War'' in 1950, and ``The Game of Business,'' about
game theory and business strategy, in 1975. He also wrote three
books on fly-fishing: ``The Complete Fly Fisherman'' (1947), ``The
Origins of Angling'' (1963) and ``Quill Gordon'' (1972).
</P>
<P>
   He retired from Fortune in 1971. Five years later he received
the Gerald Loeb Memorial Award, one of the highest honors in
financial journalism.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald worked in his father's Detroit pharmacy and became a
licensed pharmacist. He then moved into radical politics, becoming
a prominent follower of Leon Trotsky in the 1930s when the Russian
revolutionary was being denounced by Stalin as a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   His first marriage, to Lorraine Oven in 1928, ended in divorce.
He married Dorothy Eisner in 1936. She died in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his daughters, Joan McDonald Miller of
Manhattan and Christie McDonald of Cambridge, Mass., and three
grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-01-99 2354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990101.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5080 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-BOS     01-01 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEE TIME IS NEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Mark Blaudschun 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ The calls would come at all hours of the day and
night. Did you hear what happened? None of it made sense, of
course. How could it?
</P>
<P>
   How could you rationalize going to school with your buddy one
day, and you come to class the next day and he would be gone _ a
victim of some foolish act, something to do with drugs or money or
some other slight that caused an argument to flare into a major
confrontation?
</P>
<P>
   Tee Martin didn't understand that day in Birmingham, Ala., a few
years back when he was having a water balloon fight with his friend
Gary Simmons, went into his house to get more ammunition for the
battle, and heard the shots.
</P>
<P>
   By then Tee's instincts told him the worst. Another incident,
another friend dead.
</P>
<P>
   He was just 17, and he had already been to more funerals than
proms. He was already wise beyond his years. ``I learned not to be
close to anybody,'' Tee Martin was saying the other day on a warm,
sunny winter day, surrounded by people with minicams, tape
recorders, and note pads who were picking at old wounds that are
just beginning to heal. ``I took the attitude that if I allowed
myself to get close to anybody, they might die.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who will be the starting quarterback for the University
of Tennessee in the biggest game of his life _ Monday night's
Fiesta Bowl national championship game against Florida State _
already has a post-graduate degree in the study of whether life is
fair at times.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through his college years, Tamaurice Martin knows this:
</P>
<P>
   At least 12 of his friends have died since he came to Tennessee
three years ago as a hotshot quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   His father is Pierre Maurice Marshall, a onetime high school
football star whose main claim to fame is that he played on the
same team at Mississippi Valley State as legendary wide receiver
Jerry Rice.
</P>
<P>
   His father has been a ghost in his life, showing up only
sporadically, yet he remains forever linked, simply because of his
name: TaMaurice, or as Marie Martin said with affection on July 25,
1978, after her son was born: To Maurice. Taumaurice. Tee.
</P>
<P>
   Martin talks about his past the way he talks about the present
or the future, with a smile, looking you in the eye. He got up and
made the speech the other day in front of hundreds of strangers and
absolutely dazzled them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most poised, confident talk I've ever heard,'' said
Tennessee football coach Phil Fulmer, who knowing that there would
be life after Peyton Manning, went out three years ago and won the
battle for Martin over schools such as Auburn, Florida, Florida
State, and Miami. ``But that's just the way Tee is.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin knows that Tennessee might not win Monday night. Despite
being unbeaten and ranked No. 1 in the country, despite a magical
season that has been highlighted by 26 touchdowns (19 passing, 6
running) and only six interceptions, Tee Martin might walk away
from Sun Devil Stadium with a sense of disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   It will bother him, not destroy him. ``I've always felt that
something good will come out of bad situations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over as the starter this season following Manning's
record-setting four-year career as the Vols' quarterback, Martin
has proven that he is a good quarterback. And he has done something
Manning never did: take the Vols to the threshold of a national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates have noticed. ``Look at all he has accomplished,''
said wide receiver Cedric Wilson. ``He has to have had the best
season any quarterback at Tennessee has ever had. He beat Florida.
He won another (Southeastern Conference) title. Now we're playing
for the national championship. Name another QB that has done that
for this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peyton had a lot of pressure on him. He always wanted to make
the big play. Everything he did was to `Go get it.' But it cost us.
He threw a lot of interceptions in difficult situations. Tee wil
throw the ball away to save an interception.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has fought the perception that he is a quarterback who
would prefer to run. ``Ever since I've been a quarterback, all I've
wanted to do was throw the ball,'' he said. ``In high school, the
only running plays we had were when I ran a quarterback draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Martin doesn't like to run. He will take off if you
give him an opening. But his instincts are that of a pure dropback
passer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in the projects of Mobile, Ala., Martin grew up
quickly. After his birth, it was clear that his 18-year-old mother
was not ready to handle being a full-time mother. His
great-grandmother, Mary Posley, took a full-time role in that area,
setting parameters about behavior and lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Sports was the outlet Martin used to stay out of trouble, or as
far away from it as he could. Baseball, basketball, and football
were his priorities _ in that order.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his father, football became a factor. Although Pierre
Maurice was more of an occasional influence, Tee idolized him. In
high school, he wanted to wear the same No. 17 his father had worn.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was freshman at Williamson High School, he was a
starter. By the time he left, he was a two-time all-state
quarterback and a Parade All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Martin had colleges from all over the country calling and
offering him things. Mary Posley told him to try and look people in
the eye and make judgments. Be careful, she said. People who offer
you things have their own self-interests first.
</P>
<P>
   So Martin worked his way through the process. He was not naive,
not with all the violence at his doorstep, acts that had prompted
him to take a ``When-it's-your-time-to-go,-it's-your-time-to-go''
attitude toward life.
</P>
<P>
   He came to Tennessee after Tim Couch made a last-minute switch
to his home state of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   For two years he sat and watched Manning. ``I was his vice
president,'' Martin said. ``I learned a lot. We talk all the time
about a lot of things, not just football.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin looks at you and talks about all of this with a smile. He
knows things. He has said that he has learned lessons. He has been
the eyewitness to three killings, which has made it almost
impossible for him to cry anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the anger is still inside of him. The unfairness of it
all. The senselessness of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned that keeping my family around me is important,''
says Martin, who still stays in touch with his father. ``I've also
learned that football is just a game.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Tee Martin fully expects to play the game of
his life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
