<SLUG> BC-1999-CREDIT-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONDS, NOT BAD IN '98, MAY DO BETTER THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Monday, Jan. 4) 
(rl) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What was one of the best kept secrets of 1998? That being in
bonds was not such a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the selloff in December, the total return from an
investment in the 30-year Treasury bond was 17.6 percent. A bet on
the 10-year note brought home 12.7 percent. And while corporate,
junk and municipal bonds have not done as well, it was not a
terrible year for them. The return on a AA 10-year industrial
corporate was about 11.5 percent, while a 10-year municipal bond
had a total return, including the capital gain, of 6.8 percent. And
of that, 5.3 percentage points were tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that being in bonds this year will be an
even better idea, especially if investors venture out of Treasuries
and into the corporate, mortgage and municipal sectors.
</P>
<P>
   That may seem hard to believe, given the selloff in the
fixed-income world in August, September and October.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, you could not find anyone who wanted a corporate
bond, a junk bond, emerging market debt or mortgage-backed bonds.
Those parts of the bond market were frozen as the effective default
of Russia and the near collapse of the hedge fund Long-Term Capital
Management sent investors to the safety of the Treasury market.
</P>
<P>
   The investor rush pushed the yield on the 30-year bond to 4.72
percent, the lowest rate on long-term debt in more than 30 years.
As the new year begins, the yield, at 5.09 percent, is not far
above the 1998 low.
</P>
<P>
   But the atmosphere has changed since the fall. The Federal
Reserve has cut its interest-rate target three times. European
central banks have made one cut. Brazil has a bailout package in
place and is working on budget reform. Those changes have made
corporates and other non-Treasury bonds look attractive again,
although there is still a lot more than the usual risk attached.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction of these non-Treasury bond markets is twofold.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of it is that these bonds sold off sharply and
have not recovered much of what they lost. In other words, they are
relatively cheap. For example, the spread, or difference, between
the yield on 10-year Treasuries and the yield on a 10-year AA
corporate bond grew to 1.65 percentage points in October. The
spread has narrowed only to around 1.4 percentage points, which
means there is still room for enough further narrowing to lead to
nice capital gains. As the yield on a corporate bond falls, the
price rises.
</P>
<P>
   The second attraction, also the result of wider-than-normal
spreads, is that yields on non-Treasury bonds are much higher than
they would normally be. ``You start out with such a big yield
advantage that you have a cushion there,'' said Martin Mauro, a
fixed-income strategist at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Fixed-income fund managers are really interested in tax-exempt
municipal bonds. A 10-year, AA rated muni bond is offering a tax
equivalent yield for someone in the 31 percent federal tax bracket
of 6.16 percent, compared with 4.64 percent on a 10-year Treasury
note. The yield is even more attractive on longer-term municipals.
The after-tax yield on a 30-year, AA-rated municipal bond, for
example, is 7.46 percent, compared with the 5.09 percent yield on
the 30-year Treasury bond.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term municipals are ``as cheap as we have seen in our
experience,'' said William Reynolds, director of the fixed-income
division at T. Rowe Price Associates. They were an even better
bargain in October, when investors were ignoring all bond markets
but the Treasury market. At that time, the yield on a tax-exempt
30-year AAA municipal bond was actually slightly higher than the
yield on a taxable 30-year Treasury bond.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate bonds, high-yield junk bonds, mortgage-backed
securities and, for those who like more risk, some emerging market
bonds, also look good, according to many analysts at mutual fund
companies and Wall Street firms. ``High-yield, corporate bonds,
municipals and mortgages are cheap,'' said Les Nanberg, chief
fixed-income officer at MFS Investment Management.
</P>
<P>
   But while analysts think non-Treasuries will do better, they
still worry about the risk of another wave of financial
uncertainty. The outlook for some is also tempered by the fact that
the U.S. economy is expected to slow down and corporate earnings
could decline, putting downward pressure on the prices of corporate
bonds and some other bonds.
</P>
<P>
   That is why some analysts are staying away from the high-yield,
junk bond market, which would suffer the most if the economy slows
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bet is going to be in the higher end of investment grade
bonds,'' said Tracy Eccles, a bond portfolio manager at the
Hartford Investment Management Co. She argues that the yield on
lower investment-grade bonds, like those rated BBB, is not great
enough to warrant the extra risk. ``In this environment I would not
buy a bond just for the yield,'' she said. She wants ``good-quality
names'' and issues that were underwritten by more than one dealer
so there is a better chance to trade them if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a decline of just half a percentage point from current
interest rates on corporates, Treasuries and other bonds could
produce some acceptable returns this year. Mauro of Merrill Lynch
predicts that the total return on a 10-year corporate bond,
including capital gains, would be 9.4 percent, while a
half-percentage point interest rate decline for a muni bond would
earn 8 percent, with 4.2 percentage points of that tax-free. And on
a 10-year Treasury note, the return would be 8.2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
