<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5083 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-BOS     01-01 1841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT HEARING A FARCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Will McDonough 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andrew Zimbalist wasn't thrilled about doing it, but in the end,
he agreed to testify before the Connecticut Legislature Dec. 9, the
day it heard Bob Kraft's plans to move the Patriots to Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asked to testify, and it was a busy day for me,'' said
Zimbalist, a noted professor of economics at Smith College. ``But I
had to be back at a seminar before 7:30. And I told them I wanted
to speak for at least 15 minutes, because I have been to these
things before and they give you two minutes, and say thanks. You
really can't say what you want to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimbalist is considered an expert in sports economics. He has
testified before Congress, and in many lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably going to be the only one to testify that wasn't
going to be all for it,'' he said. ``I was going to tell them that
if they were going to do this because they were going to get a big
bang economically, they were wrong. It just wasn't going to happen.
I was told I would speak somewhere around 4 o'clock. I told them I
had to leave at 6:30 to get back. I never had a chance to speak.
But I heard what was said by Kraft and his people and a lot of it
was bald-face lies and bull. The whole hearing was a travesty.''
</P>
<P>
   So Zimbalist, in turn, wrote an article for this week's Street &AMP;
Smith's Sportsbusiness Journal. Under the headline ``Thanks to
Kraft and governor, Connecticut gains a team and loses its shirt''
Zimbalist paints this interesting picture of what happened that
day.
</P>
<P>
   He writes: ``For starters, (Connecticut governor John) Rowland's
close friend and political adviser, Jay Malcynsky, was hired by
Kraft to be his chief lobbyist in the deal. Another of Malcynsky's
clients owns the land on which the project was to be built.
Malcynsky's ability to manipulate the Connecticut political process
was demonstrated when he arranged for Kraft to wire the public
commentary at the legislative hearing, which began at 3 p.m. and
ended at 7 p.m., on Dec. 9th, without ever hearing a critical
voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members of the public had to wait in line to have the
opportunity to address the legislators. It turned out that Kraft
paid at least the first 15 people to stand in line, so the initial
public commentary would be all pro-stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by this reporter how he could say Kraft paid the people to
stand in line and speak on his behalf, Zimbalist responded: ``I
don't think he took the money out of his pocket (that day). I think
Malcynsky is the one who took care of those people. I talked with a
reporter from Tom Brokaw's show that day, and she said she spoke
with the people in the line, and that they were being paid by
Kraft.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufpibox &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It Ain't Over Yet, Part II:
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in Connecticut seems to be in the tank on the Kraft
deal, but Ralph Nader is not. Nader, in the last few days, has
spoken to Massachusetts Attorney General Scott Harshbarger about
joining his mission to overturn what Connecticut and Kraft are
trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nader is going to bring a suit down there, about the way this
whole thing has happened,'' said Harshbarger. ``And he has some
serious questions about the way this whole thing took place in
Connecticut. We have some issues here, but they are not the same.
My office is still reviewing whether we are going to take some
action here or not. I personally don't like the idea of the
Patriots walking out of here and costing Massachusetts millions of
dollars over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader, like Zimbalist, feels the process in Connecticut was a
farce. The usual timetables and legal hurdles to be overcome in
moving legislation of this magnitude were thrown aside. In fact, as
of this writing, the actual legislation _ which was changed _ and
would reveal the givebacks by the Patriots, still has not appeared
in public.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufpibox &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Whether Pete Carroll will be back next year has not been
decided. Kraft is not happy about what has happened with his team
the last two years. After the bitter defeat to the Jets in Giants
Stadium last Sunday, he went into the dressing room immediately
afterward and had a private meeting with Carroll. You can guess
what was said.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft will decide which way to go after the season ends, whether
that's Sunday in Jacksonville or later. It says here that Chris
Palmer, offensive coordinator of the Jacksonville Jaguars, will be
the No. 1 candidate to replace Carroll, not Bill Belichick of the
Jets. Belichick already has it written into his contract that he
will be the next head coach of the Jets when Bill Parcells steps
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer coached with the Parcells staff when the team went to the
Super Bowl and was well liked by the players on the team,
especially Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufpibox &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a rundown on the NFL playoff games this weekend from
some of the coaches and general managers who have played against
the teams this year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New England at Jacksonville: &LR;  From Bills coach Wade Phillips,
who split with New England, and beat Jacksonville at home:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very difficult for the Patriots to win down
there. No Bledsoe. No (Terry) Glenn. Those are big weapons. From
what I have seen of New England (on tape) lately, they are not the
same team we played against twice. The whole story could really be
(Mark) Brunell. If he plays, and he can play like he has, I see
Jacksonville winning. If he doesn't play, then Jacksonville, I
think, will play a conservative game and try to run the ball with
this kid (Fred) Taylor. He is quite a back. I see New England
having a tough time moving the ball on offense. Jacksonville is one
of those teams that is much tougher at home than they are on the
road. That's their history. They are tough to beat on their home
field.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Arizona at Dallas:  &LR; From Redskins general manager Charley
Casserly, who played both teams twice this year:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas has one of the most impressive stats in football this
year. Just 15 giveaways (fumbles and interceptions) in 16 games.
Dallas is plus-11 in turnover ratio. Arizona is plus-1, so the
Cowboys have done a better job protecting the ball, and turnovers
are critical factors in playoff games. Dallas should have the edge
in experience. They have veteran players who are used to winning
Super Bowls, so it is not a big deal psychologically for them to be
in the playoffs. They also have a great home record during playoffs
(undefeated in the 1990s). Arizona is inexperienced in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A major factor in the game could be the absence of Deion
Sanders. The Dallas secondary is more vulnerable when he is not
playing. If the Cardinals are going to win, they will have to take
advantage of some of the matchups they are going to have in the
passing game. Both Rob Moore and Frankie Sanders are big, and good.
Jake Plummer (Arizona QB) could hurt the Dallas defense with his
mobility, and his ability to improvise. He can make things happen
when he starts to move around. I think Dallas will try to run the
ball a lot to their left behind Larry Allen and Nate Newton. Emmitt
Smith is on a roll. He is running very well, and the Arizona run
defense is not as strong as it was when (Eric) Swann was in the
lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   From Giants coach Jim Fassel, who has played both teams twice
this season:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dallas offensive line is really doing a good job. I see
the Dallas offense trying to move the ball very systematically down
the field, not turning it over, taking time off the clock, and
trying to control the game. The Dallas defense pretty much operates
the same way. They bend, but they don't break often. They try to
eliminate the big play. This game will go to the team that can get
its way. Arizona should play for the big play, both on offense and
defense. Dallas will go for control. It really hurts Dallas that
Deion will not play. When he is in there on pass defense, he takes
away one side of the field. Now you can attack the entire
secondary. And of course, he is a great returner. He is the most
dangerous returner around.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Green Bay at San Francisco:  &LR; From Giants general manager Ernie
Accorsi:
</P>
<P>
   ``We played both teams this year and they beat us. We were just
never in it against Green Bay. We got them when we were going
through a tough period. We played better against San Francisco, and
they still beat us. These two quarterbacks, (Steve) Young and
(Brett) Favre, are exceptional. To me, they are both first ballot,
Hall of Famers. I know Green Bay has had good luck against these
guys in the recent past (5-0) and beat them out there twice in the
playoffs, which is impressive. Green Bay is also getting back some
guys from injury. Dorsey Levens will help their running attack a
great deal, and he is also an excellent pass receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the San Francisco matchup on offense, where they have
those three big wide receivers (Jerry Rice, Terrell Owens, J.J.
Stokes). Young is having a great year getting them the ball, and
(Garrison) Hearst has given their offense another dimension. The
key for Green Bay will be getting some pressure on Young, and
avoiding bad matchups with those big receivers. Favre is a great
money player. I don't think it will bother the Packers that they
are playing in San Francisco. They know they have won there in the
past. I think it's going to be a wide-open, very exciting football
game, and the quarterback that has the better day will be the
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Buffalo at Miami: &LR;  From Jets coach Bill Parcells, who has
played both teams twice this season:
</P>
<P>
   ``(Pass rusher) Jason Taylor being out of the lineup will hurt
Miami. He's the best they have. He's a force; he is always around
the ball. They don't have anyone else like him. He can chase some
quarterbacks down. Miami beat Buffalo in Miami early in the year,
and then had them by 10 points in the fourth quarter in Buffalo and
let them come back to win. That game is a big plus for Buffalo.
They know they can beat Miami. They know they can come from behind
and win on them. Miami's biggest problem will be dealing with
(Doug) Flutie's improvisation. Some of the big guys they have
aren't that fast. I think Miami will try to attack the Buffalo
secondary on the outside. Since last year, Buffalo has lost its
three best coverage corners. (Jeff) Burris went to Indy; Thomas
Smith and (Marlon) Kerner are both injured. (Dan) Marino has been
throwing the ball well lately. I give the Dolphins the edge on
special teams. I think they do a better job there.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufpibox &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The NBA owners must be trying to ``smoke out'' the players with
their latest offer. According to an ESPN report this week, one of
the offers from the owners in their last and ``final'' proposal is
a promise to drug-test veteran players for marijuana only in
training camp. They didn't say whether the players would also be
told the time and date of the test so they could be ready for it.
What a joke. This is the new tough drug policy we heard about?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
